name: Buy Me Dinner First
description: Something to do when all the gyms are closed and you can’t climb something harder.

name: Fuck My Ass Behind the Dumpster
description: -Red is start hands, black are feet, blue is finish, green are hands. -Can be topped. -Only to be climbed if every gym in the USA is closed and you are super desperate and sad.  -Rated X because you will probably die from a disease since this is only meant to be climbed during a pandemic.

name: The Boat Police
description: Pull on sharp pocket up a steep face until you can reach the jugs on the slab. Try to pull over while ignoring the rocks below.   Be carefull on the slab above.

name: Knob traverse
description: Traverse right and down a bit to get sharp incut holds. Go right above the void and mantle up and left.

name: Left side
description: Grab the left edge of the litlle Tuck and Roll and mantle up onto pretty good rock. Do 2 or 3 face moves and top out in the Mexican buckeye bush. Bad landing!

name: Cave Dweller
description: Start on a cheat stone and pull around the large boulder. Traverse right staying low until the first cave bowl. Go up and over to the next cave at 2 o'clock. Span the gap and stay high to the next cave bowl under Face Off. Down climb and continue to the next cave bowl. Stay low and pull the side edge traversing to the start of Pointless Wonder. Continue traversing low to the small Cedar Elm tree (tree is on for V0, off for V1). Continue traversing another 20 feet to the last cave bowl that has choss and the bottom lip is about 24 inches off the ground.

name: Coin Slot
description: Starting where Fist Crack takes off, go right above the cave to first bolt. Matching hands in the small “coin slot” at eye level, traverse right to the bolt. Finish on the trophy hold to the chains.

name: Face Off
description: This is the only bolted route on the wall, so you use it to set the anchor for the other lines. You'll find the first bolt just over the lip of the cave which will protect the first hard move.    The physical start to get over the cave is the crux.

name: Pointless Wonder
description: A few yards right of the other routes here, there is a crack system. The larger crack on the left is, I would say, Class 4 and makes an easy way to get to the top and set topropes for the other routes. The thinner crack on the right is Pointless Wonder. In the guidebook, it is 5.4, but just about everyone who gets on it thinks it is easier.  Going to the effort to set up a TR for Pointless Wonder probably is pointless; it feels much easier than many other 5.4 routes I have climbed.  However, it is a rare Greenbelt route that will take trad gear. Stoppers work pretty well on this one, and thus it is decent for learning to place stoppers while having very little chance of falling.

name: Unnamed Crack
description: Just to the right of the three main routes at 5.8 Sanctuary is Pointless Wonder, and "Unnamed 5.6" is just right of it.  This is not a route for a new trad leader, as it is on sketchy limestone. It's not really a route for anyone except a trad climber desperate to place gear in an area swarming with bolts. The rock is weak, some of the placements are questionable, and the top-out and belay are a mess. But for some reason, I've done this route twice now, lol. And it provides an opportunity to use a coveted Black Totem if you have one!  The finish is brushy and dirty, and then you have to fight through brush to set up a belay off trees. Lots of fun. Fortunately, you can lower your second and then crash through a little more brush to reach a trail that takes you back down.  Although my two ascents in the spring of 2018 are the only two lead ascents of which I know, I'm not claiming an FA on this because someone had probably at least free soloed it already. But if I ever find out I did do the FA, then I might name it "Really Pointless Wonder."  My 5.6 rating is an estimate; I can see reasonable people calling it either 5.5 or 5.7.

name: [Redacted]
description: Summary: Climb the obvious cave route that starts on the sloping jug pinch, and follow the moves in a circular motion towards the good sloping crimp on the lip, then move up through the edges to the top.    Details: Starting on the jug pinch, move left to the sidepull, then right to the sloping crimp.  Big move required to reach and pull to the top.    Good: All the holds are solid.    Bad: Big move to the top from the lip.

name: [Redacted]
description: Summary: Climb the arete.      Details / beta: Starts from one head high crimp and a higher crimp.  Move into a hard pinch on pockets and bad undercling.  Move up to a right crimp and blunt arete pinch.  From here, there are 2 variations to finish.  The right variation seems just as hard as the left, just completely different. The left finish has an awkward bump from a really good undercling and decent feet. The right finish has a heinous lockoff from a sharp crimp and bad feet.    Good: Both finish variations can accommodate tall or short climbers.    Bad: Both finishes are tough.

name: [Redacted]
description: Start on the big hold in the roof of whipping post with right hand on the undercling-crimp and left hand on the big pinch, paste your feet on the roof and lunge to the hold at the lip and finish whipping post. I thought it felt 6 or 7.

name: [Redacted]
description: Same start as Whipping Post Right, but instead of topping out directly above, move right through progressively smaller edges and slopers to the dueling pockets (one is a pocket edge and the other is a pocket). Top out directly over the right pocket.

name: [Redacted]
description: Summary: Same start as the Whipping Post (V5).  Move to the right from the jug pinch to a series of good crimps.

name: [Redacted]
description: Same sit start as Whipping Post Right. Move up through the crimps, but instead of topping directly above, move left into the final crimp of Whipping Post and dump to the finish.     Contrived, but then again, most climbing is.

name: Baby Whip
description: No proper whipping on this one, but at least you'll have a little fun! Start underneath on a good hand jam and kick those legs up! Follow straight up on good holds, and then tell all your friends you climbed the only limestone invert in Austin!

name: Crack of Dawn
description: Start with both hands in the lower portion of the crack and a foot in the lower crevice. Shimmy along the crack to the top.

name: Cromagnum Memorial
description: Sit start on Word (far left problem on South face) and traverse the entire top, finishing on the prow (far right side of the South face).     First crux is the first half of the traverse (in its entirety). The second crux is getting through the slopers and pumpy campus movement.

name: Left of Crack
description: Sit start on the crimps in the middle of the left boulder and climb the sloper rail up and right to the jug. Top out from there on slopers.

name: Left of Left
description: Same sit start as "Left of Crack", but move left through the sloper rail and finish on Word (i.e., top out over Word).

name: Northwest Arête
description: Sit start with a left hand on the arête and a right hand on the sharp micro side crimp. Move up the blunt arête and good holds up the center of the face. Crux is the first 2 moves in the entire sequence.

name: Secret Sharer
description: The middle problem on the west face of the Whipping Post boulder. Sit start on the split ledge and figure out a way to move straight up.     IMHO, this climb is horrible.

name: Southwest Arête
description: Southwest arête starts low and just left of Word. Use a left crimp sidepull and a small right crimp, and slap up the sloper and to the dish straight up the arête. Mantle over.

name: Unknown Traverse
description: Same start as Left of Crack V1, but traverse right and follow the edge finishing on the same finish as the Whipping Post Problem.

name: Unknown V3
description: Low traverse, sit starting on the left side of the whipping post boulder (start on Word),  move from left to right on a rail. At the end of the rail, move up and top out.

name: Word
description: Sit start on the leftside of the whipping post boulder and finish straight up.

name: DRW
description: “DRW” starts on a short steep roof/bulge to gain a big ledge at the base of the arete feature. Continue up through the arete and then slightly right into the final headwall.

name: Erin's Route
description: cool route with interesting finish through dihedral and subsequent bulge

name: Hedonistic Urges
description: Climb the large block shaped roof to a huge ledge to rest on. Then climb up heavily textured headwall to a mini-bulge just below the chains.

name: Meat and Potatoes
description: This seldom-climbed line is a rare Greenbelt route that goes on trad gear. Because there are no bolts, you actually have to do it trad unless you want to do some 4th Class scrambling up chossy rock and then do some bushwhacking in order to set up a toprope anchor. There is always debate about trad gear in limestone, but this is a solid crack (really, two cracks). On my failed onsight attempt, I took a pretty good whip on an orange Totem after pumping out above the crux, and I'm still here to write this page. Just before me, another party member tried to onsight it and ended up bailing off a Tricam; he, too, lived. The crux is about 2/3 of the way up where the crack steepens to become slightly overhanging. A solid tree up top, backed up by a horizontal crack, serves for belaying the second. My partners replaced worn slings with newer ones; rap off them if they still look good, or find a scrambling route down skier's left.

name: Moammar No Amore
description: Start on the left facing juggy sidepull under the large roof and make a difficult move into a slot up and right. Mantle up onto the headwall and finish on easier terrain.

name: Suhler Route (Cardosa Route)
description: There is a big runout from #1-#2 which should probably have another bolt to prevent decking. You may also be able to sling a tree between them. There are good rests along the way but there are hard slopey moves at the top and it is a challenge just getting to the first bolt.

name: Super Yummy
description: Awkward movements to get onto the ledge about 15ft up.  The rest of the route is great.  Some big moves, some low percentage moves, all fun moves.

name: Colbster's Revenge
description: Start on the right side about mid way out on a fin-like hold. You grab a right hand sprag and a left hand undercling pinch. Bicycle the fin and make a huge move to a good hold and go up and left to the past good hold before the blank roof at the top.

name: Joshua's Animal Sanctuary
description: Start on a handlebar hold deep in and goes left to a double kneebar end.

name: Living Stone
description: Jump and start on the large jug rail and traverse right through horizontal holds to the right side of the cave. Match and drop.

name: Living Stoner
description: Same Start as living stone (V5) Continue traversing right  Top out is the same as Ratchet Rake (V3-V4)

name: Ratchet Rake
description: Jump start to the pocketed headwall climb up and slightly left  top out through the most incut part of the roof

name: A Little Dab Will Do Ya
description: Same start as Dab-Nab-It and then go out the roof trying not to dab.

name: Dab-Nab-It
description: Starts at the bottom of the hole on the right side of the boulder. Climb up and right on good holds trying not to dab. I'm unsure of the FA or the original name; leave in comments if you know.

name: Easy Wall
description: Easy problems on the left side of the boulder. Watch for poison ivy on the topouts.

name: lowball V2
description: Fun little V2ish problem.

name: Scumalong
description: Traverse right to left the trailside of the boulder restricting the hands to at or above the lip. Sweet slopers.

name: Carlito's Adventure
description: Start on two edges and work along the roof until you pull yourself over the edge and finish by matching on a small crimp.

name: The Diving Board
description: Start with both hands on the ledge and jump for the end of the board. Mantel.

name: Dung Hold
description: Starts with hands on flat ledge feet pushed into roof then you slap out right to a rounded jug which you then match. After matching left heel hook just below matching point and then throw right again to ledge continue up the ledge until you get tho the moss at this point you mantle up and top out the boulder.

name: Longhorn
description: Start underclinging on a flake and follow the crack. Match on some shitty coral-like rock before the mini roof.

name: Moonlight
description: A fun little problem that starts on an edge and ends with a topout. you can either hike back down or jump onto a crash pad below. (I did the latter)

name: Spearpoint
description: Sit down at the right side of the boulder below the overhanging arete with hands matched on lowest slopers. Climb the arete.

name: Spearpoint Arete
description: Start sitting on the right side of the boulder with hands matched on the lowest slopers. Climb the arete but eliminate left hand holds, confining the left hand to the arete.

name: Stickman
description: Start sitting at the far left margin of the Buzzcut wall. Traverse low under the low roof via the shelf system. Exit where the roof ends.    Note: A boulder has washed up against the start of the problem, blocking the first couple moves.

name: Talking Wonkawa
description: Starts sitting at bulge left of Spearpoint with your left hand underclinging the belly of the boulder and your right hand on the sloper side rail. Climb to the arete and finish as with Spearpoint Arete.

name: The Tres Bien (Traverse V2/V4/V6)
description: Traverse is done left to right. For a V6, start on the far left of the dappled wall with your left foot on the ledge and hands matched. Move right through crimpers and scarce feet to a right-angling ledge (V4 starts here). Traverse right to a flake (V2 starts here). Follow the offset ledge system, drop into horizontal finger crack and finish by traversing the crack.

name: You Are What You Arete
description: Climb the pockets up the right side of the You Are What You Is boulder.

name: You Are What You Is
description: Starts sitting with hands in the 'pots' right of center of the wall. Climb to the knobs and traverse them right. Exit at the arete.

name: April Fool
description: This is one of two unbolted routes (that hopefully will stay that way) in between Flash Crack and Touch of Class.  Originally, this was a trad route and can still be done that way, but almost all of the few who climb it now toprope it. The PG 13 rating refers to the sketchy placements and run-out sections if you do this as a trad route.  Start below the lower end of a diagonal crack. After the pretty burly start, climb to a thin crack that leads up to a cave. The original trad route, which goes at 5.9, stops here and the climber walks off left. But the 10a finish involves pulling through the cave. Until you figure it out, it may feel a lot tougher than 10a.  This is a fun route and, if it's not beneath your dignity to toprope in a sport area, it's worth doing and you can almost always find it open because you have to actually build an anchor and not a lot of Austin climbers relative to the size of the community know how to do that or have the gear for it.

name: Arete/Bulge
description: Presently, there are five bolted routes on Guide's Wall. This is the one farthest left.  There are actually several ways to do this route:  5.7 (Arete)-- Climb the face to the roof below the cave and pull up onto the big ledge next to the cave. Finish on the arete. Many think that this feels harder than 5.7.  5.9 (Arete direct)-- Instead of stepping onto the huge ledge and then back onto the arete, go straight up from the third bolt. Opinions of this grade range from 5.8+ to 5.10a.  5.10a (Bulge Lite)-- Pull up into the cave and traverse left onto the arete to finish.  5.10b (Bulge)-- Pull the cave to the anchors.  The bolt placements seem to suggest the 5.7 or 5.9 in mind.  For extra fun, clip one of the anchors and then top out, using older chain anchors up above as your anchors. To avoid a potential backclipping-like situation, put a draw on one of the anchor bolts instead of using the sport anchors. The topout moves are fun and make the route 5.10a or b for sure. If you do this, I recommend rapping off; lowering from there or belaying a second from there will have the rope moving over a sharp edge.  Although this is a bolted route, there are older bolts up above for toprope anchors. Walk to the right past the wall and find a rugged, brushy use trail that leads up and back to the top. Or lead one of the easier routes on the wall and top out.

name: Flash Crack
description: In the middle of the wall are three crack systems. Flash Crack is the one on the right.  This route, and the other two crack routes to its left, was bolted in the fall of 2016, and there are sport anchors above it and the others.  The old TR anchors above are still there for those wanting to take the dirty trail approach to the top. For that, you need around 30' of cord or webbing to get your master point over the edge. From the ugly grooves atop some of the routes at this crag, I can tell some people have TRd without a properly set anchor, and this damaged the rock and could potentially damage the rope, no matter how polished some of the rock here is.  There apparently is disagreement about whether routes at the Greenbelt can go on gear, but this one can if you trust the rock and your placements. One problem is that there is no pro for the start of the route (which is easy but still slick enough that even an experienced climber might slip off). You can get a Tricam in one of the pockets lower down, but it doesn't inspire a ton of confidence. After the run-out, there is good pro, with good stances, the rest of the way. Passive gear recommended.  The newest edition of the guidebook slightly downgraded this route to 5.6/5.7. We'll see what the community says in the long run, but I feel many of the Greenbelt routes actually could be bumped up at least a grade due to the polish, which is definitely a factor on some climbs, including this one.

name: Stand Off
description: There presently are five bolted routes on Guide's Wall. Stand Off is the third as you go from left to right. Until September 2016, this was a TR route using bolts located on a short wall above the top-out ledge, and it served as a sketchy trad lead as well. Now it has three bolts and sport anchors. On at least one other website, this route is listed as a 5.5. It is not 5.5; the submitter likely confused this with Thin Crack (once 5.5 here but 5.6 in the guidebook), and a new leader may very well find himself in way over his head if he jumps on it thinking it is 5.5. The crux is an awkward sequence from the third bolt to a great jug below the anchors. Moving between B2 and B3 also gives some people trouble. In the photo, the rope is set on Thin Crack. Stand Off is just to the right. This picture was taken before the routes were bolted.The newest edition of the guidebook downgraded this route to 5.6/5.7. I disagree with that, but we'll see what the community says in the long run. In fact, I feel many of the Greenbelt routes could be bumped up at least a grade due to the polish, which is definitely a factor on some climbs.

name: Thin Crack
description: Broken crack climb up limestone - plenty of ledges for new climbers. Often used as a warm-up or by guides for outings with new climbers.    Recently bolted (3 bolts) with a typical sport anchor below the top ledge.

name: Touch of Class
description: Hand crack climb up face with early, small bulge which is crux.    Recently bolted like others on Guide's Wall with typical sport anchor below the top ledge.

name: [Redacted]
description: Well protected. Crux is after clipping second bolt.  A challenging pull from side pull to side pull over the bulge.  Move left to clip the third bolt and then strait up.

name: The Big Traverse
description: From John Hogge's book: Climb sections of this for a great warmup. Start at Reefer Madness and traverse right to the cave at Kingdom of Ging. Lap it! Use it when your partner stands you up.

name: Birdland
description: Climb the crack to the ledge and bolt 1, which is too high to stick clip. Bolt 2 is at 11 o'clock. Bolt three is in the roof. On toprope,you can avoid dirty holds by walking the ledge right and climbing up the left part of the column onto the roop

name: Blind Date
description: Start up a diagonal seam (drifting to the left), climb through a sort of bulgey feature at the 1st bolt, then pull the bulge at the 2nd bolt.    Has its own set of anchors, or you can just clip one of those anchors and continue up (on easy climbing) to finish on the Thumb Dance anchors, about 10 feet higher and a bit to the left.

name: Chicken Supreme
description: Climb up and to the left to some great holds and clip. First clip is pretty high so many stick clip it (about 15 feet off the deck). After the first clip there is one 5.10- move. After that move there is great ledges. Just continue up and to the right till you reach the top chains. Without the one 5.10a move it would probably be a 5.8 or 5.9.

name: Cyborg
description: High first bolt. Not so hard at the beginning, but towards the end you have to clip off of a tight mono. After that you will find a variety of crimps and sloped dishes, with a good jug a bit further up than you want it to be. A tough mantel finishes out the route.

name: Fern Bar
description: Start just right of Iranian Arms Deal on a thin face.  The first crux is just making the first clip off of the thin, greasy holds.  Once on the ledge above the first bolt, man up and clip the fixed pin before following the line of ferns across multiple slopey ledges.  Finish by manteling onto the sloping topout.

name: Gros Ventre
description: The crux is early on this one.  High step and reach up to a good sidepull.  Get a rest on a good ledge and figure out how to get to the next good ledge.  Easy peasy after that.

name: Heir Apparent
description: An outstanding route for the area that involves some thin face climbing.  Start right of Wyoming Women (a naturally protected crack climb which cleaves the Gus Fruh wall) under a small roof with a gap in it from the left side.  Layback onto an incut directly beneath the left portion of the roof and clip the first bolt.  This next move makes this route outstanding!  Laying off that incut, highstep with the left onto the outer portion of the roof and rock up into a stance just above the roof.  Follow the climb straight up through a wonderfully thin face.    This route was originally a top rope using the anchors from Wyoming Women.

name: Iranian Arms Deal
description: This route is identifiable by a ledge containing (what else) ferns about 15' up.  There are two ways to start this route: 1) approach it from directly under the ledge (5.10-ish) or 2) maintaining consistency with the rest of the route, traverse in from the right (near the start of Fern Bar).  Either way, you will get some distance before being able to clip the first bolt!  For the rest of the route, follow the bolt line through a series of jugs to a sloping top out that, for the 5.8 climber, will have you checking your drawer's!

name: Reefer Madness
description: Easy climbing/scrambling up onto a ledge and the first bolt. After moderately hard climbing through a few more bolts, enjoy a nice mono pocket while you figure out how to pull the final roof.  Use a couple long and/or alpine draws to reduce rope drag.  For the 5.11a variation Reefer Man, climb the first 4 bolts of this and then finish over to the left on the chains for Running Man.

name: Running Man
description: Start just right of a small garden of ferns. The starting jugs may be a bit slimy, but quality quickly improves. The opening boulder problem goes up a grey belly of overhanging limestone on 3 drilled pockets and then through a series of small but good crimps. Once you're under the honey comb stone, it's 5.9 to the chains. It's always better using natural features of the rock, but the ethic in Central TX back in the day was to get the most out of the rock we had and add pockets to make routes go when needed. Despite a few manufactured holds, this route has great movement and is a ton of fun.

name: Thumb Dance
description: Awesome route.  Solid 5.10 climbing to the second bolt.  Runout between the 2nd and 3rd bolt. Potential groundfall, though the climbing eases drastically.  After you are about 20ft past the 2nd bolt, you can either clip a piton (unnecessary), or clip the first set of anchors.  If you feel like you want to climb some more, clip the left anchor and climb up and left past one more bolt and mantle onto a big block and rap off some rusty chains.  DEFINITELY worth doing to second half.

name: Trash Can Man
description: 4 bolts and fixed anchors. Crux is pulling the roof after the 3rd bolt. Find the crimps to the right of the bolt and pull to the ledge.

name: Wyoming Women
description: Cool offwidth, sharing same anchors as Heir Apparent. Suppose you can place big gear, but most just set TR.

name: [Redacted]
description: This is a bolted, more difficult, variation of King of Ging. Climb to the third bolt of King of Ging, then trend left and upwards for the single bolt of Sex Dwarfs. Continue up and left to meet back up at King of Ging's fifth bolt and finish the climb.  The side pull above King of Ging's 4th bolt is off. Using it will make this variation much easier than 11c.

name: Arkansas Polio Weed
description: Highball slab. Bad landing. Crux at the top. What more could you ask for? See video.

name: The Borg (V7/8 Variation)
description: It is a standalone boulder on the left side of the trail when heading away from Kingdom of Ging toward New Wall.  This variation uses the arete and the thin sharp flake just left of center. The original line for the Borg. Eliminate. Slightly contrived since the V6 flows better. Still a worthwhile line in Austin.

name: The Borg
description: It is a standalone boulder on the left side of the trail when heading away from Kingdom of Ging toward New Wall.      Stand start with a left hand sloper, right hand on the arete and a toe/heel hook on the lower part of the arete.  Move to a good crimp and find a way to campus/move to the the shallow crimp in the center of the boulder.  Move delicately on the slab face to a hidden sloper and then to a small knob.  Topout is hard and delicate.

name: The Boys
description: Start low on a flat jug/ledge and move up left using a crack with two decent crimps and the arete. Maneuver onto the slab face by getting a high right foot on the starting ledge. Stand up and do an easy move to a jug at the top of the boulder. Top out is easy.

name: Bunion Blow
description: Starting (left of the Cube) on the double rail, move up and along the roof crack. Traverse through the crack and link the Cube. Finish on the ledge above the Cube.

name: Bunion Blow Full Left
description: Start on Bunion Blow, finish Hank's Left

name: Bunion Blow Left
description: I'm gonna keep it simple and say: Start Bunion Blow, then go left.

name: Charlie Don't Surf
description: This route starts just right of the beautiful tufa that runs down the middle of the Kingdom of Ging.  Pick your poison - mantle up on the ledge using a heel hook or lead in from the right.  The first bolt occurs at your feet - probably not necessary to clip as a fall at this point will put you on the ground and the second bolt is easily accessible next to the tufa.  Run past the second bolt through a thin, bulging section (10)  and up towards an alcove.  The technical crux occurs here - using a thin half moon, rock up onto a thin ledge.  If you can get this without whipping off, the rest of the route is smooth sailing.

name: Cherry Blossom
description: A short problem with a crux power move at the end to a solid ledge. Start squatting down on good holds and move onto a series of positive slots above and traverse right to a left hand crimp and right hand horn-like hold and setup for the crux move.

name: Circus Trick
description: Stand start at the right end of Chinaberry with the flake off. Climb through the obvious sloper and to the jug; then drop.

name: Crossfire
description: On the far right of the cave, start with hands crossed on a left slot and right sidepull. There are a few polished holds to choose from before going out to a flake-ish thing. Top out on the big ledge and ponder the massive number of people who have contributed to the polishing of the problem.

name: The Cube
description: On the right side of the cave, start underneath on the undercling and move up to a compression side pull on the right. Figure a way up to the upper ledge from here.

name: First Contact
description: Start sitting under the Wolf 359 boulder with one hand on each rail and one foot on each rail. Pull off the ground and move up the feature, exiting via the massive jug on the trail facing side of the boulder.

name: Flip the Script
description: Start climbing Bunion Blow left, but instead of matching in the undercling in the roof go out to a miserable, nearly invisible pinch on the lip, using it to compress the roof. Walk your feet around and kick your legs up into a bat hang and use that to top out.

name: Gray Streak
description: Pull the ledge below and a bit left of the route. Start on the ledge. Decent runout between bolt 3 and 4. Fairly crimpy route. Mind you're feet and you'll be in better shape. Fun, tall (for the GB) route. One tough move below bolt 4.

name: Hank's B8 Extension
description: Ultimate sit start to Charlie Don't Surf, all the way at the back of the cave. Climb the boulder problem known as Hank's B8 (Left) and once you top out on the pancake hold at the tufas, climb into the sport route Charlie Don't Surf. Fun linkup, 50+ feet of climbing, and despite the equivalency of V7~=5.13a, I think this route is on the verge of 5.12d/13a, but Mtn Proj doesn't let me select that slash grade; let's discuss. Try not to walk too far to the right once topping out Hank's B8 on the ledge, to try and avoid excessive resting, try to stay in the boltline of Charlie, because this linkup can be contrived, but not that contrived.

name: Hank's Direct
description: Summary: Start in the back left of the cave under Kingdom of Ging. follow obvious jug haul out towards the left to two crimps at the lip. Make the huge move from the crimps out to the triangular jutting jug. Traverse right on the ledge and then top out.    Details: Line begins from two jugs directly in the back, centerline of the Kingdom of Ging cave.  It moves into a jug / pocket, directly behind you (going out of the cave), into another jug to your left side.  There will be one more jug, directly center, that you will move to before you reach to a deep 2-3 finger pocket out to the left.  With some footwork, move out to the right to a 3 finger half crimp and up to the jugs above, traversing slightly up and to the right. It finishes directly under Charlie Don't Surf.    Good: Holds are very good for the first half of the route, but with limited feet / tricky sequencing, the first half of the route can feel awkward.      Bad: The deep 2-3 finger pocket.  Somewhat sharp, pulling off the pocket can shred some serious skin.  The problem is completely overhung, so figuring out your beta and moving quickly will help.    Crux: Moving from the pocket to the half crimp.  The key is using either a heel hook or toe hook & drop knee to crank up to the crimp.  Body tension should be your focus.

name: Hank's Left / B8
description: Left variation of Hank's B8 / Direct. Start inside the cave and move out through good holds. Head left through good jug holds and make a large move to the dihedral. Finish on the jug rail.

name: Hank's Right
description: Same start as Hank's Direct / Left (inside the cave).  Move out on the obvious jug haul and right through 2 crimps. Make a strong move into a shallow sidepull/undercling,then make a large move up and left, outside the cave, to the rail.  Figure out how to match on the rail (get creative) and finish by traversing right directly under Charlie Don't Surf.

name: Jerry's Kids
description: Jump to the ledge just to the right of the tufa. Climb straight up with cool moves through crimps. Trend to the right after the 4th bolt, do an awesome move to an undercling, then easy cruising to the anchors.

name: King of Ging
description: Jump to ledge and mantle up. Clip, rest and go for it.  When you reach the upper cave traverse the lip to the left and up again to access chains.

name: Must Be 72 Inches to Ride
description: Start on Bunion Blow, move into the first undercling, but instead of traversing right into the next underclings (The Cube start holds) reach out towards the lip, then bump, then bump, then top out on the ledge.   This problem is also called "Bunion Blow Direct", probably, I think.

name: Resistance is Futile
description: Start as for Simulacrum, but instead of exiting with the massive jug keep traversing along the rail through the arete and onto the front face of the boulder. Use the right arete to top out, but eliminate all the good holds on the trail facing side of the boulder (i.e.the jug used on Simulacrum and the big crimp used on Wreckage are off). Eliminates suck but you're only climbing this boulder because you've got nothing left to do out here anyway right??  Even though it's an eliminate, the movement is seriously cool!

name: Screwed Up Trick
description: Start on Tabula Rasa and finish Circus Trick   youtube.com/watch?v=pWBIoZt…

name: Simulacrum
description: Start matched on the rail with your back against the large boulder and toe hooks on the opposite rail. Compress and shuffle up the rail, using the large jug on the side of the boulder that faces the trail in order to top out.

name: Spank Bank
description: Start on the jugs of Hank's, and move into Hank's Right.  Traverse into Bunion Blow and finish the problem.

name: Tabula Rasa
description: Same start as Cherry Blossom. Traverses the lip through the crimps past Cherry Blossom's dyno. Cross your way to the sloper edges to the side pull and track back right to the jug.  Note: Holds have broken off the ending and the finishing sequence holds are chossy. Pull at your own risk.

name: Wreckage
description: Start as for First Contact but rather than exiting using the large jug, eliminate it, keep shuffling up the rails, using the good edge just right of the right arete to exit.

name: (toprope)
description: The set of glue-in anchors just to the right of Aphrodite. Lead Aphrodite and set-up anchors/toprope.

name: Aphrodite
description: The rightmost climb on Myth Wall (just to the left of the Kingdom of Ging Cave). Easy climbing to a high fist bolt. Trend up and to the left through two ledges to either sets of anchors.    A super quick warmup - you might want to run up it twice for feel warm.

name: Athena
description: Right edge of mini roof.

name: Phoebe
description: Starts up a staircase, basically, and then hits you with that typical band of blank rock that makes you do awkward things with your body. And high feet. Of course.

name: Poseidon
description: Goes up under mini roof.

name: Rhea
description: Up the dihedral through the semi-blank.

name: Jimmy Hat
description: Crux is getting to a good anchor clipping position (if this is at or near your limit). Well protected though.

name: Lifestyles
description: Crux is reaching the chains. The portion of the route above the last bolt has been called 11b if you go straight above the bolt. The 10b grade is veering right of that section. Easier climbing, but you will take a minor swing if you fall.

name: Magnum
description: Crux is at/above the second bolt, on the sequence leading to the slopey ledge.

name: Sheep Skin
description: Crux is protected by the fourth bolt, getting above the small cave.

name: Trojan
description: Crux is the sequence above the last bolt to get to the anchors.

name: Mr. Backdoor Man
description: A very unique cave climb for the Barton Creek area.   There is a bunch of loose stuff in the back of the cave, don't pull it, every hold you need is solid.  Start on the right hand wall near the back of the cave on a low jug. Make a move right then lean back and grab a pocket on the wall behind you. Continue to traverse out of the cave. The crux is orientating yourself so that your back is facing out so you can pull the lip of the cave.  When you can stand over the lip with both hands off your done.

name: 4:20 Traverse
description: Starts at the base of the small cave with your legs inside the cave and hands on the shelf. Climb the roof via pockets. Exit up one level and continue traversing left with your feet on the knobby shelf and hands on the slopes above. Top out left or step off.

name: Alcohol Arete
description: Climb the pocketed prow left of Doublewide.

name: Bad
description: Sit down with hands on the flake undercling. Climb the prow to exit just left of Bad Belly.

name: Bad Belly
description: Stand up and climb the slight prow to exit at the point where the tree branch brushes the top of the wall.   Guidebook says it 'needs a sit down start to achieve ultra classic status'.

name: Best of The Bunch
description: The vertical crimp test piece of Barton Creek.  Full grade harder than Tiny Dancer probably still easier than the borg, so v5/v8. Grades are dumb this route starts on a banana and is a lot of fun!

name: Cigarettes
description: Climb the face left of Bad. Start left, finish right at high point.

name: Crack
description: Layback the crack on the front of the boulder.

name: Crack Head
description: Offwidth the crack on the front of the boulder

name: Doublewide
description: Climb the crack left of Cigarettes

name: Right Arete
description: Sit down and climb the right arete.

name: Smokin Wack
description: Sitdown and grab the scab. Climb sharp pockets up and right.

name: The V0 Boulder
description: Cool karstic boulder with a couple easy warm-up routes.

name: Wack
description: Sit down with the left hand on the slanted edge, right hand on the layback hold. Climb the arete.

name: Yo Mama
description: Sit down and grab the flake. Get the right edge, match and top out right.

name: Disorder
description: Stand next to the boulder that sits on the ground. Climb up and exit right of the tree.

name: Left Clingy
description: Low start with hands on an undercling/block w/ bad feet.

name: Nervous Tic
description: Start sitting right of the boulder on the ground and move left to exit above this boulder.

name: Rest Arete
description: Climb the jugs to the right of Twitch

name: Right Clingy
description: Same low start with hands on an undercling/block w/ bad feet. Exit right to ledge.

name: Tourettes Arete
description: Sitdown and climb the leftmost arete.

name: Twitch
description: Start the same as for Nervous Tic but exit straight up.

name: Sculpture Falls Traverse
description: When the creek is dry the short overhang can be traversed (usually from right to left)

name: Thread The Needle
description: You will have to get wet and start in the water so bring some shoes you don't mind getting wet or go barefoot. Its a bit tight as its more like a hole your squeezing (off width) through.

name: Thread The Needle
description: Bring shoes you don't mind getting wet or go barefoot

name: Man Up
description: Grab the undercling/pinch rail and man up to the lip jug. Mantle up, sit in the jug, and drop  off.

name: The Tronics
description: This 60ft problem traverses the roof from left to right. Start with your left hand in a shallow hueco feature on the face and your right hand on the in-cut crack under the roof. Move right through the half pipe hueco feature and exit to the lip at the last hueco.

name: Cedar Fever
description: Cedar Fever is on the right side of the Geritol Wall. This route travels up some moderate low angle stuff to start. Then it enters a vertical section with some good seams and a small shelf. In middle of this route there is a long reach, which can be made easier by using a mantle. After the no hands rest ledge comes the crux. Move up and right off of a 2 finger undercling pocket and a flat edge to a good pocket/edge and then the top.

name: Prism
description: Easy route to the right of Cedar Fever. The proction is Climb Tech Wave glue-in bolts. They are low profile, so you may have to look. The low anchors are good for top rope for a 5.6

name: Rock and Roll High School
description: Multiple distinct and interesting sections await you on this route.  Start by grabbing the dusty ledge and throwing your feet on some crap edges.  Work your way over the bulge and into the double gaston section.  Take a much needed rest before you enter the crimpy, balancey crux.  The way I do it involves some zig-zagging.  It's a fun route.

name: Sunshine Boys
description: This is an interesting route that deserves more action.  It has beta that goes at 5.11, though it's not immediately intuitive.  Mount the sandy ledge.  Use a strange knob in the roof, a pinch, a foot cam and a knee bar to make this sequence work.  Another krux awaits on the vertical wall above.

name: Adam's Way
description: Doesn't get much traffic. Goes straight up. Hard moves that require reach right off the ground. Then ok hard moves out the roof and finish on Pee wee's 2nd crux.

name: Disneyland
description: Short hard 13b  Since it's FA (1990) only 9 people have successfully red-pointed it.  Alex Catlin Hank Caylor Jeff Jackson Matt Twyman Rupesh Chhagan Clayton Reagan John Gonzalez Chris Meacham Chris Grieg  youtube.com/watch?v=BUZoOz8…

name: Fook You AKA Don't Hurt the Rock
description: Old "bandit" route that had a runout has been rehabilitated. New Glue-in added in the triangle roof to protect the move under the roof and the moves out of the roof to the last bolt. Sport Anchors added, as well.

name: Heaven's Gate
description: Hard moves over the 1st bolt is the first crux. Then traverse right under the roof to exit on the right side of the Hug Thy Mother route. Possible double knee bar and another crux on thin crimps to the same anchor as Hug

name: Heaven's Hug
description: FA'ed BITD with poor protection. Glue-ins and upgraded anchors were installed March 14, 2019. Begin on the first 3 bolts of Heaven's Gate, then clip a new glue-in in the roof. Pull the roof and then climb the headwall ( clipping another new glue-in) to get to the anchors.

name: Hug Thy Mother
description: One of the 2 "hard" 5.12s in the area. Has 5.10 moves to attain the first bolt. Then hard moves under the roof with an awkward clip of the 3rd bolt to begin the 1st crux. Move up and out of that roof to the smaller roof to set up for the 2nd crux.

name: Iron Man
description: Crux is getting to and over the roof, on a hot humid Austin day this is gonna be hard (greasy).  This is kind of a one section wonder as it finishes easy 9/10- climbing to chains...

name: Peewees Big Adventure
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Power Monkey
description: The quintessential tweaky Greenbelt route. A 2 bolt V5/6 overhung crimp problem to a good rest followed by some weird vertical climbing. Start on the dusty ledge. Don't even bother to wipe your feet because the next shelf is made of dust too.  The crux is fingery and cryptic. For me it involves a throw.  The rest is fairly straightforward and a bit of a let down.

name: Shock the Monkey
description: This route is a linkup: begin with the first two bolts of Power Monkey (PM) then finish leftward on Tunnel Vision (TV).  This is a higher quality route than PM in my humble opinion, and these days it sees more action than PM.  After the PM crux, I traversed on the jugs just below the third bolt of TV and then clipped said bolt.  There was definite ground fall potential. It appears you could move left earlier to the flat ledge below the second bolt on TV.  A long runner on that bolt would prevent any drag and the safety factor would be improved.  I would say this linkup adds quality without significantly increasing the difficulty of PM.  Try it!

name: Space Cowboy
description: The crux is the bottom half.  I recommend stick clipping the first bolt, otherwise you might end up flying over the big ledge you started on.  Dyno to good jug in the beginning, work through some pockets and crimps, then finish up on jugs.  Top out is pretty loose so be careful.

name: Through the Looking Glass
description: I've always liked this climb, its got some diversity.  Start off with optional campus moves and pull up and stand on the ledge from there move up and a little left.  You get another huge ledge rest before moving out right and over the bulge (so fun!).

name: Tunnel Vision
description: Wow! Lots of pumpy fun on this one!  It's on you pretty much the whole way with some great holds and good rails to rest on (good luck with that).  Crux comes at the top when you're good and pumped!

name: Buddha
description: this is a one move wonder 12, climb up to the ledge begin out and over super thin buldge using some small crimps, lockoff strength and some a toss/dyno to a jug ledge/rail.  at this point your joining the route walk the dog (11-) and is probably easy 10 from here on out...

name: Cloud Nine
description: Same start as Hysteria.  Go left after 2nd clip and then back right at the very top to the chains.  The crux is 2nd to 3rd bolt.  4 bolts with sport anchors.

name: Hysteria
description: Short and pumpy - oh and super polished and greasy! Although don't let that keep you off of it - if your at New Wall, you're already having to deal with that!  Climb up to the cookie and head a little right to the rail then traverse a couple hand moves back to the left and go straight up.

name: Patron
description: The crux is going over the 2nd bolt.

name: Walk the Dog
description: Hard moves on a crimp traverse to go left from 2nd bolt to a good ledge and be able to clip 3rd bolt. Possible pendulum swing if the leader falls in the traverse. This was the 1st route bolted on this wall; Jan 1 1988 after the 1st ascent free soloed by Hank. Was a mildly popular toprope location for several routes at the time.

name: Wowie Zowie
description: Same start as Walk the Dog. After 2nd bolt go straight up. Shares the anchors of Buddha and Walk the Dog.

name: Gunsmoke
description: Going straight up after the second bolt provides for the full experience of this four bolt line protected at the top by chains

name: Hank's 5.10
description: Starts with about 15 feet of slab climbing with a bolt at the end of the slab. Work your way up past some ledges.  Feels like 5.8+ until the last bolt.  Super fun route. Slightly runout at the beginning.  Definitely worth it.

name: Save A Bolt for Me!
description: Easy, open climbing up until above the third bolt. The crux, which is significantly harder than the rest of the route, earns the 10d rating (at least) and occurs between the last (fifth) bolt and the anchor chains. Belayers be careful of loose belays above the fifth bolt, as the ledge beneath the fourth presents a mild fall hazard. Anchor holds may be chossy/flakey, so get yourself certain before pulling out clip slack.         This route can also be top-roped by traversing left from the anchor chains of the route immediately to its right.

name: Cactus Patch
description: Start under the left starting bolt. Crux is the start. Cruiser ledge pulling to chains.

name: Cactus Patch (direct)
description: Bolted variation of Cactus Patch. Starts under the right most bolt of the Terrace and climbs straight up.

name: Crystal New Persuasion
description: Low crux leads to mellow climbing and no hands rest before crux bulge. Go a little left for slightly easier rating or stay directly over bolt line for full grade. Super good.

name: Either Way
description: From SummitPost.Org:    Tommy Blackwell and Chris Grieg put this up in December 2016. He suggests that it is 5.7 left of the bolt line and 5.8 to the right. You can also go further right and find variations that feel 5.9 and 5.10. By Greenbelt standards, it's a pretty long route (about 45'). The rock is not (yet) polished. 5 bolts, a bit runout to Bolt 5, but a fall wont mean decking.

name: Patch of Heaven
description: Climb the first 2 bolts of Cactus Patch, move right to clip an old piton. Easy traverse to the ledge under the last bolt of Heaven's Hug. Exposed climbing to attain that last bolt. Finish on Heaven's Hug's anchors.

name: ACK!
description: Contrived start due to the proximity of the moderate dihedral to the left.  Fun pulling above that, however, on crimps and pockets past 4 total bolts.

name: Angel of Poets
description: Thin moves below the first bolt are the crux.  Move through some jugs and you're at the anchors.

name: Bird Dog
description: Fun climbing on polished limestone.  Difficult to get off the ground, but beyond that not too much challenge.  Perhaps getting up to clip the anchors is the hardest section (assuming you clip with hands -above- the anchors)    Some fun TR variations exist as well, climbing left and over the bulge to the ledge below the anchors

name: Black Slabbath
description: Crux is at the top

name: Butt Scratch
description: More polished climbing on uneventful terrain, also popular with beginners

name: Captain Morgan
description: Different style of climbing than most of this wall... watch out for the prickly pear cactus at the top of the route during a few traversing moves!  Some tricky moves down low before the first bolt as well.

name: Cuttin' Cards for a Poke
description: Hardest part is the end when hands get smaller and the the feet have to come over onto the fin

name: Die Easy
description: A great warm-up or beginner route. Located just to the right of The Mongrel.

name: Diving for Rocks
description: The crux is getting from the 2nd to 3rd bolt. The "easiest" way to do it is probably to lunge, but it can be done static as well. I reccommend doing it both ways for the full effect! After the crux, it is easier, but you still gotta hang on. Some of the rock up top can be a bit dusty.

name: Dogtailing
description: This is the longest "established" route on Seismic Wall, and it is a traverse. Because it crosses several popular lines and uses their hardware, be considerate of others and only do this route when you find this section of the wall empty. I originally listed the route as 5.8 as it is in the local guidebook, but that's a little confusing because the start is the crux and that start is also the crux of a 5.9 line. No, there's not a huge difference in those grades, but it's still a little confusing. The route has a PG rating because of the second clip and the easy runout between the third and fourth clips. The route: clip the first two bolts of the Mongrel (don't use the skinny tree if you want the 5.8 or 5.9) and then traverse left and clip Hollywood's second bolt. Traverse left and then climb Roo Dog's third and fourth bolts; climb to the anchors and clip the left anchor. Head up and left and clip Butt Scratch's left anchor. Finally, go up and left again and clip the anchors of It's a Wiggle Butt, and lower. Those anchors are easily distinguished because they are the highest on the wall.The crux is the start. The climbing on Roo Dog is 5.7/5.8, and all the rest is easy and fun.

name: Hollywood
description: Great warm up climb. It starts between Roo Dog and Die Easy. Apparently used to be labeled as Rick's Way(?).

name: Hoover Head
description: Crux is the last move before anchors (and the moves above the anchors). Smooth crimps, then over a bulge, a few more moves to the top. Crack at the left is probably off-route, and far from bolts anyway. The last bolt is right below the anchors, skip on lead and set up a TR through it if you want.

name: It's A Wiggle Butt
description: More polished limestone...  Again, popular with beginners. More interesting than some of the other routes adjacent to this one

name: Just For Fun
description: Just For Fun is a fun and varied line that traverses as much to the left as it does ascend vertically. Anchors near the prickly pear at the end of a short roof. Rare limestone hand jams are useful when working out the roof to get to the jugs to clip the chains.Rock Dog can be TR'ed from the anchors for this route. "Direct" also has one old bolt in it, about 20 feet up, left over from the first ascent by Tom Suhler and Bruce Becker.

name: Lick the Window
description: Crux is low with a very fun move below the first bolt.  Fun climbing to the anchors after crux.

name: Lonesome Dove
description: A hard finish to Diving for Rocks

name: Luminaire Noir
description: Tricky face climbing down low and some more enjoyable stuff up high.  Longest climb on the left end of the wall. Painful crux holds originally had this route named "Lick the Paw"  :)

name: Magster
description: Crux is between second and third bolt where you have to commit to a small sidepull.  Above this, move though ledges and jugs to the anchors

name: Man Hands
description: Tricky climbing on enjoyable rock of various features.  A shame it's so short.  Called "Man Hands" because the route varies dramatically depending on finger size at the top of the route.  For some women, the route is 5.10.  For myself, however, and anyone else with man hands, it's tougher because we're unable to cram our digits into the small crack at the top.

name: Matter of Honor
description: Bouldery start below first bolt.  Move through jugs over a bulge and you're at the anchors

name: Mister Blister
description: Awkward beached whaling/ mantling/ off routing or something required to pull over the bulge.  Also, as soon as this thing gets traffic and becomes polished, it will be much harder

name: The Mongrel
description: Stout start made trickier thanks to a tree. Don't cheat! Use good feet and less than ideal hands to reach the second bolt and pull over a buldge. One more bolt on good but polished holds takes you to the chains.

name: Nose Print on the Windshield
description: Short but packing a punch, "Nose Print" is a powerful route that rarely sees any traffic.  Avoid using the crack to the right of the route or it makes it .11a

name: Over Easy
description: On the right hand side of the big roof. Work your way  up the low angle face to a big prow on the side of the roof and pull up into the honeycomb holds, then  work right along a crack to the chains. The direct start is 9+/10a and the right start maintains 5.9. Awesome route. The overhang moves are not hard, but can be scary if this is your limit.

name: Roo Dog
description: Super polished climbing on less than vertical rock. Great for beginners.

name: Seismic Step
description: Crux is down low, getting on the route.  Share holds with ACK! and then it's smooth sailing to the top.  Pretty hard bottom moves for a 5.8...

name: She's No Dog   She's My Wife
description: Solid climbing right from the start.  Stick clip the first bolt to avoid the nasty fall into the bushes.  Crux comes above the first bolt as you make a powerful move off a small right foot.  Pull some jugs to the third bolt, then find an interesting move over the bulge before finishing on a short slab to the anchor.

name: Short People
description: Tricky techniques on this short but fun route. Per the Austin climbing guidebook: "This route will make you think."  I interpret this as: "This is not 5.9", but I never really have figured out the best way to get up this thing...

name: Slimy Crack aka Icecubes, Popcorn and Popsicles
description: This is the route immediately to the right of Diving for Rocks and is easily distinguished by wide-ish (fist), flaring crack.  This crack is the crux of this route - always greasy, it's tough to get your mitts to stick in this thing.      The top rope above this route is 12a, Lonesome Dove.

name: Snowtards
description: Sometime by summer 2019, the huge tree at the right end of Seismic fell, and its absence cleared the start of an entirely different line about a yard or so right of Black Slabbath. So on July 19 I led Black Slabbath and set some directionals to facilitate TRing this "new" route.  On September 22, I went back and led it trad. Because the placements were sketchy and there were fewer than I thought there'd be, I will not describe them or recommend gear. Basically, I led it trad just in case I really did do the FA and someone came along and said it didn't count because it was on TR.  To anchor, I crossed over to the Black Slabbath anchors and placed a cam and a hex along the way to protect that short, easy traverse. While I have used that rock before for directionals and have rapped off such placements, that time I found that the rock there has gone from questionable to terrible, and I even trundled some large pieces. However, there is still okay rock if you look for it.  If there is a party on BS, you will need to go up into the brush to find solid trees for anchors; the rock around the topout is not sufficient for building a safe anchor. You can TR this off the BS anchors, but a fall will mean a big swing left, possibly crashing into a climber or rope on Die Easy just  left of BS. So basically don't climb this route unless DE and BS are unoccupied or you are willing and equipped to lead the route and then crash through brush.  My 5.6 is based on not using the fallen tree to start and on pulling onto the ledge just above where the anchors likely would be were this a sport route. Otherwise, this is maybe 5.4.  As to the name-- there has been a recent fervor in the Austin climbing community to rename "offensive" route names. My name for the route is a poke in their collective woke eyes. And for the record, I am not a Trump voter; I just can't stand the woke/PC people.  It will take you less time to climb this route than it took you to read about it! Enjoy!

name: Torpedoes Away
description: Tricky beta right off the ground makes for an enjoyable puzzle of a route. A fun 5.9 once you've figured out the sequence.      Another super polished, bouldery start with -EASY- climbing above. It's fun regardless, and it also provides convenient access to the ledge where anchors for both "Angels and Poets" and "Matter of Honor" can be accessed so you can get ready for your headpoint of these two spicy leads by practicing on top rope  :)

name: Undertow
description: An extension of Cutting Cards for a Poke, 5.12a, which is and extension of Diving for Rocks 5.10d.  Climb cutting Cards and top out.  Fun time to do a big victory whip.

name: Tree Warmup
description: Very short climb on interesting features. Don't use the tree, though.

name: [CLOSED] Spelioantics
description: THIS ROUTE IS CLOSED ~ THE FLAKE IN THE ROOF IS LOOSE AND CAN FALL ~ YOU WILL DIE ON THIS ROUTE  An old project (don't believe it ever had a first ascent) that goes up the face left of Urban Assault multipitch. Many drilled holds up the face and into the roof, where you climb out a stunning flake that is just begging to be climbed. However, upon inspection, this flake is loose and easily weighs hundreds of, possibly over a thousand, pounds.  ADDED ONLY FOR HISTORIC PURPOSES

name: Buzzards Breath
description: On the far left , in the corner is a 4 bolt, no anchor 5.9  Topping out over the last bolt will feel runout.

name: Cell Block
description: Follow the first three bolts up a thin face to gain a big ledge next to the huge rotten hueco/cave. Then move up and right into the roof just below the chains.

name: Ladrone
description: The warm-up. Follow drilled 3-finger pockets... Oops: one broke-- now it's a little harder.

name: Masada
description: Involves a shallow 2-finger jam and a blocky roof. Caution is advised for the belay; a large block may fall. Belay should stand well to the left.

name: Medicine Man
description: Endurance route linkup in its finest form. Climb Cell Block and once at anchors, traverse right along the ledge until reaching Plate Techtonics, then finish Plate Techtonics.

name: Plate Techtonics
description: Back from the 90s, an old Austin classic is back in business. A classic Jeff Jackson route, only saw a handful of ascents in the 90s before falling into the obscurity of Urban Assault. Thanks to EvJohnson and Matt Glass this route has been rebolted with glue-ins (Oct. 2018) and outfitted with a few permadraws, and it's a true monster of a route. Route tops out on a triumphant ledge with an amazing view of the Greenbelt.  Thought of as Starfish's older brother, this sport route will test many weaknesses with its variety of moves, holds, and angles. Be it known that there are drilled/chipped holds on Plate Techtonics [sic, as named in Jefe's two Texas Limestone guidebooks], as there are on many UA routes. Also in keeping with UA fashion, many holds on this route get quite manky in wet weather, fortunately not quite as bad as on Starfish. Jeff Jackson thought this route ought to be restored, as the best, most historical route at Urban Assault.  Hardest route on the Greenbelt? For a long time the two hardest were Disneyland and Plate Techtonics, both at 5.13b. During the rebolting of this route, a few holds (jugs) broke off due to the choss of Urban Assault, and this route is significantly harder than it was, Hank Caylor even suggesting that it could be 13c or 13d in its original state. That being said, we're comfortable giving this 5.13+ now, until one of those team kids flashes it... Champagne n Reefer is also one of the hardest since that hold broke and there's some ridiculous move now, and I heard that some guy, who used to climb at Beehive a lot, sent it recently...  [Warning: lil beta here]: Split up into 3 sections (the face, the overhang, and the roof) with a crux each, you must excel in standing on tiny vert footholds, pocket pulling and crimping in a 45 degree overhang, and roof jug endurance. Save some energy for the topout too! Ugh, such a fun route.  List of known ascents: Jeff Jackson Paul Clark Jack Mileski Hank Caylor (twice) JLilStar (first ascent in 20+ years?)  Big ups to everyone who helped contribute to making this route a thing again, it's people like you that keep this community aLiVe

name: Starfish
description: Climb through 10ft of bad choss to gain the first bolt where the rock quality gets way better. Sustained moves will take you up and into the large hueco just under the roof. Continue up through the crack in the roof and pull over the final lip with great exposure!

name: Urban Assault
description: Classic multi-pitch sport route on chossy limestone. P1- first two moves are burly then mostly 5.8 to a seated belay in a cave.(UPDATE - holds broken off the start make the first two moves off the deck go at mid 11 climbing) P2- traverse out right to an exposed 10c move on the roof and on to another seated belay in the shade. P3- sustained 11a climbing with burly moves on good enough holds. Stay left and up. Good exposure. Many aid here (goes 10c on aid) and runners are sufficient to link bolts if you cannot climb it free. Rappel and enjoy the view.

name: Badass Arete
description: An amazing arete climb! Start low on the right side of the left-leaning arete, and ride that bad boy up through some crimps and some blocky holds, reaching the sharp point at the tip of the boulder. The boulder to the left of the arete is off, don't put your feet there. There may be a hard sit start or direct start to this climb, just waiting an ascent.

name: The Hard Bulge Problem
description: This problem is thin and hard. Start on obvious right hand half-pad crimp, left hand edge on the bottom of boulder, and slap your way up and to the left, topping out on the slab above the bulge. This is a project, and it may not go; the grade is approximate, it could be 9 it could be 12, IDK. Needs some opinions, needs some traffic, needs some love. Sergio, Thanh, BA where yall at.  Edit Jan. 2020: was informed that this problem has been done in previous years, not a project any more. was wildly wrong about the grade, both times I posted it. was a fun but sketch climb.

name: Stick to the Message
description: Tricky problem that goes up the center of the face of the boulder, with a bad landing. Start standing on the back-breaker boulder under the Hard Bulge Problem, left hand side pull, pull up onto the face and slap to the big left-facing flake, top out above flake.

name: Hand Arete
description: Sit start in between the tree and the boulder just to the left of the Hand Crack, on some knobby jugs. Ride up to the right and follow this southeastern arete. Stay off the Hand Crack I suppose, and be nice to the tree.

name: Hand Crack
description: Amazing hand crack on a boulder, with an overhanging section, varying sizes of jams, and excellent training movement. An Austin Classic. Sit start for the full effect.  [Status 8/23/19]: The grade is very much needing consensus; I don't have much experience with crack climbs, so please help out.

name: Hand Jugs
description: Climb the featured arete on the southwest side of the Hand Boulder. Jug bash your way up the arete, and just have fun with it.  [Status 8/23/19]: Didn't know what to call it but, it was jugs, on the Hand Boulder, so yeah. Name up for suggestions.

name: Hand Slabs
description: Great easy slabs up the main, south face of the boulder. Mind the tree under the starts.

name: The Blocque [name pending]
description: A scenic free-standing boulder in the middle of the riverbed. Very aesthetic and inviting, but it'll require some cleaning. Imagine you follow the arete up and right from a sit start.

name: Mr. Bubble
description: Awesome slab climbing on sharp, dark limestone. Look for the cool knobs! "Some of the best easy problems in A-town" --Jefe in Texas Limestone Bouldering.

name: Mr. Bubble Arete
description: Climb the east arete, from a sit start (ass on the ground). One move wonder? Great texture and difficulty

name: Mr. Bubble Slabs
description: This isn't one problem in particular, rather a collection of slabs across the main face of Mr. Bubble. Fun, easy slabs with varied holds and movement. A little tall but the landings are good.

name: Untilted AKA Mr. Bubble Sit Start
description: Just a lil sit start to the classic Mr. Bubble Slab, about 7 feet to the right of the black knobby slab, and sit under the mini-roof. Start matched on an obvious pinch hold, do some footwork reminiscent of the McK classic of a similar name, move out left to some sharp-ass holds, and work your way up the ridge til you top out on the slab.  It is unlikely that someone has climbed this before, because the river has been slowly eroding the base of the slab to reveal this mini-roof, but if so, please let me know. Excellent problem but sharp!  The grade is approximate, please give opinions.

name: Wander Dyno AKA Blunder Dyno
description: A nice lil dyno problem in the riverbed. V dirty but probably fun. Reminiscent of the now closed Wonder Dyno at Thy Tanks. The grade is a total guess, yall get out there and give opinions.

name: BUllSHit
description: Start sitting at a distinctive vertical pocket to the left of Court Appointed President. Pull to a tufa pinch with the right hand and exit left.  (This route is listed as 'BUllSHit' in the TLB guidebook but there's a series of photos on 0friction that could either be this route or Military Industrial Complex that are titled 'Japanese School Girl'?)

name: BUllSHit variation
description: Starts at the same vertical pocket but instead of catching the right hand on the tufa and exiting left the guidebook says you go left hand to the near tufa (and I think right to the far tufa) and exit the same as Court Appointed President.

name: Court Appointed President
description: Far right route. Starts sitting at the tufa. Crux top out.

name: Driveby Democrat
description: Start sitting matched at the far left. Pull right and top out.

name: Military Industrial Complex
description: Start sitting at 4 finger pockets and move up through pockets to top out.

name: Moral Majority
description: Sit start at the short steep wall at the far left margin of the cave. Climb up.

name: Punk A** Chump
description: Start sitting on low pockets. Move to the undercling pocket to the lip and then top out.

name: Village Idiot
description: Start at the undercling and move left to exit at the lip dihedral.

name: Afghan Rebel
description: Sit start at the tufa about 20 ft left of the right margin of the cave. Pull up to a big pocket in the roof and move right to exit just left of the waterfall.

name: Bottlecap (aka Mr. Little Jeans)
description: Really cool line out of the right side of the cave. Starts in roof matched on a big hueco, with feet split on ledge. Long moves between huecos to get to the lip exit.  ***FYI: The Texas Limestone Bouldering guidebook has this route listed as 'Mr. Little Jeans' but many in the local community have said this route is actually called 'Bottlecap' and from what I gather the variation that starts in a hueco out to the left is called 'Mr. Little Jeans'???***

name: Dug In
description: Sit down at good huecos on the far right margin of the cave. Pull up and exit just left of the waterfall.

name: Full Afghan Rebel
description: Sit down start at tufa a few moves to the left of the Afghan Rebel tufa. Pull out to a two-finger pocket in the roof and move right into Afghan Rebel.

name: Mr. Little Jeans Left
description: There are two variations in this roof, a left and right. The left variation starts in the middle of the roof and there is no ledge, you have to throw your feet up to the roof. Make some big moves right and then connect into the same finish. The right variation (which seems to fit the description of the other published "Mr. Little Jeans") is to the right and does start with your feet on a ledge. Both feel the same difficulty. Top out may need some cleaning! My personal favorite roof climb in Central Texas.

name: Osama Arete
description: Guidebook says to sit at the far left and traverse the second tier to exit at the first break in the cap.

name: Bubbles Face
description: Walk straight up the bubbly face.  Props to Christopher Lee Jaramillo for posting it- I'm pretty sure first ascent would go to Native American children.

name: Cover Your Tracks
description: Sit start on the downstream side of the boulder and traverse up and left.  Top out left.

name: Look What the Cat Tracked In
description: Sit start just right of Bubbles Face and do a hanging traverse to the far right corner of the boulder.  Pull up and top out.

name: Project
description: Start sitting, use crimps and bad feet to move left and throw for a jug

name: Where Does The Shimmer End and The Climber Begin?
description: Start sitting left and traverse right.

name: Daily Vitamin D Dose
description: Probably the most obvious line on the wall. Fun movement and clear holds, not too awkward. Use the big pocket in the middle of the ledge and go left to top out on the same ledge as Supercharged Collagen.  Toping out directly above may be possible if a lot of dirt is cleaned away, and may create a harder variation of the climb.

name: Hidden Nutrients
description: Start in an awkward position and then lean back enough to grab a crimp on the underside of the lip and use it to reach all the way to the top of the wall.   Somewhat height dependant but I think there are good options for most people.

name: Milk
description: This problem is basically just one hard mantle move, or maybe heelhook. It is possible that if you clean enough dirt away you might be able to find other holds.  If you climb farther from the same starting holds and top out over there it could be considered a different problem.

name: Precision Engineered Whey
description: Depending on your height, begin with a mantle into a big reach and match the obvious slopey crimp if you're tall or potentially reach directly up with right hand in a decent undercling if you're shorter. Then grab one of the two upper pockets and top out.

name: Soy Milk
description: Start on the same holds as “Daily Vitamin D Dose” move left hand up the obvious  pocket, right hand to the sloper, find your feet and match the sloper. Left hand move to a good pocket right hand to the smaller higher  pocket find the left foot and mantle top out.

name: Supercharged Collagen
description: Start with a high heel or smearing. Awkwardly maneuver your way in between the shelves and reach up for the obvious ledge. Grab the juggy pocket to the left of the ledge and top out.  For an easier and less uncomfortable problem, start higher and just reach directly for the ledge.

name: A Trick of the Trade
description: In the middle of the Big Chief Boulder, starting on the crimp rail below the large rail, traverse right through to a crimp and move up to a pocket and sloper till you meet up to the large rail. Finish by traversing to the end of Big Chief.

name: Big Chief
description: SDS on the far right-side of the Big Chief boulder  and climb the arete on large pockets.  The start is the crux of the route.

name: Critter Crawl
description: Crux is where the tree is at, so it's kinda sketch the first couple tries. Definitely one of the longest boulder problems in Austin

name: Daddy's Little Daddy
description: Try your best to avoid a dab on this awkward and somewhat contrived but interesting boulder. Start matched on the horn feature with your body underneath the bulge and then move right to decent holds and maneuver to get on top of the slab.

name: Hank Crank
description: The original V2 traverse. Starts sit starting on the large rail and traverses the entire rail to the end of Big Chief.

name: Sloper Groper
description: Similar start to Hank Crank, but stay on the ledge underneath the large rail. Once you're past the tree, move across through a pocket series to the finish. Feels hard for a V1.

name: Squonk
description: To the left of Big Chief, sit start on the slopes jug and move up through crimps, side pulls, pockets and a slope. Avoid the arete. Pseudo-eliminate.

name: Balanced Equation
description: Climb the front facing arete of the small rightmost boulder. WITHOUT YOUR HANDS.

name: Bill Creek Traverse
description: Traverse the entire Right Erratic boulder from right to left, staying at or below the level of the rock scar at the start of Classic. Long and technical, with two good rests

name: Bovine Perspiration
description: Start on the pockets and climb straight to the top! Avoid using the curved ledge.

name: Chimney Shorts
description: As the name implies, make some chimney moves to climb in between the two boulders. After moving up a bit, turn around and top out the Left Erratic boulder.

name: Classic
description: Stand start on good pockets and continue to climb on good pockets to the right of the arch/crescent shaped-hold (just to the right and off-center of the boulder) up to the top.  Pockets are solid.  Near classic, easy slab climbing.

name: The Crumpatonian
description: The left boulder traverse.  Start on the ride side of the boulder with the toss on Walter Weed.  Work left through several monos and a series of difficult matches in two finger pockets.  Finish out Prescription Child to the upper left end of the boulder.

name: Dazzling Desperation
description: Start at the two-finger sprag. Climb right to the large hueco then straight to the top.

name: Eigen Vector (Backside)
description: Start with left hand in mono bolt hole, deadpoint to a right hand gaston, then to pocket below the lip.

name: Face the Face
description: Stand start with a right hand in good pocket and a left hand on a small sloper.  Move up onto another slopey crimp & mono into a left gaston/pocket.  ***Large hueco is off according to topo guide***  There are two good crimps to get your feet into position to move to slopey hueco and finish on good pocket just above.  Crux is the slabby feet.

name: Freaking Feet
description: Stand stand on the good side pull and crimp edge. Figure out how to move off the start with the good foot pocket out right and move up to the lip.

name: Gitty Up
description: Stand start with your left hand on the two pockets and your right on a mono.  Move up the face on small pockets and positive crimps into a sharp mono.  Crank up to a good left pocket before topping out.   Crux is getting good foot positions and moving into the final pocket off the mono.

name: Hole in the Wall (Backside)
description: Starts on a right hand sidepull/crimp. Set your feet where you can and dyno to the V-shaped notch directly above. Graded V4 in Texas Limestone Bouldering.

name: Layback
description: On the Walter Weed Boulder, starting on the right side of the boulder, climb the left trending ramp using the jugs and pockets.

name: Left of Classic
description: Stand start on the huge hueco and climb up the face on pockets and crimps, which are all left of the crescent shaped hold.

name: Little Wimpy
description: On the small right boulder (to the right of the Bill Boulder), Sit start the crack and finger jam your way up. Note that in Texas Limestone Bouldering (2011, Jeff Jackson) this route is called "Balanced Equation".

name: Mad Dog and Beans
description: Move from a left hand gaston and a right hand pocket through small pockets to a large pocket before topping out.

name: Mission Impossible (Backside)
description: Start with your right finger in a mono about 6' above the concrete slab. Dyno up to the only pocket available with the left and dyno again to the top. Have fun with the match and mantle topout.

name: Moss Farm
description: Eliminate problem starting between Screaming Fingers and Dazzling Desperation, sharing no holds with either. Climb straight up the mossy part of the wall on small pockets.

name: Nudge Edge
description: On the backside of the "Frontside" boulder to the far right(aka Walter Reed Boulder, backside), stand start and climb the arete using a series of pinches and sidepulls on polished holds.  Beware of the concrete landing area.  Crux is topping out.

name: Pocket Walk
description: Climb up good pockets on the right side of the left boulder and top out. Nice warmup.

name: Prescription Child
description: Begins on the same two crimpers as Xanax but moves up and left. Hit the first pocket right-handed and then bust left through a small crimper and tweeky little two finger pocket. Make another move to a better pocket and top out.  NOTE: this problem is graded as "V-impossible" in the Austin guidebook due to critical hold breakage.

name: Ruffles
description: Starting on the far left side of the frontside (Walter Reed) boulder, climb the arete using jugs, easy pockets, and solid slopers.

name: Screaming Fingers
description: Screaming Fingers runs along the leftmost side of the right Frontside Boulders.  Follow big pockets and slick huecos to a slopey top out.  The crux is just trying to stick your feet on the greasy, polished face.

name: Shadow Step
description: Starts far left by the arete. Use pockets with the arete off or on (doesn't affect the grade) and then traverse right into the dueling two-fingers of Viagra and finish that route.

name: Short Face
description: Climb straight up to the large hueco. Same finish as Dazzling Desperation.

name: Short Man
description: Climb the good pockets up to the ledge and top out. Downclimb using the small boulder immediately to the right of this route. Be careful downclimbing, as the small boulder is quite polished and can be slick.

name: Tiny Dancer
