description: Begin in two dishes at shoulder height near the middle of left boulder.  Make hard moves through a series of monos to a sloping hueco and top out.

name: Underdog
description: On the backside of the Walter Weed boulder, sit-start and climb the obvious sickle-shaped flake on the left side.

name: Viagra
description: Start at shallow pockets and climb up to a decent right hand crimp. Traverse left (crux) into dueling two-fingers and fire off another boulder problem utilizing a glued edge to top out.

name: Walter Weed Shuffle
description: The first hard boulder problem in Austin remains respectable today.  A Bull Creek classic.  Reachy.

name: West End
description: Climb the thin slabby seam on the right end of the boulder.

name: Xanax
description: Starting on smooth crimps, yard up on a series of shallow but positive pockets. A very small left hand pocket and a meager crimp lead to a toss for the top edge finish. I like a small tick mark, pre-placed, on the final edge as it's sorta invisible.

name: Banana Man
description: Simple overhanging boulder problem. Good starting hands (match in the pocket) and feet. Crux is the mantle.

name: Bear Hug
description: Sit start and follow the ledge until the crack, then climb straight to the top.   There are two variations which involve climbing straight to the top of the boulder at the crack:    1.) A compression ("bear hug") variation. It involves finding a right-hand hold on the underside where Banana Man starts, with the left hand on the ledge.   2.) A two-handed, ledge-only variation. More difficult than the compression start.

name: Marshmallow Love Affair
description: Stand start on the left side of the boulder and follow slopers to the point. Great change of pace from the usual pockets and crimps. Classic line.

name: Left Arete
description: Sit start in the Hueco and climb rightward, keeping feet on the face.

name: Right Arete
description: Start on a sloping ledge and move leftward up the arete

name: Sit start on the face
description: Sit start on the face and top out.  Go static and steady.

name: Hang Ten
description: Start with hands matched on a low left ledge. Traverse right through low pockets up and around the right side of the boulder. Made more difficult by skipping the huge jug, which a bird has decided to build its nest in.

name: Low Tide
description: Sit start the left side of the face, get a heel hook and pull up to the top.   For a real challenge, transition into shallow end traverse and traverse rightward.

name: Shallow End Traverse
description: Start on the right side of the boulder and traverse to the left side using top slopers.  Alternatively, start left and traverse right!

name: Water Jump
description: Start with a low left toe and right hand in a shallow dish. Jump for the top.

name: Slick Willy's Lament
description: Climb any variation of this face. The left has a juggy pocket that you can reach up to for a quick and easy top out. The slight dihedral in the middle of the face is a bit more challenging. For a real challenge, stay off the top ledge until you reach the high right point. Avoid spider webs, the small tree, and keep feet off of Boulder 3. The start feet are slippery any way you cut it.

name: Boulder 3 Traverse
description: Starting from the top of Boulder 2, traverse your way onto Boulder 3 (keeping your feet low). The moves aren’t super hard, but the duration will get you. Try to go all the way around if you can!

name: Shamu
description: Reach up high to a left pocket for the start. Go straight up for a struggly top out.

name: Water World
description: Start with a right hand on a dirty meat hook. Move left and up into the undercling Hueco. Reach up to the left side of the ledge, get a high right foot, and pull back right for the top out.

name: Crack, Baby
description: Start the layback at the beginning of the crack with feet on the ledge (feet pointing upstream).  Traverse left and top out.

name: Crack, Baby - Extension
description: Climb "Crack, Baby", but keep traversing and top out to the far left point.

name: 7 Layer Dip
description: Start hanging from the lower ledge.  Gain the first ledge, then gain the top out.

name: Rain Dance
description: Balance or jump your way under the roof out to the ledge, then swing over the top.

name: Scuba Steez
description: Reach up into the crack, get your feet and butt on the lower ledge, and traverse to the right using a crimp, mono, sloper and meat hook until you get to the two good pockets.  Pull up and top out.

name: Scuba Steve
description: Start in the crack and traverse left (around the bulge) to the top out.

name: Slippery Fisting
description: Get a fist jam and top out

name: Blood Sacrifice
description: Follows the dihedral to the left of El Machete. Great dihedral footwork and underclings to the headwall. Get onto the head wall and prepare to make a blood sacrifice in the reachy two finger pocket.  Continue on cryptic pockets to the chains.  Probably the best 5.10 at the wall and just a hair away from 5.11.

name: Bloody Knuckles
description: Start on a left hand crimp and right hand sloper. Tic tac your way up crimps to a jug and exit to the right.

name: Bloody Knuckles Sit
description: Sit start with right hand on good dish, left hand on bad slopy crimp. Do a big move to the start of Bloody Knuckles and finish that.

name: Calcetines
description: Starts left hand on a weird sloper at 4 feet, right hand on a tiny edge. Go up through some miserable crimps and go right to a good hold.

name: Easter Uprising
description: Good mix of holds on the route! As far as I could tell, the route goes straight up and the top moves are on the left at all the pockets (to the left of the bolts). For the finish, find the sweet pocket below the top and grab the top for fun mantle up.

name: El Machete
description: Climb the blunt arete in the middle of the wall. Boulder up to the first bolt, climb right of the second bolt, and then finish on the vertical wall above.

name: Fern Bully
description: Originally called The After School Project with a suggested grade of V9-10, a fern was pulled making the route easier and changing the name ;). This route will be wet if it recently rained.

name: Fern Bully Traverse
description: Sit start to the left of Fern Bully on jugs. Traverse right to the jug of Fern Bully and finish Fern Bully.

name: Gateway
description: Climb the crack zig-zagging right then left to a horizontal seem and ledge 15 feet up where you can rest your arms. Look down and see that section was steeper than it looked!  Now climb the slightly overhanging face past 3rd and 4th bolts to the anchor.

name: Good Book
description: Climb up dihedral to far left of crag

name: Howard's End
description: Low crux, just trust the feet. Beta is wack since the breaking of a key hold, do what you can up to the ledge. After that, easy movement on nice pockets and the arete up to the chains.

name: Isomorphic
description: Start on Fern Bully, but trend up and slightly right on crimps. Crux is a deadpoint to a tooth. Still on you until you hit the 3 finger. Alternatively, link into Bloody Knuckles for a variation, "Homomorphic" V10.

name: It Bites
description: Traverse right to left on overhanging boulder. Starts about 3 feet from right edge of boulder at heavily chalked good holds, first couple moves are bit cruxy, then get in to sharp crimps and couple slopers in the crux near the end, then top over the edge to finish. don't grab too high when finishing due to the poison ivy.

name: La Campanita
description: From the inside corner (a couple feet left of where Narthex starts) traverse up and left thru the reachy crux passing the first bolt. Climb up thru a second crux to the second bolt, then up and left thru fun easier moves past 3rd bolt to the anchor. Clipping the anchors might be casual if you find the bomber hold. The moves have a nice flow to them.This route can get dirty, so bring your brush to clean the holds for the RP.

name: Leafy Endings
description: Starts at obvious big pocket about 6 1/2 feet up then lunge to next good hold about 4 feet up with tiny feet then after pulling yourself up its easy crack climbing to gain access to top. easier for taller people.

name: lizard head
description: I give it v4- it starts on a left crimp and a right sloper then heel hook the shelf on left then find nice crimp up high roll in to your heal switch your right hand in to crimp then go for a good pocket with right make cross with left to a sharp sloper then cross again with right to a chicken head ( quite large one)then in to a pinch w left the make your way over bulge to a nice rail with right then pull up over bulge and get a left foot on chicken head then head right to top out

name: Mosquito Bites
description: Do It Bites backwards then top out straight up gaining a RH crimp and LH gaston.

name: Narthex
description: Pull the crux above first bolt. Moves get easier in the corner, then do your penance as the pump sets in on the slightly hungover headwall to the anchor.    This route can get dirty, like most Gtown routes, so bring your brush to clean the holds for the RP.

name: Nico's Red Truck
description: Shares start holds with Violence) but facing boulder instead. Work your way up to the half pad crimp and get your body in position for the crux. There is a good 2 finger pocket but reaching and the following transition are the crux. You'll move up to the side pull and from there get some good high feet and throw to the top. There is a good portion of the top with a small lip, enough to dangle/pull on.

name: peaking at the vultures
description: it starts off on 2 crimps and one tiny nub near the bottom for your foot (that i thought might break but after 7 climbs its pretty tough). then make your move to the nice sloper to gain access to a nice rail to move upward into some nice jugs at the top. But to make it harder if you try not to use the sides and stay in the middle there's some maginal finger pockets to make things a little more interesting. Some of the rock is flaky near the center so be careful.

name: Poison Ivy
description: Balancy move low down at the light-colored bulge, then the steep wall where the holds don't feel as good as they look and sucker holds abound.

name: Pyramid Direct
description: Several hand and foot hold that almost appear to have been carved out of the rock specifically for climbing (unknown if they actually were) make for an easy climb to the top of the Sanctuary Boulders area. Slight balancing act around the top corner.

name: Race aginst the snails
description: starts about 5' up the boulder with a left obvious side pull sloper and a right crimp with 2 good feet. Next 2 moves up have lots of possibility to gain a right hand on a great sloper near the top. then bring your left hand over to a very small crimp that you will match after you heal hook the first sloper. then go left some more to the obvious giant 3-4 finger pocket. then either a dynamic move to the top or static slow movements to a 2 pocket pinch to top out. I like the dynamic move to the top because the 2 pocket pinch is awful.    NOTE: This route will be added to. For harder moves start where your feet go, probably V6+ V7 probably harder will be coming soon. Also depending on what time you climb this route you will find a snail racing you to the top, hence the name.

name: Skin
description: Start at 2 low holds, Same as (That rock above looks like it will crush me!) . Move out left to a crimp/finger pocket (kinda sharp, tape will help) and then the side pull. Move feet up to reach the mono pocket. Reach right, intermediate mono before the next side pull. Bring feet up again to reach the next finger pocket. Bring your feet to the ledge, good spot to rest moving in to the last mono pockets. Smear your feet  and get a good push to throw to the top. Top out is full of loose twigs/rocks/and dirt.

name: Skin Direct
description: Another variation to the boulder skin. Direct line up. Starts with hands matched on the horn then dyno up to a crimp edge. Get a high foot and match the crimp. Pull up to a gaston to get your feet up. Use a Mono pocket to get a foot up on crimp edge and pull to the top.

name: Song of Myself
description: Slabby start up a crack to nice face climbing on small crimps and sharp pockets. Fairly easy climbing until the top where it gets tricky. To drop it to a 11c,skip bolt 4 and head straight up and mantle over. To keep it lld, follow bolt line.

name: Soul Food
description: Sit start, Left 2 finger pocket right on lower edge.  Bump right hand to higher edge along arete and then bump left up to pinch. Compress both hands to get a high foot on a small chip then move left up to arete. Match hands then bump left out pinching arete. Place a left foot on the face of boulder. Match hands at top of boulder and rock feet over.

name: Soul Stone
description: Stats far right of boulder, and traverse left to top out. Starts on crimps with obvious foot holds, bump out left and match. Continue to a left pinch and set up to throw/bump to the jug side pull. Bump right up to the top edge, match and work your way left to top out.

name: Soulvision
description: Low compressed start. Left hand crimp start around the arete, with left foot same side of  arete. Right hand start undercling and right foot on low obvious foot hold. Crux is the first left hand move to a sloper pinch. Move left foot to top of right hand start ledge. Big move right to finger slot. Left hand bump to top corner, bump left foot to heel the sloper. Right hand to top of boulder and mantle the top.

name: Still Waters
description: Starts with 2 small crimps and a foot on low ledge. Throw to good corner pinch and transition to next crimp. Bump to the next side pull and get a high heel. The crux move is throwing to the 2 finger pocket off of the crimp. Once the pocket is secured you can reach out some jugs on the right to get your feet up. One more finger pocket before top out. (There are trees/shrubs along this route/at the top) They can make topping out difficult, would also recommend down climbing the slab section to the right of the problem.

name: That rock above looks like it will crush me!
description: Start low @ two obvious good holds to the right of big hole in the wall. then hook your way up and traverse right all the way to the second seam before arete. save your energy and set up for a big move to a good crimp or the two finger pocket, get your feet up, then easy balancy moves from there to gain access to the top. The big rock at the top looks like it could come down, but once your at the top you will see how big it really is.

name: Torn Awake
description: Pumpy long moves up an overhanging face, low crux but pump sets in at the top. No rests make this one fun! Begin the climb up the angled slab along the crack. Hit two not so great crimps at the edge and throw up to an angled crimp. Throw a heel over the ledge to get a good clip stance for the permadraw, reset, and throw again to another solid crimp. From there, the holds are great, just fight the pump and move up on good jugs and pockets to the top!

name: Unbound
description: Route consists of reaching up a bulge and mantling about three times. Definitely tricky for people with shorter reaches.

name: Unnamed crack
description: Obvious crack on the backside of the boulders with the tree growing out of it. Awesome introductory highball.

name: Use the Force Luke
description: Gracefully clip first bolt. Clip #2. Beast up to #4. Find nice pocket on roof. Suck it up, stay strong for #6. Either strong static is required for top chains on a nice dyno to the top.

name: Violence)
description: Fun stem/palm start facing away from boulder. Need to get both feet secure to move up to the rail. From the rail you need to move your other palm up higher(dependent on your height) to bump from the rail to the pinch. From the pinch you can reach out to grab the crimps (middle crimp is best). You'll need to move you feet up (small chips available for both feet) to grab the next rail higher up. Get a foot on the furthest crimp, match on high rail, and drop the back foot to get a pistol squat position with the high foot. Rock over onto the foot on the crimp then use the pinch to bump to the ledge. Once on the ledge you can foot swap with the foot on the crimp and smear the other, match on the ledge. Smearing foot will heel around the edge at the top of the boulder. Rock on heel and bring other heel about last ledge. Be careful with top out since most of rocks at the top are loose, grab sparingly .

name: Wasp Arete
description: Route starts under 45-degree nose. Gain the obvious hold then start up the lower nose with some rather sequency moves. Lower moves are V4. Fluid movements from here with a cryptic.    It's called Wasp Arete for a reason. Watch out for small wasp nests near the 3rd bolt along the underside of the small ledge features here.

name: Archimedes Lever
description: Same thing as Driving Miss Daisy: start on Tilted Earth, pull the roof, traverse left to jug, but then continue traversing left 5 more feet and exit straight out of the roof. Holds have broken, harder now?

name: Archimedes' Stand
description: Start at the head height jugs shared by Toothpaste Dream and finish Archimedes' Lever.

name: Backseat Driver
description: Stand start in the center of the roof, at the jug slot on Driving Miss Daisy, and go straight up, finishing Driving Miss Daisy. Be careful not to fall and tumble down the banks of the river into Onion Creek lol. AKA Creek Dart.

name: Driving Miss Daisy
description: Start on the sloping shelf of Tilted Earth, pull the roof, traverse left into a jug slot, then pull the rest of the roof straight up. Holds have broken, harder now?

name: Nine Pound Hammer
description: Start as for Tilted Earth and pull out onto the flake. Instead of going up and left (Tilted), move right to a nano-crimp, then to some better crimps. Top out. Hard shit.

name: Tilted Earth
description: Under the right side of the roof, start on a sloping shelf, pull the roof into the thin flake, then go up on small holds and top out.    Other variations exist from these starting holds. Start here and traverse left under the roof, with different topouts. Ask around for more info, because many holds have broken and the names of different problems vary.

name: Toothpaste Dream
description: Stand start to Toothpaste Highway. Start on the jug and make a big move straight up and out to a nonexistent hold on the lip. Top out above.

name: Toothpaste Highway
description: Start on the sloping shelf and head left on small holds to a jug. Do a big move from the jug and head straight up.

name: [Redacted]
description: Low start to Power Merchant.  Start on a slopey crimp for your left and a good 2 finger for your right.  Bad feet.  Big move into the slot that begins Power Merchant.  Finish Power Merchant.

name: Broken Feet
description: Sit start on a jug rail and move left into a good pocket.  Transition to a right pocket / rail, settle your feet, and dyno to the finish.  Crux is the dyno.

name: Clingon
description: Sit starting on a good rail, and move up into a left 2 finger sprag.  Move up and right into a two finger pocket and top out. Painful for the grade. Crux is moving off the sprag.

name: Leftmost Injury
description: Sit start on a decent left facing flake rail and move up to either good pocket.  Pop up to the top.  Located just to the right of the gigantic flake.

name: Perennial Blowout
description: Start on Power Slip N Slide. Move up and right to double shallow, nasty monos and dyno to the lip.

name: Perennial Blowout Stand Start
description: Stand start to Perennial Blowout.  Start with double monos and huck to the lip.

name: Pint Curl
description: Sit start on a wide pocket and go right to a mono undercling.  Move up to a small left crimp and pop to the top. Crux is moving off the mono undercling.

name: Power Merchant
description: Start in a good juggy slot at head height.  Do a big move straight up to a small crimp, then try for the lip.

name: Power prow
description: Start powerslut climb through the prow .

name: Power Slide
description: Start with left hand in a mono and right hand on a jug.  Dyno to an edge just below the lip.

name: Power Slide SD
description: Sit start to Power Slide. Start on shallow pockets and move into mono and jog. Dyno.

name: Power Slip N Slide
description: Start about 7 feet to the right of Power Slide on some low jugs.  Traverse left 3-4 moves into Power Slide. Finish Power Slide.

name: Prow merchant
description: power merchant/ power slut into the prow

name: Prower Merchant
description: Climb the Prow into the jug, then move left to the slot and finish Power Merchant. Getting the right hand around the corner makes this a little spicier than Power Merchant.

name: Right of Pint Curl
description: Stand starting on a left hand pocket and a right sloper, move directly right into a small sidepull.  Move your feet up and dyno for the lip.  Crux is the dyno.

name: Number 0
description: Climb the Chimney ¯\_(ツ)_/¯

name: Number 1
description: Start by reaching up into the chimney, but move right into the pockets and the arete of the chimney for hands.  Top out right of the chimney.

name: Number 2
description: Start in the undercling Hueco and top out straight up

name: Number 3
description: Start in the undercling Hueco and traverse a little right into the seam to top out.

name: Number 4
description: Start in the undercling hueco and do a long haul through pockets to the far ramp for a top out.

name: Number 5
description: Start at the far right end of the layback crack under the roof and traverse left.  Top out on the same ramp used for topping out Number 4.

name: Number 6
description: Campus to a crimp and two-three finger pocket, then high reach to the good pocket and top out

name: Arete Chicken
description: Starting on the Arete (V3), exit the route early onto the slab.  Hard for its grade.

name: The Arete
description: Hard for its grade.  SDS (with a left hand on the arete and a right hand jug inside the overhang) and climb the arete on incredibly polished limestone.  Multiple shallow pockets are available for heel hooks. Recommend climbing this in any season other than summer.

name: Bang Em High
description: Start on Whip Lash pockets and climb into Bangarang. Finish Bangarang.

name: Bangarang
description: Sit start on jug slots just left of whiplash, and traverse left into the Arete. Finish the Arete.

name: Big fun dyno project
description: Still a project, but I had to put it out there. Grade is just speculation.  I think hader than v10 whatever it ends up being . Start on miserable left hand pocket crimp and right on a sloping pocket , and throw for the lip.

name: Big Sharp Flake
description: Traverse up and left on big sharp flake to chossy mantle. Rock is suspect.

name: Blur
description: Start with low left-facing flake and climb the overhanging arete.

name: Born to Drag
description: One move wonder.  Dyno off of a 2-finger left hand pocket and a right hand sidepull.

name: Chronicles of JAD
description: Start with both hands matched on the lowest rail directly underneath the sloping pocket. Go straight up the wall using the sloping pocket, upper rail, 3 finger pocket, and finally matching on the lip. Top out with mantle is possible and would slightly increase the grade but seemed sketchy given the large tree sticking out across the route. Please message me if this route has been previously documented from another source like a guidebook, etc.

name: Drag Queen
description: This is the sit start to Born to Drag.  Sit start on 2 small crimps, then move into the left pocket and right sidepull.  Dyno to the finish. ***Caution: there is a fallen tree at the base.  Take caution in properly protecting the landing.  Minimum 2 pads.***

name: Hair Lip Traverse
description: long pumpy traverse( will update after I try it too lazy to brush the thing off last weekend)

name: Houdini's Escape aka Arete Chicken Sit
description: Sit start to Arete Chicken.  Start on 'Neo-Classical Arete' and move from underneath to the slab; same finish as 'Arete Chicken'.

name: Kentucky Cream
description: This is the sit start to Kentucky Dream. Sit start on a sloper and shallow pocket.  Climb off slopers into some small pockets & a micro sidepull up to the face.

name: Kentucky Dream
description: Just on the face right of the arete on the project wall, stand start and climb off sloper edges up the face.  Climb off the sloper edges into some small pockets & a micro sidepull (on the right) up to the face.  Crux is the start.

name: Neo-Classical Arete aka "Low Start"
description: Sit start on a chalked up crimp and undercling, down underneath and to the lower right of the base of the Arete. Move into the starting foothold (of the Arete) and a 2 finger pocket, and transition onto the starting pocket of the Arete. Finish the Arete.

name: Primordial Soup
description: Sit starting on a left undercling pocket & 2 right pockets, make a large move to a high pocket that is just left of center.  Reach up into another pocket (up and to the left) before moving into the sharp undercling (up and to the right).  Make one final move to the lip and top out.  **Height dependent**

name: Sea Hag
description: Stand start on a small slot and move up to the right into a series of small pockets.  Continue up the face on alternating pockets and a small crimp before topping out.  The wall on the left is off.  Crux is the sustained climbing off small, sharp pockets.

name: Sharma Problem
description: Start Blur, matched on the flake, and go right. Stay left of Kentucky Dream. Using those holds as feet is fine though.

name: Whip Lash
description: Sit start on the right hand side of the boulder on a 2-3 finger pocket and slopey crimp. Dyno to the big jug on the lip. Don't dab your feet and don't roll off into the trees if you lose your grip during the whiplash!

name: Wolf Spider
description: One of the few easy problems at Mckinney.  SDS off of low slopers.  Move to the slopers in the middle of "the Boulder". Finish sequence off another set of pinch-slopers before topping out.

name: Alterna-Chick
description: SDS on a wide ledge.  Pull into 2 tiny crimps and move into a "right-facing feature" that can be crimped as well.  Crux is finding the 2 crimps and being able to pull off them.  Route is hard for its grade.

name: Basic Female
description: Low start to Alterna-Chick. Start on good 2 finger pocket for left, bad 2 finger or chossy flake for the right. Climb straight into Alterna-Chick and finish it.

name: Dirt Bag
description: Match on a small slopey edge.  Make a BIG move to a good edge.  You can then either go to the top or move to the right sidepull before making a move to the top.  Crux is the first move of the route; the slopey edge has a decent thumb-catch to pull off of.  The key to the first move is finding good feet to crank off.

name: Douchebag
description: Low start to Dirt Bag. Start on two third-pad crimps, go to start of Dirt Bag.

name: Drier Goods
description: Same problem as Dried Goods; however, right facing flake on right side is on.  Right flake has a low pocket on bottom and a high sharp jug on top.  Exponentially easier.  Good warmup or intro to Mckinney Falls bouldering.

name: Dry Goods
description: Sit start on jugs.  Move into an unusual pocket and up into a two pocket pinch. Transition onto a small sloping horn before popping to the top.  Crux is moving off the first pocket into the pinch.  Right facing flake on the right is off; otherwise, it's a Mckinney V0.

name: Earn Your Supper
description: Start on a left hand wide pinch and right hand sidepull slightly lower. Dyno straight to the top as the FA, or use bad intermediate holds to get your feet up and pop to the top.

name: F*** Nut
description: sit start- start left hand on good edge, right hand on smaller one, go to good edge then sidepull.

name: Low Rider
description: Small edge (right hand) with a mono pocket just off to the left (left hand). Tricky foot positioning from the sit start; there is a small pocket (left foot) to cram your toes into. Crank off the start to the left and reach a good edge.  Move to a crimp jug (right) and move a sidepull (left).  Make one more move to a left facing flake and reach for the top. Crux is the first two moves of the problem.     Typical Mckinney problem. Definitely hard for its grade.

name: Lower Rider
description: Low start to Low Rider. Start on left hand 3-finger and right hand 2 finger under the lip of the wall. Lock off and bump through a pocket to reach the starting hold of Low rider.  Crux is locking off so you don't dab.

name: Naval Power
description: Sit start with two hands on jugs facing right, then right to a side pull crimp, to a under-cling and up

name: Nut Cup
description: Links Naval Power and Fuck Nut. Begin on Naval Power's start holds. Move up right into crimps. Left of Fuck Nut there is a good right hand pocket that can be used to transition between the two problems. Finish Fuck Nut.

name: Saturn III
description: Same start as Naval Power. Move left off the slanted jugs to a crimp and up to a left gaston. Finish either straight up or move left.     Crux is move to the gaston.

name: Scrunchy Wars: Episode I - The Nut Menace
description: Start on Fuck Nut Low, finish Drier Goods. Crux is moving through the two 2-finger pockets.

name: Scrunchy Wars: Episode II - Attack of the Chicks
description: Start on Basic Female, traverse under the lip through Low Rider and Dirt Bag until you hit the jug on Saturn. Top out. Crux is not pumping out because the feet are so bad.

name: Super Nugget
description: Sit start on a decent sloper rail and move up to a bad left sidepull.  Move up to another bad sidepull (right) before topping out.  **There is a possible two-finger edge that could be used as an intermediate.**  Crux is moving through bad sidepulls.

name: Unknown aka Fuck Nut Low
description: Sit start to Fuck Nut. Start in the hueco and use the undercling to move onto the starting move of Fuck Nut. Makes Fuck Nut feel like a true climb. Might be one of the best lines in the park.

name: Uranus
description: Low start to Saturn III. Start on a two-finger pocket with the right hand and a sloped pinch with the left hand. A good right foot and a smear left foot gets you to the start of Saturn. Adds three moves.

name: Vector Space
description: In between the starts of Naval Power and Fuck Nut. Start on a left hand deep 3 finger pocket, and right hand sloper. Do a big move up to the crimp of Naval Power and finish Naval Power. Crux is the first move.

name: The 37th parallel
description: Sustained and pumpy

name: Blind Spot
description: Start Trapeze Freak, move up and left on small holds to the jug at the end of Double Clutchin. In keeping with the style of the FA, all future ascents must be done with a shoe on the right foot while left is barefoot. If you don't climb this with only one shoe, it's not a send.

name: Blown Clutch
description: Sit start on same good pockets as Double Clutchin' and move up and to jug. Continue moving up to another jug (slightly left) and topout.  **Beware of bad landing**

name: Cirque Du Soleil
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Double Clutchin
description: Start left hand in a good pocket and right hand in a good pocket that you kind of have to fold your fingers over to get into.  Big moves to good holds trending slightly right will lead you to the light!

name: Eatin Dust
description: Start Trapeze Freak Direct, traverse left on low pockets into Double Clutchin. Finish Double Clutchin.

name: Evil Eyes
description: Definitely one of the coolest lines at Mckinney.  Awesome features that will get your skin screaming! Start in a slot just right of Left El Camino and trend right through a crimp, good pockets, and then the Evil Eyes! Then hit the lip and the ride is over, so come back down and do it again.

name: Evil Eyes Direct
description: Start directly under the first pocket of Evil Eyes on the large pinch and crimp. Move into and finish Evil Eyes.

name: Haunting Echoes aka "Evil Eyes' Dyno"
description: Stand start on the 1st and 2nd pockets of Evil Eyes and dyno to the micro-crimp on the lip.

name: Left El Camino
description: Start on low slots with your feet behind a big broken off part of the wall. Move straight up to one of the tweakiest holds around.  Come into a good dish, establish, dyno to the slopey lip for a difficult top out (atypical for Mckinney)

name: Local Plates
description: Start on rail system.  Move straight up through sharp crimps.

name: The McKinney Jump
description: Start standing on the little triangular boulder that faces the flake to the left of Local Plates, and jump from the boulder to the wall, over the trail, onto the jugs at the top of the flake. Don't miss

name: Queer Clutchin
description: Start on Queer Junkies and traverse right; finish on Double Clutchin.

name: Queer Eyes
description: Start on Queer Junkies and traverse left into Evil Eyes.

name: Queer Junkies
description: Starts low just right of Evil Eyes with right hand in a side pulling mono and left hand on a broken foot hold.  Move through cool crimps straight up to the top.

name: Queer Tactics
description: Start on Queer Junkies and traverse right into Siege Tactics.  finish Seige Tactics.

name: Right El Camino
description: Start on Evil Eyes and exit El Camino

name: Rupeshian Crimps
description: Start on sloping rails over the detached boulder. Climb small crimps to the top.

name: Siege Clutchin'
description: Start on Siege Tactics, traverse along horizontal break into Double clutchin and finish. fun pumpy problem.     can be done starting on either, feels the same difficulty either way to me

name: Siege Tactics
description: Crux is definitely the first move.  Start low with left hand on an underclimb crimp/pinch and right hand on a greasy pocket.  Move up and right to a sloper. Then big move to another sloper. Finish straight up.  Definitely worth doing just so you can climb some of the few slopers in Austin.

name: Siege Tactics Left
description: Start on Siege Tactics.  Move up to the left sloper and then left to a small crimp. Top out left on Queer Junkies.

name: Siege Tactics Stand Start
description: Don't know if this is a legit problem, but it actually feels like a better problem than Siege Tactics. Start on the jug (2nd move of Siege) and finish the same problem. Eliminates crux (V6 sit start)  and bumps it down a grade.

name: Trapeze Freak
description: Awesome awesome awesome.  Start on obvious side pull and iron cross right to a sloper. Move through some crimps then dyno to the lip. BEST V8 IN THE PARK!

name: Trapeze Freak Direct
description: The name of this route is a guess.  It seems to be different in every guidebook I look at.  But I did not want to leave it out because, well, its there. Start just under the sloper on trapeze freak with a sharp two finger pocket in the roof for your right hand and a 3 finger sprag a the lip with your left.  Move straight up into sloper on Trapeze Freak then finish Trapeze Freak

name: Trapezius Freak
description: Lower start to Trapeze Freak.  Lose a star, add a grade. That's how it usually works right? Start in decent 2 finger slot for left and small mono for right. Move through some small holds and then into Trapeze Freak.

name: Not So Deep Water Solo
description: This route starts standing on the shelf with hands at the beginning of the line of pockets. The crux is the last three moves from the end of the pockets to the top-out. Also, keeping your hands dry to keep from ripping your skin on the sharp pockets is extremely important

name: 4:20 (aka Shitty Warm-up Left)
description: Stand start on the big shelf.  Move into a left sloper and a right sloper crimp, and dyno to the top.  Crux is the dyno.

name: 5 Dope aka Another One Worth Doing (aka Shitty Warmup Right)
description: Stand start on jugs and move up into a good right pocket.  Make a large move onto another pocket (left) before popping to the top.  Crux is moving off the top pocket to the lip.

name: Adam's Jump
description: Stand start on left sloper edge and a right shallow pocket, then dyno to the lip.  One move wonder.

name: Baby Vulcan
description: Start sitting, climb through jugs and pockets into a sharp left hand undercling and awkward right hand 2 finger undercling. Use a left hand sprag (spock) to set your feet, readjust your right hand, and grab the lip. Pull an uncharacteristically hard top out for McKinney.

name: Flake Lunge/Break Lunge
description: Sit Start on good holds below the super obvious flake, climb up into the flake and dyno/deadpoint to the lip.  EDIT: As of Jan 2020, the flake that defined this problem has broken, leaving behind a decent edge as well as a deep undercling mono/shallow 2 finger pocket.  The climb has been re-sent using a left hand on the right hand pocket of the V2 to the left, right hand on the new edge and dyno to the top. Alternatively, this climb has also been redone utilizing the new undercling and a right hand Gaston to throw right hand to the lip. Both variations are approximately V4 and V3 respectively (McKinney grades).

name: Jazz Revolution
description: Start near the warm up flake shaped like this < on the skirt of the wall where you can stand up onto it hands-free. Basically start as far to the right on the slab as you can. Traverse left all the way across the wall, on horizontals, edges, pockets, and eventually jugs. Once you reach the start holds of The Prow, finish The Prow.     Crux in the middle where it gets real thin, then crux again whilst trying to finish The Prow. Bring yo chalk bag.

name: Prow
description: Start on the left side of the rail to an undercling pinch to the jug.  Move to a crimp or all the way to the top.  Several variations on this one exist.

name: Prow Low
description: Sit start on the sloper and crimp, down and right of The Prow (stand start). Move into the Prow and finish.

name: Snakebelly
description: Start about in the middle of Warm-Up Wall, sit start on the low, slopey jugs. Staying inches off the ground, traverse left with them tight heel hooks, and then up to the start holds of The Prow. Finish The Prow.

name: Unknown traverse
description: Traverse Horizontals, mellow warm up   If you go out and back give yourself v0+

name: 22-Eyed Beholder Hovering Near By
description: Fun route with great, thoughtful climbing. This route (along with those nearby) have good photo op potential with the over head bridge. Belayer clips into the fixed rope at the base to keep from falling into the black hole behind.

name: Balrog's S&M Whip
description: This route is on the far right of this wall and features thin, technical climbing up a good face. Sometimes it is wet due to neighbors sprinkler runoff. Guidebook says to beware of neighbor's poison ivy.

name: Crawling Chaos
description: A steep face with good holds leads to some tricky slab. Beware of the fall potential on the boulder below the route.

name: Creeping Doom
description: Stem between walls, transition to the face, then enjoy a fun jug haul to the anchors. One of the longest routes at Monster Rock.

name: Dwarven Berserker/Lich
description: Climbing is similar to it's brother routes to it's left and right...although not as good. Though good on its own, ut has the unfotunate existence of being the red-headed step sibling to it's neighboring routes. Starts out as 5.10 climbing...eases up...crux up top. Or crux down low...eases up...5/10 climbing above. I've heard it both ways.

name: Expecto Patronum!
description: This is a variation route of sky full of dementors. This route avoids upper and lower cruxes of SFOD. Can use boulder to stem off (to start) and at the cave above, clip with long draw and traverse the cave to Swordmaiden's anchors.

name: Gelatinous Cube's Deadly Solvent
description: Very thin route...on slightly overhanging start. This is a tough climb for the grade and it doesn't let up. There is a belay station below the route. The route is farthest route down the pit on D&D wall (Right Side).

name: Green Slime vs. Bag Of Devouring
description: This climb is a really fun and tricky to onsight! A fun lower crux gives way to easier climbing and an upper crux guards the anchors. A Monster Rock must-do!

name: Grendel
description: This climb can feel reachy for shorter climbers and taller climbers will probably find it easier than 5.9. Definitely and interesting crux. Stick clip is recommended.

name: Herman Munster
description: Definitely one of the best 5.9's at Monster Rock. Some interesting holds make the climb memorable. Stick clip is recommended.

name: Kraken's Deadly Dance at Sea
description: Start on Crawl-Under Boulder...clip first high bolt. The line climbs directly under the cactus. The anchors are hidden behind the cactus...Looks like cactus have been deneedled. Safe. Fun and Easy for 5.8.

name: Mindflayer's Tentacles
description: Starts 3' to the right of ledge before Crawl under Boulder. 5.10 start to easier climbing back to 5.10 climbing up above. This seems to be consistent in the 5.10 climbs on the D&D wall. Most start out at the grade, eases up, then final moves are back at the grade.

name: Ray of Disntegration
description: A variation of 22 Eyed Beholder...Climb 22 Eyed and between bolts 4 and 5, traverse left to another bolt and finish on Gelatinous Cube's anchors. Slightly harder than 22 Eyed.

name: Sand Worms Shake The Planet
description: This is a variation to "Creeping Doom" where you climb the face directly instead of stemming between the walls.

name: Seven Gorgons Breathing
description: Technical crux down low leads to easier climbing in the middle and a potentially tough finish.

name: Sky Full of Dementors
description: Climb the face between the boulders and find a way past the cave (crux).

name: Specter's Touch
description: Technical climb on steep terrain. Go left after the 5th bolt to finish on "Gelatinous Cube's Deadly Solvent".

name: Swordmaiden of Rohan
description: A very fun 5.6 route. A great intro climb to the Pit...gets you used to climbing in the pit...with both walls being so close to each other. It's easy terrain, great holds all the way up. Starts of on low angle climbing and slowly steepens up but never gets quite vertical. Very fun.

name: Tom Bombadil
description: Very fun , easy traverse. It's the easiest traverse and maybe the longest traverse at M-Rock. Starts on Grendel and essentially traverses the pit on D&D wall to either Swordmaiden's anchors (10 bolts) or anchors right of the bridge (12 bolts). Make sure you bring long draws or runners to minimize drag. I included a PG-13 safety rating because if you fell after a bolt, it would not be a clean fall...for most of the climb, you are on some kind of a ledge, which means you would be in for major cheese grating on some sharp limestone. It would not be pleasant.

name: Warg Riders
description: A variation of this climb, "Swordmaiden of Rohan", is a good 5.7. Stop at the first set of anchors. If you want to do the 5.8, clip the bolt to the left of the anchors instead and keep going. Both are very enjoyable.

name: Demonic Hordes and the Evil Eye of Orms-by-Gore
description: Shortest Route a M-Rock, but solid, quality, and pumpy. You traverse diagonally on three permadraws across rounded arete. Shares anchors with Freddy vs. Jason. There is a belay anchor right above the boulder for belayer.

name: Freddie vs. Jason
description: This climb has a super tricky crux that makes it hard to onsight, but it is very enjoyable. Overall, its short, but a good time none the less. Must do!

name: Goblin Mutant
description: Fun pumpy route. Great for those breaking into the 11s.

name: Lord of the Pit
description: Sweet traverse inside the pit. It traverses from left to right through most of the wall's midsection. You traverse by 10 permadraws over airy falls...Bolt 10 is above bolt 9...so start heading up after 9. Shares anchors with Freddy vs. Jason. This route is only for lead! Do not follow...the gates are positioned only for leading.

name: Texas Chainsaw Massacre
description: A stick clip isn't necessary but advised, since the footholds may be fragile. Soft belay until bolt 2 is clipped to avoid crashing onto the roof edge. Don't miss clipping bolt 3, which sits back in a shallow depression.

name: Thing vs. Cousin It
description: Starts in the pit up good holds to a sandy ledge. Climbs directly up the dihedral using small crimps and interesting moves past the crux to the finish.

name: Trollkind
description: Great edges down low and big jugs as the angle steepens. Very fun climbing. Must do!

name: Cosmic Encounters
description: Start as same as Icy Touch, clip permadraw and then the first bolt, but instead of clipping bolts above...exit right without using the ledge and clip the two bolts on the right side of the arete. It's another variation route...

name: Cosmic Horror
description: Climb the low angled start to the big rest ledge, than continue up on the face left of the ladders. Clip anchors next to ladder or use Icy TOuch's anchors.

name: The Dreaded Colour out of Space
description: Belay and start on the ledge of the upper ladder. This route is a high traverse of the Lovecraftian wall. It's a blind belay. Traverse high on cliff...clipping upper bolts of other routes on the wall. Do not lead this route unless you are completely crushing 5.7...there is a runout that could end really badly on a fall. Finish on Hideous ME-GO anchors. Easiest travers on wall. Good warmup if you plan on doing all the traverse variations.

name: Fear Insanity
description: Another variation of Insane Whisperings. Traverse to bolt 7 then exit up on Fear of Evil Gods final permadraw and finish to the left. Crux comes after the last clip, big moves and find the monster "thank you" jug.

name: Fear of Infinity
description: According to guidebook author Hogge, this is best variation at M-Rock. It is stout route, two cruxes. The start and right below the anchors. A Hastur's variation...start as the 11d Hastur route, but at bolt 2, traverse left on Insane Whispering for 2 bolts left, then up permadraw on Fear of Evil Gods.

name: Hastur's Insanity
description: This traverse variation will test your endurance! None of the moves are very hard in and of themselves, but keep adding them up and you'll be feeling the burn.

name: Hastur's Semi-Liquid Fishy Things
description: Route is in the middle of the wall. Find the mail slot...line goes up. Starts under roof, get your feet up, hand in mail slot...get left hand up and crank to crimp above first bolt ( crux). Rest of the route is still in the 11 grade.

name: Herbert West's Weird Instruments
description: A variation of "Icy Touch of a Dimensional Shambler", this route allows the use of holds on the arete. Beware of an awkward clipping stance that makes for an interesting (yet safe?) fall.

name: Hideous Insanity
description: Start on Insane Whisperings (right under the first Permadraw on the rightside of wall) and traverse left clipping the first 5 permadraws. Then start angling up and left towards the Hideous MI-GO anchors. After the 5 permadraws, you need to clip two bolts before anchors...one bolt being below you and to the left...so bring a long draw or runner to minimize drag.

name: Icy Touch of a Dimensional Shambler
description: Big holds down low gives way to thinner fare up top. Pulling the bulge is the crux and it is quite interesting. The arete is off for this climb.

name: Insane Whispering from a Yuggothian Braincase
description: Start on Icy Touch (as you do for all traverse variations) and head up to first permadraw. Then continue to traverse left until you clip the 9th permadraw. Then lower. This is the main traverse on the wall...the rest are variations off this route. This route is graded an 11b due to it's pump...not necessarily because of technical difficulty. Of all the traverses on lovecraftian...this one seems to get the most traffic

name: Invisible Insanity
description: 7th variation of Starspawn. Start very far right of wall, clip first permadraw and traverse to the 4th permadraw and then head up and finish on Invisible Slayer/Fishy Things anchors.

name: Invisible Slayer of the Mad Arab Abdul Alhazrad
description: This climb is a must do if you climb 5.11. A tricky boulder problem at the start transitions to a leftward traverse. Deadpoint to a good ledge (so much fun!) and then pull your way up through easier climbing.

name: Nyarlathotep Arises From The Blackness Of 27 Centuries
description: This climb shares the start with "Invisible Slayer" but goes straight up instead of traversing left. Pulling the bulge is a wicked crux, but the falls are clean.

name: Revenge Insanity
description: 4th variation of Insane Whisperings. Traverse 6 permadraw sand exit up and left to sharp jugs on darker rock. Holds below anchors are dirty.

name: Revenge of the Shoggoths
description: According to Hogge guidebook...the grade is height dependent. The crux are the opening moves. 6' and taller and it will feel easier...more like an 11c/d...avg height or shorter and it will feel harder. Using the paper thin undercling and the thin right side pull are key. Get those feet up.

name: Wurm
description: An extension of Insane Whisperings. After the 9th permadraw, continue fighting the pump and traverse 7 more PD's (16 total)...make sure you traverse on the holds below draws. If you traverse holds higher, you are then climbing (Torture-iffic 5.11c). No real 12 crux moves...but fighting pump. Crux is moving past arête and small blank section. After 9 PD you are also out of belayers sight. Have to communicate that your clipping while controlling your breathing and fighting horrible pump.

name: Hydra's Hissing Heads
description: Towards the end of the wall...between Cyclop's Eye and Medusa's snake.

name: A big traverse
description: A fun traverse with only a few difficult sections. Crux is at the flat wall towards the end.

name: A Walk with Kirky
description: Starts on the dihedral on the left side of awesome roof. Climb up the good holds and flake system to dirty ledge. Make sure you clip in to a bolt on the way to hand ledge. Then follow the permadraws across. The climb traverses to the 6th permadraw and then lower. In guidebook, the "R" rating is for new leaders who may have trouble clipping this traverse, which could result in a 15' deck. Clipping the permadraws may feel awkward.

name: The Bitchin' High Traverse
description: Do The Mexican Says So (Holladay wall), but don't clip the anchors. (Don't forget the low permadraw below the anchors.) Continue traversing up and onto the face above Awesome roof, clipping 4 more permadraws to finish on anchors just to the left of the small tree coming out of the face. Second to last permadraw is shared with Shiphon.  Variation: Do it as a 2-pitch with The Mexican Says So as P1 anchors.  Variation: Do Penolope Says So, whose permadraw is shared by The Mexican Says So and The Bitchin' High Traverse. After pulling the roof, don't clip the anchors but move onto The Bitchin' High Traverse.

name: Dinner with Dracula
description: Powerful and crimpy. Crux is on from the deck until you hit the third bolt's ledge. This route is a bit reachy and requires some precise throws to crimps.

name: Freeloader
description: Tiny crimps and difficult feet make this route a really great onsight test piece at the grade. The crux is from bolt 2 to bolt 3. Find a rest and fight the pump to the anchors.

name: Full Service Pump for Penelope
description: Start Vanilla Sky and then head left and pull the crux of Silverback Thruster and reverse Pay at the Pump.

name: Highway to Heaven
description: This is an extension of A Walk with Kirky. However, instead of lowering after the 6th PD, continue to traverse the entire wall...continuing past the roof wall on 7 more PDs. You never climb higher than 15'...however, you do climb 100', if not more on the traverse. The route finishes on the anchors to the right of the Turtle Man route. This route is pumpy! So keep ypur cool, keep breathing...as you exit under the roof, the wall starts to slightly overhang. The hand ledge across offers good holds though.

name: Lil Pump
description: Lil Pump is variation #1 to Pump Action Direct. Start on Vanilla Sky, and once at the 4th bolt, bust out into the roof on small holds to the cave on Pay at the Pump, then climb leftward and exit on Silverback Thruster. Similar in difficulty to Pump Action Direct. ESSKEETIT

name: Monkey in the Mirror
description: Starts Vanilla Sky and then heads left back-cleaning while advancing to the crux on Silverback Thruster. It then continues left for a body length on Pay at the Pump and pulls the crux on Siphon. After Siphon's roof continue left following perma-draws until the anchors on Penelope. First 2 bolts on Vanilla, then bolts 6 and 5 on Walk with Kirky, then Silverback's bolt 3, then Pay at the Pumps 3rd perma, then Siphon's first independent bolt, and then head left to the chains on Penelope.

name: Pay at the Pump
description: 12 bolts (9 are permadraws), NO ANCHORS.  Start on furthest wall you face approaching the area. Climb to large jug flake and traverse the entire roof. Pull the final boulder problem and top out. The FA of this route included the topout.  Some say that each bolt is worthy of a different grade as you progress. Ratings range from 11b to 12b as you get further into the route.   ***Below are the Pay at the Pump roof subroutes...1 of 8 subroutes. Clipping Each permadraw across is considered good enough for a route***  Pay 3 (subroute of Pay at the Pump): 5:11c Start Penelope Says So to ledge, then get on roof crack (Pay at the Pump)...climb the first 3 roof permadraws. 4 bolts, 3 permadraws, lower on third  Pay 4 (subroute of Pay at the Pump): 5:11c Start Penelope Says So to ledge, then get on roof crack (Pay at the Pump)...climb the first 4 roof permadraws. 4 bolts, 4 permadraws  Pay 5 (subroute of Pay at the Pump): 5:11d Start Penelope Says So to ledge, then get on roof crack (Pay at the Pump)...climb the first 5 roof permadraws. 4 bolts, 5 permadraws  Pay 6 (subroute of Pay at the Pump): 5:12a Start Penelope Says So to ledge, then get on roof crack (Pay at the Pump)...climb the first 6 roof permadraws.  Pay 7 (subroute of Pay at the Pump): 5:12a Start Penelope Says So to ledge, then get on roof crack (Pay at the Pump)...climb the first 7 roof permadraws.  Pay 8 (subroute of Pay at the Pump): 5:12b Start Penelope Says So to ledge, then get on roof crack (Pay at the Pump)...climb the first 8 roof permadraws.

name: Penelope Says So
description: Pulling the roof without skirting around the left side is the crux. Bolds 1-4 are on the left wall under the roof with 4 moving left. 5th bolt is one the roof. The permadraw is shared with Mexican Says So and Bitching High Traverse.

name: Pump Action Direct
description: A linkup. Start on the ground (not on the boulder you gumby) for Vanilla Sky and climb through the first 4 bolts. When you're on the big ledge at the 4th bolt, bust out left into the roof through some small holds until you reach the basketball-size hueco on Pay at the Pump. Shake out and then pull thru the vicious final crux of Pay at the Pump.  The FA of Pay at the Pump topped out the route, as did the FA of this route. If u don't top it out it doesn't count.

name: Rock-About
description: Vanilla Sky to A Highway to Heaven. Start Vanilla Sky clipping the first bolt and 2 permadraws. Move right following 7 more permadraws of A Highway to Heaven to anchors.

name: Silverback Thruster
description: This route is made of 7 permadraws, some of which are shared with other routes.  PD 1 is the left permadraw on the wall to the right of A Walk With Kirky's first bolt. PD 2 is the 3rd permadraw of A Walk with Kirky. PD 3 and 4 are the two permadraws between A Walk with Kirky and Pay at the Pump. PDs 5 and 6 are the 5th and 6th permadraws of Pay at the Pump. Pull the roof above PD 6, clipping PD 7, and finishing at the anchors above.

name: Siphon
description: Start Pay at the Pump, clipping the first 4 bolts on the left face, moving onto the Pay at the Pump crack,  and clipping the first two permadraws. Pull the roof as you clip the two bolts and one permadraw. Top out or lower on this last permadraw.

name: Turtle Man
description: Nice start on two friendly pockets. Bouldery crux moves get you past bolt three. Cruise to the anchors on mid-10 climbing.

name: Vanilla Sky
description: Start in the middle of the roof on top of the large boulder.  A direct start from the ground is viable but friable holds make it less than idea.  Climb up the face to the roof and then start traversing on monster holds.  After the third perma look for a hand swallowing pocket jug in the roof and pull some fun thugish moves on big hold over the lip

name: Bee-otch
description: No comment.

name: Bee-Roofic
description: Left most route of Bee wall.

name: Epipen: My Battle with the Bee
description: Start in front of the boulder in the trench.

name: Peace Breaker
description: Good warmup route for Bee Wall.

name: Plan Bee
description: Start in the trench next to the boulder.

name: Stinger
description: Crux makes the rating. Might be 5.11c

name: BB King
description: Starts with a slabby V1/2 for the first 3 bolts.  Bolts 3-6 are big shouldery moves on decent holds with a solid V4 iron cross drop down in the middle - this is the crux section. Rest in cave then fire the last moves from bolt 7 thru anchors on a series of small flat jugs.

name: Bangin' Buzzards
description: A fun, short but surprisingly pumpy route. Begin in the white chossy looking section.

name: Bound to Divide
description: Bound to Divide is a great warm up for the area and will test a 5.8 climber's ability with a good variety of climbing packed into such a short route. Thin edges at the bottom, juggly ledges in the middle and a flake system up top. Route starts from the ground and goes up just left of the roof.     Human stick clip the first bolt by standing on the bolder stack just behind the route.

name: Fiscal Cliff
description: Pulls the roof, slightly left of the roof's arete. The grade could be as high as 5.12a. For now I've split the difference between Rupesh & Marisa's 5.11c opinion and a few 5.12a opinions.

name: Right in Two
description: This route starts on the ground (not on the boulder you cheater) and pulls the mini roof. Pulling the roof seems to be the crux for most people.

name: Tradical buzzards
description: Starts on the staircase of ledges to the right of Fiscal Cliff. Goes up to the crack formed by the roof and the wall and then to the right of the arete formed by the roof and wall. Finish at the two trees (for now?)    Route still has some loose rocks both large and small to be removed so be careful what you grab and where you step. Also some vegetation is hiding good features. Some pencil cactus is on the route so watch out for that too.    I would consider the last moves to the trees the crux based on awkwardness, so get really good protection in before that. A fall while trying to reach the trees would be very shitty. Don't do it. There are some very nice crimps around and pre-plan where you are putting your feet. You are on a great ledge before the this so you have plenty of time to look and feel around before committing to anything.    Still requires some cleaning.    Reimer's Ranch does not have enough traditional routes.

name: Wingspan
description: Technical beta mixed with a hint of height dependency (please prove me wrong on this) make for a fun romp up this short wall. Route goes up the center of the wall pulling the roof on protruding rock along the lip. Wingspan starts with a scramble up to the base of the triangle-shaped boulder. Play with the roof a bit and try not to think about the boulder underneath you. Burly moves get you past the lip and a thin finish on the mini-wave earns the anchors. Don't z-clip the 2nd bolt.     Belayer should stand down and to the right just under bolt 1 to minimize rope issues at the start.    R rating due to possible bad landing on boulder. Have a good belayer and a cool head @ bolt 4 and you'll be fine. Do not toprope this route. A bad fall onto the pointed boulder below can (did) happen.    During development while working the roof section my right hand popped out of the slot causing me to take a grounder onto the slanted boulder below. I struck at just the right angle as to not incur any injuries but I wouldn't say by any means that the feat is repeatable. DON'T TOP ROPE THIS ROUTE.

name: Carnival
description: Really fun route. The start is pretty much 5.8 until you hit the fun crimps when you start working up from the completion of the traverse.  Beta for the crux:    Right hand to either sloper or 2 finger pocket, left hand far left to crimp, right hand to crimp sidepull above left hand, stand up to high left jug. More or less. Some of my friends do it slightly differently. It's all in the feet.

name: Icehouses
description: Climbs up the left side of the arete to a mini roof.

name: Lone Star TallBoy
description: Starts on top of the large ledge under the dihedral. Moves up the minor flake on the left then meanders right up to a V-shaped slot. Pull the bulge for the 10d crux and you'll be rewarded with a nice mellow anchor clipping stance.

name: Mickey's Big Mouth
description: The obvious dihedral crack that starts at the ledge and continues up to a set of anchors. Currently, this route is set for TR. So you can lead Milwaukee's best and set up a TR from there. Or another option is to lead it trad (ok protection). There are a couple of decent placements...but not great.

name: Milwaukee's Beast
description: Climbs the face of the left most arete. Scramble the ledge to start cimb and find the first bolt on face left of the dihedral crack. Start angling left. At the third bolt, start angling right and the 4th bolt is located above the small ledge.

name: Red Dog
description: Climbs up the arete and moved left to pull the mini roof. Minor decking potential with bad fall after. Use a stick clip and you're set.

name: Schlitz My Liquor
description: Starts on the right side of a large arete and works up to the left.

name: Corsicane Brothers
description: Clip first bolt (if you want) to get on the ledge, then clip second bolt and veer rightward clipping several more bolts past two huecos and an 'elephant trunk' to the anchor.

name: Dave's Not Here
description: Clip first bolt, climb left of it and surmount the dusty ledge. Climb up slightly overhanging section using 'mail slots' on right or crimpers on left.  Reach across to the right and get into jugs going up a faint arete that overhangs and gets your forearms pumped.  Clip the anchor.

name: Glass Slipper
description: Two small roofs, throw a heel or champ your way over the edge to a great crimp. Whale over the top to anchors.

name: Hey Mr. Lizard Man
description: Climb through a bolt to the break. Three more bolts on fairly pocketed rock. Cool crux hold. Finish left of roof.

name: Higher
description: Fun climb shares two bolts with Corscicane Brothers.  Follow the left line of bolts after that.   Crux is the middle of the face on slopey crimpy ledges.  Tougher for shorter people

name: Let's Do a Line, Man.
description: Start on the choss shelf above the trail near the large dry roots. Climb face up to tufa holds at bolt 2 (located underside of small roof). Two jugs allow for a high clip (bolt 3) before ascending on thin crimps through the crux in the middle of the vertical face. Clip another bolt (4) at the top of the face before standing up at the anchors on a ledge 5 feet below the cliff top.

name: Mickey's Crack
description: Climb the right-facing dihedral to the small roof, then it seems like the crux is reaching high for hold(s) and clipping the anchor. Bolts are on right side of the corner.   May be 10d?

name: Mostly Labrador
description: Some people use tree stump to get started but it isn't necessary. Similar to other routes on this section of wall. Fun warmup.

name: Pluto's Hole
description: Climbing on medium sized crimps and and pockets leads to the giant hole that is the namesake of the route. A big move to a jug and you can reach the chains.

name: Some Crimes
description: *** Route name may have changed, this is the name as in my version of the guidebook (listed as expired project, 4 bolts, 5.hard) ***    Gain the ledge, unprotected, to clip the 1st bolt (the tree stump may be used to make this easier.) Bouldery moves lead past the 2nd bolt to a cave where the 3rd bolt may be clipped. Top section is thin, find good feet to advance to the next bolt. A few more moves take you to the chains.

name: Still Smokin
description: Cool route through two big huecos. Neat crux comes shortly after.

name: Up in Smoke
description: The crux is definitely the start. Just clip the second bolt after you get up to the shelf and pump through and find your feet through to the 3rd bolt.

name: Charles Bergh Fan Club
description: This route is a variation that starts at the beginning of Eternal Love and traverses left after the first bolt and ends at the anchors for I Double-Dog-Adair Ya.  There are two bolts in-between those routes that are meant for this route.

name: Dreamland
description: Very odd route that starts about 20 feet to the right of Lenora Reimer's Turkey Call. Look for a wave-like wall and a left leaning rail feature.

name: Eternal Love
description: Climb the right leaning flake-crack.

name: Goats and Cattle
description: Climbs the right side of the right arête and traverses the  wave feature to the Dreamland anchors.  This route remains after the Lenora Reimer's Turkey Call anchors were removed.

name: Huck of a Deal
description: Bouldery start at the bottom, into easy 10 climbing. Hold can be a little sharp, and cryptic due to the little traffic on this route.

name: I Double-Dog-Adair Ya
description: Left leaning hand crack, one route to the right of Huck of a Deal.

name: L'arête Des Jumeaux (The Arête Twins)
description: 2 options include climbing the boltline, or climbing the right side of the dihedral.

name: Open Spaces
description: Traversing route on great hand holds with some sparse feet.

name: Water Quality
description: Hard bottom climbing leads to easy .10 moves up through the roof.

name: Years in the Making
description: Starts on a little roof and traverses left and diagonal to end near Dreamland's anchors.

name: Don't Mess With the Jesus
description: Climb the thin crack left of a leaning cedar tree on the ledge. Then work left to the anchors. Run out to bolt 2 and the anchors.

name: The Dude Abides
description: North shore's 8-flake. Fun movement on bomber holds.

name: Just Checked In
description: High bolt 1, above the roof. Runout to bolts 1 and 2; do not fall.

name: The Nihilists
description: Steep, sharp holds, deceptive 8.

name: Nothing
description: Good warm-up

name: Freakshow
description: Shares same bolt line as Hexed, but you climb the flake to the right side and climb three feet to the right of anchors...avoid the 5.10 finish,

name: Gypsy's Magic
description: This was North Shore's First bolted route.   PG Rated because of dead tree.

name: Hexed
description: Short dihedral. Awkward fall potential.

name: Living on The Edge
description: It's an okay route. Just a little warm-up before hitting up Carnival just next door. Really short. Maybe the top makes it a 5.10b as rated.

name: Love Potion No. 9
description: The crux is right below the anchors.

name: Rock Gypsy
description: The holds on this one are large and really fun. Great route for beginner climbers.
Look for the new shiny bolts. Don't get your feet wet.

name: Blank
description: The first part is the hardest part. Just go up and to the right.

name: Climb Tech Indirect
description: Variation of Monfi taverse.

name: Drillin' and Swillin'
description: The crux is definitely the beginning. Be strong and pull through. If you're short.... well good luck.

name: Holladay on Natty Ice
description: Climbs the crack under the roof and out the left side.

name: Metamorphosis
description: Although the rock on this route isnt the best it has some fun interesting movement.     Straight forward long lock-offs and pulls on crimps lead you to the lip of a mini roof where you move to a sinker 3 finger pocket. Don't celebrate yet though because there is another very long pull up to a jug which leads to easier climbing.

name: The Mexican Says So
description: Starts the same as The Mexican, however, at bolt 2 (a permadraw), start traversing right on the ledge and follow permadraws to the anchors above the start of the Awesome Roof Wall. Be aware of bees near the anchors. If bees start attacking, just lower on permadraw.

name: The Mexican
description: Pretty straigh forward. Get on the ledge, get your first clip in, and climb up...crux is at start and then eases to 5.5/5.6 climbing to anchors.

name: Monfi
description: A nice warm up for the grade. Start where just about every other route starts on this wall and move up and to the left along a line of permas. Fight the pump.

name: Ode to an Era
description: Low crux, this route follows long moves on big holds, trending up and right to finish to chains just left of those of Monfi.

name: Opticalrectuminitus
description: if you cant reach the first bolt from the ground, stick clip it.  relatively easy climbing to the second bolt, i did not stick clip it like hogge recommends but it felt fine.      from austin climbing: 50' right of the quatch start under a low dihedral roof pull a long left pointing edge.  runout to bolt 2; we recommend stick clipping it.  primo face moves.

name: The Quatch
description: ok warmup for the holladay wall.

name: Quatchatarium
description: Shares the starting bolt with 2 other routes, RIP and Blank.    The start is just a pop-up and most of the route is juggy. Really fun climb.

name: R.I.P.
description: The start is the hardest part of this. Smooth sailing from there on.

name: What's a Wanker you Tosser
description: The crux is the beginning. Good footwork will get you through with no prob.

name: Beyond The Sea
description: The crux is right at the permadraw. If you're a shorty... good luck pulling this move.

name: Big Huking Chicken
description: Route climbs up to a ledge protected by 2 bolts. There's a roof permadraw that is interesting to clip...if you don't clip this and you blow the clip, it may result in a scary fall, possibly a deck. The permadraw is long so it should be reachable by most...this route may be a bit more difficult for shorter people. Crux is pulling the roof onto face.

name: Bobby Dangler
description: Leftmost route that pulls both roofs.

name: Giggle Stick
description: Pulls the single big roof on the left through the dihedral/crack.

name: Lithium
description: Third from the left route that pulls both roofs.

name: Master of Ceremonies
description: Pulls the single big roof at the far left.

name: Ranger Danger
description: Runouts to bolts 4 and 5 and anchors. Pull the arete that hangs off the right side of the Huking Buttress roof.

name: ......Never Was, Never Will Be
description: A great route that gets little to no attention. 3 permadraws protect the short wave shaped face, traverse left for 2 perma draws and clip the chains above and to the left of the cave. A fun boulder problem between the second and third draw creates the routes committing crux. Move through the crux and clip from a great hold above the 3rd draw. Good holds traversing to the anchors will serve up a nice pump. Have a sharp belayer. Feet may hit the ledge if you fall at the 3rd bolt.

name: The Airing of Grievances
description: Do first three bolts of Insane Tree Hugger, cross the off-width crack to the left and follow three permadraws up to its own anchors.

name: Anger
description: Climb the shelf/Boulder stack onto platform. Then go up steep face clipping two bolts. Rest of the bolts have perma-draws. The movement on this route is great. The steep wall under the tiered roofs are steep, but there are positive holds...find them! The roofs are bucket holds but fighting pump is key. Falls up high are clean. Perma-draws at the anchor, like most Reimers routes.

name: Bulimia
description: Do some moderate'ish moves to a jug in the crack where you clip the 2nd bolt on the main wall. I recommend using an extended draw for the next bolt and clipping it from the same hold due to it being in the middle of the crux. Then pull the crux and cheer for the only thing left between you and the chains is a few more moderate moves. This route rewards a strong boulderer due to little pump factor. Since the FA this route has been upgraded

name: Chicken Tenders
description: Pull hard moves from the ground to glue reinforced edges culimating with a crux toss to a huge jug (also glue reinforced). Shake out here and finish the line on easier moves.

name: Dr. Jekyll
description: First two bolts  are on the boulder stack. Climb onto ledge, and clip third bolt. Big huecos above. Couple of ways of climbing onto face, dynoing is 1 option!! Be careful, there is poison ivy on this route. Anchors are below the high roof, but the route becomes overhung.

name: Fangoria
description: Starts to a big white tufa under a bulge

name: Festivus, for the Rest of Us
description: Climb up the main ledge and then follow the obvious crack up. It's almost a giant hueco. Follow the bolts along the right side and then traverse up and left on the permadraws to the sport anchors right above the third (fourth?) permadraw.

name: Global Warming
description: Pull the ledge at the routes first true bolt or scramble up by the start of Pave the World. The fun starts right off the deck with a gymnastic boulder problem requiring a right hand + right heel match. Once you gain the face, the technical difficulty eases off and a world of pumpy huecos starts. A really fun boulder start leading into a face full of quality limestone make this route a must do at the grade.

name: He Ain't My Brother
description: Climb the large bolder and mount the ledge to reach the first permadraw.

name: The Heart is Deceitful Above All Things
description: Starts first bolt of Identify Crisis, traverse the shelf left to clip at top of low roof, then left to the high bolt. Angles right behind the tree.

name: Huevo's Locos
description: Climb psycho killer's first 3 bolts, traverse to a bolt right before a deep groove. Head up towards a bolt under a roof. Clip, get your feet up, find awesome roof holds to the right and pull roof. PG rating is going to roof (5th) bolt on easy terrain.

name: I Stepped in BS
description: Route goes up into the orange rock and cave. Has glued-in bolts.

name: Identify Crisis
description: This is an incomplete route. But, its first bolt is also the start of I Stepped in BS and The Heart is Deceitful Above All Things.

name: Illusionary Mentor
description: A very fun and unique route. Climb the offwidth crack and traverse onto arête/slight bulge right below the 5th bolt. This is the warmup route for this wall.

name: Imaginary Friend
description: Scramble up the messy boulder stack left of the route and onto the ledge. Climb a seam through the wave and out a steep roof formation. All-air runout to the anchors.

name: Insane Tree Hugger
description: Big Off-Width Crack to nice jug roof. Climb up the off width then move out right toward the top of the crack. Climb up to the anchors from there.

name: Lenora's Wrath Kept 'em Lawful
description: This is an extension of the climb Huevos Locos (5.10a PG). Climb bolts 1-4 and then traverse right on 6 permadraws to finish at the anchors for Fangoria (5.12a)   35 meter rope recommended.

name: More Fun Than Bubblewrap
description: Route was first led on trad in 1998 by Mike Klein. It's a roof crack that can be plugged up by big gear. However, there are now three bolts to protect it...I give it a PG-13 rating because it is mildly runout between bolts 2 and 3. And if you blow the clip, this route will hurt you pretty bad! If you happen to carry some hand size cams (maybe #2 or #3, you maybe able to protect the mild runout). But to make it fun, just run it out...In Hogge's guidebook, it states the climb starts to left on a chimney up to the ledge (dirty too) and walk back the roof, or you can direct start on face below ledge for a bouldery start up to ledge. Once you reach back of the cave, find first bolt, and either lay back and traverse left or hand jam across...I've done both and they are both effective. Crux is definitely pulling the lip...there are a few techniques you can employ to reach anchors...I hand jammed and it hurt like hell...the stone is sharp inside those cracks. Though the route is only 20-25' up from the ground to anchors...it climbs longer since the routes starts at the back of the roof.

name: Mr. Hyde
description: This is Dr. Jekyll's brother. Located  to the right of Jekyll. Similar climb to Jekyll, but the start is easier  and the finish is harder. Also some poison ivy on this route.

name: Pave the world
description: Some holds have broken since the FA including at least one for the opening sequence making it a little harder. There are a couple crimps and footholds that appear to be friable so climb the route with caution. A little run out to the last perma but clean fall.

name: Pollution / Erosion
description: Gets easier at the top.

name: Psycho Killer
description: cool route that starts off easy, then once on ledge, have to pull up on huge jugs, then romp up on 5.6 to 5.7 climbing through middle of the route to another crux roof section, pull over on good holds and keep your cool.

name: Bengy Bengy Fever
description: Suggested rating of 5.10a starting from a boulder. Start beneath the boulder and your belayer, as low as you can, for a new crux and bump to about 5.10c/d.

name: Bergargle
description: Soft for the grade, start on tufas down and right for harder, alternate start.

name: Call of the Wild Man
description: The crux of this route starts right from the go. Side pulls and high feet make reaching up for crimp ledges a bit thuggish. Some holds are a bit sharp. Route is all but over once you've clipped bolt 3.    Do stop and take a peek at the little shrine near the top.

name: Champaign and Strawberries
description: Really fun route, a bit soft for the grade, probably a 5.10a. Pull the mini roof to the right, and move to the crux clip at bolt 3.

name: Choose Your Path
description: The route farthest right of Little Guide's wall. Starts off really easy on a ramp...slabs over, and the crux is climbing over the rounded arete. The holds are hidden...but when you find them, your good as gold!

name: Cursed Ascent
description: Warm up route for Little Guide's Wall. Starts on slab, follow big holds all the way up.

name: Drillzaster
description: A variation start of Cursed Ascent. However, after first bolt, start traversing to What a Load's first bolt and continue to traverse crossing Champain and Strawberries, PLD and finish on Bergagle's anchors. This route traverses left crossing 3 routes and finishing on a 4th line. Maybe the most fun on this section of the wall. Definitely the longest.

name: extension: Wild Men Wear Heels
description: This is an extension onto "Call of the Wild Man" that adds maybe 15 feet of bouldering to get to the start. Call was such a short route and we felt this added enough moves to denote a separate route.
