This start extends the crux on Call of the Wild man by roughly 8 hand/feet moves and has some fun V3 action.

name: Leap of Faith
description: Start on the slanting boulder on the deck to reach up to bolt 1. Start through bolt 3 is the crux to easy climbing to the anchors.

name: Live Action
description: Starts on boulder with a low first bolt. To remove the R rating, stickclip the second bolt.

name: Menopause Mania
description: Starts on sharp boulder near base. Pulls into a bouldery start. Juggy middle with a nice top out. Bonus points if you can find the dual kneebar.

name: PLD
description: Easy route, could be used for a warmup if you start at this wall. Big first move to solid hold and first bolt. Probably the crux.

name: Rambo Princess
description: Face climbing through two bolts to a series of ledges to the anchor.

name: Rattled
description: Start on the tombstone-shaped boulder on the deck to reach the first bolt, then dyno up and left for a good hold to then ascend the next section. Five total bolts with sport clips for anchors. Negative with big holds up tiers of roofs to the anchors on a face above the last tier.

name: War on Choss
description: This route goes up the orange, chossy-looking roof section just to the left of Rattled. Don't let the name fool you, the choss has been eliminated for the most part due to thorough development (over a year's worth of pulling and banging on every hold.) Crux is going to depend on your strengths. There's a bit of something for everyone - endurance pumpiness, bouldery start, roof climbing, fun anchor clips. Don't pass this route up due to its appearance, it's a gem and worth doing.

name: What a Load
description: Starts on low angle, good holds, pull your way up midway on jugs...crux is below anchors.

name: White Horse Mescalito
description: Second bolt will be to the left on flat wall around chest level while you stand in nice (short) dihedral. Easy clipping spots, but a reach to the 4th bolt, and crux is pulling through to the anchors.

name: Humanavirus
description: This is a crack route near the right end of the Matrix. In the local guidebook, it is mentioned as a possible solo with a 5.? grade, and there is no indication the author has climbed it or knows of anyone who has. Also, the route does not appear to have been touched anytime recently if ever at all. However, it would not astonish me if someone has free soloed this route before, and I have no problem being corrected and removing my claim of an FA on a 20' limestone trad route.  Since the routes at the Matrix have names that are references to the movie, my name for this route is in keeping with that since it alludes to Agent Smith's famous assessment of humanity. It also is a nod to the coronavirus outbreak at the time I climbed it. Note to virtue-signaling scolds-- the park was open to climbing at the time, and the one person with me was someone from my household.  This route has no bolts and no top anchors, and it would be nice to see it stay that way, unlike Trinity, which never needed to be bolted.  About the grade-- my son thought it felt no harder than 5.6 except for the slipperiness of the mossy part, but he admitted his perspective could have been skewed by being on toprope. I thought the bottom was harder due to tougher feet than what is typical of 5.6 around here, but I think 5.8 might be pushing it.

name: Trinity
description: Trinity ascends a double crack system formed by what appears to be a detached or detaching block.  The route makes a nice final climb of the day because it is easy to top out from the anchors and then the parking lot is just seconds away. You can sling a large tree a few yards back from the topout to use as an anchor.  This route can go on trad gear, though the rock quality is questionable. Passive gear recommended, but to protect the finish you need large cams or to rely on a pocket that will take a cam or Tricam. Clip one of the anchor bolts if you are topping out.  I believe in deferring to the FA when sharing a route here, and so I have submitted it at the grade the FA gave, but I really think it is more like 5.4 or 5.5.

name: A Mortal Life
description: Another good warmup route if you're in the area. Crux def the start and can be right before the anchors if you don't see the holds. Might be a little problematic if you're not at least a solid high 10 climber.

name: Amazing Legacy of J.R.R. Tolkein
description: Nice warmup route if you're in the area. Crux is the start.

name: Bilbo's Bag
description: A bunchy of good pockets lead up to a small roof. Get over that and your at the chains.     Found in between The Fellowship and Elvin Beauty. Bolt 1 is pretty high up there and you have to pull on some pretty lousy holds to get up to it.

name: Blood of Dwarves
description: Start on ledge with some pretty cool formations. May share climbing space with Tookish.

name: Dwarven Greed
description: Start Mines of Moria which is to the right of Moria Cave, at bolt three, start traversing over to Ringbearer 5th bolt which is a permadraw, and continue right towards Dwarves Rule 5th bolt which is located on small roof, pull the roof and finish on Dwarves Rule's anchors. This is a variation route of the Mines of Moria.

name: Dwarves Rule
description: As most of the routes in this section of middle earth, pull up to the wall from the ledge below. First three bolts are close to protect from decking on boulder below. Slight runout to bolt 4 and then 5. If you don't have a good belay, if you take a fall on 4, can possibly deck on boulder below. Crux is near bolt 4, and then you have to pull the small roof to reach anchors. Climbs the left side of the water streak.

name: Earth's End
description: Starts at the very end near Wall of Insanity.  Easy climbing up to the third bolt where you can sit on the ledge to rest before pulling a crux move over the roof.  Runs out on easy climbing until the 4th bolt before clipping anchor.

name: Elvin Beauty
description: Nice route. Crux is right before the top. You just have to look for the holds. Might not be noticeable off the bat.

name: Fallohide
description: Fun climbing up big holds. There is a feature to the right of the route that looks like someone took a giant core sample out of the wall. That can be used for interesting holds.

name: The Fellowship
description: Cool featured route, down low have sweet mini tufa holds, climb to dirty ledge. Pull jugs to get on wall. Good face climb with great holds.

name: Flight From Mordor
description: Left of Troll Teeth. First route on the big open book dihedral on the Middle Earth Wall.

name: Halfling's Leaf
description: Climb bolt line up the thin crack.  First bolt is between the two horizontal and very wide cracks lower on the wall.  Route is almost vertical.

name: Hello World
description: Climbs left of the Moria Cave. One has been known to use the opposing wall to chimney start this route.

name: Hello World extension
description: Starts and climbs Hello World left of Moria Cave. However, this route is an extension. When you get to the first anchors, continue up on one more bolt above the small roof. To minimize rope drag, bring a long draw or runner to help reduce drag. A second set of anchors are above the last bolt. Crux is definitely pulling the roof...but makes the route so much better.

name: Hobbit Hole
description: Fun warm up on easy climbing. Big holds all the way up. Angle gets lower as you climb up.

name: Mines Of Moria
description: Start to the right of the giant chimney crack that makes up "Hello World".  Climb through easy moves on big holds to the roof at the top.  Large holds and fun footwork at the top make for some fun thuggish moves to the chains

name: My Precious
description: Nice climb to set up a top rope for Middle Earth Cave

name: One Ring to Rule Them All
description: All bolts are run out. If your not comfortable leading 5.8...this route could be realy dicey. Any falls would result in pain, if not injury.

name: Orc's Drool
description: Climbs to the right of the water streak. It's anchors are on the right side of the roofs. Last bolt to anchors is slightly run out, be careful.

name: Ringbearer
description: Climb two black tufas, then thru the roof.  This route gets an 'R' rating because a fall before clipping the 3rd bolt could result in hitting the boulder at the base.  Belayer must be attentive to avoid letting that happen.

name: Shelob
description: Solid holds, most are thin and sharp, great friction. Two great underclings(occupied by daddy longlegs), one at the at the beginning and the other a few moves later.

name: Smeagol
description: Has a R rating in the Austin Climbing book for "bolt 3 being runout on hard moves"

name: Snagglefarkin'
description: Starts a few feet right of the first bolt with a high right foot on the obvious point/edge. Follow up the right side of the bolts, using the left edge of the huge huecos if you want. Alternatively, follow the bolt line straight up on thin edges, crimps, and craters. Feels a little easier than the grade with the huecos, and a little harder following the bolt line directly.

name: Tookish
description: Climb to first high bolt on easy climbing. Route heads to the right after 3rd bolt.

name: Troll Teeth
description: To the right of the roof capped dihedral that marks the end of Mossy Wall and the beginning of Middle Earth Wall.  Easy 5.9ish climbing up big holds over the mud ledge to a difficult behind your head clip and some delicate long moves over the bulge  Distinguishable by the blank scooping bulge at the top.

name: Worm Tounge
description: Has a PG rating in Austin Climbing for "bolt 3 is somewhat runout but on easy moves"

name: 28 year engagement
description: fun thin climb to the right of ctrl alt delete

name: Astro Zombie
description: Start at the ledge and work your way up a series of positive crimps to a decent jug so that you can  rest a bit for the committing crux past bolt 3.

name: The Beast Maker
description: Bolt line on the arete left of Ctrl-Alt-Delete and right of Astro Zombie.    Decipher the tricky sequence up the arete utilizing holds on either side. Some start holds may have broken in the past and shorter climbers may require a cheater stack to reach the start holds.

name: Beyond All Likelihood
description: Bolt path and climb path don't exactly match.

name: Ctrl Alt Delete
description: This climb has every time type of hold, which makes it very fun. Due to its immediate hard moves going into just as hard moves up top with even steeper terrain makes this a sustained route.

name: Deceptive Warmup
description: Best of the three left 5.11's at this wall.  Climb up to the chossy ledge and continue on great pockets and edges through 6 bolts.

name: Fancy Feast
description: Sustained and pumpy climb, with the crux around bolt 4-5.

name: The Ghost of Johnny Reimers
description: Great route! Thin crimps for a couple bolts lead to crux pulls past the perma-draw. Pumpy & safe runout to the chains.

name: Katrina
description: Sure to become a North Shore classic.   Start on side-pull tufas with a small sapling at face height.  Climb through friable hollow rock to the first bolt and the sandy ledge.  Continue straight up through excellent pockets and a thin edge to the tufas.  Some interesting features here including a pocket with a mono-suitcase handle.  The crux comes at the top of the tufas, making a left hand dead-point to a large pocket off of two thin slopey crimps.  Juggy pockets to the finish after that.

name: Man's Best Friend
description: Consider stick clipping the 2nd bolt.

name: Moss Cerveza
description: Climbs up the ledge then goes straight up on crimps and monos. Great movement with some tricky sequencing that requires really good route reading .

name: Mossotopia
description: Climb to the first bolt just below a dusty ledge. Become well acquainted with moist moss as you mantle upon the ledge and make your way up to a miniature cavern. A crimp and a big move take you to a fat knee bar no hands rest in Mossotopia's signature cave. Head slightly right over the lip of the cave and enjoy yourself some ledges straight up to the anchors.

name: The Stain
description: Sustained and fun with a little air at the top.

name: The Jodi Adair Show
description: A short, fun sport route that feels easier than the 5.7 grade. I'd call it 5.4 or 5.5, but I like to respect the FA and publish a route at his suggested grade.

name: John the Baptist's Belt
description: The crux, if there is one, might be the start. Various types of jams are possible on this short route.  Like other routes at Philosophy Wall, it has anchors that can be accessed from scrambling up top, but this one will go on gear, too. Remember that it's limestone.

name: Unnamed Crack
description: This is a wide crack, but there are also plenty of face holds to use. If you want to plug gear in limestone, here you go. The rock seems reasonably good until the crack ends. You can protect the finish, but it's choss.

name: Unnamed Dihedral
description: Apparently, this route was established as an easy way to get up top and set topropes for other routes. The 5.7 is moving past the one bolt. Before and after that, it is much easier.  The anchors are two hangers, and they are not rap bolts. The best way for the last climber to get down is to rap off different anchors or find the scrambling descent. Rapping off this routes anchors might not kill your rope, but is it worth risking it on a 20' route?

name: A Thousand Meows from Beyond the Grave
description: Shares a bolt with Dead Cats Do Meow.

name: Another Michael Bolt'n Klausic
description: Route to the right of Nac Nac. leftmost route with glues in bolts. Starts on flake, goes up then veers left. Great moves the whole way, with two amazing bouldery cruxes, with thank you god clip stance at top. Giant fun roof at top with crimp rails!!! So much traxion.

name: Catflip
description: No comment

name: Dead Cats Do Meow
description: Shares a bolt with A Thousand Meows from Beyond the Grave.

name: Electric Hellfire
description: Burly start with poor feet--I used a stick clip for this one. Gets easier the higher you go.   As one might expect from a route with only 3 bolts, its bouldery. I found myself executing some pretty funky sequences.

name: Hello Netherkitty!
description: Shares a start with Lessamir and branches up and right. Superb movement right off the deck with a V4 boulder problem to a HUGE resting just. Two more moves lead you into a shallow 2 finger right hand pocket just below the 4th bolt. Pull the bulge and clip the chains. I recommend sticking the first 2 bolts due the fall potential doing the opening boulder problem.

name: I Was Here
description: This route involves big moves from both sharp and rounded crimps.

name: Lessamir the Slashamatic 1431 Hellkitty - 5.12a
description: Fun route using good, positive pockets.

name: Life in the Cat's Lane
description: No comment

name: My Name Was Muffin
description: So much fun packed into a short route. Gain the face with powerful or static beta and enter a world of balance under the crux bulge. The wave shaped face at the 3rd bolt will test your clipping skills. Finger pockets over the bulge will test your tendons and pulling power.

name: Nac Nac
description: Start under a rectangular block located above bolt #1. Break out some sweet toe hook beta to pull the initial roof. Decent size holds trending up and left serve up a nice pump and lead you to the chains. The guide book suggest a grade of 5.11c, but the boulder problem pulling the initial roof merits 5.11d in my opinion.

name: Pie in the Sky
description: This was Kirk's last route. It is left of Unfinished Monkey Business. High Bolt 1 is left of the mini arete-dihedral pair. Bolt 3 is left of the wide "V" crack at the top of the cliff. Rope drag on lowering can get you stuck. To prevent that, clip anchors left-to-right, then separate the rope ends before lowering.

name: Purrplexed
description: Obvious line through the center of the huge roof. Crux is from the last bolt out to the chains.

name: Sleeper Cell
description: May be harder than 5.11b.

name: Unfinished Monkey Business
description: Real cool route. Crux might be between 2nd and 3rd bolts. Route starts going up, then meanders right before finishing back upwards.    Good if you like crimps and pockets.

name: The Vo-schnozer
description: Start on the obvious nose shaped tufa (the schnoz). First deadpoint move getting from the tufa to a right hand ledge is the crux. Pretty straight forward from there to the chains. This is an enjoyable route, but I've seen a decent amount of people struggle with the start.

name: Werecats
description: Fantastic route with good movement and flow. Nice degree of overhang leads to a bulge at the top.  Bottom and upper cruxes are separated by a great rest just under the 4th bolt. Good footwork will get you through the upper crux.

name: Beggars Bargain
description: Start and first few moves up past the first bolt are a bit interesting..    From bolt two (2) to the Sport Anchors the holds get bigger, with great little foot ledges everwhere

name: Frisbee Addict
description: You could possible hit the tree if you come off between the last bolt and the anchors.

name: Jesse, BCDE
description: Do you know the name of this route? There were two proposed routes for this area: BCDE Jesse and 3-Legged Wondor.

name: Poco's Piss
description: Runout to the anchors.

name: Sit and Stay, My Ass!
description: No comment.

name: 8 It Grand
description: Traverses up and to the right through a series of large huecos, slots and ledges. Anchors are on the right of a small arete at the top of the cliff.

name: Arborcidal Tendencies
description: From the top of the boulder, step up across the 3-foot gap between the boulder and the wall. Use pockets, crimper holds, side-pulls, and a sloper. Crux is between second and third bolts, where some go left and some straight up.

name: Arboricidal Dependencies
description: This variation of Juniper starts on the water streak to the right of Juniper and eventually joins back up with the original line.

name: Arbortrary
description: Crux is between bolt 2 & 3.  It can be wet after a good rain.

name: Burning Bush
description: The most difficult route at this section or Arbor wall.  Climb up through nice pockets on the left side of the small cave ("the Smoking Lounge") and then continue straight up the face.  The crux lies between the last bolt and the anchors as the holds disappear.

name: Chainsaw
description: Climb to the top of the small cave referred to as the "smoking lounge" and continue onto the face to the chains

name: Cleptomania
description: This variation of Cliptomania keeps hands right of the boltline for a more challenging route that feels significantly different from Cliptomania.

name: Cliptomania
description: The first bolt for this route is a little high, but climbing is mellow down low.  This route works left after the first bolt through good, fun holds.  Very good route on high quality limestone.

name: Deferred Adjudication
description: The Companion to Arborcidal Tendencies

name: Ferntasm
description: Climb the dihedral behind the tree past two bolts to the anchors.  There is a great flake near the second bolt that is very positive and provides a good rest.  There is a healthy runout between the first and second bolts.

name: Ferntasm Twice Removed
description: Starts on ledge with strange underclings. Work your way up on crimps. Shares anchors with "Ferntasm" and "Left of Ferntasm."

name: The Finest and the Flyest
description: Start on the tufa, and move up to the bulging dihedral.

name: George of the Jungle
description: Starts right of large tree near the wall. A bit spicy at the bottom and a bit confusing at the top. Runout to bolt 2.

name: Hack in the Fast Lane
description: Small holds lead over the bulging start and past the first bolt and then give way to easier climbing.

name: Juniper
description: Climb the face just left of the water streak through easy pockets to a long deadpoint that marks the beginning of the crux.

name: Kindling
description: Starts to the right of "8 It Grand" under a bulge. Pulling the bulge is the crux.

name: Left of Ferntasm
description: Start as for Ferntasm, but head left to the first bolt.  Climb the slightly overhanging face past two more bolts to a great hold about 2/3 of the way up.  There are plentiful and interesting (albeit small) holds all of the way to the anchors.  Watch for the runout between the last bolt and the anchors.

name: Mrs. Johnson
description: Stand on a boulder and clip the low first bolt. Climb the crux moves over the bulge, and then up easier but sustained 5.9 and 5.10a moves to the anchor.

name: Serpentine Crack
description: Starts in a shallow and sometimes wet dihedral.  Climbs past some moss and other flora to an easy finish.

name: Check Your Head
description: To the right of Chop Suey Style.  Runout over a clean fall.  Bolt 1 is above a diagonal left-leaning "crack".  Bolt 3 is up and far left.

name: Chop Suey Style
description: 5.3 climbing to the high Bolt 1.  Bolt 2 is at 11 o'clock.  Bolt 2 doesn't protect falls back onto the ramp and Bolt 3 has no good clip stance. Probably mid 5.12. Limestoner has it as 11+.  Pass up a stick clip for Bolt 3 is best.

name: Pocket Change
description: Tall route.  At the last bolt, use the arete to clip and climb up the arete to the anchors.

name: Pocket Change (Original version)
description: Instead of using the arete to finish, use the arete to clip the bolt, then move left out onto the face and finish straight up above the bolt.  This was Scott's original style for the route.

name: Swingers
description: Bolt 1 is at the bottom right of a large guitar-pick shaped flake.  The flake edge is along the bottom, left and top. The guitar pick points up and right.  The bottom of the pick is a diagonal formation completing the pick.  The anchors are up and left from the last bolt.

name: [Redacted]
description: A true one move wonder.  Stand on the rock pile while assuring yourself that it wont crumble and then grab what feels like and has been said to be a chipped first hold. Then paste your feet and make a huge throw to a jug. After that its ample 5.9 to the top.

name: About Face
description: Right hand starts 3' right of the bolt-line.

name: All Hail Broke Loose
description: To the right of Grass Attack.

name: Ant Encouters
description: Start is 7' left of a 6" hackberry.

name: Apprehension
description: The start is just right of the bolt-line on a 3-finger horizontal right-hand slot just left of the chossy drip.

name: Back Off Crack
description: Back Off Crack is located on the far right side of Crankenstein wall.  Look for a pair of climbs that start of small boulders at the base of the wall and share and anchor.  Back Off Crack is the crack climb on the right with the lone bolt about two-thirds of the way up.  Climb the solid crack with great holds to the bolt.  Large stoppers and hexes are helpful, but you can also run it out to the bolt.  At the bolt, head left on thin face moves (crux) that lead to a shallow dihedral.  The holds and clipping stance at the anchors are pretty good.  One anchor is on the face and the second is above the rim.  Be prepared to rap off.

name: Bolt Happy
description: Starts on the right of a large flat boulder. Route follows right leaning ramp up to a small roof. Anchors are just left of a large orange patch at the top.    Stick clip bolt 2 (and bolt 1 for the belayer) until you have this wired.    Large poison ivy plant dangles precariously close the the starting holds. Someone please pull that sucker!

name: Bolted like Reimer's
description: Start up the crack and quickly traverse back left to the second bolt on nice pockets. Work up the face to a difficult section getting to a ledge on the left of the line. Reach out right out clip the last bolt and make delicate moves out onto the face and up to jugs just below the anchor.    Based on how this is bolted the FA really wanted to keep you out of the crack, the first bolt is way left. However this would mean using a hollow undercling.

name: Bride of Crankenstein
description: Stick clip the first bolt and start with your left hand in the obvious 3 finger pocket.  The route initially moves right toward the start of Crankenstein but doesn't share holds.  The upper half of the route moves to the left.

name: Crankenstein
description: Make difficult moves up into some tuffa formations then over a roof. Some nice pocket holds lead up to a huge jug. some techy moves on sidepulls take you up to some mail slot type holds. A few more moves take you to huge flakes that are followed to the anchor.

name: Die Hard
description: The start is interesting climbing over a bulge (crux).  The top has fun stemming moves in the dihedral. This is a good warm-up for crankenstein wall.

name: Dude, where's my hammer?
description: difficult start with no feet and hands reached high on slopers.  Couple of good moves to a very tiny undercling which leads to jugs below a bulge.  The bulge is tough to onsight but holds are plentiful if you look hard enough.

name: Industrial Disease
description: Tough to get off the ground and onto the wall, then an interesting and reachy boulder problem up to, around and over the low roof. Above, easier face climbing on better holds up to the anchor.

name: Mona Peligrosa
description: The arete at the top is on-route.

name: More Wasabi
description: Bolt 1 is just above the curved edge of the roof.

name: The Munchies
description: Climb through thin and bouldery cruxes using big moves, bad holds, or both, all separated by big jugs, with a final little crux guarding the anchors. The jug flake system to the right is off. The hardest moves are found directly in the boltline.

name: Pearl
description: Small holds. yup

name: Santeria
description: Start on Gang Bang. Move left after the first throw.

name: Scary 7-11
description: Described as 12a in the guidebook, this route has been overgrown with vines and ivy until I cleaned it off today (12/6/2020). If you are under 6 feet tall you probably cant reach the juggy undercling full of ferns from the ground, but if you are you can, and if you can then you can skip the "12a" crux. That's stupid.Use a cheater stack to reach the undercling, or be tall and reach the undercling, climb through a low 5.10 crux to the flake, then enjoy fun 5.7 climbing to the anchors.  Bolt 1 is on a protruding shield of rock, directly under the large flake. Stick clip this, climb directly up to it, then follow the flake to Scary 7-11's independent chains.

name: Short Term Memory Loss
description: From John Hogge's book: From the boulder, clip Bolt 1 of Wife, then go down to start on the ground. Bolts and anchors slant slightly left. Runout to Bolt 3 over a ledge hazard. Rick and several committee members support a retro.

name: Sunday Mass
description: Crux is the beginning towards the top. Stick clip the first bolt.

name: Teenage Parties
description: Fun start in the low bulge to nice pockets that get sharp the higher you go. Then a balency finish to the anchors.    This route though graded harder than its neighbor, War on Rugs, seems about the same in grade. It can be a bit dirty though because a lack of traffic.

name: Wankenstein
description: Use Crankenstein's first bolt before moving left to bolts 2-4 of Bride of Crankenstein.

name: War on Rugs
description: Graded 5.10d in the guide book. This route is essentially a V2 boulder problem to get onto the wall followed by easy 5.10 climbing.    Reach from the ground up to the hollow looking and sounding flake that trends up and to the left. Pull on and hoist up into some pockets that really are not all that good. Once in the pockets stand up and continue up the face relatively easily to a thin section just below the anchors.

name: Wife in the Fast Lane
description: Slightly intimidating step off the boulder. Some cool jigsaw looking features. Then up to some tuffas out right, a long move up to a jug sidepull. A traverse left to a horizontal and up to a hard to see anchor on the left side of a block.

name: You Bet Arete
description: Start in the dihedral left of the arete. Bolts 1 and 2 are just right of the arete. R rating unless stick clipping Bolt 2.

name: Almost Nothing To It
description: Easy climbing up good jugs leads to a couple of sketchy moves under the third bolt (crux).  Pull a small, easy roof above the 3rd bolt and then clip one more on your way to the anchors.

name: Back Flip
description: Back Flip is a little harder than Scotts Pelotas, with big holds and some strenuous moves, especially near the top where it angles left a bit and shares anchors with Water Ballet.  There is a bit of distance between the last bolt and the anchors.  Make sure Water Ballet is clear before starting up.

name: Bolted like Mex
description: As the name implies, this route is sporty and there has been some discussion about retro-bolting this.  And for this reason I suspect that this route is not well traveled.  The first bolt is off the ground a bit and requires some delicate movement to get to it.  The second bolt is then a fair distance away; from what I recall the climbing is straightforward but blowing it here will possibly land you on the ground, bouncing off the tree at the base in the interim.  After the sweaty palms and heartburn of this first section, the route eases up and is fairly unremarkable.      I recommend doing this once just for giggles; but, the line is nothing special given that the crux is down low.

name: Centipede
description: The route starts out on the right side of Dead Cats Wall the next route over from Power Snatch.    The start is a three pad undercling on the left hand, the right is a comfy side pull.  Step up right and smear left, laying back on the undercling.  Throw right for a big crimp.  Rotate the left and place a kneebar on the shelf under the bulge.  Match the crimp and then fire left or right for jugs.  Smear left and step high bringing your balance up on the curb and let your right hand deadpoint on a small lip.  Move your feet below you and stand up reaching left for the thankyoujug. Work the jugs up the face and finish right on 5.6 face or finish left on the upper face of Power Snatch.

name: Clawing Zoe
description: Fun climb up a the well featured face.  Start on a less than vertical face and climb past a small tree and three bolts to a steeper head wall at the top of the climb.  There are plenty of small but solid holds to chose from on the upper face.

name: Dead Cats Dont Meow
description: The walls namesake route  fun, with a great finish.  Straight forward climbing leads past two bolts to the small roof.  Pull through the roof (crux), stand up, search for the plentiful holds above, and clip the third bolt.  Angle right past one additional bolt where a big, sloping hold leads to the anchors.

name: Dude, Where's My Cat?
description: Starts in the center of a long law ledge. It takes a long time to climb this short route.

name: The Great Unknown
description: climb through easy 5.9ish climbing to the bulge.  A somewhat technical and not easily read crux leads to the chains

name: Hair Balls and Spray
description: The crux is the very smooth section below the anchors.

name: Hello Kitty
description: An unmemorable route for a one-day visitor to Reimers.  Location beta courtesy Sean O'Grady's book "Austin Rock."

name: Hissing Cloe
description: Climb past great holds on the flake (as you lean to the right), then face climb past three bolts to the anchors.  The crux is climbing through the sloping hand holds between the last bolt and the anchors.  Great feet with some better holds up and to the left.

name: Last Meows
description: Same start as Reimerama (1st two bolts), then traverse over to Dude Where's my Cat third bolt. Route is a variation route.

name: Lessa the Puramatic 6000 Kitty
description: A ton of people's first outdoor climb and lead climb.  A small tree grows on the cliff on a ledge just right of the start.  The route's start foot holds include a gnarly left-facing flake.  Can be done with or without the help of the tree.

name: Madrone
description: Climb up and right to the first bolt (the clipping stance can be a little awkward until you find a not-so-obvious hold).  Continue up two the little roof and clip the second bolt.  The third bolt can be reached from below the roof.  Move up and right through the roof to the anchors above.  Not great, not bad.  It's considerably easier and less heady than Back Flip to its left even though they both get the same grade.  The crux is just above the first bolt.

name: Mario's Route
description: Crux is at the top.

name: My Name is Mud
description: Climb past the first two bolts to a good rest in the cave.  Exiting the cave is a little tricky, as is the third clip (crux).  There are good holds all of the way up the right side of the climb.

name: Power Snatch
description: Small, but solid, holds and pockets all of the way to the top.  There is a great slot followed by a finger crack near the second bolt that offers up some good moves through the middle of the route.  The route's crux comes near the top - a couple of ballancy mantles that lead to good holds near the anchors.

name: Ralph's Route
description: Crux move or two after third bolt. Most do it as a long throw, stronger climbers do it staticly.

name: Reimerama
description: stay off the tree, cruux is in the first couple moves, enjoy!

name: Rolly Pollly Coco Kitty
description: The hardest part of the route is getting past the first ten feet.  Once past the low crux, continue on big holds to the top.

name: Scotts Pelotas
description: Located on the left side of Dead Cats Wall, and just right of a large, orange buttress with a bolted route that climbs through a large bulge (Marios Route, 5.12a).  There are some thin, somewhat tricky moves right off the ground that lead to easier climbing above.

name: Smelling Cat Calvin
description: Start up a well featured face that is a bit steeper than the starts of the other climbs here.  Transition into a shallow dihedral at the second bolt and then continue up easy terrain to the anchors.

name: Water Ballet
description: fingery start, lots of choices for feet and hands.  balancey to a commiting finish over a nice bulge.

name: Hilti Highway
description: Traverse a little left at the start, then enjoy a nice break in a huge deep hueco before heading up for the finish.

name: Mammaz Boyz
description: Start with small seam and work above to slightly sloping small holds.

name: Quality Ivy
description: Fun moves off the ground to the first bolt, reaching bolt two is the technical crux of the route.  From there you go right to the third bolt.  Though slightly runout, the climbing to the anchors from this point is easy.

name: The Sting
description: The crux moves are at the very beginning and once you reach the large vertical jug/fissure to the left of the starting holds, the grade softens.

name: Stegosaurus
description: Start in horizontal slot, climb upwards between second and third bolts on crimps and pockets towards second bolt.

name: Triceratops
description: Starts the same as Digitalia(v6)under the third bolt, on two decent pinch/side pulls. Move upwards and diagonally on pinch and better side pull, cross over and match then work your way up on crimps and pockets towards bolt 2.

name: Blowing Smoke at the Monkey
description: Some good holds lead up to a shallow left facing corner which can be climbed in a variety of ways, delicate or powerful, reachy or not. Eventually a big hold up and left is reached, rest up for the push to the anchor. Some sloping holds take you back right and up to the anchor at which point there really is not a good hold to clip from.    This route packs quite alot into its 25 feet of so.

name: Bongo Fury Direct
description: Prototype Wall and a section of Dr. Seuss Wall collapsed on 1/15/19.  This route no longer exists.

name: Buttered Side Up
description: Easy dihedral-like climbing until the roof and 4th bolt.     Great edges/ledge to establish while pulling the roof. Then use shallow pocket to bump right hand to pinch side pull. Then use left (smallish) pinch and bring right leg up. Place left root on ledge and flag right leg. Bump for a bomber pocket. Easy from there.

name: Eight Flake
description: This climb is no longer available. The wall has collapsed.

name: Flinch
description: Right of Yertle the Turtle. This is the furthest right route that is intact since the rock fall in January 2019. 4 bolts to chains, no sport anchor.

name: Horton Here's a Tufa
description: Really fun technical climbing on small tufa features takes you to the roof.  Tough pull through the roof to a hard finish on slopers.

name: Prototype
description: On January 16th, 2019 a large rock fall destroyed much of Prototype/Dr. Seuss Wall, with climbs from Eight Flake to Bongo Fury now gone, including this climb. Take care climbing on limestone!  One of the best 5.10 climbs at Reimer's. Prototype is the right most of two lines that share the first bolt (the other is Mas Cerveza, 5.11) just to the right of the shallow dihedral at the base of Clone Call. The start overhangs a little - pull up onto a bulge using a good flake. Be sure to clip the first bolt before making any moves up the bulge or you could deck if you slipped. Look for a good two finger pocket with the right hand while you pinch with the left. Pull through the bulge to a good stance (crux). The middle part of the climb is thin, but has plenty of rests. Look for a great hold at the last bolt (a "squirrel cage"). The second difficulty on the route is moving from the last bolt to the chains. There are some small edges, and good finger pocket just below the top.

name: The ReKleiner
description: Prototype Wall and a section of Dr. Seuss Wall collapsed on 1/15/19.  This route no longer exists.

name: Smitten Psychopath
description: Smitten Psychopath is the first climb on the left side of the Dr. Seuss Wall.  Look for a prominent, short arete with three bolts.  Belay from a narrow ledge that runs along the base of the wall.  A couple moves off the ground lead to a solid ledge.  From the ledge climb up and left through a small overhang.  The last clip is ballancy.  The rock is a little sharp on this one, and the climbing looks easier than it is.

name: Socks On Chicks
description: Some technical face climbing to a monster jug

name: Star Belly Sneeches
description: Really fun face climbing to the roof.  Stay right for the easy variation that fits the grade.  Working left is harder and the pockets are EXTREMELY SHARP.

name: Sugar
description: Prototype Wall and a section of Dr. Seuss Wall collapsed on 1/15/19.  This route no longer exists.

name: There's a Wocket in my Pocket
description: Newest route on Dr. Seuss wall. Go left past the small roof and around the corner as if heading to Shortcake wall. This route is all alone next to a small tree, crux is low as the start is trickier than it looks, and the top is no gimme either.

name: Thing 1 Thing 2
description: A variation of Horton Here's a Tufa. After 2 bolt, traverse u dear roof and finish on Star Belly Sneech finish.

name: Yertle the Turtle
description: Good fun on 11- holds/moves to a tough crux at top.  I remember this climb as being a climb that started making me realize good technique will make some hard climbs feel really easy once you get it all down.

name: Annie Up
description: Short, easy climb with harder variations possible.  The bottom half is easy and straight forward with large pockets and solid moves.  Above the second bolt, climb the flake up and left, and then step right to the anchors to keep the climb at 5.6.  A 5.9-ish variation climbs straight to the anchors from the second bolt.  The climbing is much thinner, and there are good holds around the anchors, but they are a little reachy.

name: Annie Up (5.9) variation
description: Climb the gray streak to the right of Annie Up. STAY OFF THE FLAKE SYSTEM the entire time to keep it a 5.9. Gold holds all the way up.

name: Antonian
description: Same bolts as Hidden Agenda (5.11b) but climb to left of the bolts. Stay off the flake system, if you use flake than you are starting on Annie Up (5.7. Crux is right below anchors.

name: Booger Boy
description: Start just left side of large oak tree.  Start is crux to first bolt.

name: Camp Fire Jesus
description: Small holds down low, larger rough holds higher up. Northern-most route at Reimers North Band.

name: Daddys Girl
description: Climb a pocketed face about five feet to the right of a tree.  The initial moves are a little tough, but the climbing eases past the first bolt.  Continue past two more bolts on solid holds to the anchors.

name: Deception Pass
description: Climb the short face to the first bolt and then head up to the right side of the roof.  Pull through the roof using a series of small, off balance side pulls on equally small foot holds (crux).  The trick is to continuously get your feet as high as possible, transfer your weight to the high foot, and then pull up a little more.  Clip the second bolt just above the roof (felt very off balance here) and then continue up the dihedral past one more bolt to the anchors.  The climbing eases significantly above the second bolt.

name: Ezra's Shelf
description: Taller climbers can reach up and clip the first bolt while standing on the boulder. Medium- and large-sized holds up the slightly overhanging face.  Difficulty seems consistent all the way up.

name: Freedom Fries
description: Two arguably different routes share the same bolt line:    Left Fry - 5.10b: Stay left of bolt line on crimps, pull the mini bulge near the top for the crux.    Right Fry - 5.10a: Stay right of bolt line on crimps and jugs

name: Go For the Jugular
description: Start with fun moves up a huge flake/crack.  The one-move crux comes about halfway up, making a long-ish move off a left-hand sidepull to the titular "jugular" hold.  Very fun.

name: Hairlipped Dog
description: good holds on a slightly negative face. Great warm up for the area.

name: Hidden Agenda
description: Start on ground below chest-high overhang and right of first bolt. Crux is getting off the ground and feet onto the face (scrunch into a frog and ribbet). Several more hard moves on the face, clip second bolt and climb much easier moves to anchor. Some say 11a.    5.8 'Antonian' variation: start on boulder left of first bolt. Runout - be confident at the grade.

name: Monkey Boy
description: Shares start with Jugular, but then you angle left towards first bolt. It's a short 2 clip climb that remains in the tan shallow bowl to the overhang.

name: Overlord
description: Shares anchors with Deception Pass, but its the line directly under the roof...pulling roof is crux on nasty sharp 2/3 finger pocket. Tape up.

name: Power Squat
description: Starts left of arete.

name: San Antonio Drillers
description: Starts right of arete.

name: See Thru Black
description: Use pockets low down, less positive holds higher up. Routes on this wall are not climbed much, so holds are rough.

name: Shadowman
description: Crux is getting on the route.  Shortest route on the Hand Beyond Wall and most likely all of Reimer's.

name: Ten Foot Pole
description: Starts in golden overhung area right of "Waste of Bolts." First bolt is rather high, consider stick clipping. Crux is moving past this bolt. Crimp slab climbing after to anchors.

name: Tree Gnome
description: This route zig-zags. Zig left from the inside corner, clip first bolt, go up to second bolt, zag right and then up. (Going straight up to first bolt provides a slightly harder start). Gets full sun exposure by mid- to late-morning.    Location is about 30 left of Power Squat.

name: Unknown 10a
description: Start on two rounded holds. Pulling the lip is the crux. Fun route.

name: Waste of Bolts (Bluebeard)
description: Route starts on large handle bar feature. Goes up and left from here. Runout to anchors. Don't let the safety rating deter you from trying this if you're confident at this grade. The climb is a great mental trainer for runout climbing.

name: Angular Momentum
description: Start as for Jade, up on the ledge with those delicious tufas. Climb through the first 3 bolts of Jade, then instead of pulling over the mini-roof, traverse right around the blunt arete. Cross over Spanish Fly, then go up and right to the anchors of Irreverent Youth.     3 bolts of Jade, 2 bolts for AM, 1 bolt of Spanish Fly, 1 bolt for AM, anchors of Irreverent.    The crux is turning the corner and getting to the jugs on Spanish Fly. The other crux is keeping your hands not dirty/dusty.

name: Bastards in the Brothel
description: High crux over the last bolt.  Crank the gaston and then layback like a mofo and scramble up some bad crimps

name: Burning Sensations (Bastard Direct)
description: The direct line to the Bastard in the Brothel is now bolted. 4 new bolts lead to the existing two and anchors.

name: Catharsis Roof
description: Takes the pump of Jade into a more difficult finish. Make moves up to slopers and a long pull to a jug and the last clip. Slopey body tension moves take you over the final roof and some scrunchy moves getting your feet over the lip.

name: House of Pain
description: Bouldery with rests. Steep climbing off the ledge leads to a difficult and cryptic sequence getting past the second bolt, think high right heal hook. A couple small pockets and some easier climbing leads to a good rest below the final bulge. A difficult cross either going to or off of a pocket to some more jugs then up on some slopy holds to the anchor. Would be classic except for the 4 drilled pockets, quite fun none the less.

name: House of Youth
description: Climb 'House of Pain' through the first 3 bolts and up to it's rest hold, then finish up Irreverent Youth.    Harder than House of Pain. I recommend not clipping the 4th bolt of House of Pain, and instead reach left from the rest hold and clip the 5th bolt of Irreverent. From there move up and clip the 6th bolt of Irreverent, downclimb back to the jug and rest as long as you need. This puts the rope below you as you try the upper moves of Irreverent and makes falling safer and more comfortable.

name: Irreverent Youth
description: Make some tough moves up on crimps and a pinch to a big move to a sharp hold left of the second bolt. From here make some moves up on pinchy side-pulls then on some crimps, clip the 3rd bolt off of any of these. Move up onto slopers, then improving holds eventually gaining the rest on House of Pain. After you've rested make moves up on sloping holds and a sharp, small side-pull finishing with a punch to a jug that requires a bit of accuracy to hit well. Easier moves take you to the top.

name: Jade
description: Stunning route on the left side of the cliff that starts with 5.10 climbing to a mini roof that pulls on jugs, then traverses right on slopers, to a juggy yet run out top section

name: Lord of the Dance
description: Starts with long moves up and right to some tuffa features. Then a boulder problem on a really small hold takes you up to the first head size hueco. Some long moves on OK holds leads to the second head size hueco. Take a quick rest and make a huge move up to a pocket and a few more small but good holds takes you to the anchor.

name: Rain Dance
description: Fantastic Reimers route where sending comes down to a single redpoint crux at the last bolt. This climb starts on the same boulder as does stranglehold and traverses left on some suspicious pockets to the first bolt. The climbing eases off until the rusty pin. This section involves clinching an open handed pinch with your left and crimping hard on a half pad crimp with your right and bumping with your right to a jug. Don't fall at this point because the anchors are near.

name: Spanish Fly
description: Start out on a block and move up into some underclings then a big shelf. Reach up to a crimp and make a long move to a pocket. From here you can either jump for a flake jug or make a couple more moves up some nicely textured holds then reach the jug. From here some long pulls on good holds takes you up the less steep face to the anchors.

name: Stranglehold
description: Stick clip the first bolt as some of the hardest moves are before you get to it. A difficult pull off of a slopey pinch to a decent pocket gets you started. The difficulty of the start yields to big pulls on good holds and less steep rock. As the angle kicks back towards the top the jugs are replaced by pockets and eventually slopers near the anchor, the holds get better the higher you go.

name: Velcro Rodeo
description: Start on the rightmost side of the triangle slab boulder at the base of Rain Dance, Strangehold, and this route. Climb up through 4 bolts of goodness.

name: Alip
description: A very hard and tricky boulder problem getting out the roof yields to pleasant 5.11/5.12 climbing to the chains (a copy/paste description which applies to nearly every route on this wall).  It's possible that this route has broken, since there are no known ascents since the time of the FA, and having discussed beta with Twyman he described holds that don't seem to exist anymore. For now we'll stick with 13b until someone can repeat it and confirm.

name: Baby Roof
description: This great mixed route uses the 1st three bolts of Ship Of Fools pulls a small roof then follows a crack system to the right for 20+ feet to a vertical crack/flake. The protection is unusually good for cams in limestone.  Small metolios power cams have held repeated whippers.  The Crux comes half way through the traverse where the seem pinches shut for a bit.

name: Backslider
description: Shares a start with Singularity but moves up and left on a slanting rail before going straight up a mini-diehedral.

name: Block Party
description: Ramble up the face to difficult moves reaching the first flake in the roof. A long move to a sloper on the second rail is followed by several jugs heading left across the roof. Cruxy section comes at the third draw in the roof at some crimps and slopey pinches and sidepullish holds. Eventually reach the end of the roof and a couple of juggy pockets. Cryptic moves lead up the short grey face on slopey holds and sidepulls to the anchor, it is difficult to see your feet on this last section so plan ahead.

name: Brainstem
description: The namesake of this route, the brainstem, is obvious if you know what to look for. A tufa ball resembling a brain and spinal cord as the lip turns. This route follows a series of viciously small, glued crimps left of the boltline into the large sidepull feature, then heading out left onto the brainstem and up.  Unfortunately a signficant amount of choss has broken on this line and there is now quite a large jug directly under the boltline allowing for a more easy, direct variation to climb into the sidepull feature. Using these holds removes several V-grades of difficulty from the low section, avoid them if you want to claim the 5.14 grade.

name: Crack Attack
description: A unique route that utilized a large downward-then-rightward-facing flake (sorry, it's not really a crack).     Start on decent holds and up to a hueco, then begins your adventure up into the flake (crack), in which squirrels may or may not live. Go right and up the flake to a jug, then a series of wonderful crimps and ledges and pockets to the anchors. Similar to most Reimers routes, the top section gets real blank, except for the few holds that lead to the top.     This route does not see much traffic, perhaps due to it starting up on a ledge with bad fall potential: a stick clip would help.

name: Deflower Power
description: Pull moves on somewhat sloping holds out the low overhang. Mantle up onto the face , you can move left at this point to get a better rest, though once on the face it is pretty easy to rest anyway. Climb crimps up the face to some big holds just before the final overhang. Make long moves on positive holds up onto the short headwall and the anchors at the top.

name: Dragonflower
description: A linkup of Deflower Power and Dragonfly. Start on Deflower Power and lead up the first 4 bolts. Once you are at the jug rest at the 4th bolt, traverse right along the horizontals to the 3rd bolt of Dragonfly. Some local chuffer ripped off the jug block originally used to traverse, but it still goes. Pull the final, titillating crux of Dragonfly and top that shit out.

name: Dragonfly
description: First route to the right of deflower power.  Difficult boulder problem at the start (like most routes at insect wall) revolving around a long reach that may seem impossible for shorter climbers.  Remainder of the route on easier terrain with great rock and interesting holds.  Deserves more traffic.

name: Dreamkeeper
description: This route has a distinct crux going to the pocket in the middle of the lower steep wall. The climbing stays on you till you are over the lip though and the final roof provides an additional challenge. Really if you know where you are going though you should not come off up high.    Traverse right and slightly up on thin crimps. Move up to a sidepull and make a desperate (crux) move to the obvious 2 or 3 finger pocket. Move up into the short left facing block just below the lip. Make a long cross to a slot over the lip and pull up onto the face where you can get a complete rest. Trundle up jugs to the roof above. Make a long move over the lip off of and undercling. Then up on pockets and edges to the anchor.

name: Ill Ninja Skills
description: This route is the boltline to the left of the start of Block Party, essentially a direct version of Block Party. This route rarely gets traffic, due to its difficulty and the fact that the roof section (and the first vertical section) is plagued by seepage, wetness, foliage, etc.     After climbing out the roof, the route joins Block Party at the 3rd permadraw on BP's roof, then continues up BP to the anchors.

name: Lake Traverse High School
description: A big endurance traverse linkup. Start on Deflower Power and lead up the first 4 bolts. Once you are at the jug rest at the 4th bolt, traverse right along the horizontals to the 3rd bolt of Dragonfly. Some local chuffer ripped off the jug block originally used to traverse, but it still goes.  This system of horizontals extends halfway across all of Insect Wall, so start moving before the pump kicks ur ass. You'll cross over Malaria, Mantis, and then eventually end up on the jug rest of Scorpion Child. Rest up and pull the crimpy final crux of Scorpion Child.  I tried to add a bolt at one spot along the traverse cuz it was a small runout, but TCC denied it so if you fall and get fucked up there, blame them not me :)

name: Malaria
description: Disappointing boulder problem to start revolving around a shallow left hand pocket, a bad 3-finger right hand crimp, and a drilled left mono full of mud and ferns.  Dyno to the lip off the mono and the crimp with really high feet.  Or don't because you don't want to explode your tendons.  Rest of the route easier on solid rock.  Doesn't get climbed much because of the silly injury potential.  Apparently if you boulder V14 you can dyno from the start holds to the jug over the lip and skip the bad holds.

name: Mantis
description: Start left of Scorpion child on an obvious left hand sidepull and make a big move to a glue-reinforced crimp. Move slightly left and up through the roof going either left to natural edges and sidepulls or right through a drilled double-mono sprag.    From here grab the only hold on the headwall and figure out how to navigate the complete lack of holds between this and the next feature 5 feet above you. If you manage to stand on the headwall try to relax and recover to tackle the remaining 5.11 to the chains.

name: Patience Grasshopper
description: Get in position under the roof, grab the hold just above, then do a low percentage, dynamic throw to the next hold. Sticking this move is the crux. Boulder up some more difficult moves then do a relaxing 12a/11d to the chains on perfect edges.

name: Rotten Oasis
description: Supposedly one of the hardest routes at Reimers, few have even attempted this route to confirm it's difficulty, much less climbed it. It's likely in serious need of deforesting and cleaning before good attempts can be made.

name: Scorpion Child
description: Climb out the roof on some pockets that seem to have been heavily "helped" eventually reaching a sharp lipped pocket on the face. A difficult move gains the tuffa and a good rest. Turn the bulge and finish up the face on square cut holds.

name: Ship of Fools
description: Easy climbing on chossy holds for the first 3 bolts leads to a crux traverse, roof pull, and powerful moves on bullet limestone. The movement on this line is fantastic and is, in my opinion, better than Deflower Power.    Since the nearby beehive has been abandoned, and the start area and lowering areas have been cleared this route deserves to see a lot more traffic. Get on it!

name: Singularity
description: Start up the dihedral just right of Backslider, and left of Stickbug to some jug slots just below the roof. From here either utilize a roof mono to the left, or make a powerful spanny move to a bad crimp over the lip on the right side of the dihedral. Eventually gain a good hold on the left side of the dihedral and use it to get your feet over the lip of the roof.    Rest up, then run through a fun 5.12 to the chains.

name: Stickbug
description: Another potentially great route in need of attention, this route climbs so close to the tree pressing up into the roof that without regular trimming the climber will be impeded by the branches that grow over the holds!  The boulder problem on this route is tricky, and relatively long for an Insect Wall route, requiring some great 3D climbing.

name: Texas Hold'Em
description: Unlike the majority of the routes on this wall, the crux of Texas Hold Em is not navigating a boulder problem through a roof. Instead, this route kicks back at a consistently steep angle until reaching a bulge where the crux begins. If you have a wingspan less than 5'7" you can forget any notion about this route falling in the 5.13 range.

name: Wild Spider
description: 2-3 bolt lines down right from Scorpion Child. It has a very chalked up volleyball shaped sloper near the start.

name: Bros Before Hoes
description: Just left of the mini dihedral, starts on the mini arete formed by the bulge and the dihedral and then moves left up and over the bulge.    Pull hard moves on sharp pockets. 13a is the 21st century grade. 12d shouldn't be harder than half the 13a's in the park.

name: Donne Moi Tete
description: Rightmost route in the white limestone. Execute a crimpy boulder problem culminating in a jug sidepull. Finish on jugs.

name: Friends and Lovers
description: 2.5' from Snuff the Rooster but the anchors are higher and invisible.  The route uses (right-handed) three holds on Snuff.  Left hand holds are all left of the boltline and work increasingly away from it, onto the arete, so that you reachfar right to clip Bolt 3. Grab the juggy undercling block far left.

name: Repulsive Attila
description: Anchors are over the left part of the high mini-roof.  Bolt 2 is right of the other bolts.  Ledge to start.

name: Snuff the Rooster
description: After Bolt 2 you are tempted to skip Bolt 3, since it jigs right and the anchors are so close by.  Don't skip it.  Move right to Bolt 3 and then far up to the mini-roof with the hole in it, at the clifftop.  Then reach left to clip the anchors.  This dogleg path milks some fun technical moves.

name: The Tipping Point
description: Start on the rock mound left of Snaggletufaed. Move up and left to gain a jug, then bear down on terrible crimps and contort into an extremely high heel moving through a tough boulder problem. Move up and left, finishing on the anchors for "Out of the Shadow"

name: The Tonic Clonic Episode
description: Starts somewhat in the white limestone but quickly moves to the right. Execute an extremely powerful boulder problem on sharp rock which doesn't let up until you're standing above the bulge. Clip the anchors.

name: Get Yer Fill
description: Access the high starting ledge from the large boulder on the ground. Follow excellent movement up the headwall before exiting the roof on a large flake.

name: Heathers
description: Great face climb.

name: Hidden Pockets
description: Just right (around the corner) of Jugfest. Guidebook gives it an R rating. I respectfully disagree.     I think clipping bolt #1 on Jugfest is sketchier than the "run out" to bolt 3 on this route.

name: J.P. Court
description: Bolt one is high over the handhold ledge. The guidebook doesn't describe the actual start to the climb, i.e. direct below the bolt or traversing in on the handhold ledge. I traversed in on the ledge and feel like that's the most logical way to start, grade felt solid too this way.Once you get above the ledge clip bolt 2, then execute some techy face climbing to get to, and clip bolt 3. A runout to the anchors follows, with a collection of bad holds, a massive jug flake, pockets, and finally the lip of the cliff which makes for a massive clipping jug.

name: Jugfest
description: This is one of the best 5.8's at Reimers!  It starts on a huge, blobby tufa and follows three bolts up to the roof.

name: Little White Trash Boy
description: Start at a low roof and up onto a dirty ledge.  Climb through some very featured rock, left of a tufa, and through the roof.  Great climbing other than the dirt covered ledge.

name: Monkey Pajamas
description: Consider a stick clip for first bolt. Do crux move or two getting past first bolt, stay in dihedral, clip second bolt (kind of a reachy clip), then climb to anchor. Pumpy short upper section overhangs quite a bit. Decent but not great anchor. Anchor does not have sport clips as of 2/2017.   PG rating is for potential 'wrecking ball' fall if from above bolt 2.

name: Slopeamine
description: Great Route, but it my need cleaning.

name: Sometimes I'm Dreamin'
description: Climb up to a dirty/mossy ledge, through a small dihedral, then pull a small bouldery, bulgy section to your left, and then head up to the cool flake thing sticking out that's about 3 feet wide. Go up and right then do a huge move to a roof pull, can clip anchors from the last jug under the anchors. It's easy to get off-route on this thing. Maybe it's not off-route... Who knows, just go climb it! I guarantee there will never be a line for this rig.

name: Tapeworm
description: First bolt is 20 feet high at the right side of the roof (i'm giving it an R rating because of the high first bolt, it was too high to even stick clip without climbing a few feet up first).  Route begins on the unique "tapeworm" formation to the ledge below the first bolt then goes right and up for the rest of the route.

name: Tufafest
description: Sit-start to Jugfest. Bear hug the tufa and slap upward.

name: Crack Smack
description: Climbs a lieback "crack." First bolt is kind of high but the climbing is pretty easy to it.  Wandering very thin face moves which require very specific balancing combined with friction and body position towards the top. First go the right and then back to left and then slightly back to the right again and up to the chains.  Clip bolts only when on "good" holds.

name: Herbivore Connoisseur
description: Quite possibly much harder than the rating indicates.  To the right of Crack Smack.  Last route to the right on the wall.  Climb up over the outcropping to the first bolt.  Many small crimps and very small lie-backs.  Two variations:  one to the left and the other to the right.  Finish on steep terrain to chains.

name: I Speak for the Trees
description: To the right of Let the Wallies Loose. To start off, there are some kind of overhung boulder moves that require a very beta specific sequence to get over the bulge.  Once over the bulge, the rest of the route is similar to the routes to the left of it but with thinner holds at the shelf area before the chains.  Great route.

name: Let the Wallies Loose
description: Very similar to the two routes to the left of it.  4 bolts to the top passing through areas of large and small holds.  Ledge near the top with holds in back.

name: Mai Type
description: Description by John Hogge from Austin Climbing.  "Bolt 1 is over the rightmost end of the roof that's under Prototype Wall routes Bongo Fury and The ReKleiner.  Start by dynoing from the ground to a block 3 feet left of Bolt 1.  Bolts 2 and 3 slant slightly left.  Easy runout to Bolt 3.  Runout to the anchors over a bad slab fall."

name: Mega Lounge
description: Five feet to the right of "Tree".  Typical mixture of large and small limestone holds very similar to "Tree".  Steep route.  First bolt is 12 feet up.  Large shelf/cave 5 feet below the anchors with variety of options for holds inside as you transition up the face again with one hand or the other.  The top of the wall has several spots to hang from while you build an anchor from two chains.

name: Tree
description: After clipping the first bolt, mantle up awkwardly onto the face. Move up following the seam, climbing mostly to the left. Some nice holds lead up through the face and slab right up to the top of the cliff.    A nice easier route that is not quite as greasy as some of the more popular easy warm-ups. It's a little weird getting onto the ledge and maybe as hard as the route.    Beware of poison ivy growing up the wall between the ground and the ledge below and to the right of the route.

name: Food Rage
description: A very bouldery start to quality face climbing.  Starts on a ledge, there is a roof and bulge with several bouldery moves. Some good exposure near the top.

name: Millennium Traverse
description: Great traverse, longest route at Reimer's Ranch I believe.  One of the few QUALITY traverses I've done.  Great exposure for the area and grade.    Climb up to the second bolt, traverse right for 8 more bolts, then at the 10th bolt go up and right to the anchors, clipping one more bolt.

name: Rags to Riches
description: Start on the left edge of Rhetorick Wall (up on the landing) and traverse left around a huge arete. Easy runout at the top.  Named for the chossy start (rags) and the high quality flake at the top (riches).  Beware of loose rock.  Better to stick clip bolts 1 and 2.

name: Buddha's Gut
description: Start on the now broken mini-tufa of "Pinch the Buddha".  (You can also use the tree to get up to the featured band but probably makes the route 5.10b).  At about 10 feet off the ground, follow the features and transverse to the left and join "Gut Punch the Buddha" between the 1st and 2nd bolts.  The crux is joining Pinch the Buddha.  At the ledge, use either a static move or a mini-dyno from the right.  After obtaining the ledge, follow and finish on "Gut Punch the Buddha."

name: Crack Ate the Pipe
description: Very similar to Got a Dollar?, only a little longer.  Challenging moves on the lower part of the route lead to huge jugs at the top.

name: Got a Dollar?
description: Thin opening moves lead to an easier finish on large blocks and jugs above.

name: Gut Punch the Buddha
description: Fun face climb with reachy moves. Start can be hard for some.    Bolted well, but it felt a bit harder than 5.9 to me.

name: Hat Dance
description: sixth route from left (last route on right). Face climb, pockety, and the limestone is sharp (feet stick like glue). A little more technical than the other 5.9s in the area

name: Karen Carpenter
description: The lower section with reachy crux moves is slightly over-hanging and ends at a ledge maybe 18 feet up, after which the climbing is easier up to the anchor.  Surmounting the ledge can be awkward. Taller climbers might find this easier than 11a.

name: Tryin' to Be Sexy
description: Somewhat difficult start on a left hand pinch.  Move straight up the wall to a bulge.  Pulling the bulge is probably the hardest part.  Super easy moves after that to the chains.

name: The Boulder Lewis
description: Slabby arete climbing on decent rock. Sit start left hand on the arete and right in the two finger pocket.

name: Dead Friends
description: Most prominent boulder in the area, marginal rock quality but interesting moves.

name: Choss it Up
description: Start on Schizophrenic Calisthenics and arc your way towards the Talk it up anchors. You will begin traversing over the mini dihedral and mini roof towards anchors.

name: Punctuation Mark
description: Follows a line of slopey holds that get more desperate toward the top. Bottom part will be easier for taller climbers - top may be easier for shorter. Clipping holds are safe. Watch out for cacti.

name: Quest for Zest
description: Originally called Twyman's Folly.  Starts on the small dihedral at a diagonal down-facing thin crack.  Starts to the left of Rhetorick.  Climbs up and to two bolts and anchors.

name: Rhetorick
description: Sequence rich face climbing leads to a mini nose. Crux is pulling over this bulge. Hard moves on plenty of holds provide plenty of options. Juggy finish makes anchor clipping safe and satisfying.    Moves are possible for climbers of any height. We talked to a local guy who said a buddy of his (5' 2") can pull it.

name: Schizophrenic Calisthenics
description: Move up towards a dihedral from the ledge of Rhetorick Wall to the right of Talk it Up.  Instead of veering off to the left, as in Choss it Up, you move up and to the right towards the orange streak and onto juggy holds and a hueco.  At the top of the orange streak you move to the left and then up using a wide variety of interesting moves.  Definitely a great and accurate name!  Schizophrenic Calisthenics!

name: Summon
description: Start on Twyman's Folly (Quest for Zest), bypass the drilled pocket, and cut left at the steep setion onto Schizophrenic Calisthenics.

name: Talk It Up
description: Starts on a chossy face. As it gets steeper there's a ledge on the left, then a huge Texas-shaped flake left of the boltline and left of the anchors.

name: Traverse: R.O.S.
description: Start on Lessa (first route of Dead Cats) and move up to the part of the wall about 2/3rds of the way up with juggy holds and move left.   It crosses over all the routes on Rhetorick Wall. You clip the bolts above this band of jug filled rock on each route you cross.  Eventually you end up on Talk it Up where you head upwards to the anchors.  Belay TR from anchors from Talk it Up.

name: Antivenin
description: Right of Flakey Tigress, left of the two routes that go right and left around an obvious bulge at the top of the wall, heads to the anchors to the left of Moroccan Snake Charmer (left side of the bulge). Crux is getting off the ground through a low roof, then smooth sailing up to the top. There is some really poor quality rock to the left side- hang right for better rock even if it makes it a bit harder.

name: Blank Page
description: Start climb with 5.10 moves to get over the bulge at bottom. The moves are much easier above the bulge in the middle part of the route.  After clipping the second bolt, climb thru thin crux moves as the wall steepens below the anchors. A fun crux sequence requiring good foot work.

name: El Primero
description: The second route on the wall starting from the left, easier climbing down low leads to a crux 2/3 up the wall moving over and around a slight bulge.     Serpents Wall, L to R    Slither (5.6), El Primero (5.9), God Bless the IRS (5.9), Flakey Tigress (5.7), Antivenin (5.8) , Moroccan Snake Charmer (5.8) , Sidewinder (5.10c), KB5 (5.9), Blank Page (5.11).

name: Flakey Tigress
description: Route heads towards large flake near the top. Footwork is the key to this route.

name: God Bless the IRS
description: Starts in front of two trees, third route from the left on the wall. Head up to the opposite side of the slight bulge in the wall as El Primero. Crux comes when the wall goes vertical with good holds.

name: KB5
description: Second route from the right side of the wall, on the left side of Blank Page and right side of the Moroccan Snake Charmer/Sidewinder split.

name: Moraccan Snake Charmer (5.11b variation)
description: Same line as Moraccan Snake Charmer, however you start under the roof, hands on the right side of the horizontal crack. Crux is pulling the opening roof move. Truth be told...if your tired of doing the repetitive 5.8 grade on the wall...the do MSC variation before the original route. Or else, after pulling the roof, you'll convince yourself to not climb the rest of the route.

name: Moroccan Snake Charmer
description: Climbs up the left face of an arete feature.     Good quality slab-like climbing through well placed bolts.

name: Sidewinder
description: Tricky sequence with some hidden holds. Super fun crux with a really good heel hook!

name: Slither
description: Easy lead at the far left end of the wall. Probably the easiest route on the wall.     Serpents Wall, L to R    Slither (5.6), El Primero (5.9), God Bless the IRS (5.9), Flakey Tigress (5.7), Antivenin (5.8) , Moroccan Snake Charmer (5.8) , Sidewinder (5.10c), KB5 (5.9), Blank Page (5.11).

name: Blood of the Dead (sangre de los muertos)
description: If you are tall enough the crux is the pump. However if you are short there will be a few very difficult dynamic moves, one getting to the sharp flake by the second bolt and moving up off of it as well as the last move up to the horizontal below the roof and anchor.    This route has fin climbing but several of the holds are quite sharp.

name: Bolus
description: Some long moves on good holds leads up to the second bolt with a fixed draw. Make a move up to a glued edge and a long move off of it to an edge up and left. A handful more difficult moves leads to a jug horizontal below the anchor. One more long move takes you to the top.

name: Dark Energy
description: A route with a variety of holds and movement that is often overlooked in the Canyon.    Start traversing on tufa fins to the first underling and move upwards from here to the crux which is at the fourth bolt, involving a powerful move to a decent pocket.

name: High Anxiety
description: The route climbs through a tall slot with a skinny downward-pointing tree growing from it. It climbs cool formations with fun footwork. Good project for low 5.10 climbers, or hit it on your way out for a decent well-bolted burn.

name: Hyper Salivation
description: Climb Learning to Fly till you are in the middle of the crux but not through it, and make cruxy moves right passed a bolt to the start of the Bolus crux and follow this to the anchor. Clips the first 2 bolts of Learning to Fly then the bolt between Learning to Fly and Bolus and finally the 3rd and 4th bolts on Bolus. Very pumpy climbing, the hardest moves are linking the two routes plus you get the cruxes of both routes as well.

name: Learning to Crawl
description: Start on stalactites up to some jugs. Traverse right on some slopers then up to some pockets, one of which is drilled (if you skip the drilled one, give yourself and extra letter grade) Above the pockets some very slick slopers await before good holds finally appear about 5 feet short of the anchor.

name: Learning to Fly
description: Interesting moves on stalactites leads to a sloper and the second clip. A crimp and a mono leads to a jug. Some foot trickery makes the rest of the route more of a formality.

name: Let Them Eat Flake
description: Step to the right off of the boulder onto the face, work up to a jug sidepull. Then some difficult moves off of sidepulls with limited feet leads to the flake. Jugs take you out the steepening wall to an anchor over the lip.     Easiest to clean by top roping.

name: Love is a Fist
description: Undercling up to a drilled 2 finger threader, then a broken looking undercling and edge. A couple more holds that seem as though they would be better leads up to a couple of honking jugs. A hard to find hold leads up to the horizontal below the final roof. Make moves up and right to an anchor.    This route is very steep, so steep you'd be better off cleaning it on TR.

name: Mistaken Identity
description: This route has some very cool features.    Start out by getting yourself over the initial roof with some difficulty. Then work up into the corner formed by the wall and the orange feature, gaining some cool tuffas. Make moves left to stand on the grey "nose" and climb up on pockets to a loose looking flake and the final clip, good holds reside up and left.

name: No Recess
description: This route is pretty consistent from the time you leave the stalactite in the roof till you reach a jug by the last bolt.     Climb up on some scary tuffa features, some are cracked and hollow sounding. Make a big move to the lip and some bad holds. Work up onto the face with sharp holds and long moves. Take notice of the many rock scars and wonder if something is missing, based on the grade in the guide book (5.12c) it sure seems as if something is gone. Eventually gain a jug to the right of the last bolt. A few more moves on sharp holds takes one to the chain anchors.    Several of the bolts on this route are pretty badly rusted and water was dripping out of one of them, it did not really seem safe.

name: O.R.A.L (aka ORB)
description: Scramble up the rock mound used to start Snaggletufaed but immediately move to the right utilizing holds hidden in the white limestone to gain the right leaning vaginal slot. Utilize this to pull up through the overhang to a good jug just under the mini-roof. Finish on jugs.    The name stands for "Over Rated Asshole League" and ORB stands for "Over Rated Bullshit".

name: Pulmonary Choss
description: Short boulder problem near the first bolt on interesting rock quality that's quite sharp.   I had the impression of a chossy route before touching it, but in the end I didn't experience any holds breaking on me.

name: Snaggletufad
description: Starts on the rock mound left of Learning to Crawl. Grab a good incut flake to start which is a few feet to the right of an obvious stalactite, then move through a tough and reachy boulder problem to get through the bulge.

name: Super Cruiser
description: Crux is where you find it. Stalactites to start, slopers up to an OK rest above the second bolt from where you can clip the 3rd bolt. Crimpy campus moves lead up to slopers and eventually jugs below the anchor.

name: Telegraph Road
description: Steep start up to a couple of big moves to reach the traverse. Traverse right on good holds but with really high feet. Clipping the anchor is a bit funky. Even though the anchor hangs down below the roof rope drag on this is pretty bad if you have someone following which is really the only way to clean it because of the traversing nature.

name: .50 Cal
description: Linkup of Roman Orgy and 38 Special. After pulling the lip of the cave, find a wide stem to rest before tackling the 13c/V9 38 Special pitch. This is also a good opportunity to deal with the rope management issues.

name: 38 Special
description: 38 Special can be described simply as Roman Orgy's second pitch. It is climbed often as a separate pitch because the rope drag is very bad if linked with Roman Orgy (see .50 Cal). The recommended "approach" is to stick clip the first bolt (20ft above trail) and jug up from the ground.

name: Bariatric
