description: Starts on the huge jug that's just about right in the middle of the shelf in the back of sex cave and goes through a couple of mini tufas to a big tufa on that shelf. Climb straight to top out.

name: Body Wax
description: Classic Reimers route that ascends what seems like the steepest section of the sex cave.    Starts out with easy climbing till the second bolt. Use bomber underclings to set up for a huge throw to a jug. The contrived finish ends above the last bolt in the chossy cave.    Don't blow any of the clips as you will surely deck

name: Castle in the Sky
description: Castle in the Sky is a two pitch route that starts on Liposuction and traverses left across the Sex Cave headwall.  Pitch 1: 5.11+, 11 bolts. Start on Liposuction. Put a long sling on Lipo's 4th bolt (or skip) and then traverse left across Donkey Lady's 5th and Elephant Man's 6th bolt. The first set of anchors are under the small oak tree, on the large white stalactite.  Pitch 2: 5.12b, 9 bolts. Continue climbing left over the lip of Sex Cave, traversing across the wave-shaped headwall, crossing over 38 Special. Keep traversing left to end at a second set of anchors near the Sex Canyon routes.

name: Donkey Lady
description: Donkey Lady climbs the first two bolts of Elephant Man before exiting the cave on its own bolt line (between Liposuction and Elephant Man).

name: Elephant Man
description: Start out on the big hanging blob with the crack jug at the back. You can climb the first bit either feet or head first depending on your preference. Once you reach the hanging rib that Lipo climbs you are able to get your feet lower than you hands. Traverse across this under the roof to difficult moves getting to the 4th bolt. Turn the lip here (Roman Orgy continues further and Donkey Lady exits earlier)and make a couple of difficult moves onto the face, this is probably the crux. Trundle easily up the face to the roof. Make some big moves to get into a horizontal over the roof then scrunchy moves to turn the lip. This route offers up a plethora of toe hooking and knee barring jesery through the roof and getting onto the face.    Apparently this route used to feature a no hands rest stemming off of a big stalagtight just before the crux at the lip which would make the crux bit seem easier. Though there still is a kneebar to rest on and if you are better than me at using them (which would be most folks out there) it is still a pretty good rest.

name: Glamorous Pink Elephant
description: The crux is the fifth draw before entering the face.

name: Head
description: Hard pulls off of a left then a right 2 finger pocket that have been "helped" in some way, and a final hard move off of a sidepull undercling with the left hand to a juggy rail. Short and to the point.

name: Liposuction
description: Super classic route on great limestone tufas.  Start on the ledge at the front end of the cave and head out horizontally on huge tufas to the obvious large tufa in the cave.  From here start heading vertical.    Super pumpy.  good holds and good rests if you know how to get through it.

name: Lucky Strikes
description: Start up Head but break right after the first bolt and tackle the burly boulder problem on pinches finishing with either a cross to or a sword fighter gaston stab to a couple of jug slots, either way accuracy is of the utmost importance to success. After the jugs the holds start out small again but progressively get bigger till the jug horizontal and the final bolt. A few more moves up over the roof then jump off as there is no anchor.

name: Roman Orgy
description: This route climbs bolts 1-4 of  Elephant Man, then moves onto its own bolt line continuing along the roof. The route ends on 38th Special's first bolt at the lip of the cave.

name: Sex Grind
description: From John Hogge's book: A long traversing route. Climb Spider Grind and keep going on bolts on other routes to the last bolt of Lip-o-suction and finish on Lipo's anchors.(caution the unstable melon sized block/jug in the rest cave just left of Spider Grind's anchors--too textured to draw a big chalk "X" on it; also caution the moderate yet easy run-out to the anchors)

name: Spider Grind
description: Spider Grind traverses the lip of a roof just before the entrance to Sex Cave.  Climb straight up about 10 feet, clip the first bolt, and start traversing.  Traverse left through several bolts, moving quickly so you don't pump out on the jug-fest, and noting the utility of a good heel hook.  At traverse's end, climb straight up to anchor.    Fun and pumpy as hell.

name: Zen and The Art of Stick Clipping
description: This linkup starts on Liposuction or Elephant Man (Tao and The Art), climbs through Roman Orgy, mantles onto the headwall and finishes on Castle In The Sky. The rope measures 30m from the start to the chains and climbs through 19 bolts.

name: Deviance (aka 5.10 roof)
description: The left route on the light colored wall of Sunshine Roof. The opening moves on the dirty slab suck...but get past it on thin moves and the climbing gets fun quick. Make sure you have long draws or runners for bolts 3 and 4 to minimize drag. Big holds over the roof to pull...route is not as intimidating as it looks from below. On a sunny day, this wall gets hot! I see why its called sunshine roof...Wall faces SW and it's concave, it just traps heat! Great winter wall.

name: Double Take (aka. 5.9 Roof)
description: The route is pretty dirty with a few over grown plants making it difficult to get over to it on the ledge and making it a little more difficult to climb. The best part of the route is about half way up when you pull yourself around the corner with the potential for an awesome heel hook.

name: The Last Waltz
description: Start on the left end of the ledge as for Deviance 5.10 Roof. This route climbs through the first two bolts on the face of Deviance, then shoots off to the left on its own bolt line (five new bolts, then anchors). Traverse off into the sunset to a slabby finish.

name: Fearless
description: The start of Fearless is a little slick.  The first bolt can be clipped from the ground, and there is ground fall potential at the second bolt.  The crux is a mantle on a ledge just below the second bolt.  The final moves to the chains are also a little thin and committing.

name: Flea Circus
description: Start to the right of T-Roofic Detour (and T-Roofic Direct) off the right side of the ramp and under the low roof. Make your way to the drilled 4-finger slot, and pull the roof. Get to a short rest then execute a tricky little finish to the anchors.

name: Flea Detour
description: Pull the first roof on Flea Circus and then traverse left along the lip to T-Roofic’s 2nd bolt and finish T-Roofic. Fun and a little scary. Uses the first two bolts of Flea Circus and then bolt 2 of T-roofic and finish T-roofic.

name: Flea Spoofic
description: Start climb as for T-Roofic Detour. At bolt 3, traverse right to Flea Circus bolt 3. Finish on Flea Circus.

name: Grip Clip
description: Starts left of vertical stain in the dihedral. Left of "Fearless". Climbs up through three bolts then converges back onto Fearless' anchors. Tough sharp pockets with some tricky footwork and a good pump up through the third bolt.

name: Incredible Journey
description: Start on a ledge and head right under a roof. It stays overhanging through the end, though it may not appear so from the ground.

name: T-Roofic Detour
description: One of the best 5.10s at Reimer's.  Start on a tufa with good holds and climb to a ledge and the first bolt.  Step right onto the main face, and then continue up and right to the second bolt.  Head straight up from the second bolt and climb through the rocky overhangs.  There are a couple of sketchy moves just below the anchor, but they are not bad.  T-Roofic is a well bolted route - each clip protects a tough move.  You don't really realize how much the route overhangs until you rap.  Fun route, not to be missed.

name: T-Roofic Direct
description: This is a slightly harder/longer variation on T-Roofic Detour.  Both are fun, overhung, jug-hauls which test your endurance more than your technique.  You'll want a stick clip for the Direct variation.

name: T-Roofic's Big Brother
description: This bouldery route starts under the T-Roof left of T-Roofic. Boulder up left and then back a little right to the chains. Holds may have broken, choss?

name: Beelzebubba
description: Enjoy fun and powerful moves over a roof. If you're tall, you may be able to skip a gaston or sidepull.

name: The Bitch Club
description: Climb a blank face to a pumpy finish. The route may be least difficult with dynamic movements, including a left-handed dyno.

name: Crazy Straw
description: Crazy!

name: Curious George
description: The route traverses left under the large roof before pulling over the lip on large huecos to a short headwall just below the chains. The climbing itself has a variety of movement and will force a thin sequence along with a good pump. One of the longest routes at the ranch.

name: El Presidente
description: Scramble up onto deeply incut sidepulls and underclings.  Fire a few crux moves up on some non-ideal handholds (the usual sharp granulated crimper?-sloper?-dross you find at Reimers) to a big ledge for the second clip.  After the clip, hit the high nubbin-crimp on the left and then step up to the right-handed jug for the third clip and the finish.    Really nice motion all the way up... feels like a gym route!

name: Jimmy's Rig
description: Surprisingly fun route that doesn't see a lot of action. The bottom section is a bit chossy and breaking holds could make things more difficult.    Shares a starting first bolt and crux with Ralph's Rig. Stick clip the first bolt and navigate the crux boulder problem. Once established above the first bolt, trend up and slightly left through easier climbing.

name: Mikey Likes It
description: A fun tufa pull to start and then continue up on decent holds. Bolt 1 is sticking out from the rock so stickclip bolt 2.

name: Mother Buddha
description: This is a really short route, with only two bolts. But the first one is about as high as most second bolts, so you might want to stick it. You will probably find the holds to be rough on your hands.

name: Neurotica
description: The crux of this textbook "two-move wonder" comes straight off the start hold.  Make a reachy move up to a crimp with the left hand, get your feet up, and make one more long crank with the right to a sharp "pair of scissors" hold.  This move is a likely blood-letter if you go out of control.  If you stick it, enjoy 5.8 climbing to the top!

name: Nobody's Hero
description: Bolt 1 is above a boulder stack where the belayer can stand.

name: Ralph's Rig
description: Same start as Jimmy's rig but once you get your feet on the headwall and past the first crux traverse right to a big cave and then up. Interesting finish with some hidden holds. Harder ending than Jimmy's Rig.

name: Tit for Tom
description: Pull off of the ground on some interesting fractured cool looking rock to the left of the first bolt. Head up onto the slabby section and the second clip. Some horizontals take you to the 3rd bolt and a thin section going up to the anchors. Jugs to the right and left of the anchor.

name: Underdog
description: Climb up the mini tufas to the first bolt and then move right to pull the roof.  Last bolt moves back to the left.  Shares anchors with Antiqua (to the left of Underdog).  Felt hard for the grade until I figured out the beta.  Now it seems accurate for 5.11b.

name: About Face
description: Difficult, powerful crux right at the start with another tough section near the top.

name: All Hail Broke Loose
description: First crux starts from the deck. Boulder start from two head height jugs. Continues up into easier climbing with a good rest about 3/4 up the wall. Second crux is the sequence to the anchors on small pockets and sharp half-pad crimps.

name: Ant Encounters
description: Bottom starts on sharp, defined crimps. Crux is above bolt 4.

name: Apprehension
description: Route is located immediately left of Ant Encounters. For a face climb, this route has a variety of holds and features. Climb crimps, pockets, and jugs to a smooth face under a rounded ledge below the anchors.

name: Die Hard
description: Fun bottom start, climbs up to dihedral. Finishes right as the fun part begins.

name: Dude Where's My Hammer
description: Starts right of the hackberry tree at the base of the wall. High start leads to good holds up to the bulge. Pulling the bulge is the crux. I have a hard time saying this is 11b (feels like 10d/11a) but that's what it says in the book.     Get on this and boost that ego!

name: Grass Attack
description: Start on the right end of Pearl's low landing boulder, just left of the chossy low profile tufa. Bolt 1 is up and left of the choss area.

name: How to Counter Your Apprehension
description: Good warmup for this area. Start on Ant Encounters, but at first bolt head towards the left bolt line and finish in Apprehension.

name: Mona Pelagrosa
description: Arete near top is on.

name: Nudity
description: Fairly sustained/consistent, crux coming off of the diagonal traverse onto the vertical ascent to the anchors. First move from starting stance to a high right jug pocket may be the crux for shorter climbers. Handholds follow the diagonal ledge and are pretty solid. Right arm gets worked a lot harder than the left.

name: Pearl
description: Left side of War on Rugs wall, but not the right side of House of Pain (why are they separate walls i don't know, crankenstein too). Start on a boulder that usually has some cheat stacks. Pull through a small overhang crux, and then it's over. Quite enjoyable to the top. There may or may not be poison ivy on this route.

name: Sunday Mass
description: First bolt is below the diagonal right leaning ledge. Starts on cheater stack.

name: Teenage Parties
description: Loose holds at bottom. Rating maybe harder depending on what has broken.

name: War on Rugs
description: Start is possibly the crux.

name: Love Shack
description: Crux is right at the start on a one finger hold, then the holds get better. One of the prettiest boulders I've seen. It's all by itself right on the river.

name: Mad Beef
description: This is a variation using the 3 bolted routes.  Start Pocket Rocket and traverse the obvious rail system through Size Ain't Shit to the final throw on Love Shack.  Top out and Use the hook anchors to lower.  Super fun.

name: Pocket Rocket
description: Short but good route on the Worlds Greatest Boulder.  Starts on a sidepull and strong moves up to the obvious line running up right.  Move along the good holds to get to the crux.  Move off the good holds to a solid vertical slot with your left.  Pull hard into this to a small sloping dish with a good thumb-catch with your right and set high feet.  Pull off the dish up left to a sloping topout scramble.

name: Size Ain't Shit
description: 2 bolt route between Pocket Rocket and Love Shack.  Not a bad route if you go to the area, but not worth a trip by itself.

name: “Role Model” (name unknown)
description: Starts on good side-pull and easy climbing up and left through jugs and edges. Crux is pulling off a right slopey-edge to a left hand 2-3 finger pocket. From there cross right to another side-pull and easy top out. Down climb on the other side or if water is high and weather permits you can throw down your shoes and jump off.  If you know the name or FA the problem can be updated, I just wanted to ensure others would be able to know this problem.

name: Bulginator
description: This route has a couple of moves on it that are a lot of fun.  Getting the chains can be a bit tricky.

name: Clambering Kimberly
description: Short, steep climb up successive ledges with bomber hands and feet up to final balance move.

name: I Never Called You a Beast
description: Climb up to a bolt, mantle onto a ledge, and climb past one more bolt to the top.

name: Just Had To Trad Something
description: Not in the guidebook. The name comes from the rc.com page. A crack/corner route (no bolts) to the right of Zoey's Arete. I have not climbed it trad but have scrambled up it numerous times, especially as a quick exit at the end of the day; it is a bit loose and brushy, and it is not 5.5. More like 5.2 if even that, but out of respect to the person who posted this on rc.com, I am noting his grade even though I will suggest a different one.  However, as the name implies, there is very little trad in this area, so it might be worth it if you're tired of clipping bolts and want to place some gear. Passive gear recommended in the limestone here.  Up top there is not much for anchoring, so it might be better to clip the Zoey's Arete anchors, lower, and belay from below as the second follows and cleans.

name: Light Buzzyear
description: Balance moves with good feet and thinner holds -- for more fun avoid the left side until past the tree and ledge.

name: Maggies Farm
description: Climb past two bolts on big jugs to the anchors, passing a small recess on the right about 1/3 of the way up.  Easy solo if you want to set up top ropes on the other routes.

name: Sunny Fun
description: Last route on the right. Around the corner from Bulginator. The guidebook description is a little confusing and can have you thinking Bulginator is Sunny Fun.  The good thing is that most who come here don't seem to know this route exists, and it currently is not polished at all. The crux is the start.  The bad: tree branches will scratch your back as you lower. A 5.9 variation exists on the arete to the left and using only holds left of the bolt line, but overhanging brush usually covers this variation and makes it not worth trying. But if you find the right conditions (I have once, and the 5.9 is good, with the spice down low where you don't want to fall), it's worth it.  Note: the guidebook grade for this route is 5.7, but most think the start feels harder than that. I've given a suggested 5.8 and have heard others make a reasonable claim that it is 5.9. In any event, I like to note the guidebook grade in case the MP consensus is different.

name: Western Exposure
description: This variation uses the same bolts as Sunny Fun.  Keep hands left of the boltline on the arete and holds to the right of the arete.

name: Zoey's Arete
description: Fun climbing up an arete with great views.

name: Zoes First Step
description: A little more difficult than the other two climbs on Zoes Wall.  First Step starts easy on blocky terrain and then gets a little thinner at the top.  The crux is a long reach to a ledge near the top.

name: Breach
description: Start matched on the sloper rail. Dyno or campus up the ledge and beach whale over. Fun and not fun at the same time. Two move wonder. Feels way different than other stuff around here. Watch out for the cactus.  Spotters highly recommended.

name: Sea to Sky
description: Start on two juggy pockets. Very cool pockets through-out. Height-dependent. V2 if you can do the first two moves static. V3 or higher otherwise.  Spotters recommended.

name: Sweet-n-Low
description: Start kneebarred with hands free or on the underclings. Don't use the right ground boulder once you leave the kneebar. Cool surfboard.  This might be Stool Softener. Unsure.

name: 10% Kind of Orgasmic
description: Start on the roof at the far right end of the boulder before the small holds disappear. (end section of 90% Orgasmic)

name: 90% Organic
description: Start on the leftmost jugs. No info. Follow the topo line. Vote on the grade. Looks like a good line.

name: 90% Orgasmic
description: Starts on the leftmost jugs and traverses across an excellent rail with fun moves (and I suppose 10% crappy moves in the middle) and exiting on 10% Kind of Orgasmic. Might be stiff, unsure yet.  Beta spoiler

name: [Redacted]
description: Start with an undercling and climb over the roof straight up. Very reachy.

name: Bubbles the Monkey
description: Sit start on side-pulls. Tricky one move wonder, but super fun. Consider a spotter. Might be height-dependent.

name: Clint Eastwood
description: Sit start on the lowest jugs on the left side of the Wild West boulder. So spongey for limestone that you'll think you're at the Red!

name: Crackmatic
description: Corpse start in the back of the obvious crack. Aesthetic. V3 if you are Luke Bowman. Use gloves. Spotters a must at the lip.

name: Early Bird
description: Start on the lowest good pockets and crimps. Go straight up on more good pockets and crimps.

name: Fist Full of Rubble
description: Climb the right side of the Wild West boulder following the mini-roof. Vegetation up top.

name: The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly
description: Start on pockets beneath the boulder. Toe-hook the lip or toe in hard on a jib. Traverse on amazing holds out to some face crimps. Make the crux moves up the arete. Minus one-star because of how easy it is to dab the ground.  Beta spoiler

name: Love Joy
description: Start matched on the baseball jug. Very reachy, upgraded. Vote V1 if you think it's the original grade.

name: Love Joy Left Exit
description: Start as Love Joy, but exit left on the easier horn feature. Better moves instead of crimping on nothing on the direct line.

name: Mer
description: Start matched on the middle jug rail. Scrunchy moves.

name: Michael Jackson
description: Start on pockets 3 feet to the right of the arete. Move left and up. Awesome gymnastic moves. Get on it.  Originally graded V2, but I think it's harder than what Tommy graded it. I just gave it a slash grade. Send it and vote on the grade.  Beta spoiler

name: The Pink Hole
description: Traverse on amazing pockets to some dire moves at the end.

name: Reggaejunkiejew
description: Climb straight up on juggy terrain.

name: Screwdriver/Mantis Style
description: Start several feet left of Crackmatic on a left hand 2-finger pocket and a right-hand chicken head. Traverse right by stabbing at small but deep pockets and top out. I forgot to take a photo of this one, so take one and upload here and I will embed it.

name: The Worm
description: Start hands matched on the arete and a left heel-hook. Climb up and right through the dihedral. Slithery moves.

name: [Redacted]
description: Start with a right hand crimp and throw to the slopers. No additional info.

name: Anthem
description: Start on side-pull pockets. Reachy McSlabby.

name: Atlas Hugged
description: Start on two low pockets and work up and left. Good wide moves, much less scrunchy than Atlas Shrugged. My own variation of Atlas, which I (no bias, of course, think is more fun.)

name: Atlas Shrugged
description: Start left hand crimp slot, right hand pinch block, right foot heel-hook. Make some wingspan moves or scrunched moves.

name: Autobot
description: Start on low jugs. Climb the left side of the arete.

name: Cobra Commander
description: Start on the diagonal rail towards the left of the boulder.

name: Deader The Better
description: Corpse start. Lay down and lay back the offwidth crack.

name: Decepticon
description: Start on two low pinches from right of the arete 2 feet right of Autobot. Merge left into Autobot once above the flake. Adds a tough core heavy crux at the bottom.  Potential hard problem variation exiting right.

name: Destro
description: Start near another diagonal rail and pocket. Tops out just below a small tree and two stacked rocks.

name: Don't Polk Me
description: Far right of the Dead Presidents. Climb straight up and past what could be a right hand sidepull.

name: Evelyn
description: Climb the offwidth of Transformers. Funky moves. Easy warmup to lap all 3 problems here.

name: Galvatron
description: Start holds might be a crux for shorties. No intermediates for them either. Otherwise, small pockets/pinchy goodness.

name: Major Bludd
description: Right most problem. Sloper fest.

name: Megatron
description: Start on low pockets below the obvious chicken head. Must do of this boulder, especially if you are a short static climber.  Beta spoiler Beta

name: Millard Feelmore
description: Start right of the blank spot on of Dead Presidents boulder. Climb straight up and out.

name: More Than Meets the Thigh
description: Start with two crimps, reach for small shallow right hand pocket. Move left and top out on a sloper.

name: Mr. Gill
description: Start on the undercling flake same as My Wooter. Climb directly up. Easy finish.

name: My Wooter Hurts
description: Start on the undercling flake and hand traverse the cool seam. Exit up when footholds appear.

name: Nixon's Vixon
description: No info. Follow the topo.

name: Optimus Climb
description: Start on pockets 3 feet to the right of the arete. Move left and up. Easy warmup to lap all 3 problems here.

name: Real Tools for Real Kids
description: Traverse the entire Dead Presidents from as far right as possible of the jug rail. Lay back the crack to finish. No known ascents. Suggested V7 by original developer.

name: Shockwave
description: Start on matching pockets and go up and just the slightest right. Sharp.

name: Soul Food
description: Start on the low rail and climb directly up. Friendly jugs. Would be a ⭐⭐⭐ V0 if not for the lack of a landing. Definitely use spotters if you are a newbie.

name: Soundwave
description: I lost my notes on this one, but I remember it wasn't as fun as the rest of the problems on this boulder. Some slopey seams I believe.

name: Taft Dodger
description: Right of the crack, start in the hole and climb through the thin stuff.

name: Witwicky
description: Start starting on the low platform. Follow the jugs up. Stay off the choss to the left. Easy warmup to lap all 3 problems here.

name: Wooter Erect
description: Start directly below the exit of My Wooter Hurts just left of Atlas Shrugged. Climb straight up. Original grade said V0. Seems unlikely. Let me know if you find V0 beta.

name: Great Hall
description: Easy climb with obvious holds all the way up.

name: Bites the Dust
description: Marked by solid starting holds and a good 3 finger pocket.  Every hold after the 3 finger pocket should be treated with suspicion, especially the stuff on the top-out shelf which could potentially come off in large chunks.  Water levels vary, but the landing zone is about 6-7 feet deep during rainy season.

name: Ol' St. Ed's
description: Gain the first ledge using a solid outcropping of rock.  good pockets to the next ledge, then topout

name: Waterfa11
description: Solid starting ledge to two good holds sticking out of the wall.  Your next options include a dirty left sloper with some slightly better grip further back, and/or a chossy right pinch.  There is a thin but solid layback crack in the roof, and a good ledge with a struggly top out.

name: Bird
description: Start anywhere directly below the window sill. There is a good, obvious low ledge for your left foot and several options to crimp with both hands. Work your way straight up and top out by matching on the first window sill. To get down, drop straight onto a crash pad. The top out isn't too high off the ground so no worries there. Really fun slab problem and great for beginners!

name: Cops
description: Start by stepping up on the concrete slab in front of the black fence. Pull on the arete (edge of the building) with the left hand, and step on the obvious ledge with your right foot. Reaching out pretty far with the right hand you'll find a decent crimp. Match the left foot next to the right on the ledge and start the traverse from there using whatever crimps and footholds you can find. Move to the right all the way to the other side of the wall. Finish by matching on the marked crimp as seen in the picture. The problem is really fun and trickier than I expected it to be!

name: Balancing Act
description: Start on two small shallow pockets just at the over hang. Follow the small set of hands up and right to get into the slight wave section. Go towards the under-cling and then top out.

name: Burro Trail
description: Start on the left wall at the bottom layer and move up immediately to the fourth layer and then traverse right along the layers of limestone. continue right approximately 50-60 ft.

name: Dehydrate
description: This Route is decent and is likely easier than the V4 grade. The top doesn't have the best hands but you are able to transition into the slight slab section to start topping out. this is more of a head game since it goes up the highest part of the boulder and you're slightly over hung moving up the arete.

name: Donkey Ears
description: This is on the Burro Boulder. This is a stand start and is a great beginner climb it's a fun confidence builder and straight forward climb. unfortunately it's short. Start at the small ledge (two small quarts knobs are also at the small ledge, hence donkey ears) almost half way up the boulder. Move up and left to the obvious leaning edge and top out.

name: Donkey Grip
description: This shares start holds for Mules Way follow arete up and left through some okay holds to eventually find easier pockets to make the top out. Cold weather makes it feel easier since two holds are utilized by the entire hand and friction makes it feel better.

name: Donkey's Crack
description: Sit start on the obvious leaning crack the hard part is standing then keeping balance while you move through the very very shallow crack to meet up with Donkey Ears

name: Easter Bunny
description: Stand start on large large hold move up the arete. Hardest part is getting good feet to get started due to the slight over hang.

name: Holey Ghost
description: Sit start on obvious hueco on the small grounded boulder in the Balance Boulder Area. Make four moves to top out this little guy.

name: Hydrate
description: Hydrate V3/4 has some decent crimps to start. Just need to pull hard and move up the obvious cracks. The start and the top make this V3 it's a bit slick at the top otherwise a decent climb.

name: I need more Donkeys
description: Just below the edge of the boulder face located in the whiter section are two/five pockets (depending if you start facing in or out). Very hard feet to find and difficult to get a good press between the toes. If you can snag the start position it's home free. Enjoy the semi desperate move that leads into the Balancing Act route.

name: Mules way
description: The Crux on this climb is getting out of the start. The holds at the bottom are good yet the angel is steep. Good foot work can set you up to get in the wave and move towards a suspect knob of quartz then top out. It's all rather sharp.

name: Ripple Effect
description: This was a fun slab very good feet and hands. Good landing with the pad route goes right up the middle of the slab. It's a head game for sure.

name: Dog 2
description: First bolt is very high, and the climb to it is sketchy at best.

name: Da Vinci's Toothbrush
description: Start compressed on a roof feature with a good left heel hook.  Core up and pop for a jug pinch at the lip.  Finish up good holds to a sharp top out.  The low angle rock below the horizontal crack is off for feet.    Head east and down climb.  Careful not to kick any rocks down when walking to the descent.

name: Michelangelo's Beanbag
description: Start on a good jug/pinch and make a long move to a decent lip hold.  Using a cool left toehook gain the sloping lip then a good jug.  Finish straight up on sharp limestone.    Head east to downclimb.  careful not to kick rocks down when walking to the downclimb.

name: Cabeza de Cabrito
description: On the north side of the Third World arch there is a climb that starts on good pocket jugs and climbs left through slick slopers.      It is an unfinished project but felt around V5 or V6.

name: Dirty Dylan
description: This is a party trick climb.    Run and jump to the right of The Womb.  If you want another fun challenge slamdunk the lip of The Womb.

name: Third World
description: Start with a right hand under the roof on a good hold and left hand on the south face high in a positive shallow crack.  Toss a high left heel and mantle out.    A great low start dubbed "The Story of the third world" is possible but we ran out of time and the climb is in full afternoon sun.

name: The Womb
description: Although many people have probably climbed this feature it is worth noting here.    Chimney climb up the slick opening through a tight hole in the top.

name: Another Tinaja
description: Start on the undercling of Dust-in Tinaja and cross right hand to the good left pocket.  Set up and make a big move to the lip.    A fun variation.

name: Buda Slapper
description: Start low beneath the sharp prow with a slick right hand sloper and a low left hand sidepull/undercling.  Make a left hand move to a slimper with a tiny thread through pocket above it then slap your way up the prow to better holds.  The foot holds are all there.

name: Come and Take It
description: Stand start with a great jug and climb up through incut holds.

name: Come and Take It Sideways
description: Start the same as Come and Take It but traverse right and topout using a toehook.

name: Dirty Ernie
description: Start standing with hands on the flake and climb up and left.

name: Dust-in Tinaja
description: Start sitting with a good undercling.  reach two good pockets then execute a big left hand cross to a jug pocket.  Top out straight up through slick holds.

name: Government Shutdown
description: Starts on a decent right hand undercling and a small left hand side pull crimp (at chest level).  Low feet. Big move up and left to the good crimp with the thumb catch, drop knee bicycle move to keep the feet on, right hand up to a sharp crimp, out left to a good hold, bump to the jug, top out straight up on the finish of Come and Take It Sideways.

name: Slip N Slide
description: SDS on slick sloper.  Make a few moves right to better holds then the top.

name: Crowd Pleaser
description: This boulder problem is a beautiful undercling to layback crack from a stand start. Pulling around the corner is the crux.

name: Dab Factor
description: Start low and climb out of the hole to a balanct top out.

name: Fear Factor
description: A fantastic climb on the slightly overhanging south face of the the Factor Boulder.  Start sitting on a boulder with a good right hand gaston and iron cross reach to a sloped rail.  A tough and match leads to the top.  A scary fall into a hole requires several pads.

name: Free Parking
description: A nice warm up style boulder problem on the obvious north face of the boulder near the small parking spot.

name: Fun Factor
description: Start on the high sloper and top out.    A low project is probable.

name: Gadiator
description: This is the obvious sit start to Crowd Pleaser.  Start deep in the cave and climb out using an aggressive heel hook without dabbing on the spike at your back.

name: Intersection
description: Start same as Thin Line, but where the crack splits, move right into the twin cracks.

name: MD 20/20
description: This lowball boulder starts sitting low with opposing holds.  Slap up a bit then turn the lip through crimps.  A higher start makes this in the V2 range.

name: Mine Shaft
description: Start same as Thin Line and Intersection.  Move right and climb the finger crack that turns into a chimney.

name: Show Stopper
description: On the Crowd Pleaser Boulder.  Using the low angle  boulder for feet grab a left hand crimp and reach right to a bomber finger lock.  Top out.  A bit scary.

name: Sun Ripe
description: Start on the left of the sloped rail formed by the crack and traverse up and right to easier terrain.

name: Thin Line
description: Climb the crack that splits right of the lichen.

name: Two on the vine
description: Start low and climb up through a sloper to a long reach to the lip.

name: Unripe
description: Climb the prow on the north side of the Ripe Boulder.  Start crouched with small crimps.  Make a few tough moves to good head height full pad crimps.  Make a big move to the sloper.    V2 from the high crimps,

name: Upper Deck
description: Overhanging layback flake on the east corner of the Upper Deck Boulder.  A bit dirty but fun.

name: Vine Ripe
description: Climb the rail on the west side of the Ripe Boulder.

name: Crowd Pleaser
description: This boulder problem is a beautiful undercling to layback crack from a stand start. Pulling around the corner is the crux.

name: Gladiator (aka The Impaler)
description: This is the obvious sit start to Crowd Pleaser. Start deep in the cave and climb out using an aggressive heel hook without dabbing on the spike at your back. Would be a classic if that spike was gone.

name: Show Stopper
description: On the Crowd Pleaser Boulder. Using the low angle boulder for feet grab a left hand crimp and reach right to a bomber finger lock. Top out. A bit scary.

name: Dab Factor
description: Start low and climb out of the hole to a balanct top out.

name: Fear Factor
description: A fantastic climb on the slightly overhanging south face of the the Factor Boulder. Start sitting on a boulder with a good right hand gaston and iron cross reach to a sloped rail. A tough and match leads to the top. A scary fall into a hole requires several pads.

name: Fun Factor
description: Start on the high sloper and top out.     A low project is probable.

name: Pop a squat
description: SDS on a boulder with hands on the horizontal crimp rail. Climb up!

name: Two on the Vine
description: Start low and climb up through a sloper to a long reach to the lip.

name: Black Box
description: SDS on the NE corner of the Grapevine Boulder.  Right hand low on the right corner left hand on the edge near the crack.  Pull up and compress out and up.

name: El Jefe
description: SDS on the SE corner of the Grapevine Boulder and pull some long moves to gain the top.

name: Grapevine
description: Climb the slabby north face of the Grapevine Boulder through cool slot holds.  A bit tall.

name: Night Train
description: Start high on sloper dishes, get your feet on, and pop for a rounded hold.  Top out.

name: MD 20/20
description: This lowball boulder starts sitting low with opposing holds. Slap up a bit then turn the lip through crimps. A higher start makes this in the V2 range.

name: Cooper's Booty
description: Stand start with hands on a low flake and move to a crimp on the edge of the overhang. Reach up to a sloper, cut the feet, get the right leg up on top of the overhang, and top out.

name: Dorsal Fin
description: A nice warm up style boulder problem on the obvious north face of the boulder near the small parking spot.

name: Free Parking
description: Start on the boulder on climbers right of the Dorsal Fin boulder.  Execute a fun reach move and top it out.

name: A Lil Ripe
description: Climb the bulge on the west corner of the little ripe boulder

name: Sun Ripe
description: Start on the left of the sloped rail formed by the crack and traverse up and right to easier terrain.

name: Unripe
description: Climb the prow on the north side of the Ripe Boulder. Start crouched with small crimps. Make a few tough moves to good head height full pad crimps. Make a big move to the sloper.     V2 from the high crimps,

name: Vine Ripe
description: Climb the rail on the west side of the Ripe Boulder.

name: Warmup Traverse
description: Traverse the lip of the small boulder near the big Ripe Boulder

name: Upper Deck
description: Overhanging layback flake on the east corner of the Upper Deck Boulder. A bit dirty but fun.

name: Armored-Dillo
description: This is a fairly straight forward climb. It has very smooth holds but the pockets are deep and the angel starts off nice. Good landing for the pads.

name: Heart Beat
description: I would of graded this lower than V5 but the start holds are rather small and the balance required to get on the boulder was unique so I felt the grade was appropriate.   Also the Holds are Super Slick though there are rather deep (two pad) crimps along the ridge. Lastly the overhanging nature of this climb gave it the rating since the feet are hard to utilize and then top out with very little feet to work with. Currently has a wonderful landing zone that is level.

name: Muad'dib
description: This is an obvious ramp on the Dune boulder. This is the down climb/Veasy climb for the boulder plenty of other lines on the slab face.This is a decent sized boulder that has a very large obvious 20inch ramp that starts at about hip height (3~ft)Pull the ledge and then step up the short safe ramp.

name: 30 Seconds To Mexico
description: Route starts on Shitfaced and Barefoot as a sitting start. Instead of topping out on Barefoot and Shitfaced throw from the horizontal pockets to the two finger pocket on the arete. Continue up the arete before topping out directly above the start hold.

name: Barefoot and shitfaced
description: Start with hands matched on the horizontal rail. Climb left, then up to the finish.

name: Big Man on Campus
description: Start in a knee bar on the bottom of the arête. Climb up and left to the horizontal line of pockets. Follow the pockets until foot holds disappear. Campus the final moves to the finish.

name: Dynamic Duo
description: Start with a two hand under clings and traverse right and around the arete. climb up till you see a right-hand crimp, allowing you to reach around the corner and grab the good jug.  top out with a pull-up/dyno (no good feet).

name: Project
description: Start in a kneebar, then follow the arête up.

name: Shitfaced and Barefoot
description: Start with hands matched on the tail, make moves up to the horizontal line of pockets, then finish on barefoot and shitfaced.

name: Grimer's Slab
description: Shore up your kayak/canoe on the rock right below the boulder. The route I took went straight up the middle. At the start, there's a ledge to post up on. After a little hop to get up on the first foothold, the first 12-15 feet are very juggy - easy holds and plenty of feet space. About 15 feet up, the easy jugs run out, and you are left with a crack about 3 ft below the top. Place your fingers within the crack, and hike your right foot up and get a solid footing in the hold to your right. From here, you can lift up and grab the top, which is a high angle and easy to grab. Place your left foot in the small hold to the left, and use that to press up and top out. Climb down on the right side - but watch out for the thorns.  Be warned with this route - it's a pretty high boulder, and the water below is only about 3 feet deep with rocks on either side. A fall could potentially be pretty brutal. It's jumpable if you absolutely need to - but I HIGHLY recommend topping out and walking down around the boulder.

name: Crack in the Back Project
description: This is the obvious small finger crack in the back of the right facing, left angling dihedral. Unknown if anyone has tried this before. Looks to be a good climb.

name: Graffiti Boulder
description: Obvious where the name comes from. Many moderate traverse and vertical problems. The cracks at the right end are great for beginners.

name: Risky Top-Out Projects
description: This face has been bouldered up just beneath the top outs. The top out has some serious choss. Dangerous.

name: Traverse Boulder
description: Low angle slab boulder. Popular to traverse this, although there are a few vertical problems. All are easy/unnamed.

name: The Cave
description: Small roof problems left of 'More Holes.'

name: Cheap and Easy
description: Wall has countless traverse and vertical problems. Fun bouldering, can be TR

name: Holes
description: Classic climb through huge holes and sinker jugs. Has TR anchors and is often bouldered.

name: Holes Arete
description: Easy highball. Climb the arete right of holes. Connect pockets and shelves for a fun climb.

name: All Knuckles and Elbows
description: Hidden cavern behind main maze canyon.Small crimps on overhung section of wall.

name: Big Brother
description: Climbs layback crack on left. Can TR.

name: Brownwood Boys
description: Start on undercut erete. Grab poor sidepulls and reach up to unique traingle hold. Top is covered with poison  ivy/cactus. Would need cleaned before attempting.

name: Choss Boss
description: Follow sketchy laybacks and slopers on choss.

name: Choss Direct
description: Start sitting fully under overhang. Move up through crimps and slopers

name: Choss Gold
description: Follow right lip of overhang at end of maze. Start sitting on crimps. Move right and finish on face of 'Warm up Wall' and 'Tall Cool.'

name: Chossaneering
description: Start on 'Choss Gold' and traverses overhang low and finishes on 'Choss Boss.' Good luck.

name: Confused
description: Climb the tricky slab/face. Move through slopers and shouldery moves

name: Confused Arete
description: Climb the arete that is directly across from "Tall Cool Blue One". Fun, easy climb. Makes for a good highball warmup. Can be TR'd.

name: Crappiest Bolt Job Ever
description: Starts with decent pockets/flakes. Move up to sloper then catch jugs on a short but fun climb.

name: Fin
description: Start laying back on mini dihedral. Top out through slopers.

name: The Last Step is a Doozy
description: Climb the left side of the arete at the bottom of the stairs.

name: Little Brother
description: Climbs right crack until gone. Crux is shouldery moves to sloper, sidepull, and small finger pocket. Big reach for the top of the small right crack and top of problem.

name: Slab TR 3
description: Climb the short arete/slab on this boulder.

name: The Spread
description: Start on crack for 'Little Brother' and then traverse right into 'Fin' through crimps. Finish up with 'Fin.'

name: Tall Cool Blue One
description: Crimpy vertical face with fun moves and a relatively high crux. Topout on jugs. Can be toproped from bolted anchors if it seems too high to boulder.

name: Welcome
description: Climb the face midway down the stairs.

name: Mission Direct
description: Climb the slab in the center of the face without using the aretes.

name: Mission Enough
description: Climb the left arete on the park side of the main Trifecta boulder.

name: Mission Impossible
description: Climb the left arete of the lake side of the main Trifecta Boulder.

name: Mission Possible
description: Climb the crack that runs parallel below the left arete (which is Mission Enough) without using the arete.

name: Tomcat
description: Climb the right arete on the park side of the main Trifecta Boulder.

name: Ground Control
description: Fun limestone climb that starts with a few long reaches but with a large ledge halfway as a resting point. Crux is last several feet before reaching the anchors.    See campeagle.org for guidebook description

name: Stickies
description: Simple short climb utilizing mostly ledges.

name: Cave Crawl
description: In the cave below the rappel deck. Really cool holes in the ceiling of the cave lead to crux roof pull and easy face to top out.

name: Dvatsat
description: This is the twentieth route bolted at Camp Eagle.  This climb starts on a slopely ledge and then moves up into solid holds.  Consistent moves and difficulty throughout.

name: Red October
description: Like the Russian behemoth, this climb is strong out of the gate but much quieter in the finish.  The crux is the very difficult start.  An easier variation is to start on the climb Dvatsat just to the north and traverse across the slopey ledge to the climb.  The traverse has an intermediate bolt placed between the two climbs for extra safety.

name: Rise Over Run
description: A great unique climb that starts at the river and finishes beneath the power pole.  Start is very difficult, but with two close bolts to assist ascent if necessary.  The rest of the climb uses good holds and has a substantial rest section in the middle if needed.

name: Scooby Snacks
description: A moderate climb with maintained 5.8 climbing.

name: Unnamed
description: Just like Scooby snacks, only a little harder

name: Unnamed 5.10
description: Overhung most of the way, with jugs. Watch out for loose rock. Bad rope drag, and a few bolts are covered by plants that will stick to your clothes. Otherwise, a really fun climb.

name: The Lumberjack
description: Traverse problem that follows the obvious rail into the offwidth.

name: Pocket Protector
description: Stand start on the decent jug. Use the pockets to top out up and left into the cave. Downclimb to the left.

name: Pocket Protector Low
description: Low start to Pocket Protector. Start on the flat bar below the mini roof and make a big reach for the starting hold. Finish Pocket Protector.

name: Circus Boy
description: Fun short climb to the left of the Artificial Climb.  Pretty straightforward.

name: Crack the Cranium
description: Easy 5.8 with good holds and many ledges.

name: The Dihedral
description: Outstanding climb that starts with a very obvious dihedral before pulling an interesting roof that requires good foot work.

name: The Gutenberg Press
description: Starting just below this shallow left facing dihedral, move up and it will open up for you.

name: Panjshir
description: The pocketed start is the crux followed by an easy finish from a large ledge to the anchors.

name: Say No to Jimmy
description: Another face climb that ends with a tremendous overhang.

name: Snot Scary
description: Begins with touch technical section with small pockets and continues into easy ledges before a pumpy overhanging finale.

name: Star
description: This route should be a standard for every 5.9 limestone sport route. It is the classic Camp Eagle warmup that every climber at camp must be able to do when they start lead climbing on their own.  Start on a shelf then go up from a bomber side pull to good holds and end with a tricky finish with moderate feet. The first big hold is uber polished for good reason.

name: Stump the Gump
description: Easy ledge filled climb. Following the bolt line delivers the intended experience.

name: Tendon Tearor
description: This tweakie little climb will test your tendon toughness with its small pockets.

name: Timbo The Bimbo
description: Bouldery start with easy climbing that gets harder as you go up. Finish with a few boulder moves.

name: Virginia Creeper
description: A really short and really fun route. The crux is a dyno to a sloper followed by a razor sharp two finger pocket and then two bad crimps to clip from. The falls really aren't THAT terrible but falling at the crux causes a pretty good whipper.

name: Warm Up
description: Nice face climb up to a roof with long reaches.  Crux is pulling the roof.

name: Warm Up ( 5.9 )
description: To the right of Timbo the Bimbo. This is the lower half of Warm up that doesn't pull the roof. There are anchors below the roof to rappel on. A very bouldery start to some nice technical face climbing.

name: Buffet Line
description: Bouldery start with a dyno right out of the gate, and into a traverse with small pockets and ledges, and then up.

name: Ambiguity
description: The name is a play on words, as this climb is very straightforward.  Short but consistent. Perfect for someone new to sport climbing.

name: Cowboy
description: One of the most enjoyable climbs at Camp, the route is  overhanging with solid holds. Another instant classic.

name: The Cruxtibles
description: Tough start on small pockets through challenging overhang and into a technical balancy face.  Each section of this climb is unique and presents its own challenges.

name: End of the Line
description: On the very end of the sherpa where the cable starts to go away from the wall. The route is on the ledge above the cable next to the off width crack.

name: Hammerhead
description: This climb begins on the route No Guts No Glory and then heads right up and over a small roof.  The crux is the thin technical upper face.

name: Hemisphere
description: Tall climb that follows the edge of an overhang and moves up into a tall smooth face.  Great exposure and views of the river and cliffs.

name: No Guts No Glory
description: A tall, fun, sustained climb that will challenge those used to shorter lengths and obviously chalked holds.  Super fun.

name: Plumbline
description: Follow the incredibly straight line of bolts up a technical face with good holds. Easy climbing but can be a bit technical at times but once you figure out the beta it becomes easier. Good holds and great movement make this route one of the better ones at Camp Eagle.

name: Pump Suazy
description: climb up 10 feet, then traverse left around ceiling with bad feet, traverse right and finish by mantling on a ledge with some good crimps

name: Rodeo
description: Face climb followed by slight traverse to the right and up to the top.

name: Turtle Shell
description: Small boulder directly under No Guts No Glory. Traverse the crimps made of shells from left to right. End with a fun heel hook thats hard for short people.

name: Yee-Haw
description: Fun and sustained climb up and over a small overhang.

name: walk-it
description: work your way up wocket traversing to the right using the rounded rail for feet- then traverse left to top out

name: Wocket's Pockets
description: This route climbs the middle of the slabby backside of wocket boulder- lots of good 2-3 finger pockets- big move to finish where the pockets run out at the end off the route- descend to the left-

name: Bane
description: Start with your left hand on the edge of the boulder and your right on a chest-high crimp- throw for a small ledge that must be matched upon (crux) and enjoy!

name: Downclimb
description: Downclimb from Bane boulder. Slabby- but with good quality rock and positive holds!

name: Path of the Tempted
description: While facing Temptation Slab, follow the upward/right angling arete lip (where the downclimb and “temptation” join) to the top of the boulder, then top out.

name: Temptation
description: Project- very thin, very tall vertical slab. you'll be tempted to use the flakes to the left and edge of the boulder to the right- dont-

name: President's Profile
description: Climb the arete that looks like GW's face- stay mainly to the left of the arete but use jugs on the right side to finish the problem.

name: Jammit
description: A wonderful pocket-ed problem- SDS on a low jug (left hand) and an odd pocket (right)- throw for a high pocket- then, either use a mono to gain the boulder's lip, or make a big move to a hidden jug (right hand)- awkward topout on a large sloper hold-

name: Bass a'la Pecos
description: Slabby, pocketed limestone.

name: Butt Crack
description: The bottom of the route is slabby and thin.  The route has a couple difficult transitional moves into the crack.  The crack itself is a sharp, positive hand crack that lends itself well to layback moves.

name: Candyland
description: Great moderate route surrounded by other moderate climbs.

name: Chutes and Ladders
description: Fun climb if you don't mind the hollow sounding flake. Surrounded by other moderate climbs on the Candy Land wall.

name: Corner
description: Dihedral climb with crux up high in the pockety section.

name: Crocodile Tears
description: Layback moves to pockets, pinches, and slopers, with pseudo crack moves. All on slight slab.

name: Gator McKlusky
description: Slabby, pocketed limestone

name: Half Monty
description: Slabby limestone with large pockets and huecos.

name: Hi-Ho Cherrio
description: Great moderate route surrounded by other moderate climbs.

name: Perch Jerk
description: Slabby, pocketed limestone with a horizontal crack near the top.  Lighter belayers should belay from sloped ledge below first clip.

name: The River
description: An aesthetic route that follows a dihedral crack through a hueco filled section and finishes on a small roof pull.

name: Sorry
description: Fun starting moves.

name: Ten-D-Nitis
description: This route seems harder and headier than it should for the grade.  Bolts feel like they are placed in the middle of cruxes.

name: Unnamed  3
description: A technical route with great moves.

name: Wally Gator
description: Climb starts on slab and follows a crack system.  It’s the left most climb in gator farm, on the left side of the large boulder.

name: Crackalicious
description: The name says it all, it's a popular climb for a reason.

name: Over Under Sideways Down
description: An interesting crack/face climb. There is a 10 variation the goes left and up the face near the beginning of the roof crack (where the large flake ends), you should be able to see a couple bolts.

name: Piranha
description: Crux is after the large ledge to the smaller ledge. There's a bush in the way that makes the grade seem a lot more difficult.

name: Shake n Flake
description: Some chirping within the flake that might make the climb a little harder if you have a fear of bats. There are some crimps, sidepulls off the flake, and pumpy moves towards the end, which makes it a fun route with a variety of moves. Probably a 10-, but listed as a 10+ in the route map.

name: Sugar
description: Adventure style climb through sharp plants. Cruxes are at the start (for shorter climbers) and near the top.

name: Turtle Lasso
description: Start on the slab skirt and clip the belayers bolt. Make your way on to a questionable flake for the second bolt. Good, slightly hidden pockets on slab make up the remaining bolts. Move right through the small crack and go up over the ledge for the chains.

name: Mister Access
description: A relatively tiring climb if you are leaving the Weir Dam area via Mister Access and are climbing with your packs. Chain bolts at top are commonly used to rappel into the Weir Dam area as well.

name: Swamp Monkey
description: A technical but rewarding climb. It probably goes at harder than a 5.8+ and can be heady at times, especially when going for the anchors.

name: Tomahawk
description: This is the most striking line on the wall. An arete  juts out from the rock, festooned with huecos and pockets. Climb a steep, slabby opening move and grab good holds to get on the arete. Rests can be had at various ledges.

name: Wampum
description: A deceptively difficult roof hits you on the outset. Belay clipped into the lowest bolt, or consider moving down lower on the steep rock slope. Don't blow the first clip, as a fall would be bad for the ankles. Surmount the roof and pull small holds until the angle flattens out on the way to the anchors.

name: Bear Bones
description: This is a fantastic climb to the left of White Trash (5.12a). The rocky slope is close enough to pad it out so a rope is not necessary. It is a long climb for a boulder problem and there is one long move that felt in the 5.11+ range.  Start standing at the opening of a deep cave and climb out on good holds and top out.  Note: I named it "Bear Bones" because it is better than "unknown" change it if you want. -Ross

name: Bear Paw (aka Surfing Sit Start)
description: Sit start with hands in the horizontal crack. Move up towards the large tufa then make one more reach to a jug to finish the problem. The tufa is usually wet on the bottom, but positive features make the hold usable in damp conditions. Makes for a great full value start to Surfing in San Antonio.    I'm assuming this is a first ascent since there was no chalk prior to the tufa, but please let me know if I was incorrect and I'll update the FA info.

name: Fisher King
description: Crimpy start to jugs, then crux boulder problem in the roof. Good moves on solid stone.

name: Genetic Plasm
description: Jug pulling to a nice little finishing crux pulling the final lip.

name: Surfing in San Antonio
description: Good route, starts in the middle of the cave and exits straight out the roof crack in the middle of the roof, has a small roof halfway up

name: Thieving Texas Scum
description: Starts deep in the cave and climbs up to a few huecos in the roof where you can cop a couple uncomfortable bat hangs which leads you to the crux of the route at the very end.

name: Undertaker
description: This route shares the start with Thieving Texas Scum and then traverses to the left after 2 bolts. Continue up and left then follow the intermittent wide crack out the roof.

name: Unknown
description: Start in chalked up pockets, move right along the overhang to the arete, then up to the ledge with several options for the finish. Variations get harder from left to right. Topout/traverse off to the right or drop down.

name: Unknown (right side)
description: On the right side of the cave near the entrance. Start on two crimpy jugs and head right into hueco jugs. Top out above roof.

name: White Trash
description: Nice juggy line on the far left side of the cave. Moves up and left on ledges to a crux in the final 10' of climbing.

name: Celebrate Good Climbs, Come On!
description: There are 2 routes here. A dyno and a static start. There are 2 holds on the wall, you utilize these to get up onto the opposite slopes and complete the climb.

name: Christ the King Rail Bumper
description: Pretty simple top out with a leg scramble.

name: Douglas Center Scaler
description: Fun route.

name: Douglas Park
description: Pinch, Bump, Heel Hook, Mantel

name: Dove Bomber
description: Try to not crush the bushes

name: The Lawn at BluffView Bluff Veiw Diamond
description: Pretty fun, wouldn’t want to fall from the top though.

name: The Lawn at BluffView Bluff View Ladder
description: Next to the diamond route is a thin brick ladder with corner holds. Not bad at all.

name: The Shelton Budget Build Traverse
description: So many holds you have to really look to find the real ones.

name: St. Michael's Traverse
description: No Crux just a lot of moves and options to change hand position/grips

name: Toll Way Troll Way (Beginner)
description: The easier of the toll routes. Do a sit start to add some difficultly.

name: Toll Way Troll Way at Magnolia
description: In order to complete this route you must peek over the top at the cars on the tollway and flip them off. Bonus points if you get honked at

name: Worl Wide Crack
description: Ground

name: Glossopetrae
description: Here's a fun video of the FA:  youtube.com/watch?v=v2x5L1D…

name: Boat Ramp
description: Sit start on the beach side of the boulder and traverse the roof lip using good heel hooks, towards a sloping horn and a jug below the peak of the boulder. Top out on jugs, the same way as blood agar. We thought it was a wee bit stout for the grade, but still fun.

name: Card Tricks
description: Climb a tall slab left of Deagan's roof

name: Deagon's roof
description: Start on the lower side (beach side) and work your way up and right along the corner of the roof on super jugs. turn the corner at the end of the roof and climb the very easy short slab to the top. Short but fun lowball on questionable rock.        by the looks of it, years of erosion has started to fill in the space between the roof and ground making this an extremely-low low ball that kinda takes away from the quality. Not dabbing on the ground is the crux.       Easy for the grade.

name: Magic Man
description: start on rail under roof, pull one move to get over roof then climb slab to top out. careful of landing

name: CAB
description: start on a good jug down and right from the tall arete. Work your way up the face using the 2 vertical seems.

name: Detour
description: Climb the tall obvious arete of CAB boulder. Decent rock quality (relative) awaits but check before committing because there is a nasty landing below. Start down and right of the arete, move left and up as you climb the arete.

name: Egg Drop
description: Climb the easy arete (directly across from the Nice Boulder but the one farthest away from the lake).  Sit start.

name: Little China
description: To the right of Pho (the short arete near the lake), this climb (sit start) goes up  the face following crimpy holds to a small diagonal crack and then the top out.

name: Pho
description: Climb arete on crimps, stand start

name: ROR
description: remind yourself just how small of holds you need to climb a vertical face with this problem. Climb the face 5 feet to the left of the tall arete. Watch out, you'll be topping out above the pile of rock on your left, a fall would definitely result in a twisted ankle.        start on 2 good holds and good feet, then make 2 static movements onto a slopey crimp then a very small horn with a thumb catch. top out slightly left above the rock pile.

name: Sweet and Sour
description: To the left of the arete near the water (called Pho).  Climb up a small crack system (stand start) on the face on good holds.

name: Wight Way
description: Climb the arete (stand start) to the right of CAB (the face climb on the tallest face on the CAB boulder).

name: Wonton
description: Nice little problem (sit start) that follows a crack system and even has a sloper/jug.  It's on the side of the CAB boulder facing away from the lake.  It's on the right side when looking at the CAB boulder with the lake behind it.

name: Crack House
description: Start on the roof of the cave. Crux is the transition out. Fun problem with easy top out.

name: Mussel Prow
description: Climb the overhung arete/prow that faces the beach on Mussel boulder through the use of many heel hooks, underclings and sidepulls. decent rock quality for the area. Sit start. If you're on this beach, this is a must do.

name: Nice Arete
description: Start under the roof with hands on vertical crimps.      One tough move gets you out from under the roof to an easy top out.      NB: I didn't know if there is an official name for the route, so I just called it "Nice Arete" if you were the first ascensionist or if you know the official name, let me know and I'll change it ASAP.

name: Twice as Nice
description: Sit down and climb out of the small roof and then finish up by pulling up the face on easy jugs.

name: Na > Eu
description: Route starts in an odd half sit - half tension start. Start left foot on, right foot off, left hand in crimpy pocket(also can use as sidepull), right hand on an open crimp that's almost a sloper. First move, push super hard and pull up to bump left to full crimp, juggle feet over to the right for a small toe so you can bump right hand. Hit wide left foot and go for another left hand bump because this rock is unforgiving, one of the harder moves to stick because it's an undercling/pinch that isn't forgiving. You can try to full crimp if you are feeling bold. From here you have to fall into a right hand after moving feet into good position. Next move for small people is tough, taller people, probably not. You have to shift feet right and go from side undercling to a crimp by right shoulder. Immediately moving right hand to a similar crimp a little under shoulder width apart. Last hard move is a dyno or statically fast depending on confidence, to right hand full crimp on one solid shiny cube of pink granite that is scarier than all hell if you aren't confident in outdoor falls or big moves.  Topping out is fine, plenty of okay slopy finish and good ridge to grip and finish out and top!

name: Aquatic Anxiety
description: An overhanging dihedral with somewhat desperate finger locks but great stems, leading to deep jamming as the angle eases.

name: Fear of Flying
description: This is one of the most infamous central Texas climbs, and rightly so.  Fear of Flying is a continuous crack in a beautiful dihedral that widens up top.  Most choose to lieback this beast, which makes the climbing easier, but adds an interesting challenge when placing big gear.

name: Little Feat
description: A great crack, thin hands that widen as you ascend.

name: Little Hans (aka. Conspiracy a Go-Go)
description: A pebble pinching slabby bolted face.  Balancy movement.

name: Shrike
description: A strenuous thin line of crimp laybacking above a guillotine blade.

name: Snatch
description: Fun corner with some stemming moves, deep jamming and face holds sprinkled in.  Top finishes on a beautiful left-leaning hand-fist crack.  Good exposure at the start - consider building an anchor for your belayer.

name: Texas Crude
description: Texas Crude is a fantastic steep crack that is easily protected and soaks up many slightly tight hand jams.

name: Foxhole
description: This is the little brother to Skeletons in the Closet(V6) and is a great lowball climb with unique movement.  Sit start and either undercling or jam out the short roof to a strange and technical finish.  May need to be cleaned up a bit since it gets no love.

name: The Mausoleum
description: This is a short and powerful climb that starts on thin edges and climbs left through crimps to a dihedral.  Pull the roof and clip the bolted anchor.

name: Skeletons in the Closet
description: This is perhaps the best boulder problem at Enchanted Rock.  It has it all: endurance, overhang, slopers, crimps, and a nice technical highball finish.    Sit start low on a sloping flake / rail and climb out using heel hooks and some long moves until the flake turns to a thin crack.  Pull some tough crimp moves to an obvious shelf.  Mantle and finish up the technical face.    There are some variations like dropping off from the ledge (V4) and starting from the ledge and finishing to the top (V2).  Strive for the king line, though.

name: Solaris
description: Face of Sol Boulder.  Moves from right corner upwards and then to the left moving above the obvious crack and to the top.

name: Eat
description: Eat is a fun crack climb that ascends the near vertical face just to the right of P.G. 13, and left of the corner formed by the intersection of the two walls.  Look for a large tree at the top of the route.  There are a series of three cracks that lace the face - a center crack, one to the right near the bottom, and one to the left near the top.  The climb starts off as a good hand crack and then transitions to a couple of layback moves.  Above the layback, jam more cracks to the top.  The crux is getting out of the final cracks and onto the ledge with the anchors.  Continuously steep climbing (looks easier from the ground) and great jams makes this a fun route.

name: The Flame
description: To the right of the cave this route starts well of the ground.  Jump to get started. Have a good spotter for the beginning of the route.  Otherwise you will fall backwards and possibly roll all the way down the slope and into the boulder below it!  After somehow obtaining the mantel, follow the bolt-line on delicate face moves to the top.

name: Fun and Grins
description: Low crux on good jams leads to rotten, chossy rock but easy climbing. Very fun route, but be prepared for the head game at the top. 5.9 might be soft, but it is hard to say, as the crux is definitely concentrated in the beginning, and eases up considerably afterwards.

name: Goomba Crack
description: In the crack to the right of The Wick dihedral (not the off-width crack).  This route's hardest move is getting off the ground. Finish off the top.  Use medium to wide gear.

name: Joy Crack
description: Excellent chimney fun. Set gear to protect, but you won't use the crack much for climbing. Start is relatively easy but gets harder quickly due to poor feet, then eases higher up. Look for several small ledges on the face wall on the lower half and one large one on the back wall in the upper half. The crack reduces to a tight squeeze, but you should be able to fit all the way through and top out or get comfortable and set a belay anchor.  Take a headlamp, especially for the lower section.  To set a top rope before climbing, from the main entry tunnel go all the way back. There are two exits, one on the right and one straight back. The back exit is narrow, but the easiest. Upon exiting work your way right, back up and over. Pass a triangular hole, climb a couple of boulders, and look down onto the long narrow slot that is the exit for Tunnel Vision and Joy Crack.

name: La Realidad
description: Just to the left of PG 13, climb thin face holds and the arete to the top.  The bottom half is very thin.  The crux is getting through these bottom couple of bolts. The route then becomes more secure towards the top.  Start on top of the sharp flake under the route.

name: Lowe Overhang
description: To the right of Fun and Grins.  Climb the overhanging crack above the cave entrance to Second Taunt.

name: P.G. 13
description: P.G. 13 climbs the right line of bolts up the steep face to the left of Eat.  It is separated from Eat by a wide crack.  Climb the steep face past four bolts pinching crystals and smearing on the face, generally following a small ridge or bulge that winds its way to the top.  The climbing is sustained with difficult moves near each bolt.

name: Runout Chimney
description: Start in the Chimney work your up way up past this section, then transfer out onto the ledge system. Once you pass the ledges, you will be left to a large runout of simple slab. Be sure you are ready to commit to the slab. As you climb the top rope drag becomes a problem as well as communication. Recommend radios if you have em. ***Didn't find any information on this route in the guidebook or online, so if anyone knows the name of the route, or the FA just contact me to update it.***

name: Second Taunt
description: Through the cave to the right of Fun and Grins you will travel through the three rooms.  In the third room, you will find this 2 pitch route beginning.  If you look up, you can see the sky.  That tells you where the route begins

name: Stem Corner
description: Climb the corner right of the Wick. Many techniques are available, stemming, chimney, or crack for the beginning.    The beginning is the crux.  I recommend a helmet in case you climb up into the rock roof.

name: Tunnel Vision
description: This is a crack protected squeeze chimney. You'll be able to work the crack a little, but the route will very soon shrink down to a proper squeeze chimney and force you out right. 5.8, but it's a squeeze chimney, so...

name: The Wick
description: Start in the corner around to the right from The Flame.  Clip the bolt and then reach around the corner to make it onto the face.  Clip nails up higher.  Go to two top anchors.

name: Winter of Discontent
description: This route is found on large boulder to the right of Goomba Wall.  It starts on the downhill corner around to the right. It starts on the thin flakes and cracks until they run out.  It finishes by going up the steep face on small crystals.

name: Bush Crack
description: A nice two section climb beginning with a flake to a good stance followed by a sweet finger crack to the top.

name: Cubes
description: Cubes is a short hand crack that pulls over to a short loose finish.

name: Dan Jam
description: This is the wide crack just to the left of Bush Crack.  It starts off about fist sized and turns into a squeeze chimney towards the top.  Great practice for squeeze chimney technique.

name: En Passant
description: 15 ft vertical hand crack boulder problem on the West Southwestern flank of Buzzards. Very high rock quality. Worth doing on the way to Buzzards main attractions.

name: Little Bishop
description: A 12' right leaning crack problem located on the same wall, but to the left of En Passant. Also worth doing on the way to Buzzards roped climbs.

name: Retroshrub
description: This climb is the back side of Bush Crack. Work your way into the chimney following an edge that runs out just before reaching the crack. Follow the hand crack up the narrow chimney. Scramble off to the Southeast or walk off to the North.

name: Rope Eater
description: Rope Eater is a fun crack climb with a bouldery start off some cheatstones to get established in the bomb bay wide section.  Sleaze right to the lip of the roof, then boulder out the roof section on good holds and jams, before finishing on the .6/.7 handcrack section.    This climb is indeed a rope eater, and if you hang on either boulder problem the rope will get sucked into the crack.  this happened to us, and we were able to retrieve it by having the second hang on a couple cams, untie, and pull the rope through from above.

name: Missing Link
description: Located on Rappeller's Rock. Start in the wide groove and follow the seam up to the overlap/flake that forms the crack and then continue up lower angle (easier, but less protectable) rock to the top. The crux is reaching the crack and is well protected by the single bolt. The crack at the start of this route is often wet, but can be avoided.

name: ROWENS SQUEEZE
description: START AT THE RIGHT LEANING CRACK AND LARGE SLAB TO THE RIGHT OF CRACK CLIMB TO TOP OF SLAB FOR A QUIK BREAK THEN LARGE TO NARROW CHIMNEY TO TOP

name: Spaceballs
description: Scramble up the boulder pile to the right. Make a long reach to clip the first bolt. Continue up the lichen covered, steep, slabby boulder past one more bolt. There is a tremendous amount of thick lichen on this boulder that makes the climbing feel insecure. It also tends to flake off and rain down on your belayer. In addition, there is some loose rock toward the top.

name: Easy Wall
description: Low angle slab at the back can be used to access the summit and set up a toprope with gear. A #7 tricam and an extra rope will get it done.

name: The Frog
description: A horizontal crack that traverses left along The Frog deposits you in an alcove for easier climbing to the summit.

name: Megabyte
description: Very small holds and sustained climbing all the way to the top. Technical and balancey crux moves between the first and second bolts, moderate 5.11 runout to the third bolt but you won't hit the ground.  Optional to place gear in the Frog crack but the hard climbing is over by then,  First ascent 1989 and was drilled on lead with hooks.

name: Tonka Toys From Hell
description: Beautiful climbing on huge crystals up a wonderfully featured face. This is one of the best climbs in the area for its variety of movement.

name: Top Gun
description: Climb the southeast arete of The Frog. Delicate movement.

name: Velvet Elvis
description: Low, sustained crux to gain classic E-Rock steep face climbing

name: Crumbly Cookie
description: Really fun powerful moves on absolutely terrible rock, to a high/ dirty top out. Rock quality is very poor

name: Lunch Rock Direct
description: Several slab problems run up the face of this boulder, from V0-V2. The climbing gets easier the higher you go.

name: Mount Ann
description: Several variations are possible on the West Face with difficulty in the V0-V1 range. Down climb to the climbers right (South side).

name: Pimp Slap
description: If you boulder you should find the starting crimps easily. Pull off the ground and slap tough onto a slopey but good ledge which you'll be mantling onto. No hands rest, but then a very dicey move or two to gain the summit of Lunch Rock from here.

name: Army Route
description: SW side of Motorboat rock. To the right of detached boulder. Left of bastards moan. Starts on slab, climb into shallow cave with crack system to the left.

name: Bastard's Moan
description: Located just left of Beginner's Bitch.  Look for a wide crack up on the boulder with a slabby base.  The crux of the route is getting past the slab and into the crack.  Reach high for a decent hold, and then smear up the slab until you can step into the wide crack.  Once in the crack, the climbing is easy and straight forward with plenty of rests.  Almost felt like a chimney at times.  Ends at a two bolt anchor.

name: Beginner's Bitch
description: Bitch is the first climb encountered when approaching Motorboat along the purple climber�s trail.  Climb a short face to reach the crack above.
