The crack starts about 1/3 of the way up the rock, and starts as an off-width that narrows as you climb higher.  Look for plenty of hidden holds inside the crack, some of which are a little rotten or crumbly.  The protection is good (large cams up to a #3.5 Camalot help), but the crack tends to throw you a little off balance.  At the top of the crack, face climb up good edges to the anchors.

name: Ben's Dilemma
description: One fun face move brings you into a trough below a small roof.  Hand jam traverse under the roof with little feet before topping a ledge and finding the anchors.

name: Can Opener
description: Beautiful hand and fist crack in a tight corner. starts in a broken crack system and moves into 20 ft of continuous crack.

name: Corkscrew
description: Start on Navy Route and about 15 feet off the ground, just when you get into the crack, move to the left and out onto the face.  Once on the face, you make some delicate moves upwards and towards knobs and crystals eventually making a powerful highstep up to the left to get onto the top edge.  Warning, a slip here could result in a large swing into the crack of Navy Route and injury potential.  Lieback this top edge upwards and to the right to finish at the anchors.

name: George of the Jungle
description: Start on the right side of the arête (same as Tarzan was a Bluesman)and clip 2 bolts then step left around the arête and continue working your way up using a combination of the arête and crack/seam on the left. 5 bolts, bolted anchor on top.

name: Motorboat
description: This is a beautiful arching crack.  Good hand jams to start.  The dihedral very quickly forces you into powerful stemming.  Fist jams through the middle.  The crux is toward the top of the vertical crack when it widens and the dihedral constricts to force you out of it.  The flake behind your head is a great spot for your otherwise useless left hand.

name: Navy Route
description: The slab and undercling at the start is the crux of the route. After that, everything is a cruise. A little crumbly at the top.

name: Sandbag
description: Access the seem and crack 5 ft right of Motor Boat by climbing the first 15' of Motor Boat then traversing right on thin holds. Mind the tree and don't fall. The name refers to the literal sandbag counter weight used to pull the rope and runner out of the crack and around the arete. The rating is thought to be accurate but who really knows.. Could be height dependent.

name: Shocker
description: Some slabby face moves lead to a powerful undercling, then a BIG reach or deadpoint to the base of a beautiful, but short, arching fingercrack layback flake.      This route got an X in the original guidebook, although the crux is pretty protectable.  The techy smears in the upper half make it a pretty heady lead, though.

name: Agent Orange
description: Uses the anchors for Orange Peel.  Uses the face and arete combo just to the right of the arete of Orange Peel.  Starts on the wall at the base below the boulders used to start Orange Peel on the same level as the start for Clockwerk Orange.  Combination of powerful liebacks with delicate face moves.  Amazing route that is made more difficult by the presence of the tree branch half way up that the route gets in the way of.  This route theoretically could be done trad by placing pieces in the Orange Peel crack.

name: Cave Crack
description: Despite the modest grade, Cave Crack is one of the best routes in the park.  Fun climbing, great protection, and a unique location make this climb a must do.  The start of Cave Crack is located above Jack Knife (see Throne Rock).  While it's possible to scramble through the boulders to reach to base, climbing Jack Knife is a lot easier (and more enjoyable).  From the top of Jack Knife, scramble down the back side of the summit block and scamper through a small opening under a large detached boulder.  Once you stand up, you'll be in a narrow, chimney-like space with a hand crack that splits the back wall.  Follow the crack for about fifty feet until you reach the top of the cave.  The crack starts as a hand crack and gradually widens as you move up.  At the top of the cave, step left onto the face, continue around the corner, and work up the widening crack.  Above the cave, the angle eases significantly, and you can walk up the rest of the climb until you find a comfortable spot to belay.  To descend, scramble down the easy slab to the anchors above Orange Peel and rap with a single rope to the base.  Great climbing in the summer when the rest of E-Rock is too hot to touch.

name: Clockwerk Orange
description: Climbs through thin edges and crimps starting left of the tree.  Stellar climb at the grade.  Originally rated 11a, but recent repeats look to downgrade it.  A good slab climber it will feel more like a moderate to hard 10.

name: Crevice Cruise
description: Climb a long chimney to a big chockstone. Pull past this and then up through friction slab.

name: Journey To Evermore
description: Climb Thor's Flake (the triangular flake resting against the Main Dome, left of Orange Peal), find a single bolt on the wall above Thor's Flake, continue up the water streak, join with Orange Peal,  follow the protectable upper reaches of Orange Peal to the bolted anchor.  Mildly run out, but the crux is protected by the bolt.

name: Mystery and Imagination
description: This is a nice face climb on some small edges.

name: Obscured by Clouds
description: Climb the vertical crack starting from within the crevice behind the Triple Cracks buttress. Starts out as a hand crack and soon becomes off-width. The crack narrows again on the lower angle rock above the off-width section. The wide part feels hard for the grade. After topping out and bringing up the second, scramble up 3rd/4th class to Smorgasbord, and either walk off or descend the crevice down to Orange Peel area.

name: Orangasm
description: Left of Thor's Flake there is a wall and an arete running up the left side as you face it and then bends at the top.  The route follows steep holds on flakes getting up to the arete with hard boulder moves followed by steep lieback of the overhanging arete.  Powerful route.

name: Orange Juice
description: Orange Juice climbs the thin face between Orange Peel and Journey to Evermore.  Start on the face to the right of Thors Flake (at the start of Evermore) and work up thin friction moves to a flake with a good side pull.  This flake offers a bit of a rest before the crux which is adjacent to the horizontal flake on Evermore.  Once past the crux, its easier climbing to the anchors.  This climb received and X rating in the guide book, but can be top roped from the Orange Peel anchors.

name: Orange Peel
description: This route is located left of the prominent orange wall that contains two bolted face routes.  Orange Peel starts off a couple of blocks against the base of the wall and climbs a thin finger crack in a left facing corner.  After a slick start, work up the thin crack using intermittent and shallow finger holds � the majority of the crack is tips at best.  There are some good flakes a little over half way to the top that offer solid climbing a good holds on the face.  Once above these flakes, its easy climbing to the anchors.  Rap with one rope.  You can easily top rope this route, but there will be some rope drag across the low angle rock near the anchors

name: COVID Crack
description: Starts as a flared offwidth moves through each bomber size down to hands. Best feet stem on dihedral. Walk off backside.

name: Gates of Doom
description: Stalker off width dehydral. Mr Crump Soloed this for the First accent. No crash pads no gear! These days consider taking 5's and 6's...

name: New Vulgarian
description: [[]]Climb Gates of Doom through the crux from the good stance set a high piece and face the New Vulgarian. Traverse left past the bread loaf and offset seam to access the finger and hand crack on the left arete. Don't blow the last move! Easy crack climbing lead to a final exit crux.

name: Rotten Crack
description: Fun cruiser route.  At the end you exit the crack to a couple face moves to top out.  There are no bolts so anchor off the tree and down climb to exit

name: Skyline Scream
description: Start on a blade of granite at the base between two boulders.  Follow the diagonal crack that goes up and to the right.  Pull around the corner onto the face (the crux) and then easy climbing to the top.

name: Hard Hands
description: Find an angling, small hands to wide fingers crack that moves up and left. The crux is about 10 feet up and requires powerful jamming and careful footwork. Protects great though it can be strenuous to place.     Descent: Class 4+ or 5.0 walk off straight back and climbers left, along the face of the rear wall. Could also be linked with a 5.8 sport climb (rightmost of the two) along this face (although its a scary move to make the first bolt).

name: Jack Knife
description: Jack Knife is the prominent cleft in the large boulder at the top of the purple climbers trail, just left of Orient Express.  It is undoubtedly one of the best 5.5s in the park and provides the most direct access to Cave Crack on the wall above.  Climb a short face to a low angle, right-angling hand/fist crack.  The crack is a lot of fun, protects well, and has positive hand and fist jams all the way to the top.  The crux is a slightly steeper section about two-thirds of the way to the top.  Two rappel bolts are located at the top of the rock on a small summit block.

name: Orient Express
description: Orient Express is a fun bolted route on a large, narrow boulder behind the Practice Slab and right of the obvious Jack Knife crack.  Begin off three chockstones at the base of the route (good belay ledge below the chockstones).  Climb the steep face past four bolts using small scoops and dishes for your feet and a collection of large crystals and small edges for hands.  The crux is clipping the second bolt, and the moves above the third bolt are equally interesting.  At the third bolt, climb up and right to a very positive flake that leads to the fourth bolt.  There is a little run out to the top of the boulder.  There is a set of anchors on the wall behind the top of the boulder.  The best bet is to rap off and pull the long end of the rope through to minimize rope drag over the sharp, crystalline granite.  Felt a little harder than the 5.9 rating.

name: Becky's Crack
description: This is the crack to the left of Middle Crack. Very nice, sustained, with some offwidth, but mostly fist and hand jams. If one is not familiar with offwidth moves, it is probably 9+.

name: Grass Crack
description: This is the thin left leaning crack to the left of the Triple Cracks.  The start is the hardest part of the route.      At the top of the large 5.7 flake careful to avoid loose looking sloping hold on the left.  The hold will be obvious and look really good but weight it with caution.    Also just before gaining the 5.7 flake be careful of fall potential onto the large block on your left.

name: Middle Crack
description: As the name implies, Middle Crack is the centerpiece of the Triple Cracks and is located between Owl and Becky's Cracks.  Middle Crack is an excellent climb, and a must do for any E-Rock visitor.  The start is more of a flake with good lieback moves than a crack.  The crux comes early - about 10-15 feet up, the crack curves up and left, leaving a small 'bulge' on the right (protects well with a #2 Camalot).  There is a second, smaller 'bulge' above the crux.  Continue up the crack as it goes from fists to hands and eventually to fingers.  The climbing gets easier as you get higher.  Belay/rap from anchors at the top (single rope rap).  Great route.

name: Owl Crack
description: The most right crack (actually two parallel cracks) of the Triple Cracks, Owl Crack climbs past a very small roof aiming left for a finish of finger crack and slab. A terrific climb for its grade.

name: Upper Grass Crack
description: Upper Grass Crack is located to the left of the Triple Cracks.  Look for a thin flake that climbs up and left.  The thin finger crack directly below the flake is Grass Crack (5.10).  To reach Upper Grass Crack, climb the chimney to the left of the finger crack to an adjacent boulder.  From the boulder, reach up into the Grass Crack flake, and work your feet onto the face.  Continue up the flake until it merges into the wall.  Transition right and continue up the face.  Rap off the anchors at the top with one rope.

name: Synchronicity
description: A short variable size (mostly hands) crack. The crux is awkward and near the top. Be sure of yourself if you choose to boulder it. This crack really isn't worth the trouble due to the short nature of the climb, awkward crux, long scramble back down, heinous approach through hostile plants, and obscure location.

name: Connect The Dots
description: Climb the well featured slabby face on huge crystals.

name: Cool Whip
description: Climb the hard vertical face to the climber's left of the circular patch of lichen.

name: Fade To Black
description: A tricky sequence off the ground leads to a couple vertical edges and a giant knob.

name: Party Line
description: Climb the face below the big hump with the lime green lichen. A challenging first move leads to bigger crystals above.

name: Sunflower Co-op
description: Climb the well featured rounded aerate.

name: Amazon Boulder
description: Climb the steep, western face of the Amazon Boulder on incut crimps. A really fun, interesting climb that is worth the hike.

name: Euskadi
description: Currently this is the hardest graded route at Enchanted Rock.  The route is on the Arete on the left side of the Eastern face of South American Boulder.  It is to the far left of Welcome Bootcamp.  4 bolts on the face and two rings on top as anchors.  Very high and dangerous first bolt.  Usually this first bolt is clipped before starting.  The PG13 is in the case that it is attempted without clipping the first bolt.

name: Hang On!
description: Start in the overhanging crack and grovel your way up past the bulge to easier climbing. I can't find this climb in any guidebooks, so if anyone knows of a prior ascent, let me know so I can update this.

name: Little Soldier
description: Starts on the right side of the crack that splits the Eastern face of the South American Boulder.  Clip the 2nd bolt of Welcome to Bootcamp or place gear in the crack for protection.  Traverse this crack out to the 3rd bolt of Welcome to Bootcamp and finish on Welcome to Bootcamp.

name: Rock Clark
description: Overhung fist to offwidth boulder. Hardest part is pulling over the edge.    Hope you know how to invert!

name: South American Crack
description: This climb is a short layback dihedral on the South American Boulders.  At only 30' in length, it is short but is strenuous for the grade.

name: Welcome to Boot Camp
description: The right most line of bolts on the east face of the South American boulders. Using the boulder for the start to get established on the face and clip the first bolt is considered on (traversing in from the top of the boulder is Little Soldier, 12a). Sustained crimping on sharp edges that generally become more comfortable higher on the route. Route gets great afternoon shade.

name: Burning Down The House
description: This is a slightly overhanging crack that narrows and widens between finger and hand jams. There is a fixed BD Red #1 (old school) cam just above your first solid hand jam. I worked on it for a while and it isn't going anywhere so if everything stays the same, feel free to clip it. Crack finishes much wider, so don't be afraid to use the horizontal crack towards the top.

name: Ivy League
description: starts with thin hands and ends with fist jams

name: Mirage
description: A quality crack for sunny days as it's shaded by the trees. The crux is the OW top half. This pumpy route is definitely worth the effort to find.

name: Rotten Corner
description: Despite the name, this climb is a lot of fun and on solid rock. Climb up a jumble of boulders to reach several crack systems in a dihedral. Climb this for 30 feet and the cracks fade down to a single narrowing crack and the angle of rock lessens. The next 10 feet the crack is clogged with dirt and leaves, but the climbing is fairly easy. The climb is easy to protect, but setting an anchor can be tricky.

name: Whimpy Crack
description: Starts off a boulder into a dirty crack system for 10-15 feet, and then busts left through a beautiful, slanting, offset fingercrack. If only it were longer...15m

name: Chalupa Taco Combo
description: This easy but fun problem exploits uniquely featured holds.

name: Clingwrap
description: Climb the hand to offwidth crack in the right side of an almost squeeze chimney. It gets really interesting up towards the top! I can't find this climb in any guidebooks, so if anyone knows of a prior ascent, let me know so I can update this.

name: Dirty Deed
description: This overhanging diheadral hand to offwidth crack can be bouldered relatively safely, but can be a fun lead. The crux is when the crack changes from hands to offwidth.

name: The Good Book
description: Delicate stems lead to an excellent hand crack.

name: I Dropped The Ayatollah
description: long diagonal crack that turns straight up towards the end. crack narrows as you go with a large opening about half way up.

name: Less than Picturesque Arete
description: Face problem on left side of arête. Beautiful, solid rock...trust crystals and feet.

name: Nuevos Huevos
description: Thin finger crack in a dihedral.

name: Return to the Planet of the Proks
description: Slightly overhanging dihedral. Layback and scum your way up. Great foot nubs all the way up. Bush underneath makes it undesirable...but the problem is really cool.Its the dihedral in image above...not where the climber is bouldering.

name: Saguaro
description: Unique, super fun granite hueco problem. Rock is more solid than it looks. Sit start.     I couldn't find it in any guidebook, so if anyone knows a different name for this problem, or climbed it before me, let me know and I'll update the info!

name: Viejos Huevos
description: This thin crack in a dihedral is a short route but surprisingly difficult for the grade. The crux is just before pulling the top rounded ledge.

name: Begin With The Beginning
description: This layback crack in an overhanging dihedral is strenuous, but lots of fun. Watch out for the tree behind you! No tree stemming allowed!

name: Layback Flake 101
description: Super fun beautiful highball that offers great climbing and a good gut check! The crux is up high, so make sure you are in it to win it before you start up this beast.

name: Layback Flake 102
description: Right facing crack/flake.

name: No Menace
description: This slab problem has several friction moves that make it worthwhile to do if you are in the area.

name: Albacore
description: Crouching start on a mini-jug side pull and the arete. Heel hook and slap your way to the horn at the top and mantle over.

name: Albacross
description: Really great boulder problem, Start seated at the lowest edges climb up through good holds (avoiding the choss)  Climbs really well avoiding the cruddy holds, might climb easier and lose stars if you were to use any of the choss (really crumbly jugs to the right of the boulder)

name: Cat Like Reflexes
description: A decent and mildly overhanging crack problem. The rock quality is better than it looks. A good addition to the front side bouldering circuit.

name: Cool Hands Spook
description: A short vertical hand crack. For the most part great rock quality, but a little rotten after you top out. This is a very fun and worthy crack problem.

name: Hangover
description: The original grade given this route in The Dome Driver Manual is 5.8. However, it felt harder than that to me. A large piece fell off a few years ago, so the grade may have changed.    The over hanging roof section is burly and fun. However, the rock quality quickly becomes crumbly above the roof. I DO NOT THINK THE GEAR ABOVE THE ROOF WILL HOLD A FALL. So it's probably best to top rope it due to the poor rock quality higher up.

name: Salathe Cling
description: Follow undercling hand jams and mostly good feet until you can reach over and gain the positive upper edge of the flake, then top out on lower angle slab. Downclimb the chimney on the opposite side of the boulder.

name: Alex's Route
description: Located on the backside of the Top Choice crack on the opposite face of the Grade A Boulder.  Wonderful small crack for smaller bodies and people new to climbing.

name: Atmostfear
description: Found on the southwest face of Grade A Boulder.  It is found to the right of Golden Corral.  Climb the black streak to the top.

name: Cactus Makes Perfect
description: The crack is found on the southwest side of the Cactus Boulder just left of the black streak.  The crack disappears before reaching the top.  Face climb the last 8 feet.

name: Carne Asada
description: After pulling the crux on Raw Meat set a high piece then head right onto the unprotected face. Go through both scooped out dishes for full value. The rock is mostly good moves not that bad. Don't fall....

name: Cathy's route
description: Face climb to the right of the back side of the crack that forms Top Choice.  Very nice problem.

name: Egg head
description: Climb the overhung corner on the North face of flathead boulder (the face furthest away from the loop trail or at the very back of the boulders) trending left as you go up.

name: El Carnivore
description: One of the hardest climbs at Enchanted Rock.  This a top rope route that climbs the straight line from the anchors for Top Choice and meets it at the top.  The start is from the base just to the left of the start of Top Choice.

name: Flathead Direct
description: Fun slab boulder problem with both positive and slopey edges. This is the easiest climb on the boulder and can be used to set a top rope on the 2 bolt anchor for the harder climbs on the north side of the boulder.

name: Golden Corral
description: On the southwest corner of Grade A Boulder.  Climb the arete.  Use medium-sized pro to set up an anchor in the crack on top of the boulder.  The crack is several yards back from the edge.  Use long runners for top-rope.

name: Gravy Train
description: Climb the arête on southwest side of the Matterhorn Boulder.  It is found just to the left of Golden Corral.

name: High Octane
description: Nice fingercrack.  Short, but good.

name: Little Friskies
description: On the opposite side of the Hamburger Boulders from Raw Meat is this tricky off-width. Nice hands to fists then the wide-ness ensues as things get steeper and you pull over a small bulge using butterfly jams. Gear Anchor at the top.  Bring longer slings or cord to extend it and keep your rope from getting chewed up.  Rap off the Raw Meat bolts on the opposite side of the boulder (note: They're really too far away to use as an anchor unless you use your rope to anchor the leader who then brings the second up from above)

name: Low Octane
description: This route is the obvious Off-Width to the right of High Octane. Starts in a shallow Chimney that tapers into hand crack. Can chimney, stem, and jam your way up the route.

name: Matterhorn
description: Climbs the arête behind Top Choice.  Can do both sides. Both are fun nice lie-back problems.  Can also climb the face if you like on both sides.

name: Puppy Chow
description: Climb the north-facing arête closest to the Flathead Boulder.  Set up using TR with slings.  Difficult balance and power combo problem.  Watch swing into the Flathead boulder.

name: Raw Meat
description: Slighly overhanging, thin hands, leads to nice hands, fists and into an off-width, then an off-width slab.  Placed a couple butterflies on this one.

name: Return of the Flying Flatheads Direct
description: Start on an enormous jug and work your way up the arete without using the flake. Decent rock quality and gets sunlight pretty much the entire day. The Arete where the North face meets the NorthWest face.

name: The Saucer
description: Sit start and climb left along the rounded lip of the saucer shaped boulder.

name: Scorpion King
description: Start on a huge jug hold and traverse the lip to the left past some strenuous moves.  Grab the good hold (easier for tall people), mantle and finish.     A a classic that needs more traffic!

name: The Squirts Wall
description: This wall features several excellent slab problems on amazing rock!

name: Top Choice
description: Beautiful, left leaning crack that turns vertical  and slightly overhanging halfway up.  The route starts with a bouldery step into the seem between the Matterhorn and the Grade A boulder. Tight hands finishes with a bulge to the top.

name: Burnt Loaf
description: Just right of the large orange streak of Loafing in the Bakery is the obvious crack that cuts diagonally up and to the left. Mantling is definitely the crux.

name: Clown's Crack
description: Right leaning crack.  Nice little warmup.  Good hand and fist jams.  Crux is at the top.

name: I Love Toe-Cams!
description: Starts just to the right of the second crack on the first large boulder facing the Clown's Loaf wall.  You move up the crack, eventually using it as an under-cling.  At this point, get your feet into the crack and toe-cam it and move up the wall using the combo of toe-cams and face holds.  Eventually leave the crack and pull up to the face and top it out.

name: Loafing in the Bakery
description: Problem passes along the base of the wall and upwards to the right.  It starts on big but awkward holds and moves up and to the right and into the orange streak.  It tops out at the same place as Burnt Loaf.  Top out is committing and hard.  Climb passes over several sharp boulders so a good spot is needed with a big pad to cover the rocks.

name: Electric Kool-Aid Acid Test
description: There are large detatched flakes on the overhanging East face of the Acid boulder.   A Bouldery (V4) start gets you to the jug flake, which takes pro.  Then the rock angle eases, pro options cease, and the rock gets crumbly.      A sketch fest ensues

name: Space Lichen
description: This routes looks easy from the ground. It is not.  What appears to be a featured and not-so-steep undertaking is actually a series of hard mantles followed by a technical and footwork intensive crux.  The movement is excellent and varied, as is the the position.  Very well bolted.

name: A Swimming Pool With No Bodies
description: A fun, yet short, overhanging compression boulder problem. A sit start would be possible if the lower rock were more solid.     Start with left hand on the lower jug rail and right hand on a sloping openhand low on the right. Exit up and left to a weirdly fun mantle.

name: All Embracing
description: Compression double arete boulder problem. A great problem with tricky beta. An easier (V0-), less fun variation can be done by liebacking the right arete and using the boulder behind it for feet.

name: Skull Fracture
description: Fun offwidth requiring some interesting moves to get to the top. Good for the aspiring offwidther!

name: Stress Fracture
description: Sit start in the back of the cave, underclinging the crack, then hand jams the rest of the way. Bad landing.

name: Will All The Real Spray Lords Please Stand Up
description: A tough mantle and and interesting topout make this a very fun problem! Sit start on the lower left rail and make your way to the top!    I doubt I'm the FA on this, so if you know the real FA and name of the problem, let me know so I can update the info.

name: Don't Void Your Pants
description: Fun highball slab on good knobs and crystals with a few smears. Crux is up high and committing, so don't fall!

name: Fatman in Paradise
description: On the southeast corner of The Kingdom Boulder you will see a triangular rock leaning against the Kingdom Boulder.  Heel Hook and crimp the downhill arete while you ascend theis odd formation.  A tenuous downclimb is found on the north side of the boulder.

name: Forbidden Fruit
description: Behind and to the left of the big tree.  Route with solid crystals covered but lichen.  Need patience.  As you get higher off the ground some of the crystals gets smaller and more questionable!

name: Forest Crack
description: Despite it's obvious and convenient location, this highball boulder problem somehow eluded mention in the guide books. Nevertheless, it's a fun and exciting problem. Just don't fall if you decide to boulder it.    A couple face moves put you into a hand crack that otherwise requires a flared and overhanging start. It becomes a lower angle fist crack as you gain height. The crux comes early, it gets easier once you're in the crack.

name: Grodie Crack
description: Rotten finger crack/flake often used as down-climb for all the routes on the Kingdom boulder.  It is very rotten so do not pull too hard and do not trust anything!

name: Grodie to the Max
description: This problem climbs the face to the left of Grodie Crack.  It starts with a hand in a thin left-angling seam and a huge high-step.  At no time does it use the holds on Grodie Crack.

name: Null and Void
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Scrambled Egg Sandwich
description: An "S" shaped, moderatly overhung crack over a pit.  You will be hanging from your jams, and they better be solid.     A wonderful apperatus and test of your crackmongering skills. Plus, the falls are clean.

name: Way Below Zero
description: It starts behind and tree and goes up the blunt arete of the Northwest face of the Kingdom Boulder

name: Zilchlessness
description: This highball slab is a fun problem on good knobs and crystals.

name: Breaking Out
description: This crack features awesome, bullet hard, high quality rock. A challenging opening move leads to tight hand jams that get better as you go.

name: Napoleon Complex
description: A short vertical hand crack near the parking lot. A good addition for a front side bouldering circuit.

name: Seam of Death
description: Face climb along the seam

name: Granite Rain
description: Crux is the start, left hand around the slopey arete, right hand in the good crack. Follow the holds straight up to the decent top out jug. Easy downclimb to the left.

name: Chimney Crack
description: Fun stemming chimney with great protection. Good for learning stemming technique.

name: Chockstone Crack
description: Climb the crack starting from the chockstone. Reminiscent of the movie 127 Hours, this crack leaves from a chockstone wedged down inside a chimney. The crux is at the top, where it gets wider than hands. The landing is potentially very bad, especially if you fall and fail to land on the chockstone. Don't fall.

name: Drop Out
description: Start in the chimney BEHIND Sander's Traverse. The namesake Drop Out will be on your left. If you look carefully before starting up the first chimney you can find a small conspicuous placement to protect the move across the Drop Out.     Move a short ways up the first chimney (behind Sander's) then step off to your left, over the Drop Out, onto a dike on the adjacent wall and slip into the chimney between Solo Boulder and Sander's Traverse. Scoot to your right and you'll find a protectable crack to follow until finding the stance near the top backside of Sander's. Again, step over the Drop Out and onto a ramp/chimney located behind Solo Boulder. Two or three moves later you'll top out on the North side of Solo boulder. It sounds confusing, but when you're looking up at it, it will seem obvious. This fun route goes for the most part unnoticed, but it's worth it. It's especially fun to link Flake Crack, Walnut Bowl or Chimney Crack, and Drop Out together.

name: Flake Crack
description: An easy lie back finger crack/flake. Follow it up to the top of the boulder pile and step off to the right. This flake is a fun boulder problem and is ideal for accessing the chimney which houses Chimney Crack and Walnut Bowl Factory.

name: Innominant
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Sander's Traverse
description: This large boulder has a vast many vertical and horizontal variations. It is popular among soloists and sometimes guide services.

name: Walnut Bowl Factory
description: Climb the chimney following the fat protectable flake up to the chockstone. Pull a fun move over the chockstone to top out.

name: Zanzibar
description: Possibly the best, certainly the most famous boulder problem at E-rock.   "Start sitting and climb the overhanging finger crack in the (left facing) corner"

name: Snake Farm
description: Short but stout overhanging crack in a dihedral.  Also rated as V1 boulder problem.

name: 11.c
description: Hard!

name: Barracuda
description: Thin face climb on granite.

name: The Far Side
description: Thin granite face climb. Big drop off under the first bolt. Don't blow the first moves!

name: Road to Nowhere
description: Sustained steep face climbing past four bolts to a two bolt anchor.  Called the easiest and best 5.12 in the park.

name: Solo (aka. the Learning Curve)
description: Previously difficult even to TR and basically impossible to lead, this route was bolted in 2005 thereby allowing the many to experience what only the few had    Climb decent holds up low angel rock curving up and to the right, with a commiting step up and around the corner.

name: The Bold and the Beautiful
description: This is a highball crack problem found in a dihedral. Jam and stem your way to the top. Scramble off to the West (climbers left).

name: False Determination
description: Begin by laying on the boulder all the way under the roof.  Climb out and up with burly pulls on tricky jams. This is the full value start to this route.     One can easily skip the 15' of totally horizontal beginning moves by just reaching up where the horizontal break turns vert. Still stout and fun!

name: Heat Stroke
description: Start on the big flake and do really fun and easy climbing to a jug below the huge pod. Pull into the pod and place your first piece. Enjoy a solid no hands rest and then get into the big undercling and charge up the layback section that ends with solid hands. A really fun climb and a must do.

name: Texas Treescent
description: A fun crack that features hands, fists, and a little bit of face climbing.

name: Flip Flop
description: A sweet left arching crack that is about fist size.  It's a little crumbly on top so be careful topping out.  Part of the campside boulders.

name: Hooks Are For Fish
description: The problem traverses the horizontal edge of the boulder under Midget Corner.  Part of the Campside Boulders.

name: Midget Corner
description: A short, easy, fist or layback problem found in a dihedral.

name: Touch & Go
description: A short, exciting, mildly overhanging hand crack. A fun, quality problem with good jams. Although it appears wide in the pic, most of the jams are pretty tight.

name: Gilory's Gully
description: Dihedral with lot's of stemming and some fun liebacks.

name: Jessie's Day Off
description: A seriously tough start! A low left foot makes for a crumbly smear, but a high right will let you reach an obvious crystal. Tall-people-beta would make this significantly easier. There are a couple good hand holds to choose from for clipping the first bolt. The second bolt's clipping stance is a no-brainer from the ledge. After that, climb just past your waist-high protection to pull the slightly-overhanging finish! It's recommended to just top this one out if you're on lead, otherwise your anchor's going to be in the way when you're searching for those tiny nubbins.

name: Learning To Fly
description: Use the boulder to the Left of Jessie's Day Off to gain the ledge, then finish direct. Can be TR'd off JDO's anchor.

name: Not So Pumper
description: Left-leaning crack with some good jams and some face moves.

name: Pumper Number 9
description: This amazing hand crack has a bouldery roof start that can be skipped by using the cheater boulder in front of the crack (resulting in a grade reduction to 5.8). Either way it's climbed, the route is a lot of fun.    It can easily be toproped by climbing up the easy ramp located on the left side of the boulder formation.

name: Head Hunter
description: Enchanted Rock-style sport route (ie. both bold and slab) that is covered in lichen. The crystals on the top may be brittle.

name: Piranha
description: Wide crack (reach high for a good fist jam) with a white streak on the bottom. Thins out and disappears 2/3 of the way up the boulder. The face move above the crack is protected by a single bolt then run out easy climbing to the top.

name: Practicing Cannibals
description: Previously an aid line (I'd guess A2, but I'm not an aid climber - the aid grade isn't listed in the guidebook). The route follows the thin seam that takes tiny gear. There is a small tree at the top that the guidebook suggests not lowering/TRing off of. Walk off left / downclimb a tree.

name: Animal Byproducts
description: Located far left side of All Bran Wall.  Nice mantel start and then follow the flake to the top.  In the morning it's in the shade.

name: Morning Flakes
description: Morning Flakes is the main attraction on All-Bran Wall. Climb the obvious flake and edges that ascend the center of the wall.

name: Crotch Rot
description: To the right of Far and Away. In the small alley made by the two boulders climb the right face. There is a hidden angled edge for your right hand to start. High foot move to two very sharp, small crimps. This right is easy just stay calm and trust your feet.

name: Far and Away
description: First boulder up and to the right of the two rock towers. Climb the downhill facing, steep face. Start on a good jug and move your feet up and stab at another jug. The rock quality in the middle of this problem is poor which makes this semi-highball quite heady.

name: Hardy Har
description: Hardy Har is found in the alcove on the Southwest side of Pirate Rocks. It is the obvious line of nice flat edges that ascend the tall face on the climber's right side of the alcove. Variations are possible and some are documented in guide books, but this seems like the most natural and inviting problem. Down climb boulder pile in the corner of the dihedral.

name: Northwest Slabs of The Little Dome
description: Variations are possible on this small expanse of rock. For the most part it's 4th class. But you may encounter the occasional 5th class move or two, depending on the line you choose. This is a fun scramble to do when leaving the West side of The Little Dome and heading for Echo Canyon, The Backside, or the parking lot.

name: Walking the Plank
description: Climb the wall on the climber's left side of the alcove (the shorter wall). Variations are possible. Fun and easy.

name: Remote Control
description: Beautiful 30ft finger crack that leans right up high.

name: Black Pearl
description: West side of the uphill boulder. Left side of the arete.  Start facing Southeast towards the arete and proceeds to the top.  Downclmb Real Boat.

name: Captain Coconut
description: Uses the same start as seam of death and quickly moves to the left face and heads up and over to the crack system on the left(East) side of the North face of the lower boulder.  It then moves up and to the top.  Same route can be used as a down climb or you can use Hard Point as a down climb.

name: Dr. Feelgood
description: This is the exact opposite of "Black Pearl". Make a couple improbable face moves until you can grab the arête with your left hand. You'll feel much better after this, until you get higher. As soon as you start to get scared, the arête grants you with solid left handed grips and feet. Cool problem.    Descent, down climb "Real Boat" like all other problems here.

name: Eye of the Chicken
description: West side of lower boulder.  Starts on a couple jugs.  You have your choice of three starting hand holds and left foot on a notch on the face and right foot on a chip of the underbelly.  Move up with a hard move onto the face and then right to the arete and follow it to the top.

name: Kashmir
description: Starts just to the right of the seam of death.  Crouch start with left foot on the face and hands on two crimps.  Pull yourself onto the face, make several delicate yet powerful face moves to eventually gain the notch of the foothold of Eye of the Chicken.  From there it joins EOTC and goes to the arete to the top.

name: Real Boat
description: Route is on the East corner of the upper boulder.  Really good climb.  Crux is in the middle, 7-10 ft of the ground.  It gets a lot easier towards the top.

name: Seam of Death
description: Amazing and obvious line or "seam" in the shallow dihedral of the North face of lower boulder.  Two distinct crux areas with sustained climbing.  Unfortunately the second crux is 10 ft from the top of this extreme high ball boulder problem.

name: Demonic Mother
description: This erratic crack problem lies about 30 to 40 feet right of Lewis Roof.  It starts on the horizontal crack behind some bushes and finishes up a steep vertical crack.  Be aware it might be overgrown due to lack of traffic.

name: The Green Goblin
description: Great short route!  Nice lieback and hand crack and face climb combo.  There might be some vegetation in the way of the upper reaches.  At the top there is a "good" hold to use to mantel up and top it out.  Can be done trad but it is only about 15 feet tall.

name: Lewis Roof
description: Roof crack starts way back in the cave.  The landing is rough so bring a good pad and spotter. Hand jams can be painful and there is some loose rock.  It involves hand and fist jamming through the roof and then pulls over the lip and ascends the short vertical face via thin seam and face features.

name: The Sandman
description: Located at the far end of Spiderman wall there is a large crack in the corner.  You can use this to access the top of Spiderman wall and set up anchors for the routes on Spiderman wall.  Route is kind of sugary/sandy, hence the name.  So, be careful.

name: Spiderman
description: Left leaning finger and small hands crack in the middle of Spiderman Wall.  Short but nice climb.  Does not get climbed much so it is really sharp.  The crux is at the top and a little tricky.

name: Lunar Arete
description: Incut crimps on a slightly overhanging arete. Careful choosing feet especially near the top. Get down via the slab next to Negative Edge. Cool line, wish the rock was better.

name: Negative Edge
description: Climb the slopey arete on the right side of the uphill boulder. Best downclimb is either using the slab or hanging off the top and dropping off.

name: Meat Sweat
description: An easy climb or solo, with great opportunities to place gear, make anchors, or do simul-climbing.      The large flake straight and halfway up is P2.    FA'd because all of the main dome was busy with other teams, and we got bored and wanted practice.

name: Bahama Mama
description: Start on the low angle 4th class hand crack and follow it up to the head wall. Move right and up the shallow awkward dihedral. Continue up the dihedral to the huge ledge and move right to find a hand crack that starts out near vertical and quickly becomes low angle. Continue to the top. This is a really fun climb. The novice leader will need to take rope drag and possible pendulums (for the second) into consideration. It could easily be broken into 2 pitches if needed to help with rope drag and to protect to the second.

name: Caver's Nightmare
description: Cavers Nightmare is so short that it doesnt really constitute are route.  There wouldnt be much of a reason to climb it at all, unless you found yourself at the top of Chunky Tuna and needed a way to get down.  At the top of Chunky Tuna is a slot behind a flake on the right side.  Crawl under the flake and back into the slot until you can stand up.  Work your way up the easy chimney (a couple good face moves near the top).  Best climbed without a rope or harness  its short with no protection, a rope and harness would just get in the way.  Either walk off the top or traverse left to the anchors above Pro Sweat.

name: Chunky Tuna
description: Chunky Tuna is located just to the right of Pro Sweat.  This easy climb follows the long, arching overlap towards a headwall at the top.  There is good protection (mainly small cams and stoppers) found all the way along the route.  About two-thirds of the way up, you have to step over a small (4-6") flake.  If there was a crux on the route, this was it.  Continue up to the steep headwall with a slot to the right (Caver's Nightmare).  There are no anchors on this route.

name: Slam Bam Thank-You Ma'am
description: Fist and hand crack in the right facing dihedral. Scramble up the low angle 4th class face in front of the boulder pile to the large comfortable ledge below the dihedral. An anchor can be built here to belay from if desired or you can belay from the ground. Climb the corner and finish up a short stretch of low angle slab. The climb is about 30' from the big ledge, 100' if you include the 4th class terrain below the big ledge.

name: Voodoo Potato Chips
description: Start on the lower angle 5.6 slab and continue up to the much steeper head wall. The crux is protected by the top two bolts. 5.8ish moves are found well above the last bolt as you approach the top anchors. Be aware that a fall anywhere near the top anchors could result in an ugly ledge strike. It is not uncommon to find bail biners on the top bolt.

name: Zig Zag
description: Zig Zag is a short, fun hand crack that climbs a face to the right of a dihedral high on the dome.  A little scrambling is required to reach the start of the climb.  Look for a dihedral formed by a boulder leaning up against the dome.  Scramble up the face until you reach a good ledge just below the crack (easy 4th class).  The crack starts off as a hand crack, and then narrows slightly at the top.  Near the top of the wall, the crack starts to break to the right (awkward moves) and then heads to a ledge.  The crux is pulling up onto the ledge.  There is no anchor above the route, so be prepared to rig one, or save this climb for last an walk off the other side of the dome.

name: Boston
description: Boston is a fun two pitch route that marks the far left side of the Cheap Wine Wall.  It is located just right of the flake/overlap that divides the Cheap Wine and Devil�s Slide areas.  To find the start of the climb, look for a prominent notch in the overlap approximately 30 feet above the ground.    P1. Climb the poorly protected slab to the notch (there is a decent stopper placement about 2/3 of the way up the slab to protect these opening moves).  Once at the notch, look for a bomber #2 Camalot placement inside the notch and then pull through the overlap on big holds (fun moves).  Continue up the face above the overlap past a couple gear placement and two bolts before reaching the anchors at a ledge with a tree and a large flake.    P2. Climb the flake (large gear, #3.5 or #4 Camalot) to the top where it ends at a second smaller tree.  From the top of the flake, follow a black, unprotected water streak to the anchors.  While the upper section lacks pro, the climbing is easy and the angle eases off as you get higher.    To descend, rap with two ropes back to the P1 anchors.  As second two rope rap will get you to the ground.  When we climbed the route, we had a single 60m rope and had to downclimb the last 10 feet of each pitch.

name: Dome Driver
description: P1: Start between Hartford and MD 20/20.  Follow face up to large horizontal crack with tree.  Bolted anchor above.    P2: Traverse up left past one bolt to a large ledge with bolted anchors.    P3: Follow bolts (some are spinners) up slab staying slightly left until bolted anchor.    Descent: to rappel P3 a 30 meter rappel is not sufficient.  You can climb to the top of the dome and walk down but rappelling would be quicker/easier with a rope long enough.

name: Hartford
description: Hartford is a two pitch route that begins just right of Boston.  Look for a tree along the overlap to the right of the notch on Boston.  Hartford begins just below and left of the tree.    P1. Climb the thin slab past a single bolt aiming for a point on the overlap just to the left of the tree.  Pull the overlap using big holds to gain the slab above.  Thin slab climbing leads past three more bolts to anchors located just below the Beer Can Alley.      P2. From the anchors, step right and climb past three bolts to a ledge with a tree on.  The climb gets a little confusing above the ledge as you can see a number of bolts that belong to different routes.  The actual line continues straight up and then veers slightly to the right passing three additional bolts.  The anchors are on a sloping face.    Rappel the route to get back to the ground.

name: The Kracken
description: You can not rap or lower off either pitch of this climb with a single 60 Meter rope.    The Kracken is named for James Crump's internet handle. Crump is responsible for much of the parks early development and many of it's first ascents.    This route was bolted on lead in 2008 in old school traditional style. To my knowledge this is the last line at Erock to be bolted from the ground up. Since then it has become a very popular line. Presumably because it is quite reasonably protected by Erock standards.    Pitch 1: Start on the low angle slab and clip one bolt before the overlap. The second bolt can be found on top of the overlap and can be clipped before pulling the first of two cruxes. Above the overlap continue up easy well featured slab, following the line of bolts. Belay on the large comfortable Boston Ledge under the trees. Double bolted rap bolts are found here. Take long slings or know how to anchor in with the rope. The anchors are otherwise placed a bit too high and far apart to allow for a comfortable belay.    Pitch 2: There are two bolted lines leaving the ledge. The first bolt above the ledge can be used for both. Kracken is the line to the right and Newark goes left. After clipping the second bolt it may be helpful to back track and unclip the first bolt to reduce rope drag. The third bolt protects the second crux. After the crux, climb the lower angle black streak that is shared with Dome Driver. Three more bolts are located on the black streak before reaching the double bolted anchors that are also shared with Dome Driver. From here there is a short 4th class scramble to the top if you are walking off or rappelling with a single sixty from the News Wall anchors. Some will prefer to be belayed for the scramble off.

name: MD 20/20
description: Originally a top rope route, this fine Enchanted Rock climb was later bolted by the first ascensionist in order to entertain the pleading cries of the masses to make it a bold lead. Certainly bold since the average stretch between bolts is 20'+ feet, including a "heady" section between bolt #3 and #4....a possible ankle breaker on the slab underneath the overlap. A quality slab route nonetheless! Highly recommended!    Start by locating 2 bolts on the initial slab section (15' left of Ripple and 10' right of an obvious black stain...often wet). Clip the 2 bolts while heading up to the overlap/headwall. Clip the 3rd bolt above the overlap (a height dependant reach to clip) and make a balancy mantle onto the slab above. Delicate footwork and small crimps up and slightly right lead to clipping the 4th bolt (the crux...a mental one for sure!). From bolt #4, continue up the dark section of rock and clip the 5th bolt and eventually to the achors above. Lower off with a 6o meter rope.

name: Newark
description: This approximately 125' climb is one pitch, but you will have to climb something else to reach the starting ledge. The starting ledge is about 120' up the wall.    From the ledge where Boston, Kracken, and Newark meet follow the line of bolts up and left. Two bolts are found on the head wall as you leave the ledge. Four more bolts are found on the lower angle slab above the head wall. Three of the upper bolts and the top anchors are shared with Mark of the Beast.     To descend either take two ropes to rap, walk off, or rap from the News Wall anchors on a single 60m.

name: Ripple
description: Ripple is a fantastic, sustained slab route located on the far right side of the Cheap Wine Area (when facing the wall).  To find the climb follow the trail at the base of the wall past the end of the overlap (the same overlap with the notch on the left side - see Boston).  Where the overlap "merges" into the wall forming a short headwall is the crux on T.J. Swan.  A few more feet along the wall and you'll come to a boulder/slab leaning up against the wall.  Ripple starts from the top of the slab.  Climb a shallow, left-facing groove past the first bolt.  Continue up the namesake ripple (thinner than it looks) past a final steep section (crux) to the anchors.  The climb is well protected with six bolts, but they are far enough apart to keep the climbing exciting.  The climbing does not let up until you reach the anchors.  The best option for descending is to traverse left and down to the T.J. Swan anchors and rap with a single 60m rope from there (a 50m rope would require some downclimbing).  Fun, worthwhile route.

name: TJ Swan
description: Climb the flake that starts Ripple. At the top of it step off left and climb delicate edges to first bolt below bulge section. Through the bulge and to another bolt (crux), then onward past four more to anchor. A little headier than MD20/20 but still around 5.8.

name: Close To The Top
description: Ascend the slab just right of where the big overlap meets the ground. Belay using the crack below the large flake at the overlap weakness. Climb the flake and mantle to then clip the first bolt. Great feldspar crystals and good friction will get you past this bolt (crux) and to a second, which is the first bolt on the second pitch of Walk in the High Country. Continue to belay at some blocks.

name: Easier Than It Looks
description: WARNING!!!!   Conditions Update!! - Please note that the feature known as the "Fat Man Flake" has a hollow and thin section above where one pulls over the small roof on P2 of HTIL.  Recent reports from 10/17/2020 from reliable sources indicate the Flake has deteriorated over the summer from the last time it was checked by CTCC and it now poses concerns for stability and safety (mainly that it will be pulled away from the wall).  PLEASE DO NOT CLIMB ON OR BELOW FAT MAN FLAKE until the situation can assessed by CTCC and other involved parties. P2 of Harder Than It Looks should NOT be climbed at this time and caution should be exercised on any routes below the flake (Easier Than It Looks, Harder Than It Looks and Mark of the Beast). From the top of the boulder, the climb follows a series of small ledges and dishes up and right, first to an overlap, then to anchors below and left of Fat Man Flake, which dominates the skyline from the start (about 110 ft up and right). If the sun is right, you can see the P1 anchors from the start. ETIL shares the P1 anchors and upper two pitches with Harder Than It Looks. For P2, climb up the flake and continue up the unprotected slab to a ledge with the P2 anchors (60 ft). P3 goes up the slab for another 100 to 130 ft (depending on where you choose to build an anchor). You can also just clip the P2 anchors and continue to the top of P3.This is a good route for a novice leader, although the start is a bit run-out (fall potential is low). Crux is probably the first 20 ft of the third pitch which is the steepest part of the slab and unprotected, although there are small crystals for footholds. Overall its an easy route to work on slab climbing.

name: Easy Traverse
description: This is a traverse across Devil's Slide and Cheap Wine Wall to Beer Can Alley and then the massive ledge above the Shield and News Wall. The number of pitches is really up to the party, but here is what we did:  P1-- Climb the first pitch of Easier Than It Looks and belay from the anchors below Fatman Flake.  P2-- Traverse along the ledge to Mark of the Beast's P1 anchors and then to the large ledge where the Boston/Kracken anchors are. Belay.  P3-- Rappel/downclimb/lower down and right a short distance to Beer Can Alley. Belay from so-so rock at the start of BCA or from the anchors for P1 of Dome Driver and Hartford.  P4-- Follow BCA up and right. Belay from top anchors of a route just past the popular Cheap Wine Wall routes.  P5-- Follow BCA up and right. Belay off top anchors for a route on the Shield.  P6-- Follow BCA up along increasingly easy ground and end on the massive ledge.  It is possible and sensible to combine our P4 and P5. Because it was a busy day, we just wanted to get ourselves and our rope away from all the traffic as quickly as we could, so we made P4 a very short one.  There are two cruxes, and they are some exposed downclimbing spots on P2. They felt harder than 5.5, but maybe that was a head thing due to exposure, downclimbing, and a possible pendulum fall.  I have a more-detailed account of the route here: summitpost.org/easy-travers…

name: Harder Than it Looks
description: PLEASE JUST STAY OFF THIS ROUTE UNTIL FAT MAN FLAKE IS REMEDIED. It will either be "fixed" through safety efforts with the Parks Department or eventually nature will takes its course. WE CAN HELP BY JUST AVOIDING THE ROUTE UNTIL ONE OF THOSE TWO OCCUR. Thanks from one climber to you....WARNING!!!!   Conditions Update!! - Please note that the feature known as the "Fat Man Flake" has a hollow and thin section above where one pulls over the small roof on P2 of HTIL.  Recent reports from 10/17/2020 from reliable sources indicate the Flake has deteriorated over the summer from the last time it was checked by CTCC and it now poses concerns for stability and safety (mainly that it will be pulled away from the wall).  PLEASE DO NOT CLIMB ON OR BELOW FAT MAN FLAKE until the situation can assessed by CTCC and other involved parties. P2 of Harder Than It Looks should NOT be climbed at this time and caution should be exercised on any routes below the flake (Easier Than It Looks, Harder Than It Looks and Mark of the Beast).Harder Than it Looks is located approximately 10 feet left of Mark of the Beast. Follow a line of four bolts (the first one was hard to see from the ground, I was right on top of it before I knew it was there) up the center of the slab, basically paralleling the first pitch of Mark of the Beast. Once again there is no real crux, just fun climbing in the 5.6 realm throughout. Rappel the route with a pair of ropes.

name: Knuckle Duster
description: This is a fantastic and overlooked climb. Up the unprotected easy slab and throuh a left-facing corner system at about 5.5. Then step right onto the headwall to clip the first of four bolts. Some of the best slab climbing in the park through these four bolts on knobby feldspar and perfect friction. Gain the ledge and bolted rap station.

name: Mark of the Beast
description: Mark of the Beast is probably the longest, vertical, non-contrived route in the park.  The route is a well-protected three-pitch slab route that climbs the right side of the Devil�s Slide.  The first pitch is also known as Christine�s Variation and is a great 5.6 climb just by itself.    P1. Start at the base of a long, clean slab just left of the prominent overlap that marks the left side of the Cheap Wine Wall.  Climb past seven bolts to a pair of top anchors in a shallow dish just right of the Fatman Flake.  While there are a couple sections where the wall is a little steeper, there is no real crux.  Fun, 5.6 climbing to the anchors.    P2. Climb up and left from the P1 anchors past the Fatman Flake.  The crux is a steep smooth headwall that leads to the first bolt (5.8/5.9 range).  Once past the first bolt, the angle and the climbing both ease significantly.  Climb past two more bolts to a two-bolt belay on the Broadway Ledge.  Short pitch.    P3. Another short pitch.  Climb an easy slab up and right from the P2 anchors to a two-bolt rap station.    From the rap anchors on top of P3, rap with two ropes back to the P1 anchors near the Fatman Flake.  A second two rope rappel gets you back to the ground.  You could also scramble up a low angle slab and walk off the top of the dome.

name: Walk In The High Country
description: This route is a great multi-pitch traverse across the backside of Main Dome. Crosses several other popular routes, so you may have to wait or ask permission to cross other parties if its a busy day. This climb can definitely be a route finding challenge past P3 due to the sea of bolts on Main Dome.    P1-3 can be done as a standalone, topping out on several different climbs or rapping off of Easier Than It Looks anchors with a single 60m rope.    P1 (~30m): Climb the face using the arete formed by the right facing dihedral (4 bolts) to a set of anchors.    P2 (~30m): Traverse up and right across the top of the overlap (6 bolts) to a set of anchors.    P3 (~30m): Traverse across easy terrain to a grassy ledge (no bolts) with 2 sets of anchors (left is Easier Than It Looks, right is Mark Of The Beast).    P4: Continue traversing the upper shield using bolts on existing routes following a dike that angles up (guidebook says 3 bolts, 2 anchors).    P5: Angle up and right through a dish and a bulge (guidebook says 2 bolts).

name: Event Horizon
description: The Dome Driver Manual states that a line with 2 bolts was first established on this boulder with no first ascentionist noted.  This route was later established by Bill Gooch to the right of the original line, with the approval of the Central Texas Climbing Committee and the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department.  Follow the line of bolts up the right side of the boulder. From the top anchors multiple ropes can be hung and many variations are possible, making this a really fun place to climb.

name: Harmonica Jam
description: The short hand crack is found on the same boulder pile as Return to Balance and Harmonica Convention. I would imagine people passing through the area have been bouldering this problem since the beginning of time. But as far as I know it has never been named or documented. Therefore, I went ahead and named it for the sake of documenting it and because it serves as a landmark for locating Harmonica Convention. If anybody knows of an earlier name or wants to claim naming rights just PM me and I'll change it.    Follow the short hand crack to the large chossy ledge. Traverse to the climbers left were the ground rises to the point that you only have to down climb about 6 feet of low angle, but questionable rock to get off.

name: In The Beginning There Were Ducks
description: 5.9??? Originally this climb was given a 5.9-grade in the Dome Driver Manual. However, according the story I heard, the ground below the problem was washed away and badly eroded after it was first documented. Consequently, getting off the ground is much harder than the 5.9 grade implies.    After figuring out a way to start it, continue up the lower angle slab. Then pull the tricky to protect boulder problem found on top of the slab to the climber's left.    The descent is also less than ideal. It's a good idea to look at the descent before committing yourself to this one.    IMO this route really isn't worth the trouble. I'm only posting it here because it serves as a good landmark.

name: Return To Balance
description: This climb was originally graded 5.10-. However, pretty much all of the best holds have since broken off. So the grade may be harder now.

name: We Be Joes
description: I think at one time this route may have been called Mud Slide. Not sure where I heard or read that. Nevertheless, the guide books refer to it as We Be Joes.    This climb consists of two parallel cracks that ascend the vertical wall of a large obscure cave. The left crack fizzles out before the top. The right crack starts out hands and becomes fingers near the top. The rock quality is generally pretty good, but it tops out into a semi-rotten trough that is pretty much always filled with debris. About 4 years prior to this writing I cleaned out the crack which was quite packed with mud and debris. As of about a year and a half ago it was still clean. Honestly, this is a pretty good crack and worth doing.    Please don't be tempted to sling the large egg shaped boulder that is balancing on the edge of the trough above We Be Joes and use it as an anchor. I absolutely would not trust it to stay put. There is another larger boulder behind the spooky one.

name: What, A Harmonica Convention?
description: This hidden gem was first discovered and climbed during a world wide New Age event called the Harmonic Convergence. Enchanted Rock was one of many sites around the world where hippies converged to meditate. The climb is sarcasticly named after that event.    Climb the richly featured, slabby, and protectable chimney crack problem found in the center of this jumble of boulders. Return To Balance and Harmonica Jam are also found on the same boulder pile.    Two options exist for descent:    1. Reverse the last few easy moves back down to the flat alcove. From here move to the skier's right (climber's left)and scramble over or under a boulder to make an exposed move on to the wide chossy ledge with the dead tree above Harmonica Jam. Traverse across the ledge to the far end where the ground is higher and down climb about 6' of low angle questionable rock.    2. Reverse the last few easy moves back down to the flat alcove. Then scramble up the 4th class backside of the boulder which forms the front of this formation. On the front top side you will find the top anchors for Return To Balance and you can rappel from there.

name: I Dismember Momma
description: Really high quality roof crack, start as low as you feel you ought  to, traverse right into the difficulty, use knee bars and some funk to traverse to the lip and then execute the fairly ticky top out.

name: Not Bad For A Fat Guy
description: Start sitting down in the trough with left hand on great sidepull and right on good undercling/pinch. A very fun problem with great movement.

name: Standing Wave
description: Climb thin edges to reach the right arcing, overhanging finger crack created between a flake and boulder. A series of underclings lead to the top

name: Blue Bell Arete
description: Climb the face using the blunt arete for the right hand and small crystals for the left.

name: Borden Arete
description: immediately right of Milk Belly

name: Bull Knose
description: On Frog Pond Boulder (on the corner where the frong pond boulder meets the dairy boulder, on the right of the slab climb on dairy boulder)

name: Calf Practice Wall
description: Prettymuch anywhere on the uphill side of the main boulder.

name: Cottage Cheese Face
description: This is on the east face of Lactose Boulder.  Start on a small rock on the left side of a small tree.  Short face climb but with great crystals and knobs.

name: Cow Chips
description: Slab right of Milk Money

name: Cow Tipping
description: Takes about 5 seconds to climb, warm up route.

name: Crying Over Spilt Milk
description: Climb the right side of the rounded arete using a series of heel hooks, side pulls, and the arete itself. Don't escape onto the slab to the left of the arete or it isn't a true ascent!

name: Dairy Dog
description: slab on Frog Pond Boulder

name: Fight Crack
description: Start sitting under the crack and grab the undercling. Fight your way to the top!

name: Frogatron Direct
description: Start on the good crimp and head straight up to top out (as opposed to moving right to finish on Frogatron, V1).

name: Goat Cheese
description: This route starts on two slopers/crimps to the right of Schmantle Fest.  It is also around the corner and to the left of Frogatron.  Jump to the two slopers, mantle and make your way to the top via more slopers and tiny edges.

name: Got Milk
description: Blunt arete to the right of Vitamin Fortified on the Lactose Boulder.  Tricky start getting up and onto the boulder. After you move up and onto the boulder it gets easier.

name: Heavy Cream
description: Sit down start on right side of the Western slabby face of the Frog Pond Boulder.  Move up and to the right to the blunt arete and then top it out.

name: Ice Cream Corner
description: Right of the Prow

name: Ice Cream Sandwich
description: Dihedral to the left of Blue Bell Arete

name: Lactose Intolerant
description: Start low on the big right arching flake and go right on underclings to the right side of the prow then top it out.

name: Layback 101
description: Right of Mild Cheddar

name: Longhorn Flake
description: Easy Flake that has varied ratings in the books.

name: Mild Cheddar
description: A left leaning crack behind a small tree.  Start low and work your up and to the left.

name: Milk Belly
description: A good chimney that is located between Lactose Boulder and Blue Bell Boulder.

name: Milk Jugs
description: Sit start with hands matched on the obvious mouth jug. A tricky heel hook / mantle balancing act will pull you through the crux. The rock is pretty good, but you may pull off a crystal or two while heel hooking.

name: Milk Money
description: Around corner from Milk Moustache, right of offwidth

name: Milk Money Offwidth
description: Around corner from Milk Moustache. Climb the Offwidth with a standing start, then topping out. Sit start for a harder variety.

name: Milk Moustache
description: jump start mantle, right of Udderly Fantastic

name: Opps I Missed The Bucket
description: Right of Layback 101 is a large knob.  Start on the knob and move up from there.  Hardest part is the start.

name: The Prow (crouch start)
description: In the crouch version, somehow get onto the Prow with your feet down low on the boulder and hands on both sides of the blunt arete, in a crouching position.  Make your way as quickly as possible and with as few moves as possible to the lip and mantle up on top.

name: The Prow (jump start)
description: The obvious Prow on the East face of Haagen Das Boulder.  This is the jump start to the lip and mantle up.

name: Schmantle Fest
description: Start just right of the Southeastern blunt arete on the Frog Pond Boulder.  Start with a right hand on the rounded sloper, do the funky mantle and move straight up to finish it.

name: Skim
description: Located on Lactose Boulder to the right of Milk Belly and Borden Arete.  There's a shallow corner right of the arete.

name: Sugar Cone
description: Begin low on the right leaning blunt arete. Using the arete and crystals on the face, make your way up and top out on the gigantic jug rail.

name: Udderly Fantastic
description: Grab the left leaning flake, go up for a knob, top it out.

name: Vitamin Fortified
description: Start crossed hands on the good edges, high foot layback into the first moves. Pull up and over to the crack edge and you're home free

name: Wet Cow Chips
description: Using the cow chips slab, start between Lactose and Frog Pond. Climb the slopping arete and top out without using Frog Pond for assistance.

name: Ding Dongs and Taco Sauce
description: Overhanging hand/fist roof crack that turns a lip and thins down to tight hands and fingers as angle goes back to vertical. The roof crack is about 15 ft. long and you are actually climbing downhill until near the lip. Once the lip is turned, the route tops out about 25 ft. above the ground

name: Dingle Berry
description: Overhanging hand/fist crack that thins to fingers when difficulty eases

name: Zippy's Day Out
description: Dihedral crack that has a little bit of everything with a slightly overhanging topout

name: Eiger Sanction
description: Thin moves at the start and then slab climbing to the top! Start on a good crimp and then make your way up.

name: Hollow Man
description: A fun climb, but the holds are SUPER sharp. Would definitely rate 3 stars if the holds were just a little more comfortable. Start matched on a good undercling and move up and right to a hollow flake.

name: The Wraith
description: Locate the obvious circular rock scar on the route Hollow Man, and search for two left leaning crimps about 30 feet to the left. Use them to pull the committing first moves up onto the slab, proceed upward on tiny crystals.

name: Goats Can Climb This
description: This wide face features several excellent slabby lines that run from V0- to V1. The easiest are on the right and get progressively harder the farther left you start.

name: Idaho
description: Start on a broken jug/crimp rail above a small, flat rock that is shaped like the state of Idaho. Move up on more crimps.

name: Romb-a-saurus
description: To the left of Rombatron.  Step off of the boulder and onto the wall and move upward on crystals. Not climbed very often.  Sustained and sharp.  Crux might be getting onto the wall, starting the route and moving up towards the first second set of hand holds.

name: Rombatron
description: Starts on the ground and you pull over the lip and into up the left leaning crack and ascend to top. Easy to spot the large bulge near the top.  Can set TR by building anchor on the other side of the boulder or it can be bouldered.

name: T Arete-a-saurus
description: Really a great route.  Give it a try!  The route starts to the left of Romb-a-saurus.  Start on the same boulder as Romb-a-saurus but left side instead of right side.  Step across the small gap onto the triangular shaped part of the shelf.  The first hold is a sharp right facing flake.  Move to the left along the shelf and once you are under two edges, start heading up.  Move up and towards the arete.  Once obtaining the arete with your left hand, move up and to the right using sharp holds on the arete.  Eventually you will gain the obvious jug at the top and top-out.

name: Baba Wawa
description: At the time of this posting this route is largely unprotectable except by top rope. You may be able to find pro behind the flakes down low. However, it will quickly become useless as you move higher. Start on the low angle slab and follow it to a short series of flakes. Climb the flakes and continue up a system of nice edges until it blanks out near the top. Finish by smearing your way up the low angle nearly featureless slab. Crux is at the top.

name: Late Night
description: This route is largely unprotectable, except by top rope. Climb the unprotected low angle slab left of the Walter Funkite overlap and below the steep arching feature. Mount the overlap to its left. Once on the overlap traverse a few steps to the climbers right and proceed up the flake and nice foot holds. Finish on reasonably well featured low angle slab. Move left to top out into the alcove.

name: Mercy Street
description: Face Right of Pro Sweat is the right-most route on News Wall.  Very similar to Pro Sweat, but more difficult and slightly run out between bolts.  Climb to the same overlap on Pro Sweat, this time without the benefit of a bolt below it.  You could probably protect the overlap with a small cam (TCU), but the placement wouldn't be great.  The crux is pinching small crystals and stepping above the overlap.  The climbing remains steep to the first bolt and the eases up a little to the top.  Climb past one more bolt en route to the anchors.

name: No Sweat
description: No Sweat is a short, rather nondescript crack climb that shares anchors with Sweat.  Starts about 15 feet to the left of Sweat in a vertical hand crack.  After about 15 feet of easy climbing, the crack widens, and then basically becomes a small ledge that continues up and right to the anchors at the ledge above Sweat.  Short and easy, often used to set up a top rope for the other Sweat climbs.

name: Nobody Likes Bryant Gumbel
description: This is the second-to-last route on the left side of News Wall. It starts left of a large tree and follows a black water streak to a chute up top. Along the way, there is an overlap to pull, and this is probably the crux. People sometimes drift left along the overlap and use some of the Baba Wawa holds. That's fine, but that's not the 5.9.  Originally, this was done as a free solo by James Crump and Mike Head, and in Crump's Dome Driver's Manual, it is a 5.9- X. Just about everyone topropes it now, and it is listed as a TR in a newer guidebook, but I have listed it in keeping with the FA.  If you wanted to lead this on gear, you could get a marginal/poor piece to protect pulling the overlap, and there is a horizontal flake below the top-out that would probably break if you fell on a cam or cammed Tricam. If you fell on either piece and it blew, you would deck, so considering that and the quality of the rock, this really is an X lead.  In the chute at the top are two Metolius rap bolts known as the News Wall anchors. Please leave these open for parties rappelling, especially on weekends and on other busy days. There is a large boulder behind the anchors, and you can hang a TR masterpoint over it. Doing so will also result in much less rope drag than using the anchors will.  Note: in DDM, this route and Baba Wawa are part of the Prok Wall, which is part of the Shield. However, the newer O'Grady guide has them on News Wall. Since the person who submitted the BW page put it with News Wall and since most people call the anchors above BG the News Wall anchors, I have included BG under News Wall as well.

name: Pro Sweat
description: Pro Sweat is a fun route that follows a line of bolts up the wall to the right of Sweat.  Climb past the first bolt to a small overlap.  Just above the overlap is a small ripple that heads up and right.  Using the holds along the ripple, step above the overlap and continue past three additional bolts to a set of anchor just right of the Sweat anchors.  A little thin at the bottom, the climbing eases somewhat once you get above the overlap.  Felt a little easier than 5.9.

name: Slippery When Sweat
description: Climb sustained low-angle lie-back. Getting off the ground can be tricky when the rock is wet. Climb a left facing slab to first placement. Work left 10' to gain the main flake. Climb flake to headwall. Contrived thrashing through narrow opening at top of climb to gain ridge.

name: Sweat
description: Sweat is a short, but stellar, crack climb located where the blue climbers trail hits the wall.  It is easy to spot as an arching crack that ends at a ledge with a small group of trees.  The climb starts out as a fist crack (#3 Camalot), narrows to hands (the best part of the route), and then ends as a finger crack below the anchors.  Just below the anchors are two cracks that you can use to get around a large hanging flake.  You can either use the anchors at the ledge (bolts with chain links), or continue to a second set (rap anchors) located up and slight right from the ledge.  To descend, rap with a single rope back to the base.  Easily one of the best 5.7s in the park.

name: The Today Show
description: Start up Walter Funkite, pull the break, and head straight for the top.  Originally, this was done as a free solo by James Crump. Just about everyone topropes it now, and it is listed as a TR in a newer guidebook, but I have listed it in keeping with the FA.
