If you want to lead this on gear, you can protect the move pulling the break (a #6 works), but there is no pro after that, so any fall 20' or so or more above that piece means cratering.

name: Walter Funkite
description: This is a big crack, even though it does not look it from the ground.  Hardes part is the move over the overhang.  Super easy.

name: Amazing Gravy
description: Start and climb the first two bolts of Texas Radio.  Traverse to the left to the 2nd bolt of Real Gravy and climb to the top of Real Gravy

name: Ambulance Blues
description: Just to the right of where the overlap reaches the ground, clip the first bolt and then move up and to the left.  At the third bolt, move up and to the left and join Ripple and finish on anchors for Ripple.  SEE COMMENT BELOW FOR MORE DETAILED INSTRUCTION.

name: Bold Talk for a One-Eyed Fat Man
description: Taken from the Dome Drivers Manual : "From the first tree left of Gravitron, climb sustained 5.10 crystals past the overlap and the first two bolts. The crux is the 25-foot bulge leading to the third bolt. This section starts with steep edging and ends with small crystals. Climb left to the forth bolt and then embark on a 45-foot run-out of 5.9+ to the fifth bolt. Just above is a double-bolt belay with a ledge stance."    This is an outstanding pitch that really isn't as scary as the description sounds. It's all there, however, a cool head is necessary to avoid a very nasty fall!    An added bonus is the opportunity to toprope the very serious Gravitron from the anchor.

name: Carpet Crawl
description: Where the overlap meets the ground, climb up past the three bolts of Ambulance Blues towards Ripple.  SEE COMMENT BELOW FOR A BETTER DESCRIPTION

name: Deep Prok
description: Deep Prok is a typical E-Rock slab climb that starts below the center part of the Runamuck arch.  Start below a bolt about eight feet off the ground.  Clip the bolt and head right to a second bolt under the center of the arch.  Climb to the arch (good 0.5 Camalot placement here), pull over, and work up a small headwall to the third bolt.  After the third bolt, the angle eases a little, but the climbing remains a little thin up to the fourth bolt.  From here the rest of the route is pretty easy.  Head up to a good sized ledge split by a large crack passing two more bolts en route to the anchors.  Either rappel the route, or scramble up and over the top of the dome.

name: Eden
description: It is a unique start of God's Elastic Acre without using the start of Stranger than Friction.  Start to the left of the beginning of Stranger Than Friction but to the right of Stranger Direct using the face.  Should start right below the first bolt of Stranger than Friction.  Keep out on the face, well to the left of the beginning flake for Stranger than Friction. Move up over the overlap and up the face to the first bolt of Stranger than Friction.  Then move up and to the right, to the second bolt of God's Elastic Acre.  Follow God's Elastic Acre up and to the left.  Use the 4th bolt of Stranger than Friction and follow Stranger than Friction up and to the right to the top of Stranger than Friction. Here you can build an anchor and top rope multiple routes or head up and to the top.  Between the "anchors" for Stranger than Friction and the top, there is no protection.  So, be careful.   VARIATION:  At the cross-over the route and head left to the anchors of Texas Radio/God's Elastic Acre to the top.  You can build an anchor system here and TR other routes or you rap from the top of the first pitch.  Use the anchors for Texas Radio/God's Elastic Acre to belay from if you are heading to the top and the two rap rings.  Rap rings are up and to the left of the anchors in the "gap" between two horizontal slab "eyebrow" pieces.

name: Elastic Happiness
description: Climb to the second bolt of Sixth Happiness then right to the third bolt of God's Elastic Acre to finish on God's Elastic Acre.  Use anchor bolts for Texas Radio/God's Elastic Acre.  Can do second pitch up and to the left to the rap rings.  There are no bolts between the top of pitch 1 and these rap rings.  Climbing here is 5.7 but be careful.

name: Fly on a Windshield
description: This route is located just to the right of French Route.  The route can be identified by the bolt located 10 feet above the overlap.

name: French Route
description: The face climbing standard of the rating at E-Rock, this route has an unprotectable start at about 5.8 to the right end of a ledge. Go left on the ledge which has a thin horizontal crack above it. The only pro this crack will take are two (equalized) slider nuts or RPs of the smallest sizes. Then a few moves left off the ledge to reach the first bolt and the crux section follows. Work out the moves over the steep crystal face past 3-4 bolts. Diagonal up to the right on increasingly lower angle face moves, over to the two bolt anchor above another horizontal crack.  Pitch two is on a much easier run out slab with sparse pro.     Descent:   Go right on the large ledge above the second pitch to the rap station above News Wall or rap the first pitch. You can also scramble off either end of the ledge to walk over the top if you are done with the backside.

name: God's Elastic Acre
description: From the first bolt of Stranger than Friction, climb up and right to the second bolt of God's Elastic Acre instead of to the left (as for Stranger than Friction).  After the second bolt, move upwards diagonally to the left towards the 4th bolt of Stranger than Friction and then upwards to finish on Texas Radio. At the end of the first pitch, you can build anchors here, rap down or head up and to the left to the top to two rap rings.  There is no protection for this second pitch until you get to the top.  There are rap rings there or you can walk off the top.

name: Gravitron
description: To the left of Real Gravy.  Find the obvious big black streak.  Gravitron is on the right side of this black streak.  Pull over the overlap and follow the sparse bolts with run-outs to the top.  Go up to right and back up to the left for the 2nd bolt.  Then back to the right and up to the left and upwards to the anchors.

name: Happy Radio
description: Climb to the 2nd bolt of Elastic Happiness and then left to the 3rd bolt of Texas Radio to the top of Texas Radio.  Serious penduluming fall potential into flake of Elastic Happiness when traversing from 2nd bolt to the 3rd bolt of Texas Radio.  Fyi, this is the crux.

name: Intensive Care
description: Start on Ambulance Blues.  After the first bolt, move to the right instead of moving up and traverse over to La Dolce Vita.  Move up and follow bolts for La Dolce Vita and finish on anchors for La Dolce Vita.  PLEASE SEE THE COMMENT BELOW FOR A MORE DETAILED DESCRIPTION

name: Matrimonio Feliz
description: Start on the first bolt of Pummel Jenga and up to the second bolt of Pummel Jenga and then up and to the left towards the 2nd bolt of Elastic Happiness.  At the 2nd bolt of Elastic Happiness, join Elastic Happiness.  Continue moving up and towards the 5th bolt of Texas Radio and then up and to the right to the anchors for Texas Radio.  A bit run-out and extremely thin between the third and 4th bolts (2nd and 3rd bolts of 6th Happiness).  There is the usual 35 feet between the last bolt and the top anchors.  From the top of the 1st pitch you can rap down, build an anchor and use it to TR other routes or you can head up and to the left to two rap rings.  This second pitch is 5.7 but has no bolts so be careful.  The great thing about this route is that you can do it even when the algae covered area is wet at the start of Elastic and Sixth Happiness.

name: Mexican Radio
description: Climb the first two bolts of Texas Radio and instead of veering off to the right, follow the bolt line up and to the left to the top.  Finish at the two anchors for Real Gravy.  Here you can continue up to the top and walk off or use the rap rings.  You can also move down and to the left to the anchors for Gravitron and rap here.  Do not rap from Mexican Radio "anchors".  You will not be able to pull rope through after rappelling!  You can set up an anchor on these two bolts and TR Itty Bitty Black Streak, Amazing Gravy or Real Gravy.  You can do a second pitch and can proceed up and to the right to two rap rings.  There are no bolts between the end of the first pitch and these rap rings.  Climbing for this second pitch is 5.7 but since there are no bolts, try to be careful!

name: Nerdwand
description: Starting on Ambulance Blues, traverse right to the third bolt of La Dolce Vita and belay from third and 4th bolts of Bold Talk.  In theory the 2nd pitch could continue traversing the wall to eventually reach the top of Texas Radio.

name: Prok
description: You must be completely solid at the grade before attempting this route.    Prok is a pseudo-acronym meaning "protect at the crack."    Start on the low angle slab, right of Prok wall. One bolt is found on the somewhat steeper headwall. This bolt protects the hardest moves of the climb. Continue up and find quality pro in the horizontal crack below the shallow dihedral. A bold runout with ground fall potential ensues after stepping over the crack and following reasonably well featured high quality rock along the shallow dihedral. Above the dihedral there are a few confidence inspiring chicken heads before an opportunity for quality pro is found at the overlap near the top. Mount the overlap and finish.    As far as I know the earliest route on Prok wall was Farewell to Arms, which is now known as Runamuck. Runamuck followed the arching horizontal crack from left to right, then continued up from the right side to access the attractive shallow dihedral. The dihedral was left as an unprotected runout. Prok likely went up a short time later. In keeping with traditional principles, the shallow dihedral was left unbolted. Accordingly, this climb carries an X rating. The shallow dihedral feature has since been the subject of retro-bolting arguments. (If the above noted history is inaccurate, please post up or PM me and I'll change it).

name: Pummel Jenga
description: This is the direct start to God's Elastic Acre. It begins to the left of Stranger Direct. It moves up the face to the left of Stranger than Friction where it joins Stranger than Friction and God's Elastic Acre at the 4th bolt. From there it veers up and to the left to follow and finish on God's Elastic Acre. You can do a second pitch of climbing as for all the routes on the shield or you can build an anchor and lower down to repeat or do other routes.

name: Real Gravy
description: This exciting and challenging climb involves multiple 5.11 sequences. Originally, it was sparsely protected by three bolts placed on lead, making it one of the boldest first accents done at Erock. Since then a few additional bolts have been added. As a result Real Gravy is now one of the Backside's better protected hard slabs. Nevertheless, there are places on this route where you must not fall. Don't blow the clip up at the second bolt. Also, long run outs should be expected on the lower angle 5.7 terrain found high on the wall.

name: Runamuck
description: The arch that makes up the first half of Runamuck is one of the more recognizable features on the right side of the Shield.  To find the start of the route, look for an hourglass shaped flake that leans against the base of the wall beneath the arch.  Climb the unprotected face for about 25 feet to the beginning of the arch (there is a good medium stopper placement here), and the follow it to the right (protects well with a variety of cams up to a #1 Camalot).  As you traverse to the right you will past a couple of bolts on the face below you.  At the end of the arch, place your last piece of pro for a while and turn the corner up into a small, shallow dihedral.  Climb to a headwall with a couple of cracks running through it.  There are a couple places here for small, spotty stopper placements that may or may not hold a fall, but the climbing is fairly positive to the anchor ledge.  You can either rap from anchors along the ledge, or scramble up and over the top.  Fun, thought provoking climb with a healthy runnout after the arch.

name: Sixth Happiness
description: Start on Elastic Happiness and climb to the 2nd bolt, then traverse up and to the left to the 5th bolt of Texas Radio.  Finish on Texas Radio.

name: Stranger Direct
description: Start below the 2nd bolt of Stranger than Friction and head straight up over the overlap to the 2nd bolt of Stranger than Friction and finish on Stranger than Friction

name: Stranger Than Friction
description: The start is slight right of the bolt line up a flake into a dish. Clip first bolt and move left to the second bolt. It is best to remove the first clip as it will cause rope drag. Move past the bolt using a mantle move. This gives way to the second (3rd) bolt. Climb up to a good stance and clip the third (4th)bolt and the next fun moves. A small crack and a fancy foot work gets you past this fun section. Once above the crack you encounter another mantle and access to the fourth (5th) bolt. Move a little left and climb up to a short ramp and the fifth (6th) bolt. A long run out of around 35' up and right takes you to the rap anchors and finishes the first pitch. The second pitch is on easy but run out rock to the top. There are belay anchors at the base of a large boulder at the top. You may also use the rap anchors that will deposited you at the base on French Route.

name: Texas Radio
description: Start is to the left of Elastic Happiness and to the left of the big oak tree.  First bolt is just over the initial overlap.  It shares start with Amazing Gravy and Mexican Radio.  Hard route with several bold run-outs.  At the 2nd bolt, veer off to the right and follow the next three bolts and head up to finish on two top anchors.  The route has several hard mantle moves.  After reaching these anchors, you can rap down or you can do a second pitch of 5.7 climbing that moves up and to the left to two rap rings.  Texas Radio shares anchors with several other routes on the Shield. There are no bolts between the top of the first pitch and these rap rings.

name: Smorgasbord
description: Smorgasbord is located on the right side of the wall and starts in a shallow obtuse dihedral formed by the Smorgasbord wall and the Triple Cracks buttress.  The exact line that you take it up to you - there are a number of variations that are all around 5.6.  The most obvious line climbs a grass seam for about 10 feet above the slab and leads to a large flake that climbs up and left.  Follow the flake around its left side to a ledge.  Small cams protect the flake, and bring long runners to reduce rope drag.  Scramble up a few feet to a two bolt rap anchor.

name: Strawberry Jam
description: Strawberry Jam marks the left side of the Smorgasbord area.  It is a large, left leaning fissure that is most often used as an easy route to the top of the dome.  Start off a large boulder and climb the deep crack to a tree at the top.  From the tree, you can either continue up to the top of the dome, or traverse right to the anchors on Texas Flakes and rap off.  The crack protects well with medium to large gear.

name: Texas Direct
description: Texas Direct is located just left of Texas Flakes and shares the same anchor.  It is your typical E-Rock slab route with positive feet and plenty of small holds as you climb (felt easier than 5.8).  Start below the Texas Flakes anchors and climb the direct line to them.  Theres no protection until your reach the ledge, so most people simply top rope it off the Texas Flakes anchors.

name: Texas Flakes
description: Texas Flakes is a great beginner's route located in the center section of the Smorgasbord Wall.  It climbs a series of large, left angling flakes to a spacious ledge with a tree.  There is good protection all along the route.  Bring some long slings to reduce rope drag, and beware of the rope getting caught behind one of the flakes.  Fun, easy climb.

name: Butter Ball
description: Butter Ball is located about twenty-five feet right of the Central Ramp, starts off a large, sloping ledge, and climbs the right side of the southwest face. This is the second bolted line on the main wall, to the right of Turkey Hooks/Butterfingers. Climb the vertical face on using deep, in cut holds that appear just when you need them. The climb is pretty sustained with a crux about 2/3 of the way up the route (thin face moves). Like Turkey Hooks, the anchors are set a way back from the wall. There is an annoying flake that makes rappelling or lowing hard on your rope best just to walk off. Requires long slings or webbing/cord to top rope. Good route, too bad it's so short.

name: Butterfingers
description: The face climb has several thin moves.  The crux comes after the third bolt where the holds are very thin prior to a jug near the anchors.

name: Central Ramp
description: This ramp is often used by rappellers and boy scouts. Sometimes used as convenient, but exposed access to the top. Not much of a climb really.

name: Mighty Dog
description: A great climb in a beautiful position.    Ascend the left side of the face past a horizontal break, and up the arete to the top.

name: Turkey Hooks
description: Turkey Hooks is a fun climb up a short, right facing dihedral.  Work up the dihedral past three bolts to a small, left angling ramp about 3/4 of the way up.  The crux is the transition from the dihedral onto the ramp which requires a couple of thin moves on the face that lead to the ramp.  Pass one more bolt en route to the anchors.  The anchors are set a little ways back from the top of the route, so it is best to rap the route or use long slings if you want to top rope.

name: Turkey Ridge
description: This solo scramble climbs the exposed and unprotected Southeastern Ridge of Turkey Peak. Walk off using the hikers trail found on the West side.

name: Windy Ramp
description: Start below the ramp and follow smaller than expected features up the ramp to a comfortable stance below the headwall. Work your way up the left wall and into the notch, from which you can top out. Beware of a few hollow sounding jugs near the top.

name: Black Flag
description: Sit start right hand in the good small hueco close to the arete on the right side of the Bow. Use the ledge/thin seam for the left. Head straight up through the old rusty hanger to the top of the wall, finishing on the flint blocks.

name: Flexin’ Texan
description: Sit Start at the base of the large flake That runs from the ground to the top of the wall. (Prominent feature on the Bow.) Follow the flake to the top of the wall. BEWARE: The obvious jug mid-way up the route is loose. Please avoid using it. There is also loose rock in the crack near the top.

name: Jolly Roger
description: Sit start in the low baseball-sized hueco. Move right into the flake/undercling. Follow the pockets up the thin seam to the ledge before the vein of loose rock. Going to the top is trivial.

name: Pool Party
description: Sit start on the positive low ledge and head straight up through thin holds to the underclings under the upper face. Pull through to the top of the wall.

name: Black Hole
description: Star sitting low in the cave on a double-jug. Feet stay up out of choss and anything under the blocks. Move right out off the cave.

name: Black Hole Center
description: Sit start in the back of the cave on two jugs. Move up the center and out right to the Hueco rail. Then break left into the thin slot rail and top out right of center.

name: Black Hole Left
description: Sit start in the back of the cave, and up the center. Head left to the thin slot rail. Top out left side.

name: Baby Steps Direct
description: Start off on the ledge and head straight up. The side pull is a right hand Gaston that will lead you straight up through the pocketed hueco feature. Great feet.

name: Baby Steps Left
description: Start shared with Baby Steps, but head up and left to the obvious Hueco. Continue up and left to top out on ledge at 12 feet.

name: Baby Steps Right
description: Pretty consistent, easy intro climb. Straight up  and break right 12 feet to the ledge. Should have a decent left hand side pull and great feet. Top out right side of the pocketed indentation.

name: The Beholder
description: Start on the good ledge, break right into laybacks up into a good hueco. Finish at the ledge above.

name: Chimera
description: Great warm up, multiple exits. Crux is the last few moves to the ledge.

name: Dish Digger
description: Sit start on the two low left edges. Break right to the crimp, then straight up through the poor dish to the top of the wall.

name: Purple Rain
description: Crux is likely the lower traverse, or the high left hand crimp next to the pinch. Stops at the good ledge at 12 feet

name: Swiss High
description: Starts in the low obvious Hueco on poor feet. Traverse up and left, following good hand hold over the bulge. Continue left across poor feet with good hands into the Hueco.

name: Swiss Low
description: Same Start as Swiss High in the obvious low hueco. Traverse left through poor feet and sharp pockets to the same Hueco finish. Any holds at or above the bulge are off.

name: Beavis and Buttcrack
description: Sit start in the dihedral in the shallow/slopey softball-sized hueco. Move up through the dihedral to the crack. Continue up the crack to the top of the block sitting above the crack.

name: Depressin
description: Sit-Start matched on a good hole then go up to a left facing pocket and right along a crimpy-undercling flake. Press into a meat hook, reach okay holds to the crack, and top out the crack. Downclimb or bushwack your way back around.

name: Karmakazi
description: King Line right of The Bow. Sit start on the flake left of the overhang. Break right, and under the face from the start, and stay low. Use the edge of the face (Holds no more that 6” away from edge) and the slats underneath to cross and top out on the right side of the block.

name: Karmakazi Right
description: Start in an undercling low. Traverse right and up to a small pocket on the blank face, then go for the top.

name: Pocket Protector
description: Climb up onto the ledge right of the dihedral, and through the pocketed face to the ledge.

name: Starscape
description: Start sitting at the flake and break right to onto The face. Minis and pockets to flint finish at the ledge. Top out over Karmakazi for tick. Move pads out to drop off.

name: Lechuguilla Fingers
description: Face climb up to the crack. Climb it, then go left and up around the lechuguilla.

name: Red
description: Climb the column between the two corners.

name: Right Corner
description: Right-facing dihedral.

name: Thread
description: Crux is getting off the ground. Thread the small tunnel to protect the first moves.

name: Acrylic
description: Start the climb sitting down using the obvious rail.  Move to the pocket then work your way back to the right using small small crimpers until you get to the crack right before the top out.

name: Bent Yucca
description: Start sitting down with and initial reach to a good hold and work your way up the center of the face using crimpy holds.

name: Bloody Reef
description: Start on parallel sidepulls and pull up in a scrunched posistion to a sharp crimp. The arete is off.

name: The Iron Giant
description: Sit down start under the mini roof, use a knee bar to start with bad hands.  Move your hands up to the obvious Rail center of face.  Work your left hand up to secret hold and slap your right up the edge to get a final foot on and top out.     All Orange colored rock is off and should not be used.  It is likely to break.  (  Eyes of the Iron Giant)

name: Lil Merms
description: Start as low as possible with both has on the arete side.  A quick three moves up and around will finish this climb.  V-Fun for the extreme beginner or just someone who likes to climb on everything.

name: Maybe next time sucka!
description: Sit start left hand on the lower protruding rock, right and in the pocket behind. Move up using the best crimps on the face. Very slabby. Looked like it's never been climbed before or at least not in years.

name: Refried Beans
description: A small but tricky cap-rock boulder problem.

name: Sick Cat left
description: Start on the rail deep into the left with both hands matching and a left heel hook.  The original start on the nob is loose and should not be used.  Throw right to the deep pocket and then use crimpers straight up to the top.  All big ledges in the center of the boulder are off route.

name: Sick cat right
description: Star sitting down under the roof with a left hand in the obvious pocket.  Work your way up the the very sharp crack shooting off to the right.  Follow this crack right and top out.

name: Sick kids
description: Starts on a decent rail in front of a good jug (the only good jug inside the cave) the exit and top out are difficult so good padding and spotting is recommended. The moves are hard and somewhat painful but it's one of the best problems at the palisades.

name: Intro Ramp
description: This route shares the first two bolts with Yellow Line then cuts right to the second set of chains.

name: Lost Padre
description: Best route on the wall curently.  This is the bolted route to the far right on the other side of the major crack/roof.  It's the only set of bolts and chains currently on the right side, although there's certainly plenty of rock to add more routes.    Starts on a crimpy bare section leading to the crux roof.  Plenty of bolts provide adequate protection.  Staying left after the roof is easier but more chossy.  Staying right after the roof is more challenging and probably ups the grade.

name: Stiffy
description: Use liebacks and sidepulls up a vertical crack that turns horizontal to the right.  Mantle up the ledge to the chains.

name: Yellow Line
description: Left most route.  Shares first two bolts with Intro Ramp.  Chains are to the left; Intro Ramp's chains are to the right.

name: Girls with Guns
description: This route climbs the boxy ledges to a arching hand/fist crack to finish.

name: Grain of Sense
description: A steep, difficult, yet rewarding lead climb. Follow the thin, lie-back, finger crack, system. Stick-clip the first bolt. This route is labeled #8 on the wall.

name: Homogenized
description: This pumpy line follows the white water streaks to a small roof and over to the belay anchors. Finishes exiting both left or right from the small roof. This route is labeled 9 on the shot of ?Flower Power Ledge?.

name: Last Nights Pudding
description: Follow easy ledges and cracks to the chains. This route is labeled 1 on the wall.

name: New Dragon
description: Follow the ramp to a good rest ledge. Then continue up the steep face to the chains on good rock.   This route is labeled #5 on the wall.

name: Squeeze the Cheese
description: Climb the blunt arete. Then left and up. This route is labeled #3 on the wall.

name: Last Chance
description: A short, crimpy climb, on a flat face. The two bolts are easily visible. Natural anchoring is required. Can easily top out and just walk off.

name: The Dagger
description: The crux is the beginning of the route with its boulder like moves. Once you've made it to the base of the left facing dihedral the route follows a straight line up to the hangers for anchors.

name: Mini Roof
description: This route feels like a highball bouldering problem, but there are spots to add protection. It's a pumpy start, leading to the crux coming out of the roof. Great problem to top rope with its chain anchors at the top.

name: Picnic Rock
description: Start from the picnic table and scramble up to a ledge (this section is unprotected). From the ledge you can see the first bolt. The route only has two bolts for protection making it fairly run-out. Natural anchoring is required.

name: Rosewood
description: Rosewood is a classic route that sends the headwall's center face. This route has a great variety of holds with the crux being the upper section of the face using some excellent crimpers.

name: Space Seed
description: This quality boulder problem starts on the walls right end and traverses left along the hand rail. Gain the overhung face and continue traverseing following lie-back holds and jugs up to the finish ledge. Traverse left to walk down and off.

name: The Wizard
description: This route climbs a steep face section of rock with 3 golts and 1 piton to a single bolt anchor that can be backed up with a #2.5 cam.

name: Sweeper Crack
description: Begin sitting down on the diagonal cracks far left end. Traverse along the deep diagonal crack from left to right. Eventually ascend up the blunt arete on good holds via a small rest ledge then the top.

name: Cool Hhwhip
description: Follow the prominent crack running up the center of the wall's face. Top out at a miniature ledge before heading towards a smaller crack on the left side of the wall's face. Finish the route by veering right to top out at the wall's center. Natural anchor required.  High potential for loose rocks, beware belayer's position and don't forget a helmet.

name: No Turning Back
description: Start left of the yucca, head up towards the mini horizontal crack, move right towards the small vertical crack, follow this up until the rock quality changes, you've now entered the crux (slightly runout section), continue heading straight up towards the next crack, leading to a mini chimney like feature (beware loose rock) before toping out.

name: Send or Get Sent
description: This climb could start at the base of the wall, but due to rope drag and rock fall, scrambling to the flat ledge just under the crack could offer a safer belay station.  From the upper ledge - Follow the crack up the most obvious line which trends left and widens at a diagonal crack before topping out. Large boulders to sling for anchors after topping out.   From the base - head up the water carved formation towards the cactus, top out, use an undercling to traverse to the base of the crack, and then refer to the beta above.  This climb could be climbed as a top rope. It protects well the entire climb, but the fact that you are climbing a giant detached wall becomes more obvious the higher you climb.

name: East Ridge
description: Once you've reached the base of the rock on the east ridge, use your route finding skills, and adventure climb to the top. The lower areas we checked out we're pretty loose, so we hiked north and climbed 2 or 3 short pitches ending in a brushy bowl below the east face (there are several moist, moss-filled caves people have clearly camped in over the years). From the caves area, we traversed left/south to gain the east ridge again. This is where the best climbing starts. It's fairly easy, but quite exposed at times. Many will not need a rope, but less experienced climbers will appreciate the security of a belay from above.

name: East Ridge Direct (Variation)
description: Follow directions for the East ridge of south Franklin Mountain, but stay to the true ridgeline without veering like the original first ascent. Rock is surprisingly good, but protection can be hard to find at times.  About 2/3 of the way up the ridgeline will be the crux; a small roof with a tension move and high step to climbers left. Protection is fairly poor here.  Ascend to the top and descend to Ron Coleman trailhead off of Transmountain Highway.

name: Barton crack
description: L of the bolted arete, climbs the crack/slab to an old pin, then direct up. Alternatively step L after the 1st pin to a slab and thin crack and passing another pin.

name: The Big Boss
description: R most route on the L most wall in the gully

name: Chauffeurs crack
description: widish crack L of Colles route

name: Cocoa Butter Kisses
description: This route follows a prominent crack heading up the center face of the wall. It is a great route to practice gear placement in a vertical crack. Potential lose rock while topping out. Natural anchor required. Scramble to the anchor of Spanish Fly for rappel.    Potential to top rope route if you lead Spanish Fly and scramble down to the ledge that this route tops out on.

name: Colles route
description: second bolted line on the left as you enter the enclosure of red rock. south facing. Climbs a short crack to step left after the 2nd or 3rd bolt to climb the slabby arete to make a delicate move L and up to the anchors.

name: Desert Dog
description: scramble up the slabs to the L of the waterfall route. There is a 2 bolt anchor. Continue past this to the next crack on the R wall of the gully. This is the route. Fingers to hands. At the ledge, dont chicken out, step L to climb the crimpy wall past a crucial green alien sized placement to reach another ledge and a 2 bolt glue in rap station.   The 2nd best crack in the Franklins!

name: Fist of Fury
description: All the following routes are situated in a steepish gully up and R of the main waterfall. It is west facing. ( the path's origin can be found opposite Colles arete.) This route takes the L most crack system on the first buttress one encounters. This first buttress has 3 bolted sport routes. the second wall has 2 bolted sport routes routes and the third has only one longer bolted route going from R to L and 2 trad routes going from L to R.

name: Flóki
description: A scramble up to a short crack. The crux of the route is bumping into the crack. Potential loose rock if you stem too far out on the right, but the crack itself is solid for protection. Proceed up the crack towards the tree. The tree can act as a natural anchor or scramble left towards the bolted anchors of Spanish Fly.

name: the Green Hornet
description: steep slab with cool balance moves on pinches

name: Griffindor crack
description: crack in the back of the bay, to the L of waterfall route.  Scramble up slabs 15m to a double bolt belay on the R wall to keep you out the way of any falling rocks.  continue up to the deep corner system. One inital hard section on great smooth rock, then easier to the top. increasingly loose after the hard section, be very careful at the top. (OS 1st FA)  Walk off to the R and enter the top of the waterfall, down-climb to the anchors of waterfall route and abseil (35m)   or after the inital hard section low down step R to the abseil rings on Desert Dog. (recommended)

name: LIttle Devil
description: just R of Griffindor crack is a short groove with 3 bolts. Stem up this to a glue in anchor (2bolts)

name: Longstreet
description: Rising Rwards traverse on 12mm PS Fixe

name: Original Route
description: R to L crack to ledge with anchor

name: parallel lines
description: the L most crack on this wall. Finish up the corner or directly pull over the small rooflets for more exposure

name: Smith's Arete
description: The first bolted route on your Left when you enter the red rock area of thunderbird, south facing, Easily climb the slabby arete past 5 plated steel 10mm bolts, to a steep finish and a 10mm glue-in bolt. Go direct (5.4?) or easier R wards to twin Glue-in anchors and lower offs. Loose and dusty so bring a helmet and watch your belayer. It should clean up with time

name: Spanish Fly
description: Climbs a short crack (wires) to 2x bolts on the slab and move R to join the corner system and some bigger cams to the double bolted lower off.(Thundercrack is almost directly above these anchors )

name: Thundercrack
description: This is probably the best crack climb in the franklins. It starts either at the sport route at the bottom or one of the dihedrals to the left or right up to a 2 bolt anchor. Climb your way up features and ledges over loose rock untill you get to the base of the crack, the good climbing doesent really start till the base of the 40 foot  hand crack where you set up an anchor. The crux is the top where it becomes slick fingers and you must reach up to a jam. Slings at top.   Disclaimer: im assuming that i got the first ascent people right but if not just let me know

name: Unknown
description: Farthest R is a crack corner. fairly new anchor on top of the block

name: Waterfall route
description: Climbs the dry waterfall all the way in the back of the thunderbird. almost north facing.

name: Way of the Dragon
description: middle slab to crack. Techy and a bit pumpy

name: X Fix
description: Climbs Rightwards and upwards following bolts to cross both the trad crack lines , needs 2 pieces of gear as you pass the cracks (green/red/yellow cam will do.)

name: Fire Eater Cafe
description: Easy start to a reachy sequence some 10 feet above ground. Cruxy for some other 15 feet, fun and challenging to an easy finish

name: Great Escape
description: Start to the left of spirit. Ascend climbers left of dihedral using positive and small holds. Gear anchor to be built at top

name: Green Line
description: Climb up and right through a fun section between a couple of rocks up top. Another good beginner lead.

name: Holiday
description: Decent mixed lead climb that needs only 2 pieces of gear. Use the same anchor as Mona to TR.

name: Mean People Suck
description: The crux is midway up the climb with a mellow finish. The moves on this climb are fun and solid.

name: Mona
description: This climb has good solid crimps and intermediate holds all the way to the top.

name: The Nock
description: Stay to the right and lie-back the arete past 2 bolts. After the bolts climb the jugs to the anchor. It gets easy after the bolts but don't fall cause you'll be hurtin.

name: Paws for Thought
description: The climb has fun obstacles with huge features. From the fourth bolt you can finish straight up or bail off left.

name: Pop
description: Crux is mid way up this technical climb. Lots of fun movements with good holds.

name: Skin Diver
description: Climb goes into a dihedral section of rock and then goes to good crimps to finish it out.

name: Spirit
description: Easiest climb in Sneed's with bomber holds. Good to start on for beginners.

name: Star Fighter
description: This climb is overhanging with powerful moves. Very popular cause it's one of the best climbs at Sneed's Cory.

name: Straddler
description: This climb has fun technical moves that takes a bit o' strategy. The finish is the hardest section so try to conserve your energy. You'll find a good rest half way up while "straddling" the climb.

name: Terra-Tex
description: Short but surprisingly sustained/pumpy route.    Start with a tricky traverse right into good underclings but delicate feet. Then move upwards into some flakes and get a semi-rest in the sudepulls/underclings of a beautiful arch. The starting traverse and the final crimps are difficult, but the crux for most is finding good feet and making a big move out of the undercling arch to a crimp. Gave it a PG13 because the cruxy sections are on delicate feet and most falls occur as a result of slipping feet and are not so controlled. Depending on your beta there is a possibility to swing into or hit the platform to the right.

name: Broken Tower
description: Gain, then climb the right edge of the triangular tower, and finish directly up the cracks above.

name: Cleaned crack
description: Thin, discontinuous cracks protect the lower slab. Upper section finishes up the shallow, left-facing corner.

name: Finger tip crack
description: Low angle, face and crack.

name: Flared Slot
description: Large, flared crack/groove left of center.

name: Photobomb
description: Start at the top of a rock pile off to the right of the trail. The first 10' or so will be loose as hell, but once you get over the first ledge it gets a little more solid. Ride the first crack until it starts to get bulgy/overhung. Traverse right to the chimney. If you put your anchor where we did, you will be a good ways to the right of the anchor. Slither your way up to the top of the chimney. Go straight up to the top. CAUTION: there is an enticing hold several feet from the top that you'll likely want to grab with your right hand, it's a death block! I may have moved it enough for it to be a bit more obvious, but finish the climb with care.If you're a more adept crack climber, there's great potential for the line actually intended to take if you take the first crack all the way up and pull the roof of the second crack.

name: Hidden Sea
description: Ends at the last bolt below the final roof. The topout is unsolved.

name: Lost Guides
description: Climb up and right on edges past a bolt until you can get a hand in a flexible flake. Reach up and right to get on a small hollow ledge. Get the second bolt and climb to the top.  Belay or rap from small trees. To walk down contour along game trails a short distance and downclimb 2 or 3 moves. Don't go to far to your right-you may wind up on talus.

name: Because you Climb Too Much
description: Start of the same flake as Ol Butter Water then move left to a different third bolt and a white cave. Climb straight up the face on bouldery moves reaching left for desperate holds and the chains.

name: Everyone's Hero
description: Climb the dihedral and under cling out right into a flake.

name: Farewell to Texas
description: Tough and balcncybip the arete to a blank slab.

name: Lone Star Arête
description: SDS on side pulls and work up arête to large slab...now mantle. It's a very interesting top out... I about poooed myself but managed. Lol

name: Low Tide
description: Start hidden sea through the first roof and cop a knee-bar before embarking on a difficult traverse to the right.

name: Mantle Overboard
description: Traverse and mantle out onto the face.

name: Off the Hook
description: Start in the cave and climb the 90 degree roof using the crack or big moves on jugs out to the lip. The FA apparently went out the crack feet first, placed the last bolt on the slab above and ran it out to the top-out. No known second ascent.  Have your belayer anchor to the first bolt.

name: Ol' Butter Water
description: Jam the flake and undercling the chossy roof to reach the crack. Climb straight up the face.

name: The Prater Shuffle
description: Climb the left angling off width. 3-5 Camlot protects the moves to the anchors after the first few bolts.

name: The River Runs Like Hotdog Sauce
description: Pull a hard move through a choss roof and rest up before traversing left onto a varnished face with pockets.

name: Arête-dactyl
description: The tall obvious arête with cracks running up along either side. Sit start and climb directly up avoiding the protruding rebar near the top. Top out and either drop down or down climb the tree on the other side of the wall.

name: Dinohedral
description: The dihedral directly left of Arête-dactyl. Start matched on a small vertical protrusion at mid torso level and climb directly up topping out at the top. Either drop down or down climb the tree on the other side of the wall.

name: Sarahs back in town
description: Sit start near the far left side of the mini roof. Feet to the left and right with matching hands on the hold above. High right crimp, and mantle up. Go straight up from there.

name: HOUSTONE
description: Fun Route alongside of a playground. Good pump after a cardio start.  It can be fun vertically, with a decent crimp too finish The traverse across holds the true pump and can be fun for those looking to keep busy.

name: Anything but Dull
description: Climb up great rock on huecos and rounded holds with some pretty long reaches. Committing moves through the middle portion of the problem. Might be dusty due to lack of traffic.

name: Double Pecan
description: Start underclings and find cryptic sequence through roof to gain the lip. Trend right and up. The Wilder guide doesn't give this climb much love, but it has great movement. The Wilder guide also gives this climb a V9, but once the beta is unlocked, this problem is more in the ball park of a solid V7 or soft V8.

name: The Fin
description: The venerable classic, and the main reason to drop your pads at the Aircraft Carrier.   Start on the head-height jug moving into the arete with a couple positive holds, then a sloping side-pull.  Use your arete skills to gain balance for the lip, or just move into it with some swing.  Finish slightly left.

name: The Locksmith
description: Starting on the obvious jug, pull a couple easy moves going right to set up for a rather big throw to the positive lip with an easy top out.

name: Snakebelly
description: Sit start on the obvious jugs about 10 feet further in the cave, and then finish The Fin.

name: Unlock This AKA:The Locksmith sit-start
description: The sucktastic climb that is Locksmith is completely redeemed with the low start in the big hueco.  Undercling to the crimp and toe-hook to acquire a right hand.  Here's where it gets tricky as the toe release can send you off.  Figure out the balance then throw to the start hold of Locksmith while keeping your feet off the pads.  Finish out on Locksmith.      This appears to be a newer route but has excellent movement rivaling the classic of the area.

name: Winged Victory
description: Start on good holds and figure out how to get to the next set of jugs.  Most campus but there is some toe hook beta as well.  Once the next set of jugs have been obtained head up on easier moves to one more tricky move to get established on the face.  Keep it together for the high topout and beware of any Hueco choss.

name: Eh
description: start low on left hand crimp right hand slpoer gaston cross to right hand crimp and up, v0/1 starting one move in

name: French Kiss From Grandma
description: Climb begins on low edges on right hand boulder. Make a few moves up until you can transition out on to the boulder to your left using a small hueco and horizontal crack. Get established and climb straight up and to the right on the excellent iron rock face.

name: The Hourglass
description: Stem and/or pull inside of a huge hourglass shaped hueco to the lip, then make a tricky mantel over the top.

name: the humidifier
description: start on crimps at about shoulder height, biggish move to large hueco up and right

name: Its not the heat
description: on the humidifier boulder, dinky warm up

name: Macaroni Grill
description: Sit start with low crimps right of the white section of rock. Go to a left-facing flake and then continue up.

name: massive cool
description: fun climb

name: Strange brew
description: warm up, start on chalked crimps go straight up

name: Uncut Yogi
description: Make moves up pitches and the arete until you can move right to a pocket and up on crimps. The start hold on this problem is getting very greasy and presents a real problem when you are standing on it as your feet need to stay to hold the terribly sloping hands.

name: Belly of Burden
description: This short problem contains one or two really fun moves but the difficulty is open nearly as soon as it start.  Worth doing if you are here for "Belly of the Beast".    Start on the obvious slopers and move rightwards to a good hold on the arete.  Rock over on the arete and climb V0- moves to the top.

name: Belly of the Beast
description: This problem would be ultra classic if it weren't for the other boulders adjacent that are difficult not to dab on.  Start on crimps at the lowest part of the roof, and make cool moves along the rail.  At the end of the rail make a big move to a good hold over the lip of the boulder.  Figure out how to adjust / cut your feet without dabbing and move rightwards thru jugs to an easier but pumpy finish.  If you are tall / strong enough to reach the good hold over the lip from the good right hand then this will likely be an easy tick for the grade.

name: Porn Again
description: Maybe the closest backcountry climb to any parking lot? A worthy climb if you're looking for something in this range on the way out of the park  On the right side of the boulder, start sitting and go up system of holds and arete to the top.

name: The Real Bruce Lee
description: Looks intimidating, especially with no chalk on the holds, but a V0 nonetheless with excellent movement for the grade on bullet ironrock. Pretty bad landing but could be made pretty safe with 5+ pads.

name: Backdoor Man
description: Start on the high right facing flake and climb up on great holds to the top.  The first moves are the hardest, but the top gets quite high.

name: Dark Angel
description: Climb the crack in a corner. You can jam straight in, layback or stem. The crack is almost all hand sized for those with average sized mitts.

name: Heartbreaker Traverse
description: The crux is near the middle and the landing is flat.    Climb edges and sidepulls up the right side of the blunt arete until you can move around to the left onto the main wall at an angling shelf. Paddle your feet on terrible holds and thrutch up and left to the next shelf. Get yourself organized and continue along the improving shelf to the top at Dark Angel.

name: Jamocha Joe aka Purple Bunny Fuckers
description: Start on the great left facing flake under the large roof.  Make a large move out to a good hold and try to keep your feet on the wall, or cut them and keep them off the ground.  From here turn left and make a big move to a slopy pocket.  Get a good undercling, and cross into a horizontal seam.  Work this slightly left and make a big throw to a huge jug.  Match here and drop off or continue up the chossy squeeze chimney and walk around through on the kitty litter ledge.    Name and Grade are both guesses as this is a fairly new problem, and I couldn't find it on Nick's scorecard.

name: Jiffy Pop
description: Weird press/mantle thingy to a seam and chossy top out or chimney.    Start from a jug rail and move up and left on a sloper. Figure out how to get up to the seam 8 feet above you. Once in the seam work up that to the top. At this point you will be below a cap stone and the holds moving right out from under it are choss, however the opposite wall of the corridor is right behind you. What you do is up to you.

name: Julio and Me
description: This problem starts on the shared underclings of Le Chnickel but moves right traversing a ways until you get to an interesting lip encounter that has multiple solutions.    Beta:  (if I can remember right).  Start matched on the underclings and get a funky right kneebar.  Reach out left hand to a crimp and then get a right foot heel/toe cam.  Cross to the pinch left hand and drop your right hand down to a sloper that will allow you to readjust your left hand to change the thumb-catch on the pinch.  Step left foot on the crimp you just used for your right hand and surge out to the arete.  Swing feet over.  From here there are multiple sequences that involve (1) doing a high tension move to allow you to match your left hand to the arete and reach up to the jug, (2) bumping blindly all the way to the jug (that's what I did) or potentially even (3) going feet first and toehooking the jug blindly and then matching it to top out.  3 stars for cool holds, unique movement and beta and decent landing, -1 star for an indirect line and PG-13 for the potential landing in the yucca doing the redpoint crux.

name: Rose Fruited Juniper
description: Start on the great left facing flake under the large roof. Make a large move out to a good hold and try to keep your feet on the wall, or cut them and keep them off the ground. From here throw left hand to a slopy pocket and work the core tension to bring your right hand up to a good crimp.  From here traverse straight right crossing your left hand into a good pocket.  Now figure out how to obtain and match the miserable crimp directly right.   Once matched move right to a good sidepull and stand up to an undercling.  Finish up the easy slab.    Originally rated V11 but if I could do it then it's not V11, so grade is my guess.    Named after the Large Juniper that's in the area.  That Juniper tree is the oldest living thing in the park.

name: Something Different
description: Start on juggy crimps and follow a set of crimps til a throw move out left.  Match and punch to the arete again for the delicate top out.  4 stars for excellent holds, movement, obvious line and landing.

name: Swirl Wall
description: Standing start from the lower left on a small rail. Traverse right and up on decent holds to a cool, balancy mantle to a crimp. Make another move or two to the rollover lip and some friable holds. Use a bit of caution topping out. Walk off left.

name: Tall Cool Red One
description: An amazing highball with a good landing.    Start out by moving up past the right edge of the large scoop feature. Then head left across the scoop aiming for the sloping ramp that leads up to a white jug, crux. From the jug a huge move gains the obvious flake and another big move to the lip. Beware of loose rock over the lip when topping out.

name: Taxing the Pipe
description: Arete and compression climbing on perfect rock.  More about finesse than power.    Start on double underclings and lunge to a sloper.  Bump your left hand up the arete and make a hard move to a sidepull on the face.  Shuffle up the arete some more, go to another sidepull.  Move your feet out right, cross over to a sloper, match, and fire for the lip.    The last 3 moves are the hardest.  Would get 4 stars if it wasn't so close to other boulders.    The PG13 comes from the eerily close wall behind you when you toss for the top.  No one ever hit it, but it feels like you could.

name: Ultramega
description: This problem beings low (no lower) on the "holster" pocket and another jug.  Start crossed and move through the jugs until you get to an undercling.  Reach out left to an ok pocket and bicycle.  THe crux is the next two moves establishing on the next thin finger lock pocket and then reaching up to a crimp work your feet to a good foot out left and reach a juggy pocket.  Cross left hand to the next crimp then cross back underneath your left hand to an undercling jug.  Slap up to the lip and bump until you can get a left heel hook on the lip and (red point crux) surge out to a good right hand crimp.  Rock over.  3 stars for awesome holds, movement and obvious line, -1 star for the slab at your back which is annoying more than anything.

name: Ventral Fin
description: Sit start on a sloper and crimp. Climb the overhanging arete and face.

name: William's Lectric Shave
description: Start on edges around 5ft and go left hand to a sidepull. fall into the razor thin vertical crimp thingy and make a biggish move to the lip. exit up and slightly right.

name: El Burro
description: Start low on opposing sidepulls.  Make challenging moves on slopey pockets to another tricky move towards the top.  From here things ease off for the topout.  The Wilder guide mentions that this is "A challenge for any V3 climber - V10 climber for that matter."  It held up to it's reputation as I found it just as challenging as the harder lines on the wall.

name: Left Donkey Show
description: This classic line may be easy if you have enough reach, or extremely challenging if you can't reach the horizontal rail.  Start on a sidepull and jug at 6 ft, make a move into an undercling and make a big reach for the horizontal rail.  The rail is good enough to cut if you need to.  Continue up on a few small crimps to an easier topout.

name: Nuns and Donkeys
description: Start on a high undercling and make a easy move to an ok crimp.  Here figure out what to do with your feet and figure out how to get to the sharp jug.  From here things get easier but the holds though positive are still small.   Save some energy for the topout which contains more choss than jugs.

name: Two Moves for Sister Sarah
description: This one looks like it should be easy from the ground as it isn't real steep but the holds are smaller than standard for Hueco.  Make technical moves on small holds to a tricky top out.

name: Black, White, and Red All Over
description: Black, White, and Red All Over is not as classic as some of the other climbs in the area but certainly worth a try.         Start on a low crimpy rail and pull a few hard moves to an slightly chossy top out.

name: Brittany in a Blender
description: A very pretty problem, with unique holds and puzzling movement.    Sit start on an obvious slopey shelf and go straight up using edges, underclings, a very slopey pod, and some kneebar trickery until you reach two very small, sharp crimps on the lip of the roof.  Mantle up and left over a slightly scary slab.  Hence the PG13.

name: Brutus
description: While not quite as classic as some of the other V5's in the area (Dragon Fly, AKA: Dogmaticsand Hobbit in a Blender), this one is still worthy of some skin.    Starts just right of the thin arete Crimping Christ on a Cross on a positive flake about 7 ft off the ground.  Pull off the ground and make a few difficult moves up side pulls and crimps to an easy top out.

name: Crimping Christ on a Cross
description: Recommend taping your tips on this one.    From the sit, grab a few razor blades and a good pinch on the arete. Then move to a left hand hold that is just a tooth. Move up onto improving holds and into the crack. Follow the crack up and right to top out.    Fun climbing where you actually work the arete. You always have a hand and foot on each side.

name: Dragon Fly, AKA: Dogmatics
description: Once and still considered a mega-classic. Follow the left angling flake crack with good holds that are quite spaced and bad feet to its end on a monster jug. Make a huge move out left to an OK hold, heal hook right and go right hand to a gaston. Then swing the feet left to another heal and go to a left hand gaston, step up and top out.    Alternately, go the the right hand gaston with the left hand as a side pull and make a big move straight up the blunt prow over a worse landing for a slightly harder and more direct finish. Seems to be rarely done, but it is actually quite good especially if you've done the original finish multiple times.   Location   Just left of Dry Dock around the corner following the sweet left arching flake/crack.

name: Dragonfly Low AKA: Fish on a Stick
description: Start below the good left facing flake on Dragonfly, on pretty good underclings.  Smear your feet and make either a long move right up to the start hold on dragonfly, or bump to a bad sidepull then to the starting hold on dragonfly.  Finish up Dragonfly.    Probably a gimme at the grade.

name: Dry Dock
description: Crux is either the first move or the top out if you are figuring it out on the fly.  Many believe this hard for the grade.  This problem is SICK!!!!!

name: Dry Dock Low
description: Aka Wet Dock? Start matched on the lower undercling (where your feet go for Dry Dock) and finish Dry Dock.

name: Full Service
description: This is the original V10 at Hueco (the standard for V10, in fact), and it is still considered by many to be the best. It was one of the most sought after ticks in the '90's and it still is for that matter.  John Sherman originally envisioned the line and had done the stand, Lip Service, when Dale Goddard sent the full rig, calling it "Serves You Right." However, Sherman's name, "Full Service," seems to have stuck.

name: Hector in a Blender
description: This problem named in honor of the park ranger Hector, starts in Ides of March and ends to the left on Brutus. Hector always said he climbed and he understood climbers and what we were about, nice generalization since all climbers are definitly the same. Sometimes it's an honor to be put in a blender and sometimes not, Hobbit, Brittney, Alf etc. we'll leave this open to interpretation.    From the start of Ides of March make thin, long moves up and left into the middle of Brutus. The holds are particularly thin and sharp but is worth doing if you've already done Ides and Brutus.

name: Hobbit in a Blender
description: A great problem with a tough opening move and a comitting move up higher to a cool mantle. The start holds are reputedly chipped out to be better, though there is so much chalk on them now that it is hard to tell though it seems plausible.    Start on the two positive crimps and get one foot or the other on and bust a move out right to gaston at the bottom of the crack. Get a foot up near the start holds and fall in to match in the crack. Layback up a move or two and make a long move up to a jug at the top of the crack. You can top out straight up but it is better to do another long move out right to another jug and hand foot match on the first and mantle from here up to some edges on the face above.

name: Hooker with a Penis
description: Sit start with a low left hand. Sharp and uncomfortable holds, but the movement ain't bad. Only worth getting on if you've already done the other climbs...

name: Ides of March
description: The rightmost problem of the 3 on this face of the boulder.  Make sure you have a good spotter because of the boulder behind you.

name: Lip Service
description: Stand start to Full Service.

name: The Notorious D.I.G.
description: This problem starts on two crimps and does a lock off move to a odd incut pocket.  High right foot, hit the gaston and jump with the right hand to the lip.

name: The Ostracizer
description: Starts on a huge flake with the crux being the toss to the left after the flake ends.

name: Rembrandt Pussyhorse
description: Left most climb on the Sweat Loaf boulder, move up through opposing sidepulls or theres a couple good crimps as options too.

name: Satan, Satan, Satan
description: Really fun line of huecos on the far right side of the wall with Rembrandt Pussyhorse. Start as low as you can in the huecos and go straight up. The topout is the crux.

name: Strung Out
description: A short problem. Start matched in a slot (difficult for those with larger fingers). Make a couple deadpoints to reach the lip. Top out.

name: Sweat Loaf
description: Sit start in the middle of the Sweat Loaf boulder. Follow the fun huecos up, and make a big move left for the classic finish. Topout is probably easier than Satan, Satan, Satan.

name: Tri Hard
description: The stand start to Try Harder. Big moves on sloping huecos above a huge undercut roof.

name: Try Harder
description: This problem begins under the roof matched on an undercling.  Climbs through some compression moves until a toss into a pocket (inside a hueco).  4 stars for awesome holds, movement, landing and obvious line.      Beta:  Start  matched on the undercling and squeeze between two opposing feet.  Through out right hand to an undercling and toss again for a 90 degree angled sloper.  Right foot over to compress on a heel hook down and right of your hand.  Bump left hand into a bad pinch eight inches from the starting hold and switch your left foot from a heel hook on the starting hold to a good toe hook.  Sag.  Match the other 90 degree hold right next to your left hand.  Switch the right heel hook to pushing with your toe and do a dynamic move to the lip, you will begin to cut feet and swing out desperately so very quickly swing your right hand to an undercling a foot (back) into the cave.  Heel hook up and match the large hueco.  (This is the beginning of Try Hard FA Ricky O V5).  Cross into an undercling pinch at the top of the hueco and left hand to a decent crimp.  Switch you heel to a toe and surge up to a good but hard to hold hueco.  Match your right foot to your left and toe hook the right undercling by your hand, reach up (slowly... slowly...) to a jug on the lip rock over.

name: Love Muscle
description: Nice overhanging rig with a variety of movements and holds. Start matched on lowest hold.

name: Uncle Drunkie
description: Tall, vertical crimping at its finest. Truly one of the highest quality climbs at Hueco. Very tough for the grade.

name: Angry Painful Song
description: Starts a few feet to the left of the low roof of Wicked Twisted Road.  Angle slightly left and top out through the huecos on the high headwall.

name: Castle In The Sky
description: Good moves on great rock leading to looser rock and a very heady top out

name: Fearless Driving Rain
description: A tall V6 with excellent moves on excellent rock.  The crux is low, but the top keeps you paying attention.

name: Wicked Twisted Road
description: Start at the back of the low roof, climb out and onto very left side of the tall slab.  Downclimb the slab 10 feet to the right.

name: 3 Star Arete
description: Stand start for 3 Star Arete Sit. Start with the left hand flake then head right and up along the right side pull to a jug rail at the top. Topout then downclimb around the chimney in the back made by a slick boulder.

name: 3 Star Arete Sit
description: Starts on two low slopers and moves up through some crimps and into the vertical seam, carefully avoiding the baby cactus growing out of the rock. Crank up and into the large left hand jug that starts the V2 variation. Beware of loose rock at the top.

name: Babia Majora
description: Thoughtful beta-intensive lower section.

name: I Own It
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: I Own It Sit
description: Sit start at the low crimp rail. Move left through a few flat ledges, cross to a right hand sloper, and slap a sloper around the around. Move up through good holds to a large hueco on the left side of the arete and slab your way up. Watch for choss on the slab.

name: Meddle Detector
description: Start off with a big move/dyno to a comfortable jug out in the roof. Continue out on nice flake jugs untill you arrive at a couple of nice underclings. Get a knee scum to make a big move up to a sharp small crimp. Figure out how to use this to move left to another good hold at the bottom right of a huge depression, some foot trickery is required. Then traverse left along the base of the depression into teh corner which is followed to the top. Once you reach the corner the problem is pretty much over, you would have to try to fall off if you made it this far.   This is one of the best V6's anywhere. Fun movement, a good variety of hold types and moves. Long enough to not just be over. High enough to be somewhat commiting.

name: [Redacted]
description: Great diversity on a boulder problem. Great problem but can be painful, tape might help for the start.    Start out with a steep hands to cups crack. Then motor across the horizontal roof with some long reaches on pretty good holds. Finally fight through the bulge at the top on positive crimps.    Each section might be about V4 but by the time you get to the end you are spent.

name: Creamy
description: Traverse the horizontal crack up and left starting on crimp rail.

name: Dreamy
description: Start on jug rail around the corner from Creamy. Traverse right into same top out.

name: Lifestyles of the Steep and Heinous
description: A nice V8 version of a "step-off" Hueco roof climb (eg Baby Martini, Flower Power, etc).

name: Lucky the Wonder-Poodle
description: Start on a Jug and go straight up to spicy topout.

name: The Maiden
description: Amazing rock and features combined with a low crux make this a must do highball. In many areas this would be a 3-5 bolt sport climb.    Move up the short wall to the roof and reach over. use a heal to turn the lip, this in itself is getting to be kind of high. Now cruise up the 25 foot tall gorgeous wall of big huecos.

name: Otimojoginkbrute
description: Start sitting sitting on a right facing hold. Trend slightly right aiming for great jugs that set you up for a good top out

name: Sledgehammer
description: Very unique and entertaining movement on an overhanging arete. If you enjoy pinches, heel hooks, compression, and flexing biceps, this climb hits the nail on the head.    Start sitting, hugging the arete with a good right hand pinch and a pretty poor left hand pinch on the face. Make a lefthand move up to a slopey hueco and work into the opposing sidepull crimps. Clever technique should lead you to the marquee move maneuvering through the large, made to order, sledgehammer pinch. From here, span out left to a deep jug, and exit onto the slab.

name: Mystery Knobbler
description: Cute little boulder that packs a punch and has a surprising variety of movement. Sit-start with LH on good crimp and RH on low RH.

name: Two Days With Gene
description: 4-star highball in Wilder's book

name: Funk's Arete
description: Baffling that this is just now being added to MP. Sit-start with two hands on right side of arete, move left and up. One of the best for the grade in the park, no doubt.

name: Short Term Memory Loss
description: Start under the overhang on a good rail. Move up through a great underling with some potential kneebars. Work around the arete into a scoop, and finish up a few delicate slopers. Downclimb on the right.

name: Mooned
description: Start with a right hand side pull and either compress with the left on the arete or rodeo start up with the left to a good hold. Once the good hold is reached you have 2 choices, both are about the same grade. One option is to move to the left onto the slab and once up on it move back right around the arete to top out. Otherwise pull straight up the arete and finish slightly right.

name: Moonshine Left
description: This less popular Moonshine route is just as classic as the others imo.  Be prepared for a stout grade and quite a pump for a boulder problem.  Start in the shared pockets with the V4 "Moonshine Roof", and climb onto the diving board.  Where "Moonshine Roof" breaks right continue straight and around the corner thru challenging beta intensive moves.  Get established under the final roof with a good left hand and enter the crux pulling over the final lip to good holds above.  Some toe hook trickey can help to get matched on the final holds before the move to the jugs leading to the topout.

name: Moonshine Right
description: This fun climb was once a gimme for the grade, now that a large jug at the lip has broken off it may feel difficult for V5.    Start in the same pockets as "Moonshine Roof" climb out to the surfboard and continue straight.  Make a tricky move to get into the undercling and bump out to the lip.  Figure out how to keep the feet on to match the lip, and pull the tricky rock over onto the face.

name: Moonshine Roof (center)
description: Starting pockets rumored to have been chipped out, there is an alternate start that is no harder that does a couple of moves straight in line with the diving board if you need to have an unaltered ascent.    Start on a sloping boulder with hands in the two pockets, pull on and make a big move out the roof to a jug, make sure to keep the landing gear up or you will surely be dragging body parts across the boulder that you started on. Mount the diving board and work out left on the dual rails. At the end of the rails make big crux moves on slopers with heal and toe hooks on the diving board up into a higher section of roof. Eventually gain a jug under the lip, facing right reach over the lip to a hold and work up on holds that could be better.

name: Power of Landjager
description: Start low in the dihedral. Move out on jugs to a left hand crimp. Heel hook or dyno to the sloping jug and start hold of Sound of Power. Finish on that climb.

name: Sound of Power
description: The standing / jump start to the classic "Power of Landjager".  Start standing on a boulder and reach across to the flake jug halfway to the top.  Alternatively if you aren't super tall stack pads might take a few to get to the starting holds.  Once on make a big reach to a good hold, match and make another big reach to the top.  The holds at the top are good, but there isn't much to pull over on, and you are plenty high at this point.

name: The Banzai Knife
description: A hard start on crimps takes you up the initial face to where you can move left into the flake and over the higher landing platform. Follow the flake as it angles up and left above the higher landing area. At the end of the flake pull up to the sloping lip and make tough and intimidating moves onto the slab above.    The top out on this problem is not your typical Hueco Tanks finish, no jugs up there.

name: Blowdryer
description: Start on obvious hueco jugs on the pocketed face.  Climb up and right into the scoop.

name: Conservative Backlash
description: Spectacular balancy arete climb! Maybe one of the best V0s in the park if flat landings are a criteria for you.

name: Ginsu Wall
description: Fun problem on mostly small crimps.    Pull on edges in the horizontals to get up to the angle change where more difficult moves are encountered getting up onto the slab.     This problem is moderately intimidating as the hardest moves are a little ways up and the landing is not great.

name: Hobbit with a Boner
description: Great roof climb with seemingly horrific, but manageable start and finish "landings". Manageable, as in, it can be protected with good padding and spotters; but really, one should be confident in climbing in this grade range before giving this serious attempts IMHO.

name: Instant Classic
description: The name might be a little presumptive but still a worthwhile problem.    Start sitting in an undercling down on a slabby boulder. Work up positive flakes to a big angling rail out left. Then back right to the topout. The landing follows you on this one so you are never that far off the ground.

name: Low Dryer
description: Start in slopey undercling down low and hug your way up to Blow Dryer.  Don't know how the first ascentionist did the cruxy first move, but a proper sit-start definitely makes a difference compared to crouching, albeit not a grade harder imo.

name: Man Gum
description: This is a worth while problem if you are in the area and care to crush some small edges. The climbing is pretty straight forward with no trickery.    SDS and pull on thin edges up to the start of Ginsu Wall and finish that problem.    May feel easy for those with small and or strong fingers.

name: Snakecharmer
description: One of the best problems of the grade in the park.    Start on the right facing 3 finger jug at the base of the arete. Move up through the bulge to double pinches. Figure out some sneaky feet to get up to the next pair of holds, a slopy pinch and a good edge. Set your feet and make a scary move to the angling lip feature. Follow the lip up and right to top out where you can squeeze past the wall behind.

name: Peckercracker
description: The finger crack that splits the boulder. Start low for an extra challenge

name: Lungfish (aka The Sutra)
description: Start sitting with good crimps.  Move up and grab some kneebars to get to the obvious jug.  From here another hard move gets you to another good hold.  Now transfer to the boulder to the right and head up through better holds.

name: Mr. Freud
description: Neglected problem near s-curve area. Start on a high flake in the center of the scoop and climb straight up. Downclimb is to the right, you will find a flake to scramble down.

name: S-Curve
description: This interesting problem climbs a short slab to a technical traverse left.  It is low angle but the holds are small enough to keep things interesting.  After the traverse things change style with a difficult drop down onto good holds and a few more powerful moves to gain the arete.

name: Wutang
description: Start on the big undercling under the roof. Make a big move out to a crimp and climb steep crimps to a slightly chossy but juggy topout.

name: El Fin
description: Start matched on a good left facing J-shaped jug. Make a few tricky moves out and slightly left to gain the lip. Continue left on holds at the lip until you gain a massive left hand jug and roll over the top. You could probably top out straight out from the start, but it looks extremely chossy.

name: Silverback
description: Start with a good left and a bad right undercling. Make moves on crimps and set up for either a large throw, or some more crimps to gain a good jug. Another large move gains you the jug just below the lip and a fairly casual top out.

name: Amazing Little Halfboy
description: Move up through a few bad holds to two good jug flakes in the shape of a v.

name: Dwarf Toss Tragedy
description: The crux is moving from the crimp far right to the top. A fall could make you hit your head on the boulder problem behind you make sure you have a spotter behind you to prevent that from happening. Fun heel hook to the second hueco

name: Human Shot Putt
description: Sit start, casually climb up and then go to sex after death.

name: Miracle Baby
description: Start on Low good holds. Crank up to the V shaped hold and then up to a crimp before hitting the lip.

name: Sex After Death
description: Claimed to have been chipped, but I don't see it. In the Sherman guide books the ledge to the left is listed as off and pretty easy to avoid, if you are tall and it is on the problem is significantly easier, the newer Wilder book makes no mention of the ledge one way or another.    From the 3 finger pocket to start move up left to a tooth and crush to move right to a sloping 3 finger dish. Either jump or get a high drop knee to move up left to a sloping edge. Next out right to a sidepull and cross through to another sidepull. A long reach up to an angling crack that is good and is followed to the top.

name: The Trickster
description: A cheeky little freestanding bloc with a big circular flake that you maneuver around to get to top. Devious, yet obvious ;)

name: The Bulb of Percussion
description: Maybe holds broke, but the holds don't match guidebook instructions. Start with fat right hand pinch and left hand crimp, both at head height, and go up and right through obvious jug rail.

name: Lithic Technology
description: For full value, start with both hands on the lowest holds in almost a lay-down position (either way, still V4). Dynamic climb with cool holds and the sought-after ironrock.

name: [Redacted]
description: This unaesthetic problem requires good body tension, and confidence on poor slopers.      Start sitting with your hands in some very smooth scoops.  Pull off the ground and fire for a strange sloper/pinch feature.  Either campus or use heel hooks to move left to a decent spot in a huge hueco.  Throw in a kneebar and make a few more large lock offs between good holds, and escape right on friable rock.     Easy on the skin.

name: Automatic Choke
description: Climb out roof right of Crispy Critters. Start in break above the sotol, climbing up the prominent brown rock. Top out up and to the right.

name: Babyfat
description: Crimp route on kid stuff wall. It is next to juvenile offender.

name: Chocolate City
description: "Start on jugs at the left side. Go up to two crimps and then up to a hueco and a loose finish."

name: The Execution
description: Given V4 in the guide book, seems harder.    Start just right of The Guillotine. Move out from the horizontal onto a sloping left facing rail. A big move out to a good edge at the lip. Figure out what to do with this and make a loooong reach up to  horizontal and an easier top out.

name: Greasy Kid Stuff
description: Low start on big slopers and work your way up through a few good holds to a big reach to some sharp crimps to an easy topout.

name: The Guillotine
description: Located far to the right of Warm Up Roof.  Start on a big low flake and move up and right to a scary and sharp flake.

name: Juvinile Offender
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Li Stand
