description: The start hold is a horizontal pinch at head height with a good thumb catch on the bottom. There are many ways of doing this boulder so find the way that works best for you.

name: Mojo
description: Start on the "trailer hitch" hold and a foot out right power through hard to hold pinches and slap your way to the angled jug.  Most people drop off from here, but for full value do the top out.  The feet are choss, but as long as your track hands and feet you'll be fine.  3 stars for awesome holds, powerful movement and a fine landing.  -1 stars for being a drop off or for the chossy highball top out.

name: Thorny Toad
description: Left and right underclings under the roof, then throw for the lip.  Watch the swing then make a big reach to gain the face and top out

name: Warm Up Roof
description: Start low on the obvious flake and then climb up through big moves to good holds at the top.

name: Warmup Roof Right
description: Start in the horizontal crack just right of Warm Up Roof.  Move through a powerful undercling into a right hand pinch.  Set your feet and throw to the undercling shared with Warm Up Roof.  Match and continue up Warm Up Roof.

name: Young Guns
description: Crimp line to the right of greasy kid stuff.

name: Chutes and Ladders
description: Stellar looking line that improbably makes a reasonable boulder problem. Multiple place you could start, the lowest of which would involve a series of long pulls on positive edges while exposing yourself to a poor landing with evidence that some of those edges have crumbled.     However, if you start from the middle landing area from a high right edge and a seam the rock is very good and there are only really 2 moves that feel exposed. From the crimp work your way up the seam until you can reach out right to an edge in a horizontal, then punch up to a buggy rail. Move up past another rail and jugs at the top.

name: J-Lo
description: Sit start. Go up and left to the glory jug. Nice little rig on bullet rock.

name: more funky than hunky
description: The crux is pulling the roof   I like roofs   Good warm up

name: Preston Brown
description: Start at the bottom of the roof on horizontals. Move to the rail and then climb to the end of the roof. From here, climb left on huecos and mantle at the point.

name: Squeeze Me Tender
description: Start left on a crescent shaped side pull and right on an underclimg pinch feature. Use heel hooks to work up to holds on the lip. From here top out straight up or move slightly left and top out there.

name: The Egg
description: Great sloper problem. Graded V10 when first put up, I feel that the V8 grade from the guide book is a bit of a sandbag though V10 might be a bit generous.    Start in a left kneebar with some bad underclings, it might be possible to pull on without the kneebar, but it would be heinous. Reach out to a sharp jug over the lip and match. Your kneebar should kind of pop out easily considering how hard it is to get in in the first place, get a right toe hook. Reach left to some slopers and move your right foot to a heal on the jug and squeeze your left foot into the underclings. Mess around on the slopers untill you have a left false grip on the furthest left lump and ring your heal into the furthest right sloper. Move your right hand up into a crimpy undercling and smear your left foot on something just over the lip of the roof that looks as though you will not stick to it and hit the sloping rail up and left as a gaston. Bump your hand up untill you get to a good spot. Swing your left foot back under the roof to get a toe hook that is bad which allows you to match the sloping rail and push up and left to a jug at the top.    You can literaly slip off of just about any move on this problem which makes it pretty cool, you have to use your whole body to stay on the rock.

name: Flower Power
description: If you are strong enough this could be an easy tick or still impossible. It all depends on how the flying ninja kick at the end goes for you, easy for some, impossible for others, though there is alternate beta which makes the problem longer.    Start on a big tounge at the right end of the roof. Work your way left on sequency pockets untill you make a slap for a sloping bump on a vertical section of rock. Get a right toe hook to bump your right hand into a closer pocket. Then walk your feet through to a heal hook just below your left hand and pull up onto an alcove with an 8 finger fin that sticks down as an undercling. Walk your feet into the alcove in a kind of stem and match hands to go out left and out the roof to a better hold the a good right in opposition. Next reach up right into a scoop to a honeycomb crimp with a thumb catch then left to a fin that is a side pull/undercling. Get a big drop knee and make a long pull to a hueco, as you work further around the side it gets better. Now for the fun bit, cut your feet but don't try to check the swing, instead kick out for the boulder behind and to the right of you. Get your feet to stick, match the hueco and shoulder your way over to the vertical face and top out.

name: Glas Roof
description: From underclings got right to a nice long pocket that you can pinch at the bottom, then match with the left pinchig the top in a sort of back handed grip (with your palm facing you). Get a right drop knee and hit the crimpy pinch at the lip. Get a bicycle with your feet and bump your left hand out into another pocket. Then learn to foot jam and stuff your right foot in the pocket that you just matched. Reach up left to the 2 finger on the face and get a left heal scum. Right hand up to a small but good edge. Now for the crux, do something with your feet to help you throw your body up and left to a very good edge. From this edge climb up a move or two and back down to drop off.    If you want to try and top out...well I'm not sure it is a good idea.

name: The Handcuff Trick
description: Tall and aesthetic layback slab crack. Must do!

name: Je Suis Wedge
description: The opposite of its counterpart, Troglodyte, this one is nice looking and out in the open, but doesn't move well imo. Start on high underclings and go up. Easier side of V8.

name: The Man with the Black Lunettes
description: This is about the most terrifying lowball imaginable.    Start from a sit on the slab and make a big move up and left to crimps. Traverse more or less straight left on small holds to a final big move out left to a juggy flake on the arete. Roll around the corner and stand up to finish.    There was some chalk on a possible start from the level below, I don't know if it has been done or not, the climbing looks easier with big moves on big holds and a scary landing.

name: Nobody's Funky
description: Start on a high hueco to your left, a sloper just under the arete, and use nay of the low feet. Bump the right to a higher sloper, set your heel into the left hueco where your hand starts, and crank on it hard to reach your left hand up over the ledge to a side pull--the higher the better. Reach out to the right crimp on the arete and smear your right foot to get your right hand to the crimp on the shallow dish. Set a high left heel just under your left hand and rock up to on it to stand. Reach your left hand up the arete for a crimp to set your right foot higher and then reach up to the flat ledge for the top-out.

name: Pirelli
description: The crux is the top out which is easy to scope.    Start on the jug that is one move into The Egg and another hold to the left. Make a huge move up to a sidepull, set your feet and start to paw your way onto the slab above.

name: Purple Flowers (Les Fleurs Pourpes)
description: This problem begins way back in the cave scrunched up on a rock on two underclings.  Work your way around the roof to (hopefully) a kneebar and then kick over to the slab (another boulder) and finish on that boulder.  There is so much beta and so many different ways of doing this climb that I'm not going to include the beta for this one although I will say that there are up to 3 kneebars and the best beta deviates from Fred Nicole's original version that he graded V10 (and is still reflected in the Wilder book).

name: Troglodyte
description: A decent roof with a one-move crux to a classic dab fest topout. Start on obvious flake jug and climb out of the hole you're in.

name: Fluff Cycle
description: On the right side of the wall, sit start on a crimpy block, then up to a sharp undercling feature. Climb left until the undercling ends and then do something creative to get to the jugs at the lip.

name: Fluffy's Revenge
description: On the right side of the wall, start the same as for Fluff Cycle on the low block, then go up and rightward on some small holds. The feet are limited, so some inverted beta may be needed.

name: The Right Fluff
description: On the left side of the wall, sit start in a large, flat hueco, then climb to the right across a ledge, then do some body-tension moves to gain the lip.

name: Tails of the Fluffboys
description: On the left side of the wall, sit start in a large, flat hueco. Climb left through crimps to the topout.

name: Frogger
description: Start low at 3 ft. using foot rail to the right. Climb up and left on sharp crimps to the highest point on the face.

name: Robocock
description: Start in a horizontal finger slot 5 feet off the ground, figure out how to get to the ledge (probably a big move), then top out.

name: Silly Goose
description: From a sit, sharp, incut crimps lead to a big move to a ledge, then a not-as-big move to a good right hand hold, rock over, and follow the crack to the top.

name: All the Idiots
description: Start sitting in the big hueco. Work up, left, and around the arete.

name: All The Religious Idiots
description: Where it starts getting real confusing. Essentially climbing Bad Religion backwards, start on New Religion, do the first move, and then traverse left to finish on All The Idiots. V8ish.  You could also start on New Religion Sit...V9ish. Also heard of it as Good Religion.

name: Bad Religion
description: Stand start from the left large hueco and traverse to the right into New Religion.

name: The Banana Splits
description: This line while given no stars in the Wilder guide, is probably worth at least one, and worth doing if you're looking for something new in the area.  Start at the left side of the horizontal crack.  Climb up and rightward utilizing a cool pocket, to get established in a large dish.  Trivial moves lead up to the top of the boulder.

name: Big Dick Jim
description: Stand start on crimps down in pit. Climb up and right on great incut holds to top out.

name: Brand New Rligion
description: Really fun climbing that tempts a poor landing when you move over the edge of the boulder below. To bad the crux is not dabbing on the boulder once you are over it.    Start New Religion and climb through the crux of that problem. Then head out right on huecos and flakes until you are over the boulder to the right of New Religion and top out at the jutting block horn feature.

name: Bush League
description: Start on jugs to the left in the roof, a couple of moves head right to a threader jug. A big move out right to the arete starts the business, cool compression follows the steep arete to good holds at the lip.    This problem would be pretty amazing if it was 3-5 feet higher off the ground, though dabbing was not really an issue.    Originally graded V10, the grade seems to have settled at V8.     There might be a knee bar somewhere but I did not see anything that would be useful, though I suck at knee barring.

name: The Cornerstone AKA: Dean's Corner
description: Very striking line up the steep corner with a finger crack to a moderately difficult but quite high top out onto a slab. The only real line on the wall.    Get your right hand as high in the corner as you can and stand up. Arrange your feet into some sort of a wide stem and pull up as high as you can. There is a sloping edge a bit below where the crack actually opens up that you can pause on to readjust your feet or just bump off of. Claw for where the crack opens. Then get your feet up and match. Layback up the corner eventually with good feet out right till you get to the lip. Reach up to the lip and grab some good slopers and pull over to the right or more straight up.    Graded V4 in the guide book. It might be V4 if you are well over 6 feet tall or you somehow don't take into account the first moves.

name: Fight or Flight
description: Start on a high left facing hueco and move upward through sequential moves on flakes that get increasingly worse as you go.  Match the top flake and make a heady move to the top of the boulder.  Match and pull over to the finish.  The book lists this as a challenging mantel, but with the right holds it shouldn't feel too bad.  Might be a good idea to pre-inspect the topout if you are at your limit.    There is also a sit start to this that adds in a few moves and bumps the grade up to V6.

name: Fight or Flight Sit
description: Sit start from two obvious huecos, figure a way to get to the starting jug of the stand, and execute. Cool additional moves, arguably the more natural line to those who like sit starts.

name: Hey, Hey, Hey We're the Monkeys
description: Sit start on an obvious jug on the middle / right side of the boulder.  Figure out how to make a big move leftwards to a large hueco.  Get the horizontal crack and traverse left some more to finish up "Last Train To Clarksville" V1

name: The Hunger Artist aka Alf in a Blender
description: An amazing classic.  Start on a two hand undercling under the roof.  Slap out the sloping left hand rail, apply some foot trickery and make you way onto better holds.  Many ways to approach this one.  Once you piece it together it seems easier.

name: Last Train to Clarksville
description: climb up through interesting pockets, not a bad warm up for the area

name: Layback and like it
description: Start low on start of Full Monty(?)grovel up the funky start move and traverse right on a bomber horizontal ledge, finish on the vulgarian

name: man in a cage
description: the finish to Alf in a blender, start on the jug and go up and left, worth doing if your trying Alf, although you probably wont fall

name: New Religion
description: A gym climbers dream.  Steep, positive holds, long moves, mellow topout.  A sit start exists that goes at V8.  If you don't have fun on this one something is wrong.

name: New Religion Sit
description: Start from a right hand under-cling with a thumb catch on the sharp tooth and a left hand gaston crimp. Drop knee and go left hand to the start of New Religion and then campus to match. Finish on New Religion.

name: Shooting for the Hole
description: This line is pretty cool and has some really neat holds.  Unfortunatly the difficulty is a bit contrived as it is easier to go directly up from the start holds.    Sit start at the far left side of the boulder.  Climb rightwards on small flakes to a cool right hand pocket sidepull.  Slap up to the lip and finish slightly rightwards thru the hole between the two boulders.  Once at the lip both boulders are on, so you can chimney / flail / crawl thru the hole.  A little committing as it feels as though you may hit the back boulder if you fall while throwing for the lip.

name: Unknown
description: Start sitting on a right undercling and left edge or sloper. Follow angling rails up and right over the lower boulder to the arete. Pull around and top out.    While low the landing is awkward and you can't cut your feet because of how close the boulder under you is, but the climbing is at least somewhat interesting.

name: Up Tall Elliptical Pockets
description: Tall Obvious line of Huecos, little bit of loose rock, but plenty of fun

name: The Vulgarian
description: Big holds up an overhang.  How can you go wrong?  Right as you walk into The Gunks this is the first climb past The Full Monty on the same side. Starts in the middle of the face and goes slightly left.      If you're not on jugs you are off route.

name: Walrus in a Blender
description: Start on the right leaning slopey rail, and figure out how to dyno up and leftwards to the obvious jug.  Top out on the right leaning crack.  The very tall may be able to do this as a static mantle using a foot near the Vulgarian start.

name: Windy Ass
description: Start on two slopey underclings, bump the left hand, and go to the ledge hold. Continue to the top.  A proud bloc with some very, very thuggy climbing. Probably helps to be tall and have big hands. Described by Nalle in 2009 as "V11 no matter what the guide book would say".

name: [Redacted]
description: Crux is the very top.  Throw from the Right hand sloper and left hand pocket to the sloping lip.  Nice flat landing so just go for it.  No small holds on this one.

name: [Redacted]
description: Climb the crack between the Ten Foot Wall Boulder and the Slim Pickins Face Boulder.

name: Better Eat Your Wheaties
description: A classic crimp problem, Because of the nature of the holds this problem really is not all that height dependant.    From the start side pull get your feet on, either a good right or both, or a high left depending on your preference. If you are small bury the left hand side pull, if big, crush it for all your worth. Reach or bump your way up to a sharp edge that is some what of a gaston. Move your feet around and reach the pinch right at the lip. From here there are several ways to finish, and the next move or two are the crux. However you do it you will be tic-tacing your way up some pretty small holds that are on a vertical wall while your feet are still on the overhang.      To top out move left in the horizontal below the next over hanging panel and up at a flake at mid-height on this next overhanging panel. This is easier that the rest of the problem but it never hurts to have a look in advance just to see where those top out holds are over the lip.   Location   From the meadow between the Maze and East Mt head throught the tunnel formed by the big boulder that is furthest to the left and the short wall to the right, when you get through you will be looking at an overhung wall that has lots of chalk and features. This one starts high on a good left-hand sidepull and right-hand crimper/gaston, in the middle/right of the face where there is another rock behind the steep face.

name: Bildo
description: Good warmup for the Maze

name: Black and Blue
description: on the ten foot wall, one of the more fun warm-ups

name: Clumsy Plumber
description: Sit start on good huecos and move up along the arête on large holds to the top

name: The Cowpuncher
description: Stand start on the "bad landing" Boulder and move up tiny pinches to a high heady, sloper. Finish on big holds above the sloper.

name: Crown of Aragorn
description: Starts in a scoop on the arete to the right of Better Eat Your Wheaties and traverses left on impossibly small crimps to finish on Wheaties.

name: Flexin Texan
description: Climb up and finish right.

name: Godzillatron Cush
description: "Jump to a good hold at about 8 ft. Then go right and up to the lip"

name: Hector
description: Move up and left into some pockets that can be sidepulled. There are a couple of sloping terrible holds between here and the next good hold that you can use but don't have to. Some how reach out to the good straight down pulling hold from the pockets then heal hook one of the other pockets by your right hand and lever up to an OK edge for your right about 3 feet above your left but not quite as far over. This position allows you to cut the heal and hold the swing. Once under control, campus down onto the good hold and left a couple of moves to the drop off jug.    I have not heard of anyone topping this line out so the drop off is pressumed legit.

name: Javalina
description: Sweet traverse on jugs, would be worthy of 4 stars if dabbing halfway through was not an issue.    Head right from the low jugs near the middle of the wall.start out traversing more or less along the lip at one point using a hold under the lip. Eventually move up into a good left hand sidepull half pocket and make a long reach out right to an undercling, match your left foot to hand as either a toe or heal toe and drop your left down to a good seem. Now for the anti dab first crux, release the foot and swing onto the hand holds with a smear for your right foot. The rest of the problem is tough enduro climbing, big moves on bigish holds. Bump your left further along the seam and make a long move out right to the left end of another seam with a flat hold that sort of tilts toward you. Get a right heal hook and match up to make another long move right to a better hold. Some consider this the end of the problem but for full credit top it out, the climbing is easier but not neseccarily a gimmie, I've seen someone pitch from above here.

name: Jigsaw Puzzle
description: One of the best V5s, this problem starts at the right side of a face that resembles a jigsaw puzzle.  Climb the boulder from left to right trending upwards and toping out on the right side of the boulder.

name: Jingus Bells
description: Crux is the last move of this climb.  Maybe better rated as 5.12 a/b.  Begin down and left of the obvious chalked ending.  Weave your way through varried and fun moves to the end.  The dyno is SICK.  Don't be afraid to go for it as you land safe and sound onto the boulder behind every time.  Nice to have a chalkbag on this one.

name: Meat Maker
description: Starts around the corner to the right from Wheaties in a big Hueco.  A big throw to the right gains the "meat hook" hold.  Continue right and upwards to a balancy, scary topout.  In the sun most of the day.

name: Slayride
description: Good rock, nice holds, engaging top out are all good things. The hardest move right off the ground would normally be bad but with the poor landing is probably a plus as well.    Start on some small holds and explode up to a flat jug. float the jugs up and left to a hueco. Then head up past a spooky looking block to a sloping lip encounter.

name: Slim Pickins
description: Scary highball slab up and to the right of Jigsaw Puzzle.  You have to be a slab master for this one!

name: Stinkfoot
description: Tall slabby fun

name: Strip Show Faux Pas
description: Start in the giant Hueco and figure out how to catch the sharp crimp jug up and to the right. Move on sharp jugs trending further right and top out.

name: Ten Inch Plastic Boyfriend
description: Located on the leftmost arête of the Ten Foot Wall Boulder, sit start on the jug rail and climb the arête and move out right along the lip and top out.

name: This Is Your Brain On Drugs
description: Climbs in the dihedral of Dihedral Rock. Start on crimps at the bottom of the dihedral with your feet on a decent rail.

name: Trubblemaker
description: Stand start to Meatmaker.

name: Udder Destruction
description: On the left side of the Ten Foot Wall, sit start on large huecos and move up a series of huecos and good holds directly up the face of the boulder.

name: Unknown traverse
description: Used to start on a fist sized hueco with a good edge in the bottom (since broken, by my over weight self, leaving a bruised elbow). Start above the hueco on some slopers. Traverse right on slopers with small feet until you reach some mail slots. continue right and up on the slots to an easy top out.

name: Unknown wall 1
description: Start kind of low, you could probably sit. Climb up on nice hueco flakes that are mostly side pulls until you reach the angling crack across the top of the face. From here things get easier to the top.

name: Unknown wall 2
description: Start in a horizontal that is a bit on the low side and work up fun hueco seams that yield jugs. Leading to a thin move about 10 feet up. Another long move leads to the angling crack high on the face and an easier top out.    The landing has 2 tiers so padding both and having a good spot would be a good idea if you think you might come off.

name: The  Bacchanalian (AKA Balls of Steele)
description: Start with a kneebar as for "The Bomb," but head up and left above the blocky landing zone.  The crux is up high, but it is mostly a power endurance problem.  This problem is not in the current guide (Wilder, 1st edition) and is well worth seeking out if you are looking for something off the beaten path.

name: The Give
description: Same start at Smokin' Sausage, go directly up via crimps.

name: Hot Link
description: fun, starts on low right hand jug left hand crimp and traverses right along sloper rail

name: The Long Haul
description: This route begins on a jug under the roof that is on your left as you enter the center of the Sausage Factory.  Climbs out tension slopers and jugs to a big move to a gaston and a bump that will get you to the lip.    3 stars for cool holds, movement, and obvious line. -1 for the leg breaking boulder to your left as you do the committing moves to the lip.

name: Ministry of Truth
description: Pretty pure power problem and not too tweaky.    From a high two hand edge campus up to another edge. Then figure out how to get to the crack above, there are a couple of different ways to do it. The crack above is easy and you will have the edges as feet to start.

name: Quetzalcoatl (aka Glass Ass Crack)
description: Start on big underclings under the roof. Reach to a glassy rail, then move right and up to the top.

name: Smokin Sausage
description: awkward hard start, starts left hand in a hueco right on a crimp to fun easy climbing.

name: Weenie Roast
description: start sitting left hand crimp right hand in hueco   crux is the start

name: Chow, Chow, Chow
description: Terrifying top out.    Easy to start up huecos then ledges. Move up the arete to sloping edges above to a very thin and technical top out. Beware of the drop off to the right.

name: Dead Legends
description: From the two positive incuts, traverse right thru shouldery moves to an obvious incut crimp you can match on.  From here slap to the top and pull a tricky mantel to get established on top of the boulder.

name: The French Tickler
description: This route is the obvious line in the center of Stable Rock.  Begins on the large sloping jugs at head height and climbs straight up through small crimps and sloping gastons to a committing lunge at the finish.      Beta:  Begin on the sloping jugs and take the first 1/2 pad crimp with your right hand.  Heel up on the sloping jugs and reach up left hand to a good but slightly sharp gaston.  Stand up and get a horrid right hand crimp, then back step the 1/2 pad crimp with your right foot and lunge for a decent crimp out and right from your right hand (crux).  Left foot goes on a good smear onto up your left hand (coolest move ever) and lock off to the first gaston sloper.  Move your feet out left to get the second right hand gaston sloper.  Left foot up to the decent crimp and lunge for the sloping jug at the top out.  Mega-classic.  My favorite line in Hueco.

name: Gravy Train Tryout
description: This alternate start to "Hi Pro Glow" is worth doing if you have already done the classic.  Shared start with "You Bring Out the Mess in Me" on good holds up to great jugs.  Make a large span left, pull the crux which is matching and climb up easier moves to the finish.

name: Mr Serious
description: From the start make a move into a good sidepull then a hard move into the perfectly circular pocket. Figure out how to move your feet up and pull off of the pocket to get to something terrible and either use it or turn the pocket and go again. A few easier moves up on better holds takes one to the top of the boulder.   There is a lower sit/laydown start down to the right that makes this problem V10 and is called Dead Serious

name: That Hi-Pro Glow
description: Start matched on a big sloper.  Figure out how to move right through good holds to reach jugs in the crack.  From here climb leftwards on good holds to the finish, climbing under a few branches.    Very aesthetic route with great movement.  Probably on the easier side of V6.

name: Bottle Rocket
description: Go up arete.

name: First Timer’s Flake
description: Lots to grab onto with the crack on your left hand and the arete on your right. There’s a big scoop to stand in right before you top out that would make this a V0- but that gets filtered out of searches. Beware of the flaky rock, there’s lots of it. If you grab it and it sounds “hollow” don’t put any force to it. You can come back down through the large crevice on the right.

name: Inside Out
description: Line sends an arete that is located inside the North End Group maze. Standing start heads up to to two pockets and a jug top out. Avoid using your back on the boulder behind. Could be a bit height dependent for the start but is a fine line.

name: Welcome to the Dark Side
description: Standing start avoiding the right edge and avoiding using the boulder to the left. The chimney problem is a separate route. The arete edge to the right is a separate route.

name: Frankenweenie
description: Fun roll over problem.  Low start, bump, heel hook, pocket reach, and finish with throw or use some crimps.

name: Oogie Boogie
description: Has Ooggie Boogie on face of climb, so there's that.  Can add a little fun with underside heel, and heel hooks up higher.  No Maiden, but pretty nice for the grade.

name: Vincent Price
description: Easy / fun / tallish

name: Dope Fiend
description: "Start at the lip on sloping hueco... Climb up and slightly left to a scary, loose upper section."

name: Dope Fiend Low
description: If you like burly campusing problems on good holds then this is for you.  Beware the finish is both tall and not super easy.  Start down under the roof with a good pocket and a marginal pinch.  Pull your feet off the ground and fire for the good crimp jug.  Match with some difficulty and get to the next section of good holds above.  This is where "Dope Fiend" V3 starts.  Continue up the wall on unchalked and scary holds until the angle finally breaks and you can romp up the easy slab.  Can descend on the boulder behind the problem.

name: Fern Roof
description: Start on the right side of the roof to the left of a fern-filled crack.  Move left and pull the roof to the scary, loose slab topout.

name: Mexican Chicken
description: Start on the far left side of the roof on slopers. Work your way out through slopers and a key side pull using heel hooks to gain the start of 100 proof roof. Using the opposing crimps, make a big move right to the first good undercling. Keep shuffling your way right through the undercling jugs and then straight out towards the lip. Top out on the easy, but very tall, slab.

name: Mild Turkey
description: Start in the middle of Wild Turkey on good holds with your feet on the big boulder.  Pull your legs up and throw for the big undercling.  Top out on the same scary, loose slab.

name: Sôl Adûnâmentum
description: Nick Duttle ( nickduttle.com/ ), after recently sending the famed Esperanza (V14), has added a new V14 in Hueco Tanks, Sôl Adûnâmentum. It is a direct start to Fern Roof and it finishes up on Wild Turkey. Nick has suggested hard V14 and if the grade holds it will be one of the hardest problems in Hueco Tanks and the USA. Sôl Adûnâmentum is on North Mountain, which means anyone can go there on anyday with out a tour guide. I am sure that this problem will recieve alot of attention this year. Well done Nick!

name: Wild Turkey
description: Starts on good crimps on the left side of the roof and moves right through a large move, then a scary, loose top out.

name: Asylum Crack
description: This great problem is kinda like an easier version of the mega-classic dragonfly.  Longer and just as steep, this lacks the difficult footholds and challenging topout of dragonfly, allowing the moderate grade.  This would be a classic if it wasn't so difficult not too hit your back, and take an unintentional rest on the boulder behind you half way up.    Start low to the ground on good holds at the lower level.  Lieback your way up, being careful not to dab on the boulder behind at the 10 foot mark.  A little above the crux is encountered on smaller holds, but with good feet.  Hang on and reach the huge jugs above allowing an easy topout.  It is easy to step off onto the upper boulder if things get too scary.    To descend, head left from the top of the problem, through an easy  but kinda tricky to find downclimb, and work your way back to the start.

name: Eurydice
description: Start on the largest crimp shelf left of Orpheus. Traverse into the upper crimps on Orpheus.

name: Glonous History
description: Two hand start on left side pull and horizontal crimp. Continue upwards to the right. Don’t go left where holds are chossy.

name: Le Retour De Goupil
description: Powerful roof climbing leads to a rest. Get something back and do another boulder problem on sharp crimps.

name: Love 2 Chum
description: Hidden in the Asylum underneath an overhanging bouler.   Start on the flake system and throw out right to a just then crawl over the arete an climb up the rest of the face

name: Loves2chum
description: Start on the flaky crimp section, move up and toss out to the arete, top out.    Not the finest, but worth the 10 yard hike if you're working on the V1s on the back side of Nurse Ratchet.

name: Nurse Ratchet
description: Start sitting with an obvious sharp flake.  Paste your feet and make a big move to a left crimp.  From here follow more crimps to a relatively easy top out.  While it may seem relatively uninspiring due to the extreme sit start it is actually kind of fun.

name: Orpheus
description: Start on the big hueco (LH) and sloper (RH) and climb up the steep wall on a variety of interesting crimps.

name: Stop Watching Me
description: Cool movement on mostly good holds with a high intimidation factor.    Stand tall off the slab and stretch up to a juggy hueco. Match and work up on underclings and right facing holds that leave you feeling out of balance eventually gaining the right starting hold of the high problem with your left hand. Match then move left to a cool pinch and a big move up to a jug at the lip. The top out is pretty easy.    The first few moves are over a small flat landing zone in the lower area up until you make the first move out left to the good gaston. Then going into the undercling and moving up to the starting olds of the high start you are over the square edge of the platform that the high start begins on and a fall could be bad. Going to the undercling and getting your feet up is probably the most dangerous bit. Falling off the move to the start of the higher problem is relatively safe but intimidating.

name: Theatre of the Absurd
description: Where isn't the crux?  Sustained V8 climbing the separates nicely into two distinct boulder problems.  Begin way back in the cave on a sidepull sloping jug and make your way through slopey compression jugs using kneebars, bicycles, and toe hooks to get to a jug that is hard to match.  Bust out left to a crimp and a then a good sloper and get established on the lip.  After getting to the jug your can drop off or do a chossy highball finish that is about V2 (hence the PG13 grade).    Two stars for cool movement and holds.  The low ball traverse, some chossy rock and the dab potential detract from the overall obvious line.

name: V-Obsession
description: Start with one hand on each side of the steep V arete.  On the left side of the V there are two chalked crimps, with it being slightly harder to start on the higher one.  Get established on the right side of the V and climb up the headwall towards the horizontal crack feature.

name: Bastet Case
description: Start on Tobacco Chewing... and move right into the white scoop, then go straight up the middle of the scoop to the peak of the boulder. Holds are on both sides of the scoop. It's been described as an "overhanging slab" by one of the early ascensionists.

name: Butt buddy
description: Sit start, climb the fin on the left arete.

name: Dingleberry Jones and the last crusade
description: Start with your right hand in the V shaped notch at the 5ft. Level.

name: Gay Abandon
description: Climb the right arete

name: Hard Wipe
description: Start with left hand in the V shaped notch

name: The Hashmarker
description: Start standing on a boulder and climb to the right of the arete on good holds.

name: Saxon Tactics
description: Climb the arete

name: The Sphincter
description: Start saueezed between two boulders, climbing to the left of the mono pocket.

name: Tobacco chewing gut chompong kinfolk from hell
description: Casual warmup problem on fantastic jugs.

name: Barefoot on Sacred Ground
description: Same start as Dark Age, go directly up to the obvious hueco, and either continue going directly up or move right into the upper section of See Spot. Correct me if I'm mistaken, I believe the original FA was by Sharma and done with the former exit.

name: Dark Age
description: Start sitting left of the arete, MATCHED on the undercling, and figure out a sequence to traverse right into See Spot Run

name: Entrance Crack
description: This hand crack will give a great "crack workout", but watch your back.  Because the crack is on the wall of a fissure, any length of fall will hurt when you hit the wall behind.  Not safe for the cut-and-run style of leading, place lots of gear.  Seconding is bad too.  Consider only leading this. To clean, do a mix of down-aiding the crack and down-climbing the chimney.

name: Eye Gouger
description: Start low and climb directly up the overhung face on the northwest arete on excellent huecos.

name: Little Big Time
description: Low crux. I found starting around the corner to the right to be more fun, but I think starting on the face is legit, too. Long moves on good holds if you start around the corner, shorter moves on crimps if you start on the face. Gets a little thin near the top, but not as hard as the start.

name: The Rack
description: Start on the obvious 2 handed 2 pad slightly incut crimp, awkwardly paste your feet on the wall and deadpoint up to the crack undercling.  Follow this crack right through underclings, fingerlocks and miserable feet. Work yourself on to the low angle right side of the boulder and step off.    If you start on the big hueco start hold for "See Spot Run" and work your way through some miserable crimps this is "Run the Rack" for V9 credit.

name: Run The Rack
description: Start See Spot, finish The Rack

name: See Spot Run
description: This classic face climb is one of the more notorious highball problems at Hueco.  The excellent moves, stellar rock, and memorable finish make this problem a must do for those solid at the grade.  Despite the towering height of this problem, the crux is low, and the landing is excellent, so wait for a crowd, layer the pads thick, and go for it!    Begin matched in the large hueco 4 feet above the ground and 10 feet right of the NW arete of the Big Time Boulder.  The crux is the first three moves, and is quite safe with good pads.  Head up and left to an incut diagonal crimp and horizontal sloping crimp just above.  Work the feet, then dyno for the obvious pocket/crimp in the middle of the face.  From here, 6 or so more moves of V1/V2 crimping lead to a huge jug and easy mantle at the lip.  Descend the SE ridge.

name: Spud Boy
description: Start sitting and climb directly up the overhung face on crimps with a couple of fun throws. Left of Eye Gouger.

name: Wife on Ice
description: Standing start, follow ledges up and right.

name: Woman Of Leisure
description: Start sitting with hands on good huecos on the right hand side of the boulder. Low traverse left on a fun line of huecos, then top out up the hueco groove.

name: Bloodline
description: An atypical hueco rock climb. Great movement that requires balance and technique. There's a left start and a direct start that's a little more difficult.

name: TNT
description: Start on the left facing jug. Slap right, around the bulge, and do a rising traverse following good huecos, maybe enjoy the sweet cross match undercling midway. Keep cruising, and top out!  Started messing with this with Phillip Sweeney, while Mike and the gang were crushing Bloodline. The holds were sandy and chalkless. I assumed my send was the FA, while Mike M. got the second in flip flops, and called it, "classic Hueco V2".

name: Cakewalk
description: Solid climbing up huecos and patina for two pitches, with good exposure and comfy belays. The first pitch is the more dififcult, mainly due to the route-finding challenges. Finding the "5.6" start may be tricky as there are several slightly more difficult ways to start. Also, the protection on the first 30-40 ft is not all that obvious, sometimes relying on the small gaps between patina plates. The second pitch is much more straightforward, following the obvious hand-sized crack for half a pitch. When the crack ends, an exposed traverse to the right leads to a ledge, from which one can scramble up to the top.    A beginner leader should take this route fairly seriously, as the protection is not obvious. However, there are plenty of good stances, and as long as you can be creative with your pro, you'll enjoy this route.

name: Cakewalk Direct
description: A group of us were climbing this area a few weeks ago and while we were running laps up Alice in Banana Land just to the right, this climb kept spitting climbers off the start. While there is a line of small holds directly underneath the first bolt, most of us ended up starting in the initial crack of Banana Patch and then traversing over a move at the top of the crack to reach the first bolt. Once the first bolt is reached the climbing becomes pretty straight-forward, following some decent huecos and face-holds up the nearly vertical wall.

name: Return of Cakewalk
description: Fun climbing up left side of Cakewalk Wall. Maybe some 5.7 moves, but largely 5.6 or easier. p1: 100 feet to 2-bolt anchors. We climbed left around "umbrella-size hueco" described in Sherman, then slightly right to anchors. p2: 100 feet to 2-bolt anchors. Stay left at wall near top to find anchors.

name: Son of Cakewalk
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Alice in Banana Land
description: Reach high for a jug (may be a difficult start for the shorter  folks), and trend up and right to the first bolt about 15 feet up. Continue up through the bolts. The bolt spacing is enough to make you think, but not terrible for someone who is solid at the grade. Fairly well protected for Hueco standards. Excellent climbing will eventually bring you to a point where there is a crack and no more bolts. The options here are a few medium to larger sized nuts, some small cams, or running it out.    The guidebook notes that this route is 105 feet. This is clearly not true as the mid mark of our rope was a good 15-20 feet up. Two ropes are required for the rappel.

name: All the Nasties
description: the first pitch is fairly bold, with scant bolts and some loose rock. Climb past the first bolt (~25ft high) to a thin crack which can be protected with small wires. Then head right past 2 bolts before heading left underneath a small bulge to the last bolt. Belay on a nice ledge with a solid two-bolt anchor (100' to ground).     Pitch 2 is easier, has better rock and excellent protection. Gear required for the belay at a huge ledge. A short 3rd pitch up cracks leads to the top.

name: Banana Patch
description: A clean line following a thin crack. It starts up a thin seam for about 15 ft. The crux is traversing 10 ft to the right to reach the bottom of another thin finger crack. It is mostly a mental crux, requiring good composure as you face a near groundfall. A few moves up the finger crack and the climbing becomes easier although still steep. Big huecos to either side of the crack provide rest holds and gear-placement stances. The crack ends by petering out next to a huge chimney.   A very exposed move bridges the chimney at an obvious weakness, and traverses right for a few feet before climbing up to a ledge/bush and a bolted anchor.    An alternate start (also 5.10) is to climb the face 4 ft to the left of the chimney to a bolt 15 ft off the ground, and then make a few moves to the left to reach the upper thin crack.     Some delicate climbing involved, fun exposed moves, and good gear makes this route a worthy tick.

name: Bitchin Chimney
description: Why would anyone jump onto this squeeze chimney route while surrounded by quality sport and trad lines and even higher quality bouldering? The Sherman Guide for Hueco tanks (2nd edition) states "... it has only been climbed once by a skinny and lanky person who said it was tight.", so you'll probably feel like the second person ever to climb this route. I sure did. Not being an avid wide-crack or chimney climber, I was intimidated by tackling the route. Nothing about it looks all that difficult, but you may as well forget about protection. Much to my surprise and enjoyment, I realized that for squeeze chimneys such as this one, protection isn't required for making you feel secure. Of course, I'm also a fairly skinny person... If you're here and up for it, jump on this route for a secure-feeling, but mostly solo squeeze climb.

name: Brain Dead
description: If you've been loving those iron-rock in-cuts on the boulders, then this might be the pitch for you.  Laurel Lacher, in Rock & Ice #36, called this pitch:  "...one of the most tenuous 5.10+'s at Hueco."       To begin, climb either Divine Wind / All the Nasties up to the two bolts on "Urinal Ledge".      Brain Dead is the second pitch and starts off the right side of the belay.  Follow a line of nine bolts up the center of a steep, perfect, slab of iron-rock.      After 50+ meters, the pitch ends on a big ledge with no easy anchor. We did it with a 50 meter rope and barely had enough rope to sit way back on the anchor-less belay ledge.  I remember dusting off a nub on the ledge to sling like a horn and using a fat rope and hip belay for bringing up my second safely.     The final pitch is a 100 foot exit crack, maybe 5.5, from the big anchor-less ledge to the summit.

name: Busted
description: Ascends a steep buttress above the anchors for Alice in Bananaland. Fun climbing with a great position. Tops out near top of Cakewalk. Walk off as for Cakewalk.

name: Cowboyography
description: This amazing route has 2 distinct cruxes at 1/3 and 2/3 height. Expect a couple arm-melting runouts on large huecos with the crux being small crimps and shallow dishes.

name: Divine Wind / All the Nasties
description: From the top of the Malice Boulder, this route is located on the shoulder immediately to the right of Paul Bunyon Chimney.      P1 Climb well featured rock as you angle up and right towards Urinal Ledge to 2 bolt anchor.      P2 First bolt off of Urinal Ledge is to the left and up about 6 feet.  Follow featured rock up to the headwall, wandering right past a rusted 1/4" bolt, and then continue without gear to a large ledge at the base of a few short cracks.  You can traverse further right on this pitch and start clipping the bolts of Brain Dead/All The Nasties, or move left off the belay and pick up some mystery bolts that randomly appear.    P3 is 18' of 2" hand crack to reach summit via 5.5 climbing.  Use gear and natural features to set anchor.      Walk off to climbers left towards Laguna Prieta.  Be sure to scramble down to a break in the wall before reaching the lagoon. Continue back across toward the Front Side and Lunch Rocks.     Note:  Descent can take as long as 20 minutes even if you know where you are going.

name: Hueco Syndrome
description: Two short pitches (could be combined?). the first is 5.8+ up moderate huecos. The second tackles a short corner and some face climbing.

name: Lunacy
description: This is a nice crack for those who want to practice carrying a big rack.  It looks like a 100 foot offwidth but is really a stemming corner with a big crack for pro.  After the wide section, the crack decreases in size to fingers.  Above the finger crack is a ledge with two bolts.  Outstanding pitch!     From the end of pitch one it is possible to do a 60 meter rappel.  (two 60 meter ropes)    Pitch two is a wide crack through a roof, above which more squeezing leads to the summit.

name: Lunar Abstract
description: One of the shorter pitches on the Front Side.  Barely overhung, but with fun moves.  Lunar Abstract even gets a little sun, unusual for Hueco 5.12's.    The pitch begins with barn door lie-backing up a left facing, left leaning, small flake-corner.  Hard to see the gear placements on the way to the first bolt.  Three bolts protect face climbing on ivory-like rock. End at a double bolt anchor, about 70 feet up.

name: Malice In Bucketland
description: Pretty good intro to the Hueco roped routes. Right off the Malice Boulder, jungle gym your way up big deep huecos to the first bolt (about 25' up), then move left and up the rounded arete past seven more bolts, working huecos and good edges. Head up and right at the last bolt to get to the two bolt anchor. There are some pretty good stretches between bolts on this route, so climb carefully!

name: Purple Microdot
description: My friend George Bracksieck told me Mike Head described this route to him over the phone when Heuco Tanks was still a "secret" climbing area. This description is the variation 1st pitch of Purple Microdot. Find the middle crack with a hole near the bottom.  Start from below the crack and place a fat nut in the slot below the hole. Return to the ground and start the climb on the right face traversing left into the crack, stepping on the nut you placed. Climb the varying width crack till the right "hands" crack joins, some 25m. Move out onto the right face (Begin R section), girth hitch a dubious hole before clipping the bolt. Move up then traverse back left toward the incipient crack in right facing corner. With the slot over your head move up to place the #4 and exit left to two bolt anchor.  P2 Follow the arching right facing roof around corner then climb corner to the top (hope to add details at a later date if I'm not to old to lead it again.  The right crack is very nice & is an easier lead, it can be TR.  From P1 60m does NOT make it to the ground, for the decent, don't know if a 70m will make it?

name: Sea of Holes
description: A popular route. Both pitches are long and with widely spaced bolts which makes it feel less like a sport climb. It is possible to supplement the bolts by placing large cams in some of the "holes", but this hardly feels necessary. The 2nd pitch traverses right to within 15' of the tree in the corner, before going straight up the steep headwall (crux).The entire climb is steep climbing up huge huecos. Pumpy, but not technically difficult.     The good exposure and stinginess of bolts are what make this climb exciting.  Take it for what it is.

name: Uriah's Heap
description: Good fun climb with a small roof section on p2. Third pitch is kind of run out with very little for placements. Bolts on third pitch are far to the left near a cactus, this is also the first set of bolts for the rap down.

name: Walking on the Moon
description: Described as "hair raising" in the guide, this runout route fits the bill.  Very fun bouldery start directly in front of juniper tree using large huecos.  Climb up 10' to first bolt then follow features up another 10' or so to a second bolt.      Wander up and left using the path of least resistance for 80 feet until you reach a small vertical crack that takes marginal small to medium nuts for protection.      Travel another 15' up and right to a 3rd bolt directly left of a flake with huecos that can be slung if you don't see the bolt or like a little added protection.  Cross over the flake by traversing up & right 8' where you will find the 4th and final bolt before running it for the anchors.    Bolted anchors allows for easy rappel (1 84m or 2 50m+ ropes required)

name: Window Pain
description: The line follows clean and well featured rock with the bolt line easily seen from the ground.     3 or 4 bolts and 35' up you will encounter a roof where there is a bolt hidden above.  Continue on steep rock up and right to 2 bolt anchor & rappel.     More tightly bolted than neighboring routes it provides some welcomed comfort as the rock is steep and sustained.      Excellent climbing and a must do for any Hueco Tanks visit.

name: Papal Bull
description: Begin with left and right underclings. Step up and find a way to gain the hollow flake in the middle of the face. Top out up and left towards the horn. Down climb is chimney to the left of climb.

name: Dab
description: Start low and left on the lowest chalked crimps and traverse right on progressively better holds and bad feet until you can make a big move to a sloper on the lip and top out.

name: Luther
description: If you find yourself in Hueco itching to climb on gear (haha), this is a fantastic crack set back inside a massive corridor/ cave. I spent several hours cleaning this crack, so doubt if it has seen an accent in many many years. That said, its clean now and climbs and protects well. One of the most uniform cracks in Hueco.  Climb up a easy wide flare with a crack in the back (optional #4) to the beautiful finger crack splitting a varnished streaked panel.  Goes from fingers down to tips before you can throw a foot out and stem the massive chalkstone to the left. Finish by stepping left onto the chalkstone when the crack ends. No bolts, so bring a #4, #3, and 0.75 to build an anchor up above the crack. Walk off to the north toward the asylum. This climb is briefly detailed in the older Sherman guide to my understanding. FA?

name: East face
description: thin slab on pretty dark rock, fairly committing top out

name: NE Face
description: The north face of the north deliverance boulder ranges from V0 to V1. Climbing directly up to the peak is a great clean line that goes at about V1, and is thinnest about 3/4 of the way up.

name: Southern Hospitality
description: super fun middle line on south deliverance start down and left of hueco in undercling/s.   top out is pretty thin

name: Dilated Pupils
description: Sit start back in the cave and climb a cool feature on good holds up and out of the cave.  From here pull on some tiny crimps and dishes, work the feet and pull onto the slab.

name: Double Vision
description: Classic tall problem with a high crux. Exciting!    Start on the undercling with your feet on the block. Snake eye pockets in the middle of the face mark the beginning of the business. From here it's not many moves, but you start relatively high and the crux is gaining the lip. Fortunately the landing is flat and open, just watch the yucca at the left side.

name: Hueco of Dan-ocles
description: Climbs the arete to the left of Double Vision. Start on the jug climb on small pockets and edges up the wave-like arete to a Hueco with a crack around its bottom (hence the name).

name: Seka's Specialty
description: Sit start on good Huecos just right of a fallen block at the right side of Double Vision boulder.  Move slightly left and make a big move to a good crimp.  From here make a big move to a nice Hueco Jug and top out up and right.

name: Fast Foods
description: A three bolt 5.8 leads up to an anchor at 50 feet.  A rare, "easy", sport pitch.  It is a slab, not a hueco pull.

name: Short Hands
description: A hand and fist crack in a right facing corner, just left of the three bolt face called Fast Foods.

name: Fox Trot
description: Upon walking up to Fox Tower, about 96% of climbers will be saying "what route goes up those really cool hueco-monkey-bars?" That would be this route. Start just below and left of the huecos at a cleft, climb up and right out of the cleft to a pretty high first bolt (30'), then just follow the bolts up to the anchor. Crux is like the last bolt and crack (bring a large stopper) where the big buckets you've been swinging from disappear and you have to edge your way up the finish. Really nice route!

name: Head Fox
description: Climb up left of the cleft in the middle of the Fox Tower formation (left of hueco field that forms Fox Trot route), folling the crack initially and moving up past ten bolts to a two bolt anchor 150 feet up. Excellent route on pretty good edges with some thought-provoking moves between bolts.

name: Denizen
description: Low start matched with right hand on undercling left hand on the slopey top. Follow the arête eventually pulling a long move left to the side pull jugs on the face pull a long move to the right hand jug then hit the hidden jug up top then pull the easy top out.  Fantastic arête climb with long powerful moves.

name: Ghetto Simulator
description: A very, very long climb with a cruxy finish. Amazing line though, everyone should do this climb when visiting Hueco! This is a very long climb, but not too tall because an angling ramp follows you the whole way up.

name: Quetin Tarrantino
description: The crux is doing a traverse after getting established on a good jug.  Took much cleaning and is not the best rock quality,  but the line is obvious and the holds that are there are quality.      Begins low down on a sloper and does a move to a good right hand sidepull and do a large lunged to a good hueco cut jug.  Match and cross to slopey hueco.  Heel toe cam in the jug and reach out and rigth to a crimpy undercling.  Rock over on your left foot and find a smearing right foot.  Pop into the undercling at the top of the juggy hueco and lunch out left for a slopey jug.  Easy top out.      Two stars for the holds and movement.  Negative two for the death landing and crumbly rock although I'm sure this will clean up with traffic and time.  So a potential 3-star line that as of the time of this posting hasn't had a 2nd Ascent.

name: To Die For
description: This line climbs a series of slopey jug huecos to a commiting gaston move and cross over high off the deck.  An amazing find only done (I'm guessing) in 2008.

name: Black Mamba
description: Start on pinches and move up and left to top

name: Boys of Juarez
description: Start sitting on the right hand wall on thin holds. Pull some moves then go out the roof to join Girls in the middle.

name: Girls of Juarez
description: Start on an adjacent rock on a huge flake.  This rock is considered on for both hands and feet.  From the flake work your way out underneath the capstone on mostly good holds utilizing toe and heel hooks.  As you approach the end of the capstone grab good holds over the lip and pull up onto the boulder.

name: Girls of Texas
description: Position yourself on the starting jug holds and throw a heel up on the huge ledge.  Move the left hand to a small sharp crimp and make a hard stab for a slightly larger sharp crimp.  Latch this move the right hand up and grab another sharp crimp.  From here the difficulty eases as you can get alot of weight on your feet but things remain tricky until your fully on top.  Fun moves but quite sharp on uninspiring holds.

name: Mexican Love Handle
description: fun sloping pinches

name: Supergoose
description: Really fun climb starting on a undercling. Make a big move to the lip match and awkwadrly mantle the slab, careful not to hit your head though! Short but sweet!

name: Unknown
description: Start on the same jug as "Girls of Texas" and work your way right to a 3 finger gaston pocket for the right hand.  Make a big move to a sharp crimp for the left, then a sharp crimp for the right.  Continue up the boulder on easier ground a good amount of choss.    I imagine this line has been done before being on North in an area that sees alot of traffic, but there was not chalk on it when I did it.  Pretty fun line with good movement, but the sharp and chossy holds keep it from being more stars.  If all the holds stay it will probably be better than "Girls of Texas"

name: What is the Soul?
description: From big jug sit start, crank up to a right facing side pull, bump to a crimp, finish up and over the small boulder.

name: Dean's Trip
description: This is the arete which is the first problem you see on the Grenade when you come through from the Potatoes.  Apparently Dean Potter put it up while on "a trip" and it's very sandbagged.

name: Fire In the Hole
description: Just around the corner to the left of Dean's Trip. Start on the biggest and farthest in of the two undercling jugs. Move up and left through tiny crimps before topping out. No dabbing allowed!! Be careful for choss during the top out!

name: No One Gets Out of Jaxons Alive
description: Start on Nobody and traverse right into Pull the Pin.

name: Nobody Here Gets Out Alive
description: This fiercely overhanging problem is the best V2 in the world.

name: Nobody left
description: Are you sitting at the grenade with nothing better to do(like any of the many classics around you?) start as for Nobody traverse left struggling not to dab to squeeze through to the lip

name: Nobody Original Start
description: Low sit to nobody. Start on the pedestal with a sloping undercling jug with smear feet. Throw to the first jug on nobody, foot lead to match. Crux is not dabbing

name: Pull the Pin
description: Climb the dihedral to the right of Nobody.

name: The Cleghorn Memorial Route
description: This route starts on the same slanting crack as Speak to me O Toothless One but traverses left on the crimp rail then up to another rail before the top out.  I believe this is an FA because of the lack of (there was absolutely zero) chalk, ticks, and any other signs of any climber ever being on this. I chalked up all the holds and did what I think is the FA. Please let me know if this is not an FA.

name: Gums
description: Crux is at the bottom, technical climbing on small holds.

name: Power of Silence
description: This Fred Nicole test piece will offer up a challenge for anyone climbing the grade.  Stack pads or get a lift and start matched on the lowest good crimp. For most people the crux is sticking the decent pocket out right. This move requires tension and accuracy while using a left hand crimp and worse-than-it-looks right foot. A desperate stab into the fingerlock guards the last reach to the lip before topping out.  Classic and hard, Power of Silence shouldn't be missed on your trip to Hueco Tanks.

name: Speak To Me O' Toothless One
description: Climb the face opposite Sarah. Start on the left leaning crack at 5ft. and climb straight up.

name: Guns of Navarone
description: This savage crimp line would be four stars if only the holds weren't quite so sharp!    Begin sitting on your choice of two of three heavily chalked crimps.  Make a hard move, possibly the crux, up to better holds.  From here work your way left through several holds and eventually a long reach.  Top out on good but potentially very chossy holds.  Beware the huge flake on the right of the topout as it is very hollow sounding.

name: Pinch Face
description: Start laying down on a low shelf and move up and right to where you can throw a left hand over the lip.  Make a hard move to get your right hand up to a pinch and a difficult move to get your feet up.  Climb up and slightly right to the obvious hueco.  Drop off from here or continue up the easy, but chossy and high face.    There is also a V5 variation that starts the same but goes up and left as you pull over the lip.    Being that this is on North it could have been done before.  Not sure as there was a decent amount of choss and dirt.  But since it was a pretty good line, I felt it was worth naming it and adding it here.

name: Unknown
description: This stellar problems ascends the bullet iron rock face.  While fairly tall there is a large slab behind you can step off onto if you get flustered.  The first move is probably the hardest but it doesn't get that much easier.  Everything is solid but use care on the topout.

name: Bad Axe
description: Jug bash up the obvious line of superb huecos and pockets to the left of the tree and water streak (that roughly marks the enter of the gymnasium). head rightish for the top out, which might be a little heady for a new climber but an excellent flat crash-site lies below you.

name: Gag Reflex
description: Start on pockets at about head height and setup for the big move to a hueco at the top of small black streak. Pull the lip on somewhat friable holds.

name: Jimmy hats on parade
description: The right side of the big huecos.

name: Only the Little people pay taxes
description: A short but fun problem. Start on edges and pockets right of the black water streak and move up and left to the "v" notch at the top of the water streak. Slap the slopey but good V and top out without the help of the tree behind you (you cheater ha).

name: Rhymes with Rich
description: SDS Move right through slopey pockets and to a big throw up the black streak.

name: Solid pleasure
description: The left side of the big huecos.

name: Suck In Dick
description: Start on good huecos. Climb up through scoop and gain the lip to top out on jugs.

name: World without lawyers
description: The center line of the big huecos

name: Epilady
description: start to the left of obvious chalked hueco(start of shaved pits) on good underclings, go left

name: Five O'Clock Shadow
description: Start, and first few moves are the same as Shaved Pits, but then go right for the finish instead of straight up. Significantly harder than Shaved Pits. Goes directly over the large boulder. Very steep!  Start on the very lowest hueco with a nice horizontal ledge in it. Go up through a couple glossy huecos to one with a good lip on the left side. From there get to the jugs out right, and finish using the crack for your right hand.  V2 in Sherman's book, but felt at least a grade harder to me.

name: Ghherkin in a Merkin
description: Kinda scary but fun, on the tall slab side of the boulder, climb up the middle start standing on a rock

name: shaved pits
description: start in lowest hueco, go left a bit, and go big to the jug

name: 99 Heroin balloons
description: Interesting climbing, starts low on a good right hand side pull and a decent left around the corner

name: The Berserker
description: Thin and committing. The landing is a square just big enough for one pad with a 5' tall boulder on either side, you definitely don't want to be hitting the edges of either. Follow slashing seams with thin edges up to a horizontal that is followed left to the top.     Crimpy moves on holds that you can never really pull straight down on and bad feet take you up past one hold that looks spooky. Finish the difficulties with a slightly terrifying deadpoint to the thin horizontal crack that is followed out left to finish.

name: Daedelus
description: Start low on positive incut and make moves to a jug shelf. Continue up the smooth face to the horizontal crack using any means possible.

name: Hebro Sausage
description: Sit start with a good left hand and right hand matched in a sloping dish.  Move up to a sloping shelf and figure out how to match without loosing core tension and cutting the feet.  Once matched make a big move to another sloping shelf, match again, and throw to better crimps.  Stand up and get established on the arete and drop off, or continue up the easy choss.

name: Hebro Sausage Variation
description: This variation is worth doing and maybe slightly more fun than the original problem.    Start sitting slightly to the right of the start of Hebro Sausage.  Get a left hand and heel in the large scooped hold that is used for the right hand on the original problem.  Right hand goes in a good undercling under the roof.  Make a challenging move to a undercling / sidepull pocket and work out the lip on mostly good holds.  Pull the lip and get the horizontal crack as an undercling and stand up.  Drop off or continue up the chossy face.

name: Hercules
description: Start matched in big hueco and make some moves up and right, passing a positive in cut flake, a pinch and more huecos. Take care on the top out.

name: Hot Wax
description: Not as scary as its neighbor. The landing is better in that you just have to deal with the lip of the ledge that you will pass over, and once you are over it it is a relatively flat landing. Climb good horizontals straight up to the left of The Berserker on the N face of the boulder. A good warm-up to check your head space.

name: Icarus
description: The striking center face that has a piton sticking out from the crack up higher. My estimation is that this climb could be "safely" bouldered with probably 10 pads minimum, with 3-4 of those pads being used as fillers in the massive gaps between the 5 ft boulders underneath. Worth it? I think so.  (MP made me choose a star rating, but I haven't climbed this)

name: Laments like Lullabies
description: Starts on Hebro Sausage variation (as described here on Mountain Project) and when the right hand finger lock in the crack before pulling the lip is gained, traverse 8 feet right with hand jams to a giant undercling jug. From here, finish straight up the tall ironrock slab above the large sotol. The finishing slab, although having an unprotectable bad landing, is fairly easy edging through bomber rock. The typical Hueco slab choss isn't encountered until you start moving over to descend the boulder.  I have changed the name of this problem after coming to the realization it was not inclusive and could be offensive to members of the community. I would like to express me deepest apologies to anyone harmed by this boulder problem's name and should have thought more deeply about the potential implications of names I choose.

name: The Upside Down
description: Very cool roof crack with mostly slopey holds. Start at the back and work your way up to the chossy topout with a bad/dabby landing (the only drawbacks of this climb). Not a highball by any means, but good spotting is recommended.

name: Amplified Heat
description: The name Amplified Heat applies to the first pitch.  This is one of the best elevens on the front side.    Approach by walking the road past the Mushroom Boulder restrooms and following a trail into the Deliverance Boulders.  Climb left, along the base of the wall, up to the start of Tree Crack.  Tree Crack is the big corner between Sea of Holes and Indecent Exposure.  Start from the nice sandy belay cave for Tree Crack and Sea of Holes.  Amplified Heat is the second bolted line right of the Tree Crack.  The line of brown huecos next to the crack, with a first bolt way up, is Eternal Apples, 5.11+.     When looking up at Sea of Holes from the belay cave, you'll have your back to the first moves of Amplified Heat.  The fixed pin is visible from the ground.    Start by aiming right and then back left to the fixed pin, 5.7r.  The pin is a soft iron blade only half in.  Next, tricky moves left to the first bolt, 5.9.  The easy way up to bolt #2 is out right.  A blind reach back left to the second bolt makes for a wild on-sight; 5.10+, almost "r".  Closer bolting and fun, steep, climbing lead up to bolt #6 and the start of the crux slab.  Approach the last bolt from the right, 5.10+.  The psychological crux is pulling up rope to clip the last bolt.  The hardest move is tip toeing left past the last bolt until you can reach a good edge about five feet up and left, 5.11b.        The easiest second pitch is called Amplified Apples; 5.10+, three bolts.  It climbs up the line of giant Huecos just right of Tree Crack.  Other head-wall finishes to the right are harder.

name: Indecent Exposure
description: P1 - Start on stack of boulders and climb up 20 feet to first bolt.  Climbing up and left of the arete using good features and slinging hueco's for protection before climbing past 2nd bolt and a small playing card size brass plaque.  After the memorial plaque traverse right 15' to a ledge with a 2 bolt anchor.      P2 - Looking to the right from the ledge it looks as if the arete feature drops into no-mans-land and improbable path.  But yes, this is correct.  Move up and right from belay to a crack which can be protected using 3" camalot then drop your hands down and move over to a large flake that is towards the front of the buttress.  Just above this flake/pillar is a bolt with well featured and amazing climbing ahead to the summit.  The guidebook states something about a thin crack, which I don't recall seeing.      No rap stations so you'll be walking down.

name: optical promise
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Rainbow Bridge
description: The first pitch is perhaps the most fun .10+/.11- on the Front Side.  The second pitch is 5.9.  The last is "one of the wildest pitches at Hueco Tanks", 5.11r. (Sherman, Head, Crump, Head, 1991)    Pitch one starts in an open, grassy, area below the oak tree and cave ledge of Tree Crack.  Follow six bolts up right on clean gray rock and along a bolted right leaning crack.  After connecting with Deliverance, #2 and #3 Camalots are nice for protecting the 5.9 crack to the belay bolts.   It is a 25 meter rappel off from here.  (Now your set to top rope Deliverance)      Pitch two starts with a 5.8/5.9 step right onto a black rib. 50 feet up to the belay bolts.  Small stoppers are useful on this pitch. (Paul Piana, 1992)     Pitch three climbs the overhung buttress right of Indecent Exposure.  Move right off the ledge, then up to the first of two bolts.  Move right to the second bolt and a rest.  Next move up to a bulge and pass it on the left.  After the bulge, climb straight up easier rock to the summit.

name: Tree Route
description: The start is slab that can be protected well about 20 feet up. Run out on easy slab to the start of the crack. Climb wide crack and chimney to ledge with chock stone for a belay anchor. The second pitch continues up chimney to finger size crack, dihedral up to a tree and big ledge. One can scramble from the tree up to the summit of north mountain on low 5th class terrain.

name: [Redacted]
description: This fun line would get done more often if only the landing weren't so scary.  It feels like if you fall you may roll all the way down the hill back to the meadow by the ranch house.    Start on a good left facing undercling and head up through a right facing jug.  Make a big move to obtain a marginal crimp for the left hand and commit to moving your right hand up on whatever you can find.  Once established make a few more committing moves to get established on top of the boulder.

name: Rear Burner
description: Closed June 2017 due to rock art.  No sign marking closure at problem, but it is on a list of closed problems in park office.    Sit start on bad undercling holds this might seem improbably at first, but isn't too bad once you figure things out.  Move straight out through sloping huecos to a tricky move to a right hand sidepull.  Go up and left to an OK hold and bump to a huge jug.  From here climb rightwards on easy jugs to the topout.

name: Short Order Cook
description: Short Order Cook is essentially a one move wonder on excellent rock. This will be an easy tick at the grade for some, but others will leave with nothing but a handful of bloody flappers.     Begin lying on your back, with hands matched on an undercling hueco. Move along the horizontal roof on sloping huecos to the lip. A three-foot dyno leads to what is surely one of the sharpest jugs at Hueco. Tape highly recommended! Snag the jug, then move up the vertical wall, heading slightly left to a plethora of great jugs. Topout the slab, then head west to the big chimney to descend.

name: Birth Rights
description: Sit start at good holds (you'll likely sit on the exposed roots of a fallen tree). Climb up and slightly right to match on a crimp rail. Go for a big right-hand move to the flat/slightly slopey hueco. Use the arete and a right-hand pinchy side-pull to make your way to the lip, topping out near Wicicala Cave.

name: Evergreen
description: Proudest line of this area. Highball with a committing move up top and perfect landing. Lots of sun midday.

name: The Giving Tree
description: An easier, less obvious variation to Evergreen. Start to the right of Evergreen, go up and then left to connect into Evergreen's topout.

name: Wicicala Cave
description: Start sitting back in the cave with the obvious left facing jug.  Climb out the roof on fun jugs, then climb left out the cave and up onto the boulder.  The moves are fun but the crux is not dabbing detracting from the quality somewhat.

name: Loaded Direct
description: Start matched on horizontal sloper pinch and go directly up.

name: Loaded With Power
description: A beautiful, almost uncanny Hueco feature. Stand start left side in big undercling. Go up and right through a sharp, but incut crimp.

name: A Minor
description: far right of look sharp two moves, nothing exciting, start on good holds

name: Be Flat
description: Start on high slightly sloping holds and make a big move left to a pinch or sidepull depending on where you hit the right facing flake.  Another move to a good crimp up and right leads to an easier finish.  The first move is by far the hardest.  Get this and you shouldn't have any problems.

name: See Sharp
description: tiny bad crimps on a slightly over hanging face. start sitting, feet under roof on low crimps(good right, cruddy left with thumb catch)

name: The French Route
description: Fun warm-up on very sharp rock. Start on the left side of the boulder, work right, and then up to a jug.

name: Bloody Flapper
description: Start with either hand on the tooth-like incut crimp at 8 ft (the bloody flapper hold).  Make a few hard moves to get the jug and finish easily.  With the right beta this problem will feel fairly easy, without the right beta it may feel hard.  The finish while high is easy just watch out for loose rock.  Don't let the name scare you while the starting hold is sharp none of the other holds are too bad.

name: The Bore
description: Hard climbing on jugs, sketchy top out so tread lightly.

name: Dean's Journey
description: The crux is releasing the left hand from the sloper to lean out to the good sloping rail, matching it, and holding the swing.      One of the most unique boulder problems in Hueco Tanks if not the world, Dean's Journey is a unique experience full of fun thuggy moves bizarre mantles and improbable holds.

name: Free willy
description: Note: My understanding is that the holds to the left (on the Pussy Route) are off limits for Free Willy.     Start with a good right hand in the low pockets and a left sloping crimp. You can start with a right heel hook by your right hand and a left back step (traditional beta), or just toe down on some bad feet. Go left hand to the sloper, right hand to the tooth and continue up and eventually right on pretty decent crimps. The finish can be done one of two ways: go left hand to the bad crimp, hike a high right foot and dyno to the lip with your right hand, or you can use the bad 1/4" sloping crimp with your right as an intermediate before going to the lip. Not really sure which one is easier, but I felt the intermediate was more consistent.

name: Gloria
description: This problem bakes in the sun for most of the day making it a good stop at the end of the day or on a cloudy day.  Start on good holds at the left side of the face.  Move through two pockets and hit a thin slot up and right.  From here make a shoulder move to a big hold for the left hand, one more move leads to good holds for the top out.
