name: Lip Sync
description: Fun climbing on incut jugs. The start is the crux, start on the very right side of the boulder and follow the jugs left working upwards to a good lip. Once you hit the dish, mantle the lip and climb straight up to top out.

name: Shamu
description: Start Free Willy, but continue up through thin holds to a less victorious final crux. This less contrived, more direct variation of Free Willy utilizes the thin left hand crimp you normally dyno from as a right hand instead. It is an excellent problem in it's own right, and for those who can't pull the dyno of FW, a good consolation prize.

name: Another Day Another Dollar
description: Start sitting on the left side of the boulder just right of the slab. Start in a good horizontal seam and make a challenging move up to a crimp. Keep it together and move slightly left to a gaston then to the topout.   Also this climb is listed as V2 in the John Sherman guide, unsure if this is a mis-print or if something broke.

name: Chong Li
description: Start with a good right hand pocket and a bad 2-finger left hand pocket. Put your left toe next to your shoulder and figure out how to lock off to the next set of shallow pockets. Once matched, the top out is casual.

name: Diamond In The Rough
description: Start sitting with sidepull slopers. Compress to a left crimp then make hard moves to a crimpy crack. Finish on jugs.

name: The Dripping Gash
description: Good landing, gets thin up high, but it's all there. Fun slab problem!

name: Hard Again
description: Climb the left side of the blunt arete.  The first move is tricky, an off balance throw, then it eases up.  The finish is kinda high but the holds are positive.

name: No Wonder
description: Sit Start on good jug down and right of the Wonderhole.  Make a big move right to an ok crimp and figure out how to heel the starting holds.  From here pull the harder than it looks low angle topout.

name: Orifice Affair
description: Sit start and climb the line of hueco's.  Beware some aren't quite as good as they look.

name: Roughage
description: **Effective December 2014 this climb is closed**    This stellar problem doesn't have any super difficult moves, but every move is solid with a consistent difficulty until the top.   Begin on a good left facing sidepull and climb left through a decent pinch to a small undercling.  From here make a big move to a good crimp, match and make a committing move to a jug.  This gives a chance for a shake as while from here things ease up, it will keep you on your toes until the top.    Probably on the easier side of V7, but the excitement of a possible fall makes up for it.

name: Sculpture
description: fun problem, starts in bomber undercling, climb through slopers to good holds

name: Smooth Move
description: Start on any part of the huge undercling hueco, likely with left foot low and right in the bottom of the hueco. Go big, slam dunk. Match, trend a bit right and then up.

name: Tell Mama
description: Decent route, chossy rock up high

name: The Thighburner
description: Not clear if it starts high on the jugs, or if you're supposed to start lower. Seems fairly committing.

name: The Wonder Dyno
description: This is the obvious sit start to Wonderhole. Sit start matched on the rail down and right of the hole, with one heck of a greasy foot. Make one huge throw to the large hueco and top out.

name: Wonderhole
description: Start by reaching high to the obvious hueco on the face. Get feet and then throw up and right to a jug. Top it out!

name: Home of the D-Cups
description: Simply follow the huecos up. The holds are huge making this a fun and easy route for beginners.

name: Pearl Necklace
description: Start on a nice hueco jug and make a difficult move rightwards into a layback crack.  From here the difficulty eases the higher you go.  Fun starting moves, but the difficulty doesn't last long.

name: Big Iron on His Hip
description: Start facing right with your hands in the left side of the hueco and get your right foot on a sharp spike. Reach right to a crimp right of the hueco then get your left foot up into the hueco, if you feel like a pretzl you are doing it right and you should impress your SO if they are present. Flip your left hand into a good pinch on th right side of the hueco, flag your right foot and make a long reach to a line of holds that get better the further they are away from the hueco. If youcan't reach the goodness, don't dispare because you will be sinking a heal toe in the hueco to match the line of holds and work your hands across till your left is in the far right good hold in the line. Now cut the feet and check the swing. Make a long reach again out right to a good flake and lock in another better heal toe cam in the line of holds, this one is almost scary it is so good, it feels as though if you peel your foot may stay. Reach up left to an edge just below the lip of the overhang and stand hard on your right foot to release the heal toe. Go right for another edge then over the lip slightly untill you can step off onto the boulder to the right. Be my guest and top out but the rock is terrible.   Location   As you enter the cave before you get to the true roof stuff, there is a head size hueco at or just above head height, the problem starts here.

name: Dirty Martini on the Rocks
description: Start standing on a good right hand crimp and a bad left pinch. Pull on with difficulty and make the dyno to the good hueco and top out to the left on good crimps.

name: Esperanza
description: Sit down start at the hueco in the back of the roof and climb on crimps that look pretty good, if only it wasn't so steep and the feet weren't so bad.

name: Martini Hotbox
description: This one move wonder may feel pretty easy if you are tall, but probably will feel about V9 for the average height climber.  The stretch is more from foot to hand than armspan so it shouldn't be impossible for T-Rex's.  Start underclinging the obvious Hueco and make one big move out to the oval hold on Baby Martini.  Get established on Baby Martini and finish for that.

name: Martini Roof
description: A classic Hueco roof problem.  Start sitting far back in the cave with a good undercling hueco.  Pull the hard initial moves crux, and move into roof enduro climbing on big holds.  Pull a few final hard when your tired moves and finish on the rock at the far end of the roof.  The leg breaking boulder towards the end is off, but with some toe hook beta you don't need to put you're feet above it.

name: Martini Roof short aka Baby Martini
description: Great roof problem. Start in the first good left facing hueco and make your way out the roof to a tricky section towards the end. The leg-breaking boulder towards the finish is off, although with some toe hooking beta you don't need to put your feet above this boulder. To finish, climb onto the small boulder, while this is a different finish, I found it pretty cool.

name: Schadenfraud
description: Sit Start with an undercling hueco right of the finish to Baby Martini and Martini Roof.  Make a tricky move out of the undercling to an ok crimper, pull off of this and join into Martini Roof.  Finish as for Martini Roof by climbing onto the boulder at the finish.

name: Shaken Not Stirred
description: Great movement but awfully low to the ground, though it is not like you want to be cutting your feet right and left on this thing.    From the jug undercling at the back of the cave. Make huge moves out the roof on good holds untill you get to another good undercling. From here cross left over to a very positive flake  then bring the right out to another edge a bit lower. move your feet around and reach out and up right to a pretty terrible sidepull with a tooth at the top, make sure to get a finger behind this tooth as it is the only good part of the hold. Walk your feet around to the right and fall into an undercling with your left. Get a good right dropknee and start bumping your right hand out edges eventually getting to the hueco that Big Iron starts in, you can use intermediates or just go all the way in one toss. Walk your right foot into the hueco and match, then drop your right foot down to a spike and you are ready to start Big Iron. Finish Big Iron to the step off onto the boulder to the right.    Most people blow it on Big Iron at least once as this problem is not about any one hard move but holding on for the duration.   Location   Crawl all the way to the back of the Martini Roof and find a big chalked jug undercling, start here.

name: Tequila Sunrise
description: Start matched on the right hand of Tequila Sunset and go into the DMOR

name: Tequila Sunset
description: This is Tequila Sunrise but starts with one hand on the pinch and one on the half moon undercling, go into DMOTR

name: Chocolate Thunder
description: Crux mounting the boulder, but it'll keep you on your toes all the way up. Great slab movement! The only thing keeping from being four stars is the awkward first couple moves.

name: Donkey Head
description: **As of January 2010 this problem has been closed**    Start sitting in the back of the cave on flake jugs.  Traverse left on jugs until a hard drop down move is encountered.  Stay tight and avoid the dab, and pull out of the cave,  Finish up the steep face with good holds above.  Careful if your pumped enough it's still possible to fall off here.

name: Michael Kenyon
description: This problem is the namesake for the area. If you're short jump or pad stack to gain the first two holds on the lip. Throw a high left foot rock over to a good left hand dish and figure out how to work your feet up.

name: Tralfaz
description: There is a bulging flake with a small tree growing in it to start.  After the flake it’s low angle slab to the top.

name: Big Nose Milley
description: Lowball roof climb to a pseudo topout, but excellent movement through a sea of comfy/juggy pockets.

name: Lithologic
description: Start matched on the breast shaped slopey jug.  Climb out the roof using jugs and underclings to a big move at the lip.  Catch the left hand crimp, stay tight, get the right hand crimp and pull over the lip.  Watch out for some potential to break holds while pulling the lip.

name: Mop Boy aka Mop Buckets
description: Traverse the long overhanging wall from right to left.  Sit start on Jugs behind a bush and finish left of the groove where the angle lessens.  The top while not required is easy and doesn't have too much loose rock.    The first 10 feet are the hardest and consist of a V4 / V5 boulder problem.  After this it is just a matter of fighting the pump, through mostly easy V0 climbing with two short V2/V3 moves.

name: Mopbiys crack right
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: mopboys crack right
description: Warm up at mop boys boulder, starts on jugs to the right of the angling crack and takes crack to the top

name: Room of Voices
description: Start on large sloper shelf in middle of corridor. Discover how to mantle up and reach sculpted holds above to top out. Watch out for the wall behind you as you get higher.

name: Squirm
description: Sit start on a left pocket undercling and a right slopey sidepull.  Make a big move right to a series of pockets and pinches, and figure out the best way to match and get established (hint undercling) for a big move left to jugs and an and easy topout.

name: Baby Morgue
description: There's an error in Matt Wilders guide stating that this is Playtex Husband. However. Playtex Husband was established many years before this and can be found further down on the blunt arete. The correct listing is in J. Sherman's 2nd Edition Guide on pages 36-37. I established this BP with friends during 1997. Anyway,    Start way back in the cave on the deep jug flake. Under-cling the flake and follow it out to the lip. The flake turns into a vertical crack. Climb the crack to the top.     V2 Variation:   Escape the vertical crack finish by traversing left on the lip to the hueco line. Follow the huecos to the top on easy rock.

name: The Morgue
description: This is the best roof crack at Hueco Tanks.  There are several starts - my preferred start is a low sit start. Two finishes to this route: exit when the crack ends at V4 or squeeze through the gap at V5.    Good tape job mandatory.  Send this one and you're ready for Separate Reality.

name: T-Bone Kerfuffle
description: Start T-Bone Shuffle and when you get to the horn head straight up the arete with long moves. The holds start a little thin, but get better the higher you go. Beware of choss.

name: T-Bone Shuffle
description: This route starts low and right with a campus move, then traverses left beneath a bulge until you are under two distinct huecos. Make a long reach for a dish with the right hand, then lunge for the hueco to finish.

name: Center El Murray
description: Start from the nice 10 finger horizontal edge that is just out of reach for most folks without the help of a pad or boost. Move up witht eh right into a nice sidepull/undercling and if you can get it a thumb catch. If you are short move up left first to the triangle pinch then into the sidepull. Get into a scummy backstep and cross to the triangle, you may have to take it just as a sidepull first but it is best to get your thumb around. You can also move to this first with your right and match off of another hold out left. Fall out of the cross or match and hit a right gaston, adjust your left hand and get your feet way up onto a sloping 2 finger size edge, gun for the slanting jug just below the lip. If you are short there is a pretty good edge a bit lower. Match up on the jug and top out with ease.

name: Crap Arete
description: Use the Huecos on the arete to the right of Mushroom Roof.  This route may be a bit sandbagged.

name: Left El Murray
description: Second from the left on the north face of the boulder.  High crimp start to small holds.

name: Left of Les
description: Start in the huge hueco on the left side of the north face.  Get established hands and feet in the hueco and dyno for the top.  Also possible to use a crimper on the face and climb to the jug.

name: Left Wannabe
description: Start in a left-facing hueco up to a right-facing good flake.  Feet are a little greasy.

name: Local Flakes
description: A classic V2.  On the right side of the North face, starts on good crimpers and continues up and right through more good crimpers.  Footwork is key.

name: Mushroom Roof
description: The standard for V8 according to Sherman and a classic as well. A couple of the slots are supposedly chipped out on this problem but I'm not 100% sure of I belive that, still classic none the less.     Start on the jug at the end of the low flake that goes all the way to the bottom of the boulder, one can start lower but it just turns it into a butt dragging...    Move up with either hand to start to an edge for the left or a tooth for the right. Bury the right heal toe cam to the right of where your hands started on the jug and move either right to the first "chipped" slot then cross to the second or cross off of the tooth left to either "chipped" slot. Move the right out to a good crimp, now for the first crux, releasing the heal toe while fully extended, it is possible to hold the swing but very taxing, better to step out carefully onto the point of the starting jug then up into the roof out to your left. Move up left hand to another seam and backstep the tooth to move up and right to a pretty good hold just below the lip. Step up onto the crimp that you used with your right either with a toe or a heal and catch a bad hold at the lip and bump up to a better hold. There are several ways to work your hands up over the lip but ultimately you want to get onto 2 crimpy pinches about 3 feet over the lip and your foot up onto the good hold just below the lip, from here you can stand up and grab some higher holds and top out.   Location   Starts under the roof on the east side of the boulder of the jug at the end of the obvious flake/rail on the right side of the overhang.

name: My Fifteen Minutes
description: Starts on the same good crimps as Local Flakes and heads left on the somewhat small crimps, which get smaller and further apart as you go higher.

name: New Chautauqua
description: neat climb on the backside(not closed) of mushroom boulder

name: Right El Murray
description: Same start as Center El Murray, but take the furthest right line.

name: Right Wannabe
description: The problem to the right of Left Wannabe.

name: That's Entertainment
description: Starts on the other side of the small boulder to the left of Mushroom Roof on good jugs.  Traverses up and right into Mushroom Roof.  The crux is getting into the Mushroom Roof topout.

name: Twisted
description: Start in a good hueco sidepull and move up and slightly right to a sloper jug.  From here make big moves up and left to finish on Legal High.  While the top out gets high the moves are easy.

name: The Woman With a Hueco in Her Head
description: The micro crimps to the right of Right El Murray.  Looks hard.

name: Coffee Achiever
description: Big Moves to big holds, High start left hand sidepull in a Hueco, right on a vertical crimp

name: El Techo de los Tres B
description: Rad, roof starting deep in the cave on an obvious jug.

name: Anal Intruder  10
description: Start on Lobster Claw and go left.  This thing looks way hard.

name: Beach Time
description: Start with the arete, traverse left, top out in the scoop.

name: beer can traverse
description: lowball, traverse, high dab potential, start at the back and head towards the meadow, traverse jugs and slopers, drop off when holds run out.

name: Blackmail
description: crimps on a sight overhang, big move to a right facing jug

name: Everybody Wins
description: Start on a good left side-pull and trend right through slopers and an undercling to a long move to the top-out jugs.

name: german hatery
description: start on low good undercling hueco, climb face between two cracks(the left crack is formed by this boulder and 2 star arete boulder)

name: Gumby Direct
description: Same start as Gumby Traverse. Start low traversing right, but go straight up to top out.

name: Gumby Traverse
description: Start low traversing right with the flake up to the jug and top out.

name: King Cobra
description: Sit start on the overhanging prow.  Step off to rock behind you once you've established on the vertical rock after the big throw to the jug.

name: La Delicate
description: starts on left hand chalked crimp (i palmed the wall with right)stand up on good feet long reaches to tiny protrusions

name: Lobsterclaw, AKA:Mr. Negative
description: This problem is in the shade all day.  Once you enter the meadow, hike up and left on slick slabs and over a boulder.  This problem starts in cave down and to the right on huge huecos to a difficult throw to a delicate topout.

name: MotherTrucker
description: Start sitting with an obvious right facing sidepull. The crux is the first move, going from the start to the undercling rail with greased up feet. After the undercling, grab another right facing side pull then an easy top out.

name: Penis-Puss
description: If you're standing in the cave below King Cobra/Redneck Hole, turn 180 degrees and look at the opposite (east-facing) wall. This problem climbs through chocolate-brown rock near the left edge of that face, about 20 feet from King Cobra.    Hard moves getting up into an undercling/rooflet feature off the ground. I remember climbing up the face, making awkward moves into a scoop, and being so pumped the first time through I had to bail left. The second time through I moved right out of the scoop, to top out on long reaches to incuts on the face.    Problem named for the graffiti (and diagram) already scratched into the rock when we found it. If it's still there, you can use it to educate yourself about where babies come from.

name: Pudgie pussack
description: start on far left traverse right on slopey cool holds, or kill all the fun and grab the lip(im guessing the FAist considered the lip off)

name: Rudy
description: Starts to the left of King Cobra as you are looking at the wall. Start on a good crimp and move right past slopers to a powerful undercling move. From here merge into the slopers and undercling jug of King Cobra. Would get more stars if it was a more independent line.

name: Schwerer Gustov
description: Start with low, poor opposing slopers (compression). Go straight up to easier terrain.  This one is not instructed to sit start so starting crouched is "fair game", unlike Speed Bump.

name: Shower Cap
description: Just to the right of speed bump, toe hook till you bleed.

name: Speed Bump
description: Sit start with opposing sloper sidepulls and a left kneebar. Move into a left hand undercling and make a powerful move to the obvious Speed Bump rail. Work the heel hooks and pull onto and over the lip to the easy but loose topout.  Best to get to there early as the "speed bump" and small crimps above catch direct sun.

name: Time Bomb
description: Start on an obvious low rail and climb directly up on sharp crimps

name: The Two Star Arete
description: Start on an enormous left facing jug that sits below the arete. Work your way up the arete using the enormous undercling just above the start. after reaching the top of the arete start heading left for an easy top out. You can make this problem as difficult or as easy as you want since there is a bunch of stuff off on the sides.

name: Unknown FAR Right Overhang
description: Start matched on the far right side of the boulder. Make a move up right to a sloping side pull, then work your feet so you can stab backward to the good left hand undercling. Reach back right hand to a good side-pull pinch, set a knee bar and fire for the crimps at the lip. The top out is no gimme, so keep it together.

name: Unknown Left Overhang
description: This problem follows the obvious line of good holds up the left side of the overhang. Start sitting (laying) on the lowest possible holds at the bottom of the overhang. Please let me know the real name of this route if you know it so I can update this page.

name: Unknown Right Overhang
description: Start sitting on sidepull huecos, made a big move up and left to a big jug, move out onto the undercling on the roof. Avoid the large detached looking block while you go up and right onto the slab top out.

name: Flake Roof
description: This mini showstopper has seen plenty of action and spit off more than a few of them.  The easy looking dihedral is more awkward than you would think, and the roof move is, well, very roofy.  If you can unlock the secret to the circus type moves that get you over the lip, it might just feel like hard 5.10.  If you botch it, it will probably feel like 5.12.  For most leaders, it will clock in at mid 5.11.

name: Flake Roof Indirect
description: This pitch starts from the same exposed and sloping ledge as for Flake Roof.  Climb the hueco arete up past the right side of the roof.      To end the pitch there are two options.  One finish is to step left to Flake Roof anchor.  Piana's book advises placing a nut for a directional.  The other finish is to continue up and right to the belay on True Grip.  Then finish via the excellent second pitch of Flake Roof, 5.10.  The left finish is nice for top roping the 5.11+.  The right hand connection to Flake Roof is the recommended classic.     I liked the Indirect better than Flake Roof because the holds were more fun and the protection was better.

name: The Hourglass
description: Two pitches, start in a small alcove at the base with a fist sized crack that trends up and to the left to (2) sheltered ledges.  Then you have a choice of going center, left, or right.  All seem to go at about the same difficulty although the amount of protection varies.  Climb about another 100' to a very spacious ledge and belay.      Pitch 2 runs up to the left and starts about 15' below a medium sized crack, climb the crack and continue upward either by climbing out onto the face with sparse protection or by continuing to the left.

name: Perverts Delight
description: After clipping the first bolt, the business is right there for you.  As of 10/07 it "appears" a hold has broken near the first bolt.  If so, it may be much harder than the original 11+ rating.  The fixed pin will probably keep you off the deck if you blow the second bolt clip.  Continue up and right via a few long reaches to some nice buckets.  This thing bakes in the sun, so hit on a cold day or early in the a.m.

name: True Grip
description: Pitch one is 5.8 trad with one bolt. Decent but not great. Good pro. Full rope 50m pitch. Hard to see belay legde up and left. Ledge is good with two bolt abchor. Pitch two is classic full rope 50m pitch. Five bolts and a piton. Can add some small cams. Crux is headwall with large hueco and super crimpers. Pitch two is exposed and awesome. This climb is often overlooked. Pitch two is 10a.

name: The Melon Patch
description: Crux is at the bottom, then you follow jugs up the gently overhanging face.

name: The Laughing Sutra
description: Start stemming up the alcove heading for the see-thru hueco. From here, go right for the top out.

name: Choss Training
description: Start matched in a nice hueco and make a big move up and left to another good hueco.  Set up and dyno up and right for a good jug and top out the easy finish.  Don't try any of the other crimps and small features on this problem as they'll break right off.

name: Diaphanous Sea
description: Diaphanous is a classic Hueco testpiece climbing out a steep ironrock wall on incut crimps. Start on an obvious low incut and make a few moves to a dyno and a good flake. Finish up the V5 above.

name: Hershey's Symphony
description: Classic low angle face climbing up a left leaning crack / flake.  The first moves are probably the hardest, but best to be solid before going too high on this one.

name: The Rhino
description: There are a variety of right hand starting holds used for this one, probably attributing to the range of proposed grades from V10-V12. Apparently the lower hold broke, justifying the higher right hand start & stand start (seen in most videos online)? It definitely still goes from what is left down low (there's both a slopey pocket and a crimp), and doesn't feel unreasonable. Regardless, it's a sit start!Update (9/20): In the new Kehl/Wilder book, it's given V11 and stated to use the slopey pocket for your right hand.

name: Sign of The Choss
description: Start in opposing sidepulls at head height.  Crank up to a poor left hand crimp, toe in hard and grab a slightly better right hand crimp.  Re-set and reach with the left hand to a good sidepull.  The crux next move can be done two ways, drive-by up and left with the right hand for the jug, or crimp a bad gaston and go with the left hand.  From the jug the moves ease off but your getting high.  Traverse right past Choss Training to get to the top.    Considered a difficult tick for the grade.

name: Chablanke
description: Sit start to Sign of the Cross.

name: Choir Boys
description: Would be 4 stars if you did not have to grovel in the dirt and the adjacent rock was not right behind your back as you are finishing the problem. Stellar movement none the less makes for a great problem.    Start on the right facing sloper shelf down under the roof with a foot out right. Move to a left facing sloping shelf out right and push yourself into it getting a foot up back to your left. Move into an undercling and push out to a juggy horn with your right hand. The original Choire Boys (Choire Boys Lite) starts from here. Move out left to a sloper on the far side of a block that hangs down and get a right heal on a little tooth to the right of the horn. Come right hand into an undercling on the back side of the block and step on the horn to make a reach out left to a pretty good rounded hold in a crack. Plug some kneebars, right, left or both. Work the rounded crack untill you can reach out right onto the face and a good edge that you can match. From here reach up left to the lip then up right to a flake pocket. Foot work is cruscial going for the lip as the next boulder is right on your back, through a sweatshirt on it or something so that if you blow it you don't tear up your back.    Location   Starts down in the cave just left of Sign of the Cross from a low SDS.

name: Choir Boys Lite
description: Start on the jug after the cave portion of Choir Boys and move left on the slopy underclings to the crimper top out.

name: Lughead
description: Facing "Sign of the Cross" and "Choirboys", this is an obvious seam of big huecos.

name: Nuns On Their Knees
description: Start on Chablanke and go into the starting holds of Choir Boys Light. Big move out to a slopey hold from starting holds of Chablanke with your left hand then do a heel hook with your right heel to the starting hold and a left toe hook in a hueco just below. Getting to the starting holds of Choir Boys Light and let go of your footholds with a swing out!

name: Rocking Cradle
description: start low in vertical crack traverse right into scoop top out left (if anyone has the proper name/grade, im just guessing)

name: Sign of the Cross
description: High start (may have to stack pads if you're shorter) on good holds.  Big move up to a right-hand decent hold then up to the cross.  Another big move then top out to the left.  High and scary, but super fun.

name: Sign Of The Simmons
description: Sit down start on slopers on the right hand side of the little cave/entrance. Make some fun moves up on slopers and finish by groveling through a hole at the top of the tunnel.    A fun problem marred by an awkward and uncomfortable finish.

name: Skimmer
description: Start deep in a pit on a good right facing flake.  Climb up to a great left facing flake then make a big move right.  Establish yourself in the dihedral and throw for the top.  Well protected as the rock behind is never far behind.

name: The Thin White Line
description: Climb the left side of the east face on small edges. Avoid good holds to the right and the arete to the left.

name: Two Percent
description: Start skimmer and make the moves up to the big left facing flake. Then instead of going right make a big move up to a flake on the left side of the arete. Top out from there.

name: Baco Bit
description: Bad feet at the start and then up

name: Bassin'
description: Start slightly above and to the far right of the route Honey Hole. As you reach the top there will be a nice hold to your left and a perfect rail to your right to top out.

name: Bawl and Chain
description: Beautiful straight forward highball, great warm up for your mind and body.  Mostly your head.    It can get pretty windy at the top of these boulders. Walk off near In the Bucket of Parts.

name: Beefy Reef
description: Sit start on the right hand side, traverse left, then go up, mount the slab, and keep going. The last couple moves as you leave the huecos and get onto the slab is the crux, which is pretty safe, but there's no way down once you're on the slab. The slab is cake.  Super fun!!!

name: Cast Iron
description: This line makes for a good warmup for your bouldering head.  It's different than most of Hueco as it's mainly footwork with very little in  the way of hands.  Feels quite a bit harder than most of the other classic V1's.  From the back of the A-frame climb up the smooth bullet face on your left.  As you get higher the angle lowers, but somehow it still feels like you're climbing.    To descend walk around to come down the standard Bawl and Chain descent.  Or continue over to the Gymnasium to continue on the highball warmup tour.

name: Cast Iron low
description: Start on jug under-cling and right hand divot on wall, up to jug rail, big ugly move to start of cast iron.

name: Chive Sucker
description: Short climb on the right side of Baby Baker coming up from the chains.

name: Eye Gouger
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Frankenstem
description: Stem up the dihedral. I haven't done this, but it looks like a lot of fun. If anyone has any insight, please feel free to add it! Otherwise, I'll add more detail once I do it!

name: Hidden Pleasure
description: SDS start on sloper, bump right to gaston, finish up slopers and top left.

name: The Hog (left)
description: Start LOW on right hand rail and left hand gastone. Make thuggy moves up a sort-of arete feature, squeezing your way to a hard encounter to gain crimp edges on the face above. Drop off at large in-cut or climb right and top out slab.

name: The Hog
description: This climb is aptly named as climbing this is probably like wrestling a hog.    Sit start squeezing an arete and work your way up and right into some handjams.  Make a big move around the prow to obtain some good holds and work your feet out from underneath the boulder and up by your hands.  From here wrestle your way up to make a big move to good hueco's above.    It felt like the wall next to start is considered off for feet but ok to hand jam against and fingerlock against higher, not sure on this however.

name: Honey Hole
description: Start in the large round hueco and climb straight up to top out.

name: IG5
description: Start inverted or not on hand jams or a butterfly stack low in the crack. Kick your legs up and past constrictions on hand stacks or face holds, then shuffle upward feet first until you can reach the lip and pull yourself upright to top out. An easy introduction to inversions and hand-stacks.The moves may only rate 2 points on the V-scale, but consensus was they would earn at least 5 on Insta for style.

name: In the Bucket of Parts
description: sit start with matched hands, long traverse up and left with plenty of options for both your hands and feet.      the crux is rounding the arete.

name: Man of Leisure
description: Casual jugs by the crack splitting the northwest face.

name: Men in Chains
description: Climb the crack. Top out. Getting down might be harder than getting up.

name: Mr. Potato Head
description: Start on a hueco about 6 feet off the ground and 15 feet left of where the trail ducks between boulders

name: Mrs. Potatohead
description: A short but fun climb that features a powerful top out. Start on incut holds at shoulder height and go straight up.

name: O'Grady's
description: Start on a good left hand pinch, good feet and a slimmer of a crimp for the right hand. move up through a good right hand side pull and hueco patina crimps.

name: Psuedo Feather
description: Start on left sloper climb right into crack feature

name: Psuedo left
description: Start on sloper to the left of face, climb up into pinch and exit left

name: Spud Boy
description: Sit down start at the black streak on the north face.

name: No Time to Die
description: Start matched on the lower of the two side pulls just above head height. Climb up the center of the face. The crux is throwing for the jug, which is as scary as it is hard. From there continue straight up and then slightly left at the top. The moves after the jug are still hard, so make sure you have enough pads and spotters. I gave the star rating 3, but Its really up to you to decide what you think it is. Same goes for the grade, It may be harder than V6. Be careful with the tree! Please protect the plant-life.

name: 7-10 Split
description: A super fun problem that goes up the middle of the east face on excellent holds.

name: A-Scape
description: Begin sitting under the boulder on furthest back section of the crack. Climb the crack out around the corner and top out straight up or by following the rail.

name: Banana Split
description: Highball on the left side of Split Boulder. Climb the steps to a small corner.

name: Divine Descent
description: Begin sitting down under the boulder that forms the base stone to the route Divine Wind. Climb out left around the corner to a horizontal crack-line. Traverse the crack-line to the top.   Down-climb and drop to descend.

name: Split Crack
description: Obvious 20' hand crack that separates the boulder on the west side of Split Boulder.  Slightly leaning start but perfect 2" hands to the top.      Flat landing, no obstructions.

name: Split Grain
description: Highball. Start with left facing holds and go op and over the bulge to the right of Banana Split (V0). if you get sketched out higher up you can move into the Huecos on Banana Split. A variation called "Splitting Headache" starts in the scoop corner just to the right and works up and left into this route, and also goes at V1

name: Blueberry Wine
description: Very slopey traverse next to the Mousie Adame problem. On the block that forms the left side of beginning on the entrance going to the New Meadow. Sit start on the right hand side of the block, two moves up and then traverse left following tenuous slopers leading around the corner of the boulder finishing on edges up and left.

name: Iron Whole
description: start low in hole to the right on decent-ish crimps, bust out left to sloper, go up.

name: Mousie Adame
description: Sit start on left hand hueco pocket and right hand edge. Make moves up to shallow dish and huck for the jug.

name: Rainer Maria
description: Facing Stegasaurus, this problem is directly behind you. There is a short crack problem (v2?) and a small low roof to the left under the boulder. This problem starts under this roof to the left and makes a lowball roof climb to join into the crack problem to finish. Start deep in the roof left on poor holds following cool holds and moves right. Original beta invloved a full 360 rotation to make use the holds. May be harder than v8? Very cool moves on super nice rock but a butt dragger. Takes away some of the appeal.

name: Rhinosaur
description: Climbs the scoop left of Stegasaur. Start sitting in the back and stem like crazy to gain the lip and do some wicked jive to exit

name: Stegasaur
description: Start feet first out the large roof on two opposing slopers.  Climb out to the fin, match, and pull the lip on small crimps.  No real fingery moves on this one, mostly just core strength to stay on the roof and avoid dabbing.    With the right beta this will probably feel pretty easy for the grade, or maybe it is easy for the grade.

name: Easy Dilator
description: Start on cluster of three huecos, climb straight up through cool undercling move, jugs to the top.

name: Groupie Alert
description: Located on the South Groupie Alert boulder. Start on the left side of the face, 5ft. left of the tan streak, at a good hueco. Climb straight up through long pulls to a committing and highly satisfying finish.

name: Jugular
description: Climb the main line of huecos on the far right side of the South Groupie Alert boulder. Jug hauling at its best.

name: Long Term Memory
description: About 3ft to the right of Memento. Sit start. Climb crimps to the top staying left of the big shelf

name: Memento
description: This problem goes straight up the middle of the face

name: Mid-term
description: Around the corner from Termite, climb the face about 4ft left of the arete

name: Short Term Memory
description: About 3ft to the left of Memento. Sit start. Climb up the small features above the right side of the small rock (do not fall on this rock!)

name: Term Crack
description: Sit start about 2ft below the nice lip and climb the crack to the top.

name: Termite
description: About 2ft to the left of Short Term Memory. Start near the rock, climb left and up along the arete.

name: The 40 Watt Range
description: Start on the left most jugs on the horizontal crack.  Traverse rightward for a long ways until you hit jugs and an easy section to top out on.  There are a few decent rests along the way to keep the pump factor low.

name: Adjust your Attitude
description: This line was closed in 2017 due to rock art.This line was among the best V8's on North, however it is now closed for archaeological reasons.  Start on the left side of the boulder with a left pinch and a right undercling. Make a big move to a good pocket, then a jug undercling. From here figure out some trickery to match in the gaston hueco and obtain the holds on "Serious Attitude Problem". From here keep it together for the tricky topout shared with "Serious Attitude Problem".  There are no small holds so the difficulty comes from the amount of core and shoulder strength required.

name: Assisted Living
description: Super fun movement, starts on underclings at Shoulder height, big move to fingerlock feature and t/o

name: Couch Potato
description: Try not to dab as you traverse to the right through interesting huecos on low quality rock, crux comes on higher quality rock transitioning to the wall behind you  Note: Maybe this thing broke but it felt pretty hard for v6. Felt more like V8 range to me.

name: Fuck You Asshole
description: The best thing about this problem is the name, which provides endless comedic opportunities along the lines of the famous Abbott & Costello routine "Who's On First?"    For example:    Your partner:  "What route is that?    You: "Fuck You Asshole"    Your Partner:  "Dude, chill, I just want to know the name of the boulder problem!"    You: "Fuck You Asshole!"    ...and so on    Begin with a good undercling for the left hand, and a good flake up on the face for the right, with the feet on the polished choss block in the back of the roof.  A dynamic move gains the good 1" climp/pinch below the horizontal break.  Climb into the break, then traverse left along the break with wild, dynamic moves.  Traverse off left, or head up once you are established on the S-facing slab.  Descend easy slabs to the north.

name: Governator
description: start matched on undercling, go straight out the roof, drop off at the jug crack or traverse right to top out

name: McBain
description: Sit start with a left pinch and a good right sidepull.  Move slightly left to a good crimp and a cool pinch hold.  Figure out how to move upward to a bad undercling pinch and finally a good jug in the horizontal crack.  From here traverse right on good holds to the prow and drop off or continue traversing until it is possible to top out with the problem "The 40 Watt Range"    There are several different ways of doing this problem ranging from heel hook trickery to desperate deadpoints.

name: Predator
description: Start left hand gaston, right hand undercling, left of the starting hold for Governator. Move through a cool undercling sequence to connect into the crack system. Top it out!

name: Serious Attitude Problem
description: Serious Attitude Problem climbs a horizontal roof with burly moves, and intricate footwork, ending with a challenging top out.    Begin with hands matched on the undercling/pinch thing in the back of the roof.  Its debatable where the feet should start, but purists will avoid the choss blocks near ground level, smearing their feet strenuosly on a rubber-stained divit at roof-level.  Dyno south-ward from huecu to hueco, match on the protruding undercling at the lip, then move up to sharp crimps on the sunny headwall.  Work the feet onto the lip and mantle.  This topout is difficult, as the crimps on the slab are not nearly as good as one would like.  Head north to a chimney and descend to the west.

name: Terminator Start
description: The movement on this problem is really fun, it's kinda like climbing a roof arete, however the dab factor and contrived finish detract from the overall quality.  Start on a good flake far back under the roof.  Move to a good right hand, then an okay left hand crimp.  Work the heel hooks to keep your feet on and make a big right hand move to an okay hold.  Reset your feet to avoid a swing and the dreaded dab, and cross left hand to the finishing jug just before the chimney.  Match and drop off.

name: The Terminator
description: This is a spectacular and burly sandbag.  Start at the very back where the crack meets the chimney, stepping off the boulder to the left to gain the first sinker hand.  The first ten feet will warm you up for the rest, which is unrelenting until you can stand up over the final lip.  This is a world class rock climb involving a distinct sequence of wild moves up a striking line on good rock.  Climbs like this don't get near enough respect.  Tape up and get after it because this is one of the best burly cracks anywhere.

name: Gay Abandon
description: Smearing with a side pull gets you to better holds until the top out.

name: Top Guy
description: Smaller holds lead to big jugs and side pulls. Easy mantle up top.

name: Aftershave
description: A great, slight highball with nice holds of some fine ironrock. Stand start in the pit and go straight up. Probably don't want to fall off the top, so if you're a new climber, make sure your headgame is strong.

name: Baby Face
description: This route ascends the NW arete of the Trac II Boulder. Begin with the right hand on the heavily chalked hold on the arete, 7 feet above the ground, and the left hand pinching a crimper sidepull 5 feet above the ground and 4 feet left of the arete (this start is reachy for shorties). Bring the feet up into a high stem, drop your left knee, and move left hand up to the high sidepull crimp. Adjust feet, and bump the left hand to the obvious 1/2" horizontal crimp. Move the right hand up the arete (crux?), then bump. The next pocket out left is relatively jug-like. Hit the lip and mantle easily. Descend the west side.

name: Brut
description: Climb through nice iron rock

name: Call Me Nick
description: Start just a little left of Babyface and reach up to a left facing crimp flake. Continue straight up.

name: Daily Dick Dose
description: Start with both hands on the rail.   Normal Beta: Throw your left foot on a small sharp edge on a vertical section of rock. Throw your left hand out to catch the crimp half way between the starting hold and the big undercling. Match feet and backstep, throw across for the jug undercling. As you swing out make sure to keep the landing gear up or you will dab.  Shorty Beta: Start with both hands and possibly a healhook on the rail. Move out left to a small crimp gaston and rise off of your right heal to the crimp half way between the starting rail and the jug undercling with your right hand. Match feet and go left to a pinch near the undercling then into the undercling itself with your right hand.    Once in the undercling step on the edge and cross your right hand over to a hold above the lip. Toehook in the undercling and make a couple of moves up the face. then step out and top out.     Location   On the left side of the low roof that you walk by on your way to the Trac II boulder. Starting off of a low somewhat sloping rail near the back of the roof.

name: Dry Shave
description: This problem climbs the part of the boulder that is closest to Babyface. Climb just right of the gap between the boulders from a sit start low between the boulders with a good sidepull crack.

name: Flying Marcel
description: Cool technical climbing on small holds requiring pretty good foot work and body position. Maybe V9 or so to get to the start of Babyface, then you just have to climb one of the best V7's in Hueco to finish. 17 moves, not power but not really enduro either. Would be classic I think if it did not start in a hole, really good movement.    From the start move left up to a good edge then right up to a higher edge. Haul your feet out from under the roof to near the start hold and cross your left over to an OK edge. Bump your right foot way out and float over to a faint edge with a good thumb, then bump up the "Fredrique Nicole Crimper" and bring your left into the thumb catch as a sidepull. Reach right and down to a bad edge in a horizontal seam and with a high right and low left foot sag slowly into a good 2 finger pocket sidepull just below. Hop your right foot around the corner and move your right hand around as well to a bad edge. Rock way up and over on your right foot so you are leaning off of your left hand in the pocket and reach up for the starting "jug" of Babyface. Match feet and slide your left hand around the corner to the shallow pinch that Babyface starts on. Step up into the stem/drop knee and climb Babyface to the top, it's significantly harder after the traverse.

name: Mesozoic
description: On the same boulder as Pumped Full of Semen but on the other side of the cave.  Starts on a sloper, moves right through crimps and tops. This much easier variation of Paleozoic is also sometimes referred to as Paleozoic light or Paleozoic right.

name: Paleozoic
description: On the same boulder as Pumped Full of Semen but on the other side of the cave.  Starts on a sloper and go straight up for full value instead of going right.  Mantle around corner and topout.

name: Pumped Full of Semen
description: Start in a low hueco and move left on pinches, pockets and crimps then topout straight up on a V1 slab.

name: The Reject
description: Start with high crimps at the lip. Climb over the lip and up the slab.

name: Roger in a bath
description: Sit start on Rogered in the shower, but climb easier moves to the left.

name: Squatter's Rights
description: Sit start low, climb to the jug where the crack turns, and continue straight out the roof.

name: The Used Blade
description: Climb the crack. Top out.

name: WPA
description: Start in the obvious undercling in the center of Reject Rock.  This will be to the right as your looking at "DDD".  Pull on and make a big move to a good left facing flake.  Match this and continue up on good holds.  The start from the left facing flake is "Veto Powers" V1.

name: Zulu Flex
description: Starts on a good flake to the right of DDD, and moves left into the good undercling on DDD.  Topout.

name: Barnstormer
description: Same start as Thunderbird, but go up and left along the left angling flake.

name: Big shot
description: Traverse the horizontal crack to exit ok easier terrain to the right

name: Big Time
description: Traverse the incut jug rail all the way right and shoot up to the jugs under the tree.  No shoes required or feet for that matter.  Top out as the ever growing tree destroys your back.

name: Bumble in the jungle
description: Slab right of the tree

name: The Butter Dish
description: Start on the flake on the right-hand side of the south face.  Climb straight up to the "butter dish" high of the deck.  Supposedly the sit start is V3, but both these problems feel pretty stout.

name: Decent Warm Up
description: Part of the South face, climb up right through a rail like crack and then veers left to top. It's also the descent for the boulder.

name: Dumbo
description: Climb the middle of the face

name: Elder statesman
description: Climb the line of huecos starting at the white rock scars

name: Juju wall
description: Featured rock face with many huecos, no obvious line, plenty of variations.

name: Loopzilla
description: Climb the arete

name: The Murray Lunge
description: Essentially one move.  Crab high to two relatively painful holds and huck for an incut below the lip.  Top out.  Tape on the right hand is nice.

name: Name Dropper
description: Starts on the left side of the south face in a low hueco and trends right on huecos and crimps with slippery feet.    Sit start with hands on a rail. Move left through several big dishes and continue left and up.

name: Picnic Jugs
description: Fun highball climb on huge jugs. Great to get your head straight for Melon Patch or other highballs.

name: Pounding System
description: Starts around the right side of the south face on good holds into a big hueco and around to the south face.  Then you move into a left-facing flake and into underclings.  Keep moving left on jugs and top out following a crack.

name: Thunderbird
description: Start with high hands above the "thunderbird" carved into the rock at chest level in the shallow dihedral.  Either use the few slick feet there are or campus the first move up and trend left up the crack and crimp line to the topout.

name: Tree Killer
description: Start on the rails of the dig dish about chest height. Hit the sloping dish to the right and move up for an easy top out.    Sit start off of Namedropper makes it a little harder and more fun.

name: The Backscratcher
description: Very fun line right in front of tree, it will be directly on your back the higher you climb (hence the name). If you are not confident enough to climb V1 don't do it, you will fall on a tree. Big moves on big holds.

name: El Rauncho
description: Start on two crimps, the crux is the first move to a crimp then it is mostly juggy climbing to the top.

name: Best of the Best
description: One of the nicest problems in all of Hueco, long problem with a wide variety of interesting moves

name: The Hand That Bleeds
description: Start sitting matched on an obvious down-pulling double crimp flake. Make hard moves up past a razor pinch to an interesting slot crimp and trend right to top out through edges and pockets. From the stand about two moves in it's somewhere around V6 or 7 and far less sharp.    This could have been done previously but had zero chalk or boot rubber and crumbled significantly in the first few tries. If this is your FA, please let me know and I will update the description/name/etc; I just couldn't find anything and Foose said he hadn't heard of anyone doing it.

name: Kristi Yamaguchi Lifetime Achievement Award
description: This problem is just up hill and out of the cave from the finish hold of Life Begins at 40.  Start on a left hand undercling and a right hand crimp. Jump to right hand edge then continue up to better holds and a tall top out up the dihedral.  Starting a few feet to the left on an undercling match and finishing in the same dihedral as Iron Lotus, V8

name: Between the Cheeks
description: Same start as Sheets. Pull the first couple of moves, then veer off right into a rad sequence that gets you into the crimps and undercling jug.  Like Sheets, this climb is awfully dabby, but has excellent movement.

name: Between the Sheets
description: The instructed starting holds are on the lowest ledge; not the most natural start, as it feels like crawling out of a box while avoiding the ground dab. Many opt for the higher, larger, less awkward, and more obvious ledge.  Climb out of the roof directly (there is a left and right variation; this line is the middle line). Very, very dabby, but good lines.

name: Death by Mambo
description: Start on the left side of the wall with a jug undercling. Traverse right on good holds making a shouldery crux in the middle of the roof. Good footwork and jugs lead to a thin, but easy mantle.

name: Natural Disaster
description: Start standing in the back of the roof, and work your way to the layback feature and final jump to the jug. As good as any 10 out there.

name: Three Sheets to the Wind
description: SDS. Starts back in the cave. Nice lowball. Crux is the top out

name: Bobby Boston Cream
description: Although it might seem obvious to start on the huge left facing jug, it actually starts on two sloping jugs just to the left. Make some moves right off the jug into a bad left hand pinch. Find a way to grab the good in-cut right hand crimp and top out as for Bobby's Doughnut.

name: Bobby Donuts
description: Start on a right facing right hand sloper-edge and matched left just above. Do a few move straight up and slightly right then continue trending left making sure not to bash your dome on the adjacent rock.

name: Crash Dummy
description: This line gets credit for being the only 4 star V7 in Hueco according to the Wilder guide.  I'm not sure if it's the best, but it is certainly classic and up their with BabyFace and Roughage.  Start laying down up on a shelf with a heel / toe cam and hands on a left facing shelf.  Climb leftwards thru a good pocket and a big reach left with a kneescum.  Figure out how to get the good pinch hold without dabbing on the rock behind.  Climb up through the series of cool pockets and pinches to a fun but still engaging topout.

name: The Devil's Butthole
description: This one of a kind rock climb, although in a less traveled area, is a must see problem in the Hueco Tanks backcountry when the usual locations are starting to get a bit bland and monotonous.    Starts with a large tongue at the bottom exit. Squeeze your way out 36 feet of roof climbing with the landing never being more than 5 feet behind you. Halfway through you will encounter the infamous Devil's Butthole, a dark, vast hole that easily fits six grown men inside of it (possibly more?). Venture in as far as you dare, but according to Verm, "flashlights are off route."    At the butthole you have two options - either crawl in for a rest, a game of cards, or possibly a cup of coffee, or, bypass the butthole and grit your way around the rim, continuing upwards leaving the darkness behind. Work your way towards the light and finish on the slab above.    With a little bit of everything, from jugs to pinches and kneebars to heel hooks this one is guaranteed to not leave a bad taste in your mouth.

name: Echo Chamber
description: The full package. Filled with crimps, slopers, jugs; bicycles, heel/toe hooks, knee bars; small moves, big moves, in-between moves. A must-visit if you can find a guide who knows where it is. Seems to have settled at V8, but it's a fun problem to work even if it's a little above your pay-grade, as it is broken up into sections and you can pull on from various points.

name: When Legends Die (aka Legends)
description: The best 13a in America? The physical crux is right at the 1st (2 bolts). The pump factor continues for (3 more) spaced out bolts to the headwall. Get ready to have your psyche melted on the 11d(ha!) headwall (2 more bolts). The list of radsters that blew the final headwall is staggeringly awesome.     Try to imagine, the steepest wall with the most shallow huecos ever, slopetastic! 20'-30' falls are lobbed here regularly, in particular due to the belayer not being able to see or hear the leader for a bit of the last part of the climb.

name: The Secret Sharer
description: To quote Paul Piana:  "Outstanding!  One of the finest Hueco climbs."  Before we had bolted caves in abundance, there was The Secret Sharer. Not really a cave, but that steep with a line of huecos and then fingerbuckets at the top. Most of today's caves are not the caliber of rock found on The Secret Sharer.

name: Long Dong Roof
description: If The Wheel of life were half as long and 2/3rd's easier AND at Hueco Tanks you'd have a climb like Long Dong Roof. Super fun. A really cool feature to climb on.

name: Fire It Up
description: Climb huecos through a short roof, then go left to the arete and up to the top

name: Fire Proof
description: Straight up the center of the tall face to gain a slightly left leaning seam.  Follow the seam to the top.

name: Problematics
description: Stand Start with low crimps on steeply overhanging wall.

name: Pyro Iyskys
description: Sit start under right side of short roof.  Harder for shorter climbers.

name: Warm-up Slab
description: Excellent warm-up area if you're going to be in this area or just don't want to go to The Maze. Bc I'm lazy I'm just putting them under one climb. There are 5 climbs or so on this face, but 3 stand out. 1) Cookie Butter V0- (start left of the shallow hueco dish in big rock scar) 2) Nookie Butter V0 (start with the shallow hueco dish) 3) Bushman V0 (to the right of the above two climbs; start low on nice crimps and go up very nice scar features)

name: Max Headroom
description: There are two bolted routes on the morning sun side of Natural Buttress.  The first reached is Sunny Side Up, 5.12b. Max is up right.  After the first bolt, Paul Piana's gear beta: "a few 1"-2" pieces might be nice.  A 3.5 friend protects the move to clip the 2nd bolt halfway up..."  I think of the first half as the funky appoach and the upper half as six bolts protecting vertical-plus, sustained, 5.10 "finger-buckets" on great rock. (Piana quote again).     Not the best belay zone, but one can get in a sunny pitch here two-plus hours before the Frontside gets radiated.     I plan to use the guide system for Max Headroom and get a photo before 2009.

name: Corey The Pimp
description: A long roof traverse capped with a cruxy start and finish. Start in two underclings below obvious left hand edge and right hand slope, and venture through a sea of jugs to the heartbreaker finish into the toilet bowl. You could also extend into the Lead Belly finish, making it probably around V8.  The real Mark of the Beast: this line, Long Dong, and Devil's Butthole.

name: Lead Belly (aka The Norwegian Wall)
description: Starts on right facing rail wayyy down there. Climb some 40-50 feet into Corey the Pimp, and continue climbing past the toilet bowl into another 45 feet to the topout. Wilder says it's ~140 feet total; mega. 5.13+ depending on how you see it.  You can also exit earlier into the toilet bowl, and it goes at about V8/5.13-. Honestly, this is the more natural line imo.

name: Planet Zeist
description: Bullet proof 45 degree overhang starting matched in undercling and climbing out left and up for top out.

name: Pizza Face
description: This is a slightly scary highball immediately on the left side when you walk in. Climb up perfect hueco sand pockets stepping off onto the boulder once high enough to do so easily. Guidebook says V2 - feels much easier.

name: Round Room Traverse
description: Simple! Traverse around the room either clockwise or counterclockwise. See how many laps you can do without stepping off!  For a really fun challenge try and do it in under 1-minute. The record is supposedly around 30-seconds!

name: Rubbing Uglies
description: Crux is at the start. Do not fall from the top. The rock quality is so-so so be careful

name: Bodysnatcher
description: Start on good underclings on the left side. Climb right on great holds to the lip.

name: Booty Slapper
description: Start on Bodysnatcher and go left to the lip.

name: Best of the West
description: Best of the West climbs a beautiful squeeze feature at the top of west mountain, directly behind the scepter.   start on low pockets, a couple of throws, slap moves ,and slopers lead to a fun mantle into a hueco off the the left.   some of the most classic moves and features hueco has to offer in the most ideal of settings.

name: Chewbacca
description: Chewbacca climbs the middle of the iron stone on the north face of The Scepter, about 30 feet to climber's right of the eponymous crack line. The business is in the first 25/30 feet, and I'm not really sure how to rate it. As a boulder problem, sheer terror might add a V grade or two, so it could be as "easy" as V7 or as hard as V10.    I did Chewbacca as a ground-up boulder problem, over two days, with crashpads and spotters. At one point, I climbed the easier (V3) corner to the right as a boulder/solo, to look at the lip holds and suss the top on Chewbacca, but that was the only pre-inspection.    The upper slab on both problems seemed to be 5.9/10 and went for another 20 or 30 feet, so don't fall up there. The wall is not radically overhanging, so I'm sure a good toprope could be arranged.

name: Animal Acts
description: Referred to as the slashface of V5.  Start sitting in an obvious hueco on good holds and move up and right to small crimps on the rail.  Make a few moderate moves on the rail to a big reach right and a hard match.  Reset and hit a good hueco then a huge jug.  From here walk up the easy finish.  Originally this problem was finished by avoiding the finishing jugs and using small crimps to the left.  This variation bumps the difficulty up to V6.

name: Animal Acts OG Exit
description: Start sitting in an obvious hueco on good holds and move up and right to small crimps on the rail. Make a few moderate moves on the rail to a big reach right and a hard match. Reset and hit a good hueco. Originally this problem was finished by avoiding the finishing jugs and using small crimps to the left. This variation bumps the difficulty up to V6.

name: Honeycomb Hideout
description: Start on a large shelf way back in the roof.  Climb out on good pockets and pinches, to a tricky move before the lip, (watch the dab here).  Finally pull the crux moves on slightly loose holds over the lip.

name: Scream
description: Nice setting and just a sick power boulder with the coolest ice "scream" scooped pockets. The traditional version (v11) starts on the lower set of sprag-pockets around head/chest height. There are two other recognized starts: the high stand version (V10) starts on the higher set of better pockets, and the sit-start, called Ice Cream (v12), starts on the ledge down low.

name: A.K.A.
description: Sit start on the far right side of the roof, almost outside of the cave. Move up and left across the roof to gain the left arete.  The crux is turning the lip after 35' of roof climbing.  Top out with a 20' V1 slab.

name: Some Like It Hot
description: This is the left sit start to AKA, which is a little easier and a little more fun

name: Thundercling
description: Start under the roof.  Climb up and trend left until you're standing on top.  Down climb to your left or squeeze through a really small hole to exit up.

name: Camel Toe
description: juggy pumpy fun, start low on horizontal sloper jug, climb through more jugs to a powerful move to top out

name: Odd Fungi
description: Sit start on obvious huecos on the far right side of the face.  Make a move left to a small incut crimp, figure out some foot trickery and move to the lip.  From here big holds lead up over the top.  Top out on the choss if desired or drop off from jugs above the lip.    There is an obvious extension starting around the corner on Hueco Jugs.  It doesn't make the line any harder, but does make it more fun and dangerous!

name: Shroom
description: Start with a left back step and move up and slightly across with your left to a very shallow, sharp edge. Step yoru right foot out onto a good point and rock up into an OK hueco undercling along a flared groove. Work your feet up and make a long pull to a sinker left handed sidepull pocket. Another long pull up to a pretty good edge with your right and bring your left foot up to a sloping edge near your hand level and pull over left to a good hold and an easier top out.    Pretty much pure power pulling, no real trickery, either you can hold the holds and pull off of them or you can't.

name: Slovenian Classic
description: One of the most alluring jughauls to a committing and somewhat blind lip encounter. Start by reaching for bottom hueco lip and campusing to the next. Loses a star for all the choss.  Beware: Once you pull onto this thing, it WILL be difficult to reverse and step back down (you'll understand when you look at the landing). You must have good head game for this one. Also, as mentioned, it's chossy up top!

name: Locals Only
description: Start matched on a good fin a little higher and 8 or so feet left of the start for Star Power.  Head up then right on crimps with the final hard move to gain a big hueco in Star Power after the constriction.  Finish out on Star Power.

name: Sir Farts Alot
description: This problem is decievingly difficult and without perfect beta may feel many times harder than Star Power despite having the same grade.  Start low and right in a large heuco, and figure out how to move left on the wall through an undercling.  Make a hard dynamic move to a pretty good crimp and make another big move before topping out on easier but chossy ground.  Fun movement but the rock is extremely sharp.

name: Star Power
description: One of the best V5s at Hueco.  Don't be deceived by starting at the constriction between the floor and roof - look down into the dark depths for the real start.  This climbs over 30 ft and you can step off at almost any point!   Start all the way at the back moving a bit left then back right into the ass-dragger constriction and a rest.  Continue up the face with a heart-breaker pinch near the end.

name: Hoppity Spills His Guts
description: obvious tall line in the center of the wall, follow the right angling features to the top

name: The Bathtub
description: A really good long and varied rising traverse. The landing follows the problem for much of it's length and you are not far off the ground until the very end which is a bit easier.    Start low and left from a sit and boulder up on some smaller crimpy holds, there is one that is pretty bad. Eventually you move up and right into slopers along the bottom of the "bathtub" feature. Work across the slopers to the other end of the "bathtub". Move up into the right end of the "bathtub" and out on underclings and pinches to a big move up to a jug. At this point you are starting to get up off the ground a bit. Move up the face with long moves between pretty good holds.

name: The Bidet
description: Start on the first couple moves of the Bathtub, then exit straight up.

name: Clawfoot
description: Start matched in good juggy huecos.  Make a long reach to the left for a crimp. Match and continue left until you can go up and top out through jugs.

name: Eckagrata
description: Eckagrata is essentially two moves of V6 do a hard dyno to a V2/4 top out depending on if you choose to go straight up at the top out or traverse to the left on jugs.  The PG-13 rating is for the latter top out as you climb over a boulder that would hurt to land on.  This problem is also known as the Wellsite Dyno.

name: Off the Bat
description: Underrated roof climb inside the cave at the well site. Start on slopey huecos and climb through jugs, pinches, and slopers to the face. Then move up the face.

name: Rock'em Sock'em
description: Excellent quality highball about 20' to the right of Splash it On And Be Selfless.  Start standing on the skirt with small crimps (directly across from the base of the tree). Do a couple of moves on crimper plates then up the right side of the giant Hueco.  There's a good rest in the second Hueco at about 20'. Easier climbing on good incut crimps all the way to the top.

name: The Shower (aka The Bathtub Stand)
description: The stand start to The Bathtub from the rest jug right after the tub. Just something for the less strong to climb, but also a worthy climb in itself.

name: Snakeskin Tracksuit
description: This problem starts on good holds to the right of Eckagrata. Climb up and slightly left on fun moves. The boulder to the right of the top is off making the top out quite challenging.

name: Splash it on and be Selfless
description: Start directly below the obvious black water groove on a right facing hueco. Navigate through the short roof and continue upwards towards the airy summit. Stay attentive on the somewhat solid, lichen-covered holds as you near the top - a fall from up high would be disastrous.    Note - At opportune times throughout the year the Wellsite is filled with water, completely covering the fallzone in ankle-deep ponding water. For the bold, this marks the moment to either send or splash.

name: [CLOSED] The Whale
description: THIS ROUTE IS CLOSED ~ BOLTS ARE ROTTEN ~ NEEDS REBOLTING ~ REBOLTING IS NOT RECOMMENDED DUE TO MASSIVE AMOUNTS OF CHOSS IN THE FIRST 20 FEET OF THE ROUTE  An old project (supposed 5.12b to the last blank roof) that goes up the overhang into big roofs, and ends over the lip at an anchor, but there's an 8 foot blank section that seems impassable. Discussion is needed within the community if it's worth rebolting this choss.   ADDED ONLY FOR HISTORIC PURPOSES   To the right of the Whale and left of Breakfast of Champions there are a few bolts from an abandoned project, beware, that is not a route and should be avoided too.

name: Being & Time
description: For Whom the Bell Tolls' meaner big brother.  Move through the crux of FWTBT and into the cave shared with Time Marches On and Borrowed Time. Traverse from the cave left to finish on the anchor of Lunar Being.  Sustained, powerful movement through a line of pockets across the sky.  All of the cool movement is done with the lake below.  Good fun!

name: Breakfast of Champions
description: Start next to the boulder and climb through steep terrain on good holds to the anchors on the final blank roof

name: Chossbuckler [openprxject]
description: An absolutely brutal monster of a route.  This route is an openprxject, and if you snag the FA of this climb, the bolter asks that the name remains as is. Grade needs consensus of course, could be 13c, could be 14-  Start on a chossy face with 3 bolts that have black hangers and climb up to a series of tiered roofs where the climb gets real steep real fast. Span out the chossy roofs/shelves to a reachy, horizontal crux, then traverse left across the infamously-named "sand bar". Rest up and bust into the last section of the climb involving a rowdy dyno at the pinnacle of the cave. Madness. The last section of this climb is often wet :( In the same way that The Island was "ze last great probem in ze Forest", this may be the last great roof climb in Belton, if the choss ever cleans up. The Chossbuckler was bolted by ClaytoR himself  This climb has cruxes as fierce as those on Sky/Señor/Pentzatu, with all the pump and length of For Whom/Time/Being/Borrowed. A true monster. Some team kid may flash it one day, and we'll talk about it for years.

name: Discotheque
description: The King Line of the cave. Fight the pump as the ground falls away from you climbing on a line of pockets that go out the center of the massive roof. Keep it together for a stout boulder problem between the last bolt and the chains

name: doomtheque
description: Extension to Discotheque.  After clipping the last permadraw of Discotheque, clip the next bolt a few feet above it and to the left, and finish on the anchors of The Sky Left. You'll need a quickdraw for the last bolt of Discotheque because it's a bit runout (horizontally) to the anchors of Sky Left.   When you get to the rail/hueco/two finger pocket on Discotheque before the final dyno into the cave by the anchors, instead of dynoing, go right hand to the two-finger, and left to a jug slot about 2 feet wide. From here, there's another two-finger pocket above the slot, use that and go big left to the open-mouth-hueco right next to the anchors of Sky Left (purple biners on the anchor). U thought Discotheque was pumpy !  enter umbra : smoke and mirrors

name: Feels Like Borrowed Time
description: Endurance climbing and a heartbreaker finish. Start on For Whom the Bell Tolls and when you get to the black ledge, traverse left. There's two permadraws kinda close together, don't clip the permadraw on the right, that's for For Whom. From the left side of black ledge climb up into a cave left of the cave on For Whom. Move left to a smile-shaped hueco and climb up through crimps to the top. Big ups to everyone who's helped with this section of the cave, Mike for bolting For Whom, Matt for adding a bolt on the black ledge, Evan for envisioning the line above and adding bolts; more to come.   feeling good, i'm feeling fine feels like i'm living on borrowed time

name: For Whom The Bell Tolls
description: This line goes straight out the middle of the cave starting on a white ledge and pulling into some coral fossils.  Jug haul up to a lay down rest then hit a big move as the ground drops away.  Climb into a huge cave with heel hooks and knee bars.  Very unique, very fun but keep an eye out for choss.    Once the anchors are clipped traverse the jug rail right to toll the bell before taking a victory whipper.  Thanks to Mike Klein for the vision, bolting, and hard work on this!

name: Hombres
description: Start in the obvious seeping spook eyes near the ground. Pull up and left into a black hueco then up.

name: Los Olvidos "The Forgotten"
description: Start Discotheque and out right to a ledge system. The route cuts left into a hard crux and up.

name: Lunar Being
description: Start as for Moonlight Man but continue traversing rightward for 6 bolts to a finishing crux on undercling jugs and sculpted incuts (the anchor above and right of bolt 3 is for a different line, Waning Crescent 5.10+). Finishes on a Rogers Park-esque V2 with great exposure.  Lower down to the diving board for a satisfying finishing point.    Stick clip is mandatory for first bolt.

name: Moonlight Man
description: Stick clip is mandatory for the first bolt.  Traverse in from the left along a rail then head up into the big huecos via a cruxy pocket pull.  Pull the roof and gain a cool hanging stance to clip the anchors.

name: Pentzatu Kolpatu "think and kick"
description: Line just left of Hombres. Hard boulder problem start and finish on Hombres anchors.

name: Sailor Bear
description: Climb the first 3 bolts of Breakfast of Champions and then traverse right on a separate set of perma draws and clip Hombres anchors. Holds are pretty consistent the whole route. The grade comes from the pump factor

name: Señor Muerte [openprxject]
description: Left variation of The Sky That Refuses To Die. My super project.  Formerly known as The Sky Left, this openprxject now has a new name. If you snag the FA of this climb, the bolter asks that the name remains as is. Mountain Project won't let you add the grade of 5.13d/14a, but that's what is proposed. Needs consensus of course.  Climb up the ledge left of Discotheque, up through some juggy shelves, pull the ferocious first crux involving an undercling spanning to small holds and the crescent feature. Rest up and from the crescent, bust out left into two finger pockets, a tiny three finger thread, choreographed footwork, and eventually a heartbreaking dyno of staggering genius to a blind, blocked pocket-edge. Climb up through the open-mouth hueco and clip the purple chains. I want to say that this climb should be topped out, because there are holds there, but the top of the cliff is private property, trespassing is bad, we never trespass.  This climb is the original line envisioned by the one and only Mike Klein, before any of the bolts were up. This climb is a teacher. This climb is a battle. This climb is a dance. All climbing is dance. This existence is a dance on earth until we move onward. This climb has challenged me in every way, physically, mentally, all of it, down to my core. Although I didn't send, I learned more hanging in that roof than on any other climb. This is why I climb.  Señor Fuerte is at Rogers ~ Señor Muerte is in this cave ~ who will complete the triumvirate with an FA of Señor Suerte?  Can't stop won't stop I love climbing.

name: The Sky That Refuses To Die
description: Proud. A 30-foot roof climb finishing on Discotheque's anchors. Formerly known as the Crescent/Sickle Project due to the obvious flake in the roof that looks like a crescent or sickle, depends on your fancy. Tip toe up on the ledge and pull thru jugs. Big span out the undercling to a pocket, then teleport into the flake and rest up, followed by some bouldery moves out the flake and onto the last crux move of Discotheque. Truly a beautiful hard roof.  The FA did not clip the last permadraw or last glue-in on Discotheque, although it may help if u want. Big ups to Mike and Evan for their vision and support, respectively and cumulatively, and shoutout Clayton for donating gear. Next up is the Chossbuckler project!

name: Time Marches On
