description: Start on the same white ledge as FWTBT and Borrowed Time.  Do the crux of FWTBT but instead of breaking right into easy terrain break left at the jug hueco after the crux.  Stay on the right side of the clean cave and finish directly above.    Extremely fun, flashy, gymnastic movement on clean rock and big holds defines the upper headwall of this climb. The final crux puts one doing a deadpoint or dyno at the highest point of the cave 80ish feet above the water below.  My favorite climb in Centex Cave.      -1 letter grade and -5 style points if you use the kneebar in the left cave before the last crux.

name: Waning Crescent
description: Stickclip first bolt is a must.  Traverse right for three bolts then up to a single perma. Perfect warm-up climb for the crag... with a bit of everything: jugs, heel-hooks, deep pockets, crimps, heel-toe cams and a couple amazing no-hands rests.

name: Hyperactive
description: Climb through 1, 2, and 3 finger pockets up to a large cave, climbing the left hand side up to the anchors.

name: Mr. Sir
description: If you've never cared for manufactured routes this one might change your mind. Start with a dyno to a jug pocket, then boulder your way through drilled pockets on an otherwise blank face to gain a few natural features, including the asthetic Dragonfly feature which offers the only rest on this route. After resting pull difficult moves on monos and two finger pockets through a very hard ending.    This route will test your mono strength like no other!

name: Pocket Envy
description: Pull a huge move off the ground from a massive jug to a good pocket, then move through worse pockets, dealing with a difficult clip for bolt 2 before reaching some better holds. However, getting better holds means making bigger moves, be prepared to go big off every jug.

name: Zenith
description: Start on the pocket sprag which is the shared start of Cosmic Thang, Zenith, Steel Wheels, Gauntlet, and Wrath. Dyno to the flake and move straight up through the light grey streak. Hard start on pockets with an easier finish on jugs.

name: A Line
description: The route left of the warm up.

name: Anglo Saxon
description: Climb up and left through the roof.  Pumping off the slopers at the top is fun.

name: Coup D' etat
description: Things get serious right when you pull off the ground. Start with a tough boulder problem and then continue up the steep arete passing tweaky pockets, slopers, and even a mono wrap. Powerful with big moves! The route eases up a few moves before you clip the chains. Classic!

name: Lackey
description: Located on the right side of the wall, traverse out of the roof to the right, then past a single bolt to the anchor.

name: Lefty
description: Move right from the second bolt on Anglo Saxon.

name: Mikey's Warm Up
description: Epic route with dynamic movements. The crux is about 3/4 the way up throwing from a undercling to a cresent shaped crip.

name: Nubian Nation
description: Overhanging gray pods and pockets into the alcove below the roof.  Hard last clip.

name: Orange Huecos
description: Start to right of Whitey. Climb through the orange huecos and to the bulge. If you find LOTS of bird droppings over the bulge, you are on the right route.

name: Pancho
description: Pull out the horizontal roof into thin pockets and to the top.

name: Poseidon
description: Super good route that trends right into the wide black streak.  Be careful on the second clip, decking looks possible.

name: Unknown
description: This is a largely vertical face climb that starts with mantling a giant ledge, then go bolt to bolt for the first two bolts, then for the rating go left at the second bolt to make a few moves to gain the lip, traverse the lip right to clip the anchors. It looks like it used to be easier and more direct, there are some rock scars where some blocks broke off. Watch for people tossing things off the deck above, and as always don't top out.

name: Unknown Left
description: Follow the textured rock bolt to bolt about vertical, and the route lessens just after the hole hold.

name: Whitey
description: Starts on pockets, and through to a rail for the first clip. The crux is between the 2nd and 3rd bolt with a shallow crimp.

name: Abase
description: Sit start in the back of the cave on the same holds as Abash, only go left once out of the roof on big slopey huecos.

name: Abash
description: Sit start under the roof on weird looking good holds at the back of the wall. Go out and up on good limestone pockets and huecos. Getting the lower sequence correct is crucial to this climb, as is finding the key hold for the top out.    This climb is quite popular and during a busy day its not uncommon to see people working it.

name: Centex Zuluflex
description: A roof climb linking into Abase. To the left of Reflection Eternal there is a beach-ball sized hueco at chest-height, start matched here and traverse left using huecos and crimps and two-finger pockets under the roof. Make a big move onto the jug hueco of Abase/Abash, and then finish all the way left on Abase. Formerly known as the Roj Proj.

name: Desert Storm Trainer
description: Hard for the grade. Start on the same large hueco as Abase. Move left through a deep pocket and an undercling turkey leg, shift your feet and set up for a thorough right hand throw to a sloping dish. Left to a slightly worse dish then through jugs to the top. Fancy feet.

name: Devine Hee Haw
description: Start Abase and Abash, climb right into thin bulge, and pull into deep mono at the lip.

name: Reflection Eternal
description: SDS- Start in a right facing hueco under the small roof. Move out to edges and then left and follow the obvious line to the top.

name: Scales
description: Start on underclings (spook eyes),  and use a tiny bad crimp to help propel your body straight upwards into the jug. Top out.

name: [Redacted]
description: Sit start/low start in the belly-button-height hueco that has a two finger pocket in the bottom of the hueco. More pockets and crimps abound. The starting hueco is about 6" in diameter and should be obvious.

name: Billard's Wall Traverse
description: Start on Glory Putri, traverse left on pockets, finish Impact Addict.

name: The Fifth Commandment
description: Starts on ledges in a dihedral. Traverse right across sloping jugs to a horn followed by tight moves on crimps to an awesome, orange stained hueco about 10' high. Careful topping out.

name: General Hospital
description: Start on a large, round hueco. Move up through good pockets to a interesting topout. This is a fun one

name: Glory Putri
description: Starts in the jugs just in front (behind) of the tree. Move up and through the jugs, finishing slightly left on horizontal crack. Top out is covered in lichen (and scary).

name: Happy Trail
description: Start in a two finger pocket to the left of The Scream (Scream is the two giant obvious huecos stacked on top of each other). Climb upwards. Thin.

name: Impact Addict
description: Pull straight out through large shallow hueco, and up the highest part of the wall, moving through a pinch sidepull to the large hueco in the middle of the wall; make a long reach for a pocket. Also the finish of the billiards wall traverse.

name: The Pinch Problem
description: Start in an oval hueco and good feet. Move up to a rad pinch and make some tight moves up and left. Follow good huecos in good places up to a"capstone" and top out to the left.

name: The Scream
description: Climb the overhanging face up through two large gold streaked huecos. Great problem with lots of good movement. A committing highball top out makes it even better.

name: Senor Fuerte
description: Sit start on the right side of the cave and move up into the large flake. Move left through pockets and crimps to the bulge. The grade is based on guidebooks, but this is so hard for the grade (much harder than V6).

name: Starburst
description: Start sitting under horizontal roof below Senor Fuerte; climb in Senor Fuerte and finish.

name: Vile Betrayer
description: Fun blind dyno problem that can shut down those who climb much harder than V2. The top out is easy, but committing, so make sure you keep your head on.

name: Dugout
description: SDS- start in good undercling hueco. Long reach to 2 huecos followed by lots of feet moving and and a powerful move to an uncomfortable hueco. left to the solid mono and topout.

name: The Third Nipple
description: SDS- Huge hueco up to rail. Make a big move to a crimp on the face, followed by your choice of dynamic moves. It helps if youre tall for this one.

name: The Unholdable Pinch
description: This is a project. So please disregard the rating(i had to put something). So, this is a project known for the awesomely difficult pinch which gives it the name "unholdable". SDS- Starting in a large, sharp hueco. There's a sloper, pocket, then a pinch that makes you wonder.

name: Bake Flake
description: (SDS) Sit start with good hold under the center of the flake. Move right and up (at first) through pockets until you're standing on the start and you can take on the flake. Move straight up to where the capstone has vertical crack through it, just left of the tree up top. Hard for the grade.

name: Pocket Jockey
description: A nice little highball with a slightly scary top out. Start at the protrusion (low bulge) with many large pocket to choose from and work your way through good holds, past a small dead tree/bush, to the top. The top out can be a little nerving if your new so consider moving over to the right for an easier top out.

name: Buckshot
description: Make large moves off bad feet between small two finger pockets and monos.

name: Diagon Alley
description: Sit start in the obvious two finger pocket at the bottom right hand outer edge of the cave. Move diagonally up and left through pockets to a big left hand side-pull (crux), move left then down-climb through the huge sloping rail of 'Slopes' to the jugs above the 'red-varnished hueco.' Top out up and left on 'Mexican Affairs.' Great fun. That line really tied the area together, did it not?

name: Erection Eternal
description: Sit start a few feet left of Sent in the horizontals, with an obvious good left heel. Power out the roof to a pocket, pull the roof and top out on jugs. Named after a few things lmao. May not be a first ascent but idgaf someone let me know https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pZJLelPchgo  ||  https://www.mountainproject.com/route/108337463/reflection-eternal

name: Honey on Bread
description: Start in small alcove with a three finger on the left and two finger on the right. Trend right with fun feet on shallow pockets and small holds to get to a large side pull before heading straight up the face

name: Jackson's V5
description: Sit down start and move through a couple sharp but deep, secure pockets.  The short crux comes at the top, where some long reaches to somewhat hidden holds help get you over the bulge.    It was tricky working out the beta for this but after I settled on a sequence it seemed pretty soft for V5.  Has this seen a lot of ascents lately?

name: K7
description: Another CLASSIC Rogers v4. Im sure you will agree. This climb starts in a black hueco under the roof with feet on the skirt. Move out to a ledge with several hand holds and fix your feet. Throw and use the crimp and pocket to set up for the strong move to the jug and top out. Good idea to check that pocket out before hand.

name: Mexican Affairs
description: Start on the "red varnished hueco" shared with the neighboring problem "Slopes." Follow good holds up and left to the top out.SDS (V4): Start in large hold under roof and move into the starting hueco.

name: Poker Face
description: A fun, short problem. Start in the slot and go left to the bomber pocket. Top out where ever is cleaver.

name: Sent
description: Start in a vertical hueco under a steep roof. Follow more vertical huecos using fun feet to get to a betaful pocket on the face. Big move to a bomber pocket, then campus your way up.

name: Slopes
description: Start on the "red varnished hueco" shared with the neighboring problem "Mexican Affairs." Move up and right to the huge, obvious sloping rail. Throw a heel hook and mantle up to a standing position, then negotiate some tenuous holds to the topout.    SDS (V4): Start in large hold under roof and move into the starting hueco.

name: Bozo
description: Starts low with two good pockets and reaches straight up (if you're tall, to the left if you're not so tall) over the bulge.

name: The Chin
description: Short.  Climb in the corner to the large holds under and over the roof.

name: Clean Slab
description: Another really good, really easy, really obvious climb that doesn't seem to be documented, even though it is often climbed. Just before little cave proper is a hard to miss pretty slab you can top out right or left of a large capstone above the boulder A fun but dirty variation starts seated in pockets to the left of the slab, could be topped out directly but I traverse into the typical slab top out as its direct top out is dirty and I am lazy

name: Cool Breeze
description: Slabby climb starts on two pockets, step up and reach for jug slightly to the right.

name: Finger Crack
description: Fun little problem.  Start in the crack and follow it to large holds at the top.

name: General Malaise
description: Start low on the wide hueco, but move up on slopers through a slab topout (V4).

name: Jaws
description: Fun problem with a committing finish! Great moves through the roof.

name: Right arching crack
description: The most obvious line on the boulder that for whatever reason isn't in any of the guides. follow the right arching crack from the bottom to the top, a very easy boulder problem, the top out is probably the crux

name: Serpentine Crack
description: A good, obvious route that’s in the guide but not on MP yet. Follow a juggy crack straight up to a sloping topout. Fun holds and worth the time.

name: Serpentine Traverse
description: Really fun traverse with lots of great movement. Even if you don't like traverses, try this one!

name: Serpentine Traverse Direct
description: Start at Serpentine Traverse and move directly up on the blunt arete.

name: Wadder's Direct
description: Just to the right of jaws and left of the finger crack. Start on slab and head straight up and topout over the bulge. Tight topout. The reach is extremely arm length dependent. Head slightly right for shorter arms.

name: [Redacted]
description: A Rogers classic. Start in the same hueco as Fire in the Belly. Go up to a flake, set up and make a strong move to good crimps on the face. continue up the shallow dihedral(type feature) or make a committing move to the lip.

name: Con Cuidado
description: start on the same "window" as nada (V0) but move left and up through the vertical cracks with decent quality rock. This route ends at the cracked block.

name: El Jardín
description: Start low on the orange stained rock in the middle of the wall. Work your way up a cracked block, into 2 good pockets before getting into the seem of small pockets (crux) in the black rock. skipping smaller pockets is in order for tall people. Rock quality is not bad at all but the first couple of moves on the cracked block are sharp as all get out.

name: Fire in the Belly
description: start in a large hueco with your feet on the skirt. Move across a good pocket and crimp to a large hueco undercling(an interesting feature). Get ready to leave the skirt up to a shallow pocket and 2 bomb proof pockets. Follow ledges to the top.

name: Mono Bruiser
description: Soft for the grade... for the area. SDS- This problem starts under a bulge with a jug. Right to a solid mono and then up to a ledge. The concensus is to drop off the jug a few feet above the ledge. But the topout is fine/dirty.

name: Nada
description: This route is on the right side of little new wall and starts in a "window" (when you see it you'll get it). Move straight up through the various large pockets to the ferns on top. Decent route, great for a warm up, toping out may be the hardest part of this line.

name: Que Lindo
description: Big moves up a slightly overhung face with an interesting throw. End with the obvious match or do the dirty top out.

name: Slam Dunk
description: short. but a fun problem. start standing on the skirt with a high, good sloper  and left hand pocket. Pull up and get a large, sloping horn with a lip. posture up and fight for the big sloper topout.

name: Lost and Alone
description: In the center of the Buttress, look for the obvious large pocket about 6 feet up, most likely with nature growing out of it. Follow a line of pockets (monos) up and then trending to the right. There is a larger hold hidden at the top.

name: Acoustic Elvis
description: Start on low shelf with high feet. Move up to a good crimp, and .....another crimp. Set up for a long move to a sharp pocket(finish).

name: Catlyn
description: Caitlyn has the same start as Zen. Begin in the two huecos moving right through the positive shallow pockets. Last move is a very committing dynamic move from a sharp two finger pocket moving with the other hand to a large hueco.

name: Choppy Seas
description: Start on a large orange flake. Traverse left across good pockets, ledges, huecos, and underclings and step off on the last rock. Traverse

name: The Fun Way
description: Same start as Zen, taking a more direct approach ignoring the sidepull flake out right. Grab a tiny crimp and dyno straight up to hueco and continue to top out.

name: King Krosly
description: Start in two pockets at about 7’. Move up and left to the hueco bucket in the roof, then straight out and up the head wall on bad pockets.

name: Moment of Clarity
description: Start on Acoustic Elvis and finish the heady top out.

name: The Reach Problem
description: Start on the large hueco about chest height. Left to a good hold, then right to another large sidepull, undercling hueco.

name: Zen
description: Start on a big hueco under the roof. Make your way out of the roof and on to the face via more good huecos to get to an obvious sidepull. Continue up through a pinch and more huecos to top out.

name: Sad Cyclops
description: start on a sloping rail and trend right across his face. dont worry, he loves it

name: Shin Bone
description: a beautiful line. a-typical of the rogers persona. no pockets here. ledges, crimps, and slopers to get up. start on a ledge and crimp, move up and slightly right. basically straight up after one lateral move to establish on an uncomfortable ledge

name: Cross Training
description: Sit start on the big left facing flake. Traverse left along the thin horizontal crack and go up to the ledge once the crack begins to taper off. Finish by topping out straight up toward the small pocket near the top. Boulder is a bit dirty at the top.

name: Beached Whale
description: Stand start from a round pocket.

name: Big Slopey
description: The bulge to the right of right finger crack. Start with a pinch and work your way up slaby moves.

name: left Finger crack
description: start on a ledge then climb the finger crack in the dihedral on the left side of the wall. If someone knows the actual name of this problem let me know. short.

name: Martin Luther Cling
description: Climb the slab in between the 2 dihedrals with finger sized cracks. Previously called "Aunt Jamima"

name: right finger crack
description: Climb the right finger crack in the second dihedral from the left. This finger crack is less consistent and there is no ledge to start on at the bottom.

name: self righteous suicide
description: Start on high pockets move left to the giant hueco then  blast up to smaller but good hueco  and top out straight up.  need to use a few crash pads for this one.

name: Suicide traverse
description: traverse the seam of slopey pockets and pinches from left to right of right to left, which ever floats ya boat.

name: Peace Grenade
description: Left hand has small jug and right hand starts on bad pinch,aim for the two finger pocket on the right and then go up. Sketchy Top Out.

name: Neds Redemption
description: Very technical slab if you can get the start it gets a whole lot easier as long as you can keep your balance and slowly use your feet it's a gorgeous boulder.

name: Ant Farm
description: On the right hand side of the face. A fun problem on good but small holds.

name: Ant Farm left
description: A good companion line to the original Ant Farm problem. Crimpy.

name: Sunday Surprise
description: A different style of problem from the crimpy lines on the main face.

name: The Full Banzai
description: The plumb line on this face. A little bit of loose rock takes away from the quality but this is still a line that screams to be climbed.

name: Acacia
description: This is a challenging problem that climbs the semi-prow dividing the west and south faces of this boulder. The stopper move is a precise stab into a 2 finger pocket.

name: Hold the Swing
description: This problem climbs the overhanging lowball south face of this block. The rock quality isn't great but the holds are more or less solid. For full value start with your butt in the dirt rather than on a crashpad. The crux is keeping the feet from swinging off when moving to the lip, and because the ground rises up under the overhang it's easy to dab.

name: Shade
description: This problem climbs the tallest part of the shaded west face, thus the name. The rock is a bit sandy at the bottom but improves as height is gained. The upper part features some solid crimps.

name: Slopers and hueco
description: This is a one and done type of problem but features a short, fun dyno. (Unless you happen to be really tall)

name: Veasy
description: A good easy/warm up on jugs.

name: Bring on the Climb On
description: This is the obvious and most attractive line on the first face seen when approaching this boulder.

name: Forgotten
description: The crux on this one might be getting through the bushes to the base of the climb. Otherwise the holds are good and the rock is solid.

name: Fragile Balance
description: This is a unique style of problem for the area involving a lieback of a thin fin of rock. This feature does appear to be potentially unstable so proceed with caution

name: Heel Power
description: The alternate name might be "out of the bushes" due to the thick shrubs growing around it. Despite that this is an interesting feature providing a semi-compression style problem.

name: Panhandle Boy
description: This is a fun problem on good pockets.

name: Hidden
description: Unfortunately, this is the only line on the face due to surrounding interferences. There is some questionable loose rock in the upper part as well so tread carefully. The large flake in the center of the wall can be used in a variety of ways but it's anyone's guess how solidly it's attached. Nonetheless, this is an attractive and challenging problem.

name: Face the Snake
description: A little bit of a contrived, but fun line. Named for a feature that resembles a snake crawling off the top of the boulder. *Please refrain from yarding on the snake feature as it's fragile and not a viable hold.

name: West face, aka the Warm up.
description: A nice intro to the rock and climbing style here. Top out with care because the top of the boulder is riddled with sharp edges. The overhanging south face holds several lines that are not recommended due to the sharp rock.

name: Unlikely Outcome
description: This is a really crimpy, technical problem on good rock following a rather inobvious but not contrived line. The crux sequence requires a couple of difficult leftward moves with tricky footwork to avoid the namesake tree. Get creative.

name: At the Buzzer
description: This problem is a total one move wonder and slightly contrived, although the one move is fun and challenging.

name: Squat Center
description: Short and sweet, this is a fun problem despite being only a few moves long. It features some cool holds with a nice texture.

name: Squat Left
description: Probably the 'scrunchiest' of the sit starts on this face...harder than it appears at first glance. The start hold is a neat feature.

name: No Fun after 1
description: This problem was named for the hot sun that hits it around lunchtime in spring and summer. Despite that it's a nice looking line and one of the harder and longer lines here. The rock is kind of chossy at the very bottom but improves as you gain height.

name: Anything goes
description: Pretty much the whole face is on. Climb straight up, sideways, whatever.

name: Traverse and Slab
description: This is an interesting problem requiring a horizontal circumnavigation of the boulder.

name: Unnamed
description: This is a good, juggy line that climbs the downhill face of the boulder.

name: Into the Woods
description: A neat problem on really good rock that avoids the bad landing potential of the other climbs on this boulder. Features a devious crux move to a small pocket.

name: Out of the Woods
description: This is a fairly easy problem on good rock.

name: Past Prime
description: After a juggy start this line sneaks up the nearly blank center section of the north face on barely there holds leading to a committing topout. It’s most likely easier if you’re taller.

name: Avoiding the Chop
description: This is the obvious line on the boulder consisting of pretty good holds until the sloping topout. At least one campus move is pretty much unavoidable.

name: Skin Unfriendly
description: This is a short problem on sharp holds. Probably the easiest of the potential lines on this face.

name: 120 minutes
description: Unfortunately this is the only actual boulder problem on this huge block. The crux is getting up on to the slab after climbing the short overhang.

name: Unbalanced
description: This problem features a rare for this area crux compression move. The name comes from the better holds all being RH. The landing is flat but a decent drop lurks just behind the LZ.

name: Gettin' High
description: Start on the right hand side of the Corral on a dark colored, slightly overhung and hueco'ed section, get up high on the wall, then traverse left for about 100 feet until the obvious topout on the left most side of the wall.    Once you get high, the rock quality is pretty good, but be sure to check for lose holds before committing.

name: Jug Crack
description: This tall, right facing layback jug crack is a very impressive line. Don't fall from the top!

name: Nikki's Flake
description: This route starts on a large layback flake (when the water is low to average height) then continues up on pockets and sloping edges up a vertical face.

name: Overhung Flake
description: This climb follows a right leaning flake and then pockets up an overhung face on medium sized holds.

name: Pedro, Paddle Harder!
description: Start on Nikki's Flake, but after pulling the crux and hitting the awesome right hand slot, go left and up for climbing that is a bit steeper than Nikki's Flake.

name: Pocket Protector
description: A nice warmup ladder for those days out on the Lake.    Begin on two obvious jugs about shoulder width apart and use pockets and blocks to climb the less than vertical face.    It's possible to topout through the shrubs, but a solid stand position just below the greenery facilitates a forward-facing dive back into the lake.

name: Flip Flop Crack
description: So easy you could do this route in flip flops. This is the easiest way to get to the top of the small cliff to jump off it. Water level is good, just be careful with it being a slab.

name: Slapper
description: Use some underwater rocks to get on, then slap your way up the route. If you can't find a hold just keep slapping up higher on slopers.

name: Diagonal Crack
description: Follow the long, obvious right leaning flake crack up the face.

name: Stalactite Project
description: Really cool problem that moves through big stalactites.

name: Left Project
description: Awesome climb on roof with good pockets.  Gets hard pulling the lip and gaining the face.

name: Right Project
description: Feels easier than the left version.  Moves out same pockets as left version then moves right to shallow pockets

name: Gravity Sac
description: Start on the obvious huge tufa under the Point and go straight up. An amazing line!

name: Gravity Sac Traverse
description: Start on the obvious huge tufa at the base of the Point, but instead of going straight up, traverse right once half way up the wall.

name: Close your eyes kids
description: Easy route with good hand holds, run out it's a little bit exposed, there are 2 bolts on the top to make it a top rope route.

name: a small person on a rhinos back
description: Keep to the left not hard and keep your feet up

name: rain dance
description: Not to complicated solid hands and feet

name: sandstorm
description: Solid left hands but a sketch finish good overall route, best route on lapstrike

name: something blue
description: Not to exciting straight forward route look for small hands

name: something borrowed
description: Search for good hands keep to the right easy route

name: something good
description: A bunch of small moves to the bottom platform crux all the way up

name: something new
description: Big slopey hands

name: sunny day
description: Nothing really hard going up is advised

name: ...Lest
description: Top out on the gutter. Be gentle with the hardy board under the roof. Don't be an idiot and break the window.

name: Big Boy Diaries
description: Watch out for crumbling bricks. Top out on the upper wall ledge. Ledge of the lower wall is off.

name: Bliff's Bulge
description: V0 builder on broken brick wall. Top out on the vent above broken bricks. Vent is off until top

name: Five Pints Bully
description: Decent chimney between brick walls. Arete off, vents off, pipe/gutters off. Top out to finish.

name: The Great Wall of Jang Milk
description: V0 builder on broken brick wall. Top out standing on wall.

name: PAWG the Bounty Hunter
description: Top out on the gutter

name: Wasp Honey
description: Builder on broken brick wall. Top out on the vent above broken bricks. Top is vent. Watch out for crumbling bricks, it'll do that to ya.

name: crack project
description: thin seam that runs up, starts off on bad jams with a jug foot, then smear and jam to the top.

name: find the feet
description: start on good holds with no feet to gain another solid pasted block, then find a one finger crimp to grab the jug.

name: Brizzy
description: Scramble up so low angle rock to start at a the base of a small, right facing corner/flake.  Clip the 1st bolt and than pull up onto the ledge.  Climb up easier terrain past 2 more bolts on the slab to the main ledge system below a chain draw.  Clip the chain draw and make powerful moves up the "Fins"  until you're below the main bulge.  This is the Buda Belly I think.  Climb up and left past a bolt in the roof onto the pocketed face above the roof.  Clip one more bolt as you move up and right to the anchor.  Fun!      Note: The belayer should be attentive and minimize slack in the rope as the leader makes their way up the "Fins" and especially when clipping the bolt in the roof (Belly).  A fall there with a crappy belay will land you on the ledge.

name: Bullet the Grey Sky
description: Begin 6 feet left of Two Cracked Teeth.  Scramble up stepped, low angle rock to the first steep rock.  Clip the 1st bolt and then make a few moves to pull up onto the first ledge system.  Climb easy rock past a 2nd bolt into a upward slanting left to right ramp behind the large flake.  Scramble up the ramp and face to the base of the left Arete to find the 3rd bolt.  Climb up and onto the Arete proper pulling pockets and edges up the Arete past 3 glue ins.  Finish at "Two Cracked" Teeth anchor.    The gunshot heard in the morning combined with the cloudy day and the Arete gave this one it's name (a play on another famous route)

name: COVID Corner
description: Climb up the lower slab on fun, large holds aiming for the obvious corner above.  Surmount some stepped rock to the base of the corner before making the crux moves.  Finish on nice edges up the corner to the anchor out right.

name: Covid Crack
description: It’s a good crack for practicing on. I was able to use two hand jams(unable to see in the photo from this angle) till I got my foot placement. Topping out can be tricky as there is a lot of loose rock and leaves at the top as well as low hanging tree branches. Be ware of the loose stones inside the crack that appear to be solidly attached.

name: Fear of Falling
description: Head straight up the main slab past the left pair of 2 bolts.  At the ledge, clip a bolt up and left and follow pockets up and slightly left past a bolt near the "golf ball" hold.  Move up past the bulge and punch it to the top past the final bolts

name: Holey Moley
description: Climbs up cool looking swiss cheese rock left of the darker water streak. Start on the far left side of Buda Belly. Look for a light facing corner/crack and climb this past one bolt onto the ledge. Climb up a clean slab with some nice holesk past one bolt heading for the base of the obvious, dark pocketed wall above. Make some moves in the blocky corner to clip the first bolt on the headwall and then climb up great pockets past two more bolts to the anchor generally staying out of the brownish, dirtier rock on your right.Steel Biners for anchor.

name: Ketosis
description: Start left of the prominent block/arete on the far left of Buda.  Look for a lower angle ramp just above a large, horizontal gap.  Climb up the ramp/corner past one bolt onto the ledge below a slightly right slanting crack.  Follow the crack past large pockets and a bolt to the base of the headwall right of the large hole around mid-height.  Move up onto the head wall using a shallow flake that curves up and left.  Continue up, following the arete after  the flake end following pockets to the top.Steel Biner Anchors

name: Pediatric Clinic
description: Climbs up between Holy Moley and Bullet the Gray Sky into the right leaning ramped corned near the top.  Should clean up to be a nice "entry level" route.

name: Redux
description: Climb the lower slab after making a strenuous mantle head up easier terrain onto a ledge below the major bulge above.  The route climbs up through the steepest part in a white streak.  Pull over the lip trending right towards a downward facing flake before moving over a smaller bulge onto easier terrain and the anchor.

name: Social Distance
description: Climb the lower angle rock through pockets and good holds to the ledge.  Climb up to the base of the bulge  aiming to be below the lowest part of the downward facing triangle of rock above.  Climb up to the bulge and surmount it moving a bit right as you do.  Turn the bulge onto lower angle rock and climb the right facing corner crack and face to the anchors.

name: Two Cracked Teeth
description: More exploration and cleaning yields good returns!    Cracked Teeth is on the left side of Buda Belly wall proper, just left of Breezy.  Climb up some easy ledges to the base of a small, shallow corner.  Clip the first bolt on the right face and then make fun moves, pulling on the crack and pockets on the face to a stance.  Clip the 2nd bolt and climb easy terrain up the "plates" past a 3rd bolt, heading to the base of the broken looking crack and corner looming above.  From the ledge, clip the 4th bolt and then climb up the broken corner and left face arching leftward past 3 more bolts (7 total).  Lower from the chains.

name: Group Triage
description: Short climb following big holds for a few feet before blanking out and getting thin and "desperate".  The "Horn" looks funky but is good to go - It's been pulled on pretty hard.

name: Maggot Therapy
description: The Right route on the wall currently.

name: Necrosis
description: The Middle Route on the Wall

name: Nitrous oxide
description: First line at the new dental wall!  5 bolts and two anchor bolts. Find the shallow left facing corner in middle of the wall. First bolt is left of corner. Stay farther left for a little thinner slab moves. Can also look for big white and orange rock scar 15 feet up, route runs by it.Climb past rock scar, clip a few bolts, climb just right of small tree in middle of wall, slight slabby moves takes you to small ledge.  Look right to see a big spider cave. Climb left of corner past a chockstone to clip anchors. Bomber handjam above chockstone.

name: Defective Implant
description: Fun climbing up surprisingly juggy holds.  Start up the steep face past two bolts to the first ledge.  Pull above the first cave on the right past more bolts.  Follow easier climbing up the shallow groove to the anchors.    For an easier start, climb Unnecessary Procedure to the first bolt and then head up and left into the route, joining at the 2nd bolt.

name: Rock-Ectomy
description: Scramble up the easy "steps" section to gain the first ledge and bolt.  Tackle steeper rock past some large holes towards the base of a "loose" looking pillar.  Stay right of the pillar as you climb up and eventually left past two bolts (glue ins).  Gain the upper ledge system and continue up and slightly left on easier terrain past more bolts to the anchor near the top of the wall.

name: Same Day Surgery
description: Climb up easy terrain onto the first ledge.  Trend left and up to surmount the bulge on the left side.  Climb up the lower angle rock trending right and up towards the black rock above.  Head straight up through the compact blue/black rock to reach the chains.

name: Unnecessary Procedure
description: Face climb up good, gray rock left of Rock-Ectomy.  Head up and right.  Continue up towards the "cave" aiming LEFT of the "loose pillar".  Clip a bolt in the cave and then pull through the roof past one last glue in above the lip.  Scramble up onto the ledge and then head straight up on easier terrain.  Join up with Rock-Ectomy near the top.

name: Take 2 (pads) and Call me in the Morning
description: Start matched at the 6' high crimp rail, throw your right heel around the arete. Move up the next several obvious crimp rails. Last move is a decently long throw to the top. Plenty of eliminates to be had to increase difficulty.

name: Future No More Uncertain than the Present
description: Climbs the left edge of the Arete branching off from "Blake and Ted's Excellent Adventure"

name: Honeycomb
description: Originally a TR setup by unknown parties and locally known as "Honeycomb".  Lead bolts were added later as was a different name - aka "Loopy Likes it on Top" ...    Head up the lower angle slab past 2 bolts.  At the base of the headwall, clip a bolt on the face to protect you making the clip above the lip.  Steep climbing up and left through SWISS CHEESE Rock leads up and right to a Crack before toping out with some face climbing.

name: Judgement
description: Climb up the lower angle rock and slab heading toward the base of the first, steeper corner right of the main, Honeycomb Bulge.  Climb up the shield and make thin moves left into the base of the corner.  Steeply climb the corner until the angle eases and head to the anchors.

name: Mayor's Mark
description: Starts off with a couple of nice mantles to comfy clipping stances, followed by some easy scrambling to the base of the headwall, where a good undercling will help you get the next bolt clipped. The moves up the headwall are not obvious (there are some sweet spots on the flake and some decent pockets to use), but once you find the right sequence and body positioning it isn't too hard. Unlike many Med Wall routes, there isn't a good clipping jug above the anchors - clip a little below the anchors for the most secure stance.   Named in honor of "The Mayor of Med Wall", Matt Markell, for his forethought, leadership and hard work in the rebirth of this fun local crag.   Currently the route is still a little dirty, but should clean up with some more traffic and brushing.

name: Mistaken Identity
description: Start below a short, right facing corner with a shallow crack.  Scramble up the low angle rock into the corner and use that and holds out left to pull onto the upper ledge (2 bolts).  Move up and left over the perched block and climb the 2nd slab (1 bolt) to the base of the headwall at a large hole with vertical, featured rock (just right of the The Pacifist corner).  Climb straight up past the hole onto the main shield of rock with a shallow, vertical tips flake.  Continue up the flake until it runs out and then use pockets and other holds to reach the top.  Lower Off Anchors

name: Onion Peel
description: Start just right of Honeycomb climbing lower angle rock onto the ramp above.  Continue up the slab trending slightly left on smooth, solid rock towards the base of the blocky roof below two cracks that slant downward to an "arrowhead".  Pull the blocky roof on edges and pockets and makes moves upward. Continue up using holds and pinches until you can get a left hand onto the flake above (shared with Honeycomb but you don't stray into that route).  Move up and right around the corner onto easier terrain continue up to the anchor.

name: The Pacifist
description: Start below two bolts leading towards a rock perched on the ledge above.  Make easy moves in a right facing corner to step up and left and clip the first bolt.  Move up to the 2nd before moving onto the ledge (either over the block or around it to the left on the dirt ramp).  Easy climbing up the ramp leads to a 3rd bolt.  Head up to the base of the corner RIGHT of the steeper Judgement.  Climb the fun corner/layback on large holds clipping bolts on the face out right until you reach the anchor.

name: Split Personality
description: Starts 6' right of the obvious "Mistaken Identity" corner, also climbing a right facing but more broken corner with large, flat holds.  Any more right and you get to easy, 4th class benches that trend up and more right under Urban Sprawl.  Up top, look for a large, obvious cleft in the rock.  This climbs LEFT of the groove.  Climb the easy moves in the corner, pulling up onto the ledge above.  Climb the easy slab past a hole and one bolt aiming for the bulging rock just left of the base of the cleft above.  Pull up on very featured, slightly chossy rock into the steep, excellent pockety rock above.  Climb the rock above with your right hand using the edge of rock (left side of cleft) to the top. Feet do stab out right into the cleft proper.  You can also try and climb JUST the face staying left of the bolt line - harder for sure 10a/b?.

name: Urban Sprawl
description: Face climbing up edges and pockets.

name: Adventures in Purulent Discharge
description: Fun, clean rock and moves up to an overhanging and slightly more dirty corner.  Climb lower angled "stepped" rock near the base to the first bolt. Follow good rock up and left along a left leaning ramp past a second bolt. Continue up past the third bolt making fun face moves to top out on a ledge (4-5th). Climb easier featured rock straight up (6th) heading towards the obvious, overhanging corner above.  Climb up into the the overhanging corner past two more bolts to the anchor.  The upper-most section sees some drainage. It's been heavily brushed but will still need more traffic to get it really clean. Get on it as the moves are pretty fun!

name: The Cheeks
description: New Full Length Route. TR anchors were put in years prior but were chopped during the great shutdown. Now fully installed. Climb up the initial steep rock right of Cute w/o E start. Pull onto the first ledge (tree roots and dirt). Surmount the second wall section and take easier climbing to the base of the steep headwall below “the cheeks”. Hard boulders moves through the headwall takes you to the anchors. Lower Off.

name: Cute without the E
description: Probably the 2nd best line on NT after Bow Legged.  MIGHT even be the best.      Head up past the cave and into a shallow groove past 2 bolts before pulling onto the grassy ledge. (Some gardening should clean that ledge up).  Pull past the bulge, onto easier ground heading up and slightly right towards the base of the overhanging, left facing corner.  Climb up the corner on edges and pockets before reaching a small crack near the top.

name: Dr Joe Joe
description: Scramble up easy rock to the right of Texas Caterpillar. Pull through some harder moves heading up and right of the "chossy chunk" area of the wall. The meat of this climb follows three bolts off the ledge up the steep headwall.

name: Evolution
description: One right of Bow Legged. Climb over the lower roof bulge past one bolt onto the first ledge. Follow bolts up easier climbing to the base of the headwall where it bulges out. Climb up the steep  "prow"on small pockets between Bow Legged and Cute  to the top.  Same anchor as for Cute Without the E.

name: Here's to Swimming With Bow Legged Women
description: Probably the Best Route at Med Wall.  Fun moves, good rock and a great position make this one hard to beat.

name: Time Machine
description: Just left of Bow Legged Women.Start right of Dr JoJo.  Pull up onto the first large ledge using good holds.  Clip a high bolt off the ledge and then pull up into the slot before clipping a 3rd bolt and climbing up to the base of the headwall (4th bolt just below small stance).  Clip another high bolt and make the crux moves though the "blankness" into a thin left facing corner/flake.  continue up and slightly left past more bolts to the anchor.  Mussy Lower off.

name: Accelerated Entropy
description: Start left of the classic TX Caterpillar.  Fun moves to the first stance.  Make moves over the bulge trending left slightly past a hole (watch the Cat Claw) and then trend up and right climbing the steep face until you reach the next ledge.  Make the final moves over the steep bulge through the V notch to lower angle rock and the anchor above.

name: Bermuda Triangles
description: One of the original "old routes" with an unknown name, Bermuda Triangles used to go all the way to the top of the wall over two small triangle-like blocks.  Those blocks and a large section of the upper corner gave way to gravity last fall (see orange rock scar) and with the missing triangles came a route name.  Recently restored with two bolts so it again goes to the top of the wall.    Head up through the small notch at the base past one bolt onto the lower ledge.  Climb straight up past more bolts though pockets and blocky holds eventually heading up the ramp to the base of the left facing corner and corner crack.  Climb the corner and crack past one bolt to anchors on the left at the upper ledge. Lower/Rap or continue up past two more bolts staying left and out of the orange corner. Watch out for loose rock near the top.  It's got a more alpine feel but remains fun as you "get up high" on the wall. Chains at the top.

name: Crossover
description: THE classic at OT.  Fun moves on good (for the most part) rock to the top of the wall.    Follow a mixture of hangers and glue ins up the left side of the "swiss cheese" bulge to a ledge.  Lower or continue up more broken terrain to the top of the wall.

name: Glue Steel
description: Pocket Pulling through the steep middle part of the OT bulge.  A variation breeching the steep headwall left of Sleep Deprivation.  For the most "new" climbing, start as for Sleep Deprivation. After the flake, trend leftwards aiming LEFT of the huge hole.  Climb the main headwall pulling on small pockets staying on the right side.  Pull the lip to anchors on the main upper ledge.

name: Old 5.7
description: Located on the far left side of the main OT wall.  Follow ramps and corners past bolts to a high anchor.    Start on the far left of OT at the base.  Scramble up the low angle rock trending left to a small arete and the first bolt.  Climb up on the left and follow the slab past another bolt up the base of the steeper rock on the far left.  Pull over the bulge and into the base of a left facing corner.  Follow this up past more bolts until you can pull onto the ledge.  You'll pull past one more bulge and continue up easier climbing to the anchor.  Mussy Hooks to lower.

name: Resuscitation
description: With the complete re-bolt of MedWall this is the re-aligned old bottom section of Sleep Deprivation following a better line slightly right.  Start as for SD to the first ledge.  Take the right bolt line straight up on horizontal, blocky holds through fun, vertical moves.  Continue up into large pockets to finish at a mid-anchor below the corner.

name: Sleep Deprivation
description: Fun flake and Pocket pulling leads to a fun little crux surmounting the upper bulge on the arete.   Scramble up the lower angle rock to clip the first bolt. Pull up onto the lower ledge.   Move slightly left and up, aiming for a left slanting flake (watch for PI in there).  Climb through the flake and up into fun pockets on the rounded bulge. Continue up on the bulge aiming to the right of the massive hole below the steep, grey headwall.  Reaching the headwall, move up and right surmounting the headwall and arete to finish on the large upper ledge.

name: Texas Caterpillar
description: The last route on the right side of OT before the prominent break right near the large trees at the base.

name: 007 (Shanty Town)
description: An easy slab route to practice technique or for beginners.

name: Steppin Razor
description: A straight forward slab. Good for practicing on. I’d like to see someone start this route in the seated position.

name: Aleve Dyno
description: Start with the good feet and a side pull. Dyno to the top. Top probably needs to be brushed and finding the right spot to grab can be tricky.

name: Pad-vil
description: Find the good low feet and work your way to the top - arete is off.

name: Perc - 30
description: Great rock with big enough holds. Start on the far right face of the boulder and climb the arete to top out. Keep your feet on the face.

name: Easy Nose
description: Easy slab nose that is great for new climbers or first leads. Easy start and finish, with the crux being the middle third or so, which has a few less good holds than the start and finish.

name: Mission Impossible
description: Update: By J. Thornton on Dec 25, 2012   This problem is actually on Big Overhang wall, and is same start as Hidden Jewel.   ---- Thanks for the help J. Thornton. -Tyler    1080p HD Video of the first send by Tyler Garrett VIA GoProCam.  youtube.com/watch?v=NEB-HUQ… watch to learn the moves to make this a must see at mineral wells.    Route Name:   When working this out I felt like we were on mission impossible because of how close to the ground you are, can't even get a pad underneath it. Luke, a sick sick sick sport climber, thinks this is a V5, but since I made the video I'm calling it a V4 ;-) because I sent it first.    Route Rating:   There are a lot of ways to go about solving this problem. My beta/moves will make it V4. A lot of intermediate moves to get to the finish but these moves will give you a challenge. At the very least do the start, drop into the bottom shelf, and work your way to the largest shelf and continue on to the finish, I wouldn't give the other beta more than a V2 rating.    Beta:   Two hand start, fall into the lower shelf of holds. Heel hook and move your way up to the crimpy right hand then off to the AMAZING pocket on the left. From their high feet and dyno for the sloper. The slope is a terrible hold, very sharp rocks near the top, and bumping to the last pocket from this is very challenging and I would consider it a V4+ if you use the slope and bump to the finish.     Rules:   Now remember boys and girls... bouldering or free climbing as they call it, is not allowed in the Park... But one climber is allowed to free climb to set the top rope! But only one person can do it!! So every time you start bouldering, be sure to tell everyone what your intent is.    Hope you enjoy the route, drop some feedback in the comments.    Cheers,   Keamo

name: Unnamed sport climb
description: An easy climb on ledges that can be used to access the anchors and rappel rings at the top. Also a good warm up climb for beginners.

name: Left Bridge face
description: Solid holds, easy top out.  Pretty self-explanatory

name: Atlantis
description: The Prow on the right side of the boulder.  There are a few variations (arguably different climbs).  Climbing up left from a sit start (V2), climbing directly over the prow (V3 line, careful of the boulder behind you) or climbing from inside the crack all the way right using hand jams (also V3, crash pad won't fit but it's easy to bail by stepping backwards on the boulder behind you)

name: Big and Tall Arete
description: Sit down at the huecos on the left side near the water and pull onto the low-angle face and top out.

name: Rags to Riches
description: Start the roof problem, but instead of pulling the lip, traverse to the right using pockets and finish with a difficult lip encounter.

name: Roof problem
description: Start under the big roof on the left side of the boulder and follow the chossy jugs to the lip where a difficult transition awaits.

name: Different Folks Traverse
description: Start Power Stroke and then traverse right and finish Stroke of Genius. An extension that finishes No Feet is a V8.

name: Different Strokes Traverse
description: Starts on Stroke of Genius and tops out on Power Stroke.  Crux is low moves just before going into power stroke.

name: Feat with no Feet
description: Start Stroke of Genius and move right using a sprag to a crimp at the lip and then move a little more right and do the hard mantle. This used to be a soft 7 until holds broke making the mantle a problem in itself.

name: Gary Coleman for Prez
description: Start on jugs middle of wall and trend left towards large bucket.  High step and top out.

name: Mother of All Strokes
description: 2 crimps to nice feet to the top then a tricky mantle.

name: Power Pooch
description: Start and Power Stroke and do the dyno into the Gary bucket and then traverse right and do the finish on Sloppy Pooch.

name: Power Stroke
description: Starts to right of tree on a jug and stops out after crimp on slopers

name: Sloppy Pooch
description: Starts on Giant Hueco between stroke of genius and willis and go up to a BAD lip and try to mantle...

name: Stroke Gary
description: Start on Power Stroke and dyno into the bucket on Gary Coleman and finish that problem

name: Stroke of Genius
description: Sit-start in the far right low hueco and climb up to a crimp rail over the lip.  Mantle over the lip.

name: Willis
description: Go up the largest hueco and mantle in middle of wall crux is the mantle.

name: El Raton
description: low ball. Start on the right side of the boulder under the overhang and exit right

name: El Raton Traverse
description: Start on the left side of the boulder just before it dips into the water on starting jugs. Traverse right on micro-features below the lip. Crux is figuring out how to get your left hand into the pocket. Tops after making it to the sloping rail.

name: Unknown
description: low ball. Start under the overhang on the right side of the boulder and exit left.

name: Bandito
description: Starts on flat hold and goes us to a slanted ramp with an easy but high mantle

name: Cesspool
description: Climb the face about 3 feet right of the water groove.

name: Dissolution
description: Start in underclings and get the right hand 2 finger pocket.  Straight up for the top out.  A variation exists by bumping out far left to the wonderful side-pull rail.  This is the same rail used as a right hand in the problem "Flood".

name: Flood
description: Grab a left crimp and right sloping ledge over the buldge.  Throw a left heal or toe.  Reach left to a sloper and right to a good gaston ledge to top out.

name: Hydrophobia
description: Climb up the water groove on the big outcropping boulder

name: Lava River A.K.A. Arachnophobia
description: Start on the bank to the far left (left of "Dissolution" and "Flood"), and traverse rightward under the bulge.   Good warmup. Watch out for spiders! For an extra challenge, top out "Cesspool".

name: Undertow
description: I'm tired of being what you want me to be.

name: Whisper in the Reeds
description: Climb up over the bulge using the underclings, slopers, a mono, and side-pull-slopey crimp

name: Dimitris groove
description: Climb the obvious water grove, a nice layback style problem.

name: Jizzercise
description: One of the best here. Start on right hand side pull and left hand slope. Bounce left hand up, bump right hand out to 3 finger pod. Set up for dead point and throw!

name: Left of groove
description: Climb left of the groove.

name: Left of jizzercise
description: Sit start on the face left of Jizzercise.  The crux is the start.

name: Lip Traverse
description: Start as far right and low as you can and move all the way left to the end of Jizzercise.  The pooper scooper boulder is off.

name: Pooper Scooper
description: Small boulder that leans on the backside of Jizzercise. Start on the two far left huecos, traverse up and right to the poop scoop. Top out.

name: Right of groove
description: Medium- high climb to the right of the groove.  Sit start would add a couple of grades.

name: Borreau des Couex
description: Start to the left of Quality Control on the right side of the alcove on a shelf. Pull onto the wall and use the thinnest thumb press you can think of to top-out.

name: Breakout
description: Tall wall. Start on a shelf and dyno to a jug and then figure out the chossy topout.Careful of holds breaking.

name: High Fly
description: Start standing on holds left of the finish on Swing Set and pull hard moves into it

name: Insomnia
description: Start far left at the back of the roof and a few moves left of Super Fly and climb into and finish Super Fly

name: Man From Nolan River
description: Climb through roof utilizing a two-finger pocket and then climb the shallow dihedral headwall

name: Moving to Salt Lake
description: Link-up of Man and NicArete. From the 2-finger on Man make a big move into the starting shelf on NicArete and finish the arête.

name: NicArete
description: Climb the arete

name: O-ring
description: Stand or stack pads to start on slopey hueco and crimp in the roof. Straight up

name: Pitfall
description: To the right of Quality Control, start on the shelf and make a toss to a decent hold and then climb through the overhang to a crimp rail at the lip. Drop from the rail. Many loose holds exist above and I took a face plant after breaking a few.

name: QC Check
description: Similar to turtle power. Climb the arête/prow on the left side of the alcove

name: Quality Control
description: Start on shelf with a heel and then move to two small crimps and toss for the jug. Drop from the last jug for V7 or manage the difficult top-out for the full send and the extra point

name: Super Fly
description: Start at the back of the cave on the far left and traverse into the start of High Fly

name: Swing Set
description: Start on big chossy jugs at the back of the roof. Climb jugs to the ledge at the lip and then traverse left and make a big toss to more jugs. Ryan Sewell has campused this problem.

name: Swing set direct
description: After getting to the shelf on Swing Set, go straight up.

name: Tree Hugger
description: The last route on the wall. Arete with a giant tree banch in the fall zone.

name: Baby Arm
description: Start under the roof and do a backwards stab into an undercling that looks like it's going to break. Next, move into the jug at the lip while thinking to yourself, "I made it; I'm going to flash a V7." And then get shut down on the headwall. Hardest V7 at Nolan, and in my opinion, harder than Baby Power.

name: Baby Power
description: Start Baby Arm and then traverse right at the lip to the finish on Turtle.

name: Diggin for Gold
description: High traverse on features that are always dirty. Drop after getting to the hold past the chicken head.

name: Turtle Power
description: Start on the right of the arête/prow and traverse left and up.

name: Garbage Traverse
description: Long, sweeping traverse from right to left with a V0-- section in the middle (basically walking)

name: Cat Burglar
description: Low crux involves a dyno from the dumpster to the fire escape, the rest is straightforward. I established this route in Jan of 2020 in order to retrieve my beloved pet cat from an ex boyfriend.

name: Left to Right Traverse
description: Please DON'T climb this boulder problem as there is native american artwork on the lower left of the wall.    Name says it all.

name: White Coats and Ice Picks
description: Please DON'T climb this boulder problem as there is native american artwork on the lower left of the wall.    Start at the chest high jug in the middle of the traverse; problem goes straight up using the big holes at the base of the roof and the small jug in the middle of the roof.

name: Gravy
description: East/left side of the North face. Start on two ledges and head up through the most positive holds on the slab.

name: The Vein
description: The crux is in the last moves making this climb pretty heady. Use the crack/seam with the small bush  and the holds out to it's left. Go straight up to the lip.

name: Earthenware
description: On the southern face start sitting on pad with left hand on crimp and right in sidepull with feet on nice ledge. Head straight up from the big jug. Great quailty stone for area with nice holds and moves. There is also a deeper sit start that makes is substantially harder and is still a project as far as I know.

name: Easy Wood
description: Perfect warm up on the Hard Wood boulder. Starts in a nice pocket on the right side of the boulder, and heads straight up to nice pockets and crimps.

name: The Rebirth
description: Starts far left on small crimpy rail, right move into pocket, heel hook rail. Left move to small crimp and cross over right into nice slot. Toe hook pocket and set up for large dynamic move to a tiny crimp/ knob (crux 1). Walk feet left and fall right into shallow crimp. Cross over into two crimps and set up for another huge dynamic move to slopper (crux 2), top out.

name: Chariots of the Gods
description: Start sitting on bottom ledge of the left side of the roof and go out the roof on a pocket and good holds with bad feet.

name: Jean-Luc
description: Start sitting on deepest rail of the NW arete roof and head through rails to set up to long move to flake at lip. Please hit on the right side of this flake because of risk of braking. V3 if you sit start on rails straight below flake, V3+ if you start from deeper right rail which adds 3 more moves.

name: Sweet Nebula
description: Sit start on bottom ledge under the SW arete roof of the boulder. Head out on great holds to the apex of the arete and top out on the south face.

name: Tidal Force
description: Sit start under small roof on ledge(same deep start as Jean-Luc) and make big first move to lip. From lip traverse a little left on the face to pocket and proceed to top out.

name: Welcome to Earth
description: Sit start on big rails and head through small crimps to a difficult mantle.

name: Zeldar
description: Located on the SW arete and crosses through Sweet Nebula to top out on the other side. An easier version with a little different climbing then Sweet Nebula. Sit start on a sidepulls under arete and head to jugs on west face.

name: Takin Flake
description: Classic sit start at bottom right of arrowhead flake.  Work way up horizontal section of flake until the vertical section, there are two nice pockets along the vertical line of the route.  Match on the top of the flake, static move for top out. Walk off back of boulder.

name: Barefoot
description: This is the easiest line on the boulder, it doubles as the down-climb. Locate the North face of the boulder and climb the middle of the face to the top fallowing the path of least resistance.

name: Steel Heel
description: Stand start with a good left-hand crimp and bad right-hand sloper. Work through slopers to the top out.

name: C.F.B.
description: Start in the back of the cave on an undercling flake, move out to the face and straight up to the top out.    This is a scary problem because it is committing with a sketchy landing.

name: Jason in a Blender
description: Sit start and climb the overhanging face.  The edge is on but the other boulder is off route.

name: Unnamed 1
description: Sit start from the lower underclings and top out on jugs.  Using the standing start lowers it a grade.

name: Chaka no Daka
description: Amazing quality of rock on this route would be four stars if it was longer and landing was better. Start on wicked corner crimp rail on western face and head through mono to top out on northern lip. Traversing to the left toward an easier top out drops grade.

name: Dos Equis
description: Left of Dos Mos. Starts low on gaston and crimp, large throw to nice ledge, continues up. Committing top out.

name: Dos Mas
description: Start at a sit low on the face. Make some strong moves and dyno to the top of the aret feature. climb up and make a slightly chossy top out.

name: Callous Cowgirl
description: Sit start in middle of roof using bottom ledges for feet (similar to Hardtack). Traverse up and left towards the horn of the arete using dyno for reach - utilizing a small crimp hold and a couple 'bomber' jugs along the way. Then hook heel around arete and "shimmy" towards the horn utilizing a series of heel hooks and jugs until you reach the horn/ledge for top out (or, instead of the "shimmy" method, use a Higher placed Left heel hook onto ledge of the horn and dynamically rock/pop-up over the the lip to a top-out).

name: Hardtack
description: Start on middle crimps inside roof and head straight out on edges to mantel lip.

name: Tender Cowboy
description: Start sitting and on lowest rail on the boulder's left/southeast arete. Continue up arete then cross into roof and complete same lip mantel as Hardtack.

name: Bad Grammar
description: This climb is on the face to the left of "Heros". Sit start 2 feet right of the broken tree on some tiny crimps, move up to the nob, than make some very thin moves to a better hold where you can make a very high move to a rail, from here use the crack to aid yourself up and climb to the highest point on the boulder.

name: Dark As A Dungeon
description: Start's very low on two heinous under-clings. Desperate first right move to semi-good pocket, technical left move to a gorgeous under-cling, continue into dungeon line.

name: Dungeon Line
description: Sit start in the cave and follow the line to the right to top out.

name: My Heroes Are Cowboys
description: Sit start on the deepest undercling behind the pockets, follow the crack out and top out left.

name: Easy Traverse
description: Sit Start as low as possible and traverse the edge; top out behing the tree

name: Goodnight Tree
description: PG 13 because of the tree you cross over in the middle of the boulder where there is no way to protect so don't fall.

name: Micro Cuts
description: Starts very low on one of the worst crimps I've ever crimped on, and micro pinch. Power into side crimp and static left into horrible pinch. High feet and fall into gaston and bump to nice ledge and hueco. Proceed to top out.

name: Unscarred
description: Starts on arete with crappy sloped pinch and good crimp. Dynamic move to jug, cross into jugs and set up for crimpy gaston. Fall into left crimp and throw for hueco, then proceed to top out.

name: Gravel Left
description: Start sitting on the left side of the face. fallow the good holds up and right to the top out. The crux comes just before the top out.

name: Gravel Right
description: This route starts low and contrived from a sit start and moves left to meet the same top out as Gravel Left.

name: Looks Easy
description: Start on the obvious rail to the right, use a good heel hook to proceed straight up past good slopers to the lip.    Crux is the first move

name: Pistol Grit
description: Start from a sitting position with your right hand in small pocket jug and left hand on a bad sloping pinch. There are two tiny foot holds from which to push off of. There is a good heel hook on the rail for the start of Looks Easy. The route fallows the line up and slightly left using the slopers on the left of the boulder for compression up to a big move(crux) to a left facing ledge.

name: Half Cocked
description: Start sitting with right hand on crimp near ground and left on bottom most part of rail and head up the face.

name: Hammer Head
description: Start on the side of the Hammer Head on small crimps, move left to a sloper that allows a transition onto the face of the boulder, make a difficult crimp on the left and move up the square feature to an easy topout.

name: All Star Chuck Taylors
description: Starts with match and right heel hook on the crimp rail, lock off and rock body to gain momentum for HUGE dynamic left throw to nice hueco on the opposite side of the bulge/pillar and proceed to top out.

name: The Johnny Boulder
description: This is probably the most popular boulder in the canyon. It is a good warm up spot because it is on the way to most of the other boulders in the canyon. Though this problem has been said to be hard for the grade it is simply the slopers that make things dicey. Bring plenty of contact strength.

name: Cry
description: Sit start on the rock on good holds.  Climb up into the pockets.

name: Dorsal Love
description: Start sitting match in main crack on south face. Head west through jugs to technical fin mantle and top out.

name: Get Lost
description: SDS on left side of the boulder on a good rail.  Move up and right to the juggy sloping rail that is the start to unnamed 1.  Get up from here to the hollow jug and work back to the left to top out at the highest point on the boulder, left of the finish of 1 and 2.

name: Lost
description: Stand start from the large holds just below the jug rail.

name: Simon Birch
description: Sit start below the mono pocket. Goes straight up finishing right of the tree and left of Cry.

name: Sit and Wait for Help
description: Sit start in the middle of the boulder on the crimp and sidepull and then follow Lost.

name: Wandering Star
description: Good movement and unique holds make this a great problem. Start sitting with two pinchy holds and foot and main crack on face. Head up straight to crimps and make awesome move to lip hold. Pocket to the left is off.

name: Shape of the Formless
description: Starts on huge shelf directly in the middle of the boulder, extremely good feet. Match  huge shelf, long left to Arête, lock heel in slot and throw to dynamic powerful right crimp. Cross into huge jug, match and throw to superb ledge and proceed to top out.

name: Mice and Men
description: This is the only climb in the cave. Sit start on a low shelf and make your way out the cave opening.    This climb is lowball and it is hard not to dab.

name: Mini Blue
description: This route climbs the low side of the boulder where the approach trail meets the boulder.    This is sunny in the morning.

name: The Neo Project
description: Same start as Transitional Matrix, but instead of going right to the dyno set up you exit out left to tough moves through a mono and micro crimps.

name: Transitional Matrix
description: This route climbs the steep overhang on the back of the boulder. It has had a hold break off in the past making is harder by about a grade.    Start from a sit down on the bottom left of the roof, fallow the crimps to a big move over the lip to top out.

name: Bloody Shnidbit
description: This fine line is an excellent traverse problem. It is a great route for people who aren't quite up for High on Fungi.

name: Bloody Shnidbit Sit
description: Start way low under the aret bulge that is the start of Bloody Shnidbit but crawl down inside the big hueco for an undercling sloper start. The first three moves into Bloody Shnidbit are hard and they make the entire problem complete. This is a must do problem!

name: Champiñón
description: Start matched on the undercling of Bloody Schnidbit low.  Climb through Bloody Schnidbit but instead of exiting at the end of the face, continue around the corner to top out just left of the finish of High on Fungi in the shallow dihedral.

name: The Fane of the Psilocybin
description: Use starting crimp rail of Bloody Shnidbit, from there explode out directly vertical to top out. One powerful move, short but sweet.

name: High on Fungi
description: This is arguably the best problem in the canyon. Sit/campus start on the right side on two good pockets. After a campus move or two, move out left to the two good jugs, from there throw up to a sloper rail on the face. Traverse left then  either dyno or reach high for an obvious pocket (crux) then climb straight up and top out.

name: Sweet Shitake
description: Same start as High on Fungi.  Climb straight up from the sit start on small crimps to the top out.

name: Double Stuffed
description: Start on the Unnamed 3 start hold and head to the right side arete. Use the big hole with the tree inside of it on right side of arete and top out. Top out area is the toughest because you go from jugs slots to spares crimps and sloppers. Be careful once you get to the rightside arete because the bush tree.

name: Oreo Warmup
description: Great route and boulder to introduce someone to bouldering.Shares sit start with unnamed 3 and goes straight up to the lip and traverses left to top out right of the overhanging section. Nice slot jugs the whole way. Be careful of black widows!

name: Unnamed 1
description: Sit start on the left side of the boulder and follow the crimps to the top.

name: Unnamed 2
description: Sit start in middle of boulder.  Follow big holds and top out on left of lip.

name: Unnamed 3
description: Sit start and traverse to the jug and top out over the left side of lip

name: The Creep
description: Sit start inside the small slot on the backside of the boulder with hands on compression rails. Head straight up through pockets and rails to the finish. IMO high quality for the area.

name: The Night the Earth Cried
description: Starts at poison ivy direct, until you hit slope ledge, traverse left into pocket and proceed up to sloper and crimp, then top out.

name: Poison Ivy Direct
description: Sit start with hand/hands in bottom jug then hit the dual 2 finger hold and precede to top out using the hueco. Beware of alot of choss on top of the boulder.

name: Long Stuff
description: Start matched in the small sloping hole with a heel on the large rail to the left on the start of "Short Stuff" make a difficult move to a sloping crimp pinch, climb up and right to an awkward topout.

name: Short Stuff
description: Start on the biggest rail, with a heel on the lower rail. Pull up and use the crimps to climb up the boulder.    This is a canyon classic, with great holds and an easy top out. This is the climb you take the newbies to.

name: Side Stuff
description: Start on the starting hold of "long stuff" and the right hand starting hold of "short stuff" and traverse your way across to the left side arete and top out. The crux(ish) area is getting around to the arete. Aside from that awesome feet.

name: Cheese Grater Simulator
description: Start in the middle of the boulder on nice crimp ledge and go directly up where holds start to disappear. Topout with the same top hold as Simulator Seam. Fun and commiting face

name: Simulator Seam
description: Stand start at the crack on the right/east side of the slab. Direct topout using seam and higher holds.

name: Slip'n Slab
description: Techy and sketchy is the name of this game. Using mostly crimps you head toward the whiteish hueco at the top of the face where your best holds to top out are.

name: The Aret
description: Start on the overhanging aret on the side of the boulder oppesit the road. Climb straight up the aret to the top.

name: True Grit
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Ranga Seat
description: Sit start on pebbly rails and head right and up using pockets to the thank god seat hold then top out mellowly.

name: Flat Tire
description: Great holds in the middle of the boulder. Real easy top out.

name: Wheel Boulder Left
description: Another Easy warm up route on the wheel shaped boulder. Great feet and hand holds with easy top out.

name: Unnamed 1
description: Sit start and climb the crack.  Top out at ground level.

name: Ol' Red
description: A beautiful small hands crack that is left facing for the first half of the climb than right facing for the second half. In the middle there is a good rest on a jam undercling, than the crux comes at the direction change of the crack after the rest. Classic!

name: Afterthought
description: Low sit start on crimps.  Watch the loose flakes.

name: Calumet
description: Start standing with left hand in slot and right hand around the corner. Head up arete and face and top out at the pinnacle of the arete.

name: Busted Goods
description: Start at the bottom right of the smooth overhang from a sit start. Traverse left onto the good sloper and make a big dynamic lunge to a sharp juggy ledge. Use the pocket and slopers to move up to the tallest point of the boulder for the sketchy top out.

name: Overhang Left
description: Campus start on good holds reached from a kneeling or sitting start.

name: Overhang Right
description: Sit start on the right most part of the roof and move left and up on good holds.

name: Left Route
description: Start as low as possible on the large rail feature on the left side of the boulder. Heel hook/bump/campus your way over to the same top out for the V4 problem avoiding the low choss-

name: The Roof
description: Sit start on the tiny crimp and the dish at the base of the roof. Top out to the left of the big overhanging peace above.

name: Slab Left
description: Stand start on the lowest holds possible and climb the slab without use of the crack

name: Slab Right
description: This climbs the crack in the middle of the slab from a sitting start

name: [Redacted]
description: Starts on low sloping rail, powerful left move to superb pinch, match. Right to horrbile intermediate and bump to decent crimp. Left follows into crimp and dynamic move onto top rail. Traverse left into huge jug and proceed to top out(sketch)

name: Acronym Left
description: Start low and left, traverse to the big hole and top out straight above it.

name: Acronym Right
description: Sit start on the big sloper underneath the boulder on the right under the overhang, traverse to the left and top out in the same place as Acronym Left

name: Medicine Man
description: Start sitting on left hand edge and right hand crimp directly under the crack feature. Use the crack to hit the lip and traverse left to NE corner to top out. Be careful with the dusty flake. Please don't intentionally destroy.

name: Justin Went Left
description: Stand start at the bottom of the roof and top out right.

name: Gus’s blueberry
description: Start on two sloped pinches down and to the right. Move up and to the left to small crimps and pocket. Finish straight up on slopey finish.

name: Horsefly Traverse
description: Start on the far right side of the low face with all of the slopers, traverse left along the rail of slopers and top out around the corner.

name: The Two Fingered Foxtrot
