description: Start from a sit, use the two slot  jugs to move up to the big ledge, climb right through the two pockets to a big move for the lip and top out.

name: Figure 12
description: Start from a sitting/kneeling position on the lowest rail above the cave. Use the good edges to make your way to the big hueco. Climb up and slightly right through 2 finger pockets and top out. Avoid holds around the aret to the left.

name: Root Route
description: On the North face of the boulder sit start on crimp rails near the NE corner and head straight up using a two finger pocket and other rails to the top. Though small for this area this problem has nice movement that I thought made it worthy of a record.

name: The return of Quetzalcoatl
description: Match in the huge under-cling,and lock feet into HORRIBLE micro incisions into the rock. desperate left move to crimp, bump to slopey pinch. Right move to a nice gaston, left to moderate gaston. Left to deep pocket, and proceed to top out(Kind of scetch, trust yourself)

name: Cinderella Crack
description: Great fist-sized and larger jams for the first half depending on hand size. The crux is the transition from the crack to the opening below the roof via sketchy sloping holds. Once past the crux, move right and up the ledges leading to the roof.

name: Three Blind Mice
description: This is one of the oldest climbs in the canyon that I know of. Climb straight up the crack in the dihedral until it becomes overhanging (5.6).  Make a bomber anchor in the roof, then traverse left under and clip the three old 1/4 leeper hangers, but don't expect them to do anything as the last two are spinners (crux). Make your way up to the top and belay off of the trees via a ton of webbing or cord.

name: Welcome to Greenville
description: As a follower this route was scary. Climb up the crack with decent pro close to the ground then it gets chossy and sandy. Belay from the tree to the left.

name: The Dihedral Crack
description: This is a great line on the left side of Hueco. Most of the climb is easy with the first few moves being the hardest. Be very confident at the grade as this is soft sandstone so gear can never be completely trusted.     Climb up the hand crack to the ledge. Continue up an offwidth crack to the top. Belay off trees at the top.

name: Sandy Sandwich
description: This is my second favorite trad line in the canyon.    Note, a fall off the start could pull you and your belayer off the ledge so it is a good idea to set up a belay anchor. The 5.9 grading is pretty stiff and should not be taken lightly. Though the rock here is pretty solid it is still soft sandstone and a fall could very likely pull gear. Make sure you are very confident at the grade before attempting.    Follow the crack up and left (crux) under an overhang then climb through a keyhole at the top.  Belay off of several cracks at the top or the tree further back.

name: Arrowhead Stack
description: This route follows a series of broken blocks stacked on top of each other that range from easy block moves to long hands with fun footwork. This eventually leads to a good stance below the crack to finish the line. The crux is the crack which uses high feet on chossy holds that make the final moves committing.

name: Arrows Point the Way
description: This route follows a crack and face moves that eventually starts leaning to the right. First few moves involve strong hand moves with smears for feet (1st crux). The mid section contains some good foot moves that are slightly off-balance. The final section is the right-leaning section. This part has slabby hands and high feet (2nd crux).

name: Barrel Full 'O Braves
description: A fun route that climbs directly up a dihedral crack with some face moves. The crux includes enjoyable foot moves that leave some feeling insecure just below halfway. Be careful as rock quality is decent but there are some tempting holds to the far right that will prove to pitch off the route when weighted.

name: Smoke Signals
description: Start at base of dihedral crack with obvious large chock stone. Follow the crack through a roof (crux). Once the roof rounds the corner and continues upwards the route begins using more face holds.

name: Warpath
description: Another great canyon climb. The rock quality of this route is superb. (until the very top at least). The crack ranges from big hands to off width and is an excellent test piece for a variety of crack climbing skills.     Access the lower ramp by either climbing straight up the leftmost crack, or start on the right and traverse over. Continue up the crack in the dihedral to the top. At the top, either top out by climbing the choss straight up, or traverse right.    Perhaps the best option would be to pre-rig an anchor by throwing some webbing over the huge block so that you could avoid topping out.    Another anchor option is to use the tree located far right of the climb. This works, though the follower would experience quite a swing.

name: Easy Does It
description: This climb follows straight up a diherdral crack using some face moves. The crux is a simple mantle at the bulge about a third of the way up. Afterwards, the climb moves up some slabby feet with cracks for hands.

name: Just stick it in there
description: Climb the crack with good feet up until the overhang.  Fairly easy crux with bomber hands to a slopey topout.

name: Not so easy does it
description: Climb the crack on the left side of the dihedral for "easy does it".  The crux is before halfway up when you run out of feet and need solid crack technique.

name: Skinned elbow
description: Super fun route, crux starts at the second crack above the broken section.  Strenuous climbing for 5-10 feet until some nice hand holds help you finish

name: The Enema Crack
description: The hand crack on Triple Cracks.    Climb up using jams and stemming where necessary. In the end we really just stemmed the chimney  and used the crack for pro. If you tried it with ought stemming this would easily be a hard 5.10.

name: The Bridge to No Where
description: Climb from bottom left corner through the roof to top out at the top right. Could be wet for a while after major rains under the boulder.

name: The Art of Story Telling
description: Start low on shallow pocket and side crimp. Traverse over into mono and horrible pocket, set up for huge throw to sharp edges.

name: Human Automaton
description: Sit start on a big ledge under the roof on the corner of the boulder that faces the stream. Climb out the roof using the ledge around the lip and the pocket in the middle of the roof. Finish on the crimpy face.

name: The Human Pinnball
description: This route starts on the smaller boulder under the roof and climbs up the inside face of the boulder. Continue up the tight topout between the two boulders.

name: Dimples
description: Climb up the middle of the diamond shaped slab on the back of the boulder. There is a good step up on to the slab than it's easy climbing on perfect pockets to the top.    To make this more interesting climb with no hands (forearms allowed).

name: Down Climb
description: Fallow the really easy jug pockets up the right side of the slab to the top.

name: Misfire offwidth
description: Super awkward route. However it was really fun. I don't know if it's been climbed yet but I figured I'd put in some information to help further develop the area.

name: Pocket Full of Shells
description: Start with left hand in a good low jug and right hand in a high jug, (there is also a right foot cam), climb straight up and pull the fun top out.    Try to stay away from the chossy blocks to the right of the climb as they may rip off in your face.

name: Buffalo Hump
description: Sit start with the great smooth pocket and wicked sloper with feet on lower rail. Get to the top through face pocket and sloping arete.

name: Short Buzz
description: Start in huge horizontal rectangle hueco on the north face. Hit the lip and have fun toping out.

name: 3 move wonder
description: starts somewhat low and goes up to sloper holds with a fun mantle.  thats really the best part.

name: A Wing And A Prayer
description: Start matched on right facing side pull. Go up and left! Really fun!

name: Baby Saucer Direct
description: Start under the overhang and go straight up! Short, but fun!

name: Baby Saucer Traverse
description: Start on the left side of the Baby Saucer Boulder (around to the left of Baby Saucer Direct) and traverse uphill. Keep your feet under the overhang of Baby Saucer Direct and top out after you traverse through it.

name: Beesechurger (for Monch)
description: Start with both hands on the right side of the crack and your left foot on the left side. Get your right foot up onto the right side and then it’s just a matter of adjusting the hand and foot holds slightly to mantle on top of the rock.

name: Butt Rock
description: Start seated with a match on a low left facing flake. Get poor feet, move right to a slopey crimper, then make a huge bump to a good fist sized hueco. Top out!

name: The eyebrow
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Getting Out Of Texas
description: Start matched on a flat ledge in the lip of the cave, get feet, throw a heel and mantle. Short, but a good mantel challenge. A sit start in the back of the cave would be a really good problem and would probably go at V5/6.

name: Heathen In A Handbasket
description: Start low with left hand on good sidepull and right down really low on the arete on your choice of sidepulls. Get your feet on the wall and then throw for a good hold high on the arete with your right. Top it out!

name: Heeley Speedbump
description: Start on the flat edge to the right in the crack. Move left under the rock to the slopey edge. Get a high Heel and then big right-hand move to right crimp. Bring left hand up level with right, bump one more left, and then move heel to slopy edge. Right hand to 2 finger edge at top of rock. Bump one more left to be able to mantle to the top.

name: Just Say Yes To Drugs
description: Start with both hands jammed in the crack below the rock scar. Go up and stay left of the arete on the face. Don't get sucked into the right of the arete and don't dab the right side boulder! Its easy to do both.

name: Like A G6
description: Start sitting/laying with good hands and interesting feet. Throw for a good high right hand or use a sea of marginal intermediates. Fun topout.

name: The Long Wave
description: Start on the far left of the Wave boulder, left hand on a weird sidepull and right on a sloper. Go left under the crest of the Wave, then mantle out on the far right.

name: Low Pass
description: Start on the jugs in the cave, move left to more jugs, throw a heel, top out through crimps and slopers.  Good luck not dabbing; this is about as low as a low-ball gets.

name: moo shu buttresses
description: Start on the flat edge on the right side of the crack and move your way up in the crack in the rock.

name: One Eyed Rooster
description: Start with right hand on a pocket jug, left hand on an obvious circle sloper, and find feet that will get your butt off the pad. Move up through a crimp, a pinch, and a sloper into three crimps around the corner. Top out using the sloped top. Have a good spotter with you, a fall on the last crimps/top out could send you into the boulder behind you.

name: One Man Down and a Hole in the Ground
description: Start with your butt on the ground and pull up the arete.

name: Right around the "EYE"
description: stars just right of the eyebrow, right side of arete/edge and goes up obvious face arete

name: The Screamer
description: This problem is short, but is lots of fun. Start sitting with good holds under the overhang (or use the lowest undercling for a harder variation). For an easier variation, start standing.

name: Sol Worship
description: High start with right hand on right of the blunt arete on good sidepull crimp, left hand on crimp above and left of your head. Fun moves gain the interesting topout.

name: Some Days Are Better Than Others
description: Start with the dead bush between your legs and your butt on the ground. Go straight up over the point.

name: Teahupoo
description: A problem that reminds of the crest/lip of a phat wave, (teahupoo) this problem starts with your butt on the ground and goes up just a few holds (3) to a nice top out.

name: They Don't Get Much Easier Than This
description: Start on the far right side of the rail and go straight up. Fun mantle.

name: The Truth Is Out There
description: Start on the incut rail with your butt low. Look way up and right for a hold, then top out by going left. The first move on this is really reachy, so if you're short, it may prove to be very difficult.

name: UFO
description: Start matched on a flat ledge, get a good right heel, and then work your way around the lip of the boulder. Top out once you reach the pocket.

name: Wanksters Make The World Go Round
description: Start on two good edges just above the overhang. Campus or go for a super fun heelhook and go straight up!

name: Wanna Throw Up?
description: A short problem, but it has some great moves. Start butt on the ground with your right on a bad sloper with a thumb catch, left on the lowest hueco left of the blunt arete. Move your hands up and then pull some weird (yet fun?) moves to gain the slab. Tricky beta.

name: Yukon Cornelius
description: Very short problem with enjoyable moves. Sit start (or low start if you're short) on good holds.

name: "Just Dyno To The Top!"
description: Run and jump problem on the middle of the downstream face of the River Boulder. Look for a good step, run, jump, and grab the top lip where it's squared off and flat!

name: Amoeba Orga__sms
description: really fun climb; although it was alot better before we found the right hand crimp, then it got alot easier.

name: Anni Kookoo
description: A few roof moves lead to pulling over the bulge, crux, then pretty easy slab climbing

name: Bass Boomer
description: This problem is short. Sit start and go straight up.

name: Daycare
description: Low start. Go up and right on slopers with a weird top out.

name: Eat The Children First
description: This problem is short, but features some fun, difficult moves. Start sitting with a poor, low left hand crimp and a better, slightly higher right hand crimp. Go up and slightly left.

name: Eye Of The Cyclops
description: Stand start on the left side of the upstream face, beside the "eye" feature. Climb straight up, staying left.

name: Flying Irishman
description: Awesome! Just run and jump up on slab

name: Free At Last
description: Start with left hand on a good crimp at ~5' and right on a thin crimp at ~6'. Go straight up over the overlap and slab.    A harder variation, "Free'er At Last" (V0+), starts with the same left hand but with the right on a pinch crimp at ~4'. Definitely a fun move going to the thin crimp!

name: Happy Birthday
description: Sit start and climb straight up the left side of the face, staying right of the arete.

name: Hollowgraphic
description: Awesome footwork.  Problem is really good except the rock quality is pretty low. Start holds are lose and chossy.  The first move could be skipped by starting at blocky hold in center of cave without affecting the grade  youtube.com/watch?v=2WgIXkF…

name: Hollowgraphic Right
description: Do start moves of Hollowgraphic and then move right through the jugs. Hardest part is not dabbing.

name: Loose Dog
description: Start on high holds directly left of Mary Kay.

name: Mary K
description: Sit start below the large bulging feature with left hand on good crimp and right on a gaston sloper, then go straight up staying on the left side of the arete. Part of the bulge has broken off subsequent to the FA, resulting in a slightly easier climb.

name: Mothership
description: Cool problem, but the top out is a little akward

name: Nemesis
description: Start on good holds and climb up through the jugs till you have your feet on the good ledge. Move left onto the slab (crux) and pull up through the slopey topout.

name: Olsen Twins
description: Short and Sweet

name: Paluxysaurus
description: Sweet crimp problem

name: Pond Sex
description: Funky start with a low left side pull and a mid height choice of slopers for the right. Slopey topout if you don't find the good hold.

name: Shake and Bake
description: Start on flat rail and move up and right through sharp halfpad crimps to sidepull pinch

name: ship prow
description: 6+ moves to the top.  bring a pad, and some gloves lol to clear the pile of sticks and crap away from base. Only access when river is completely dry.

name: Social Feedback
description: Start in a pocketed seam ~5' high. Go straight up on slopey crimps. Very fun problem!

name: Still Dre
description: Start with left hand in a good slot and right hand on hueco sidepull. Do a couple of really fun, easy moves and then decipher a very tricky top out.

name: Teenage Drama
description: Sit start with hands matched on a ledge at ~3 feet. Go right and up. This problem is short, but a lot of fun with good movement on big holds.

name: Texas Is The Reason For The Season
description: Fun face climb that has some tricky balance moves. Stand start and go straight up on slopes and crimps.

name: You Want A Piece Of Me
description: Start matched on a wide slopey ledge ~5' high, get feet, and go straight up. Be prepared for a slopey top out!
Start low with left hand on good side pull and right on slopey pocket/dish. Go up and left. First move is the crux.

name: Candyland
description: Located between "187" and "Snoop Scoop," on the slab.  The climb is pretty straight forward just move up slab.

name: Charmander
description: Sweet climb that starts alittle high and goes up the arete.  Many other possibilities are on the boulder, but all are considerably harder

name: Charmeleon
description: Same start as Charmander, just goes straight up instead of using the arete.

name: Home Is Wherever I'm With You
description: Start semi-seated on the far right of the boulder and traverse left. Starts off with big feet and then slims down to smears and tiny pockets. An interesting traverse!

name: Honor and Obligation
description: Start with hands on the lowest arete edges/rails and go up and slightly right.

name: I Sharted
description: Start sitting with a good right side pull around the right arete and a poor left sloper on the left arete (or use the under cling for an easier, less consistent variation). Make some big moves and top it out!

name: It's Always Sunny In Glen Rose
description: To the right of Point Break.  Start matched on ledge/rail move left around arete into Point Break and top out.    If you climb in the later afternoon you'll discover the reasoning behind the naming.

name: Jumpin' Hump
description: Short little jump start problem. You could just jump from the base, but the run makes it more fun! Stay left for the harder variation, or go right to make it easy.

name: Las Plagas
description: Start low on the blunt arete with a great crimp with a thumb catch for your right and a marginal sidepull crimp for your left. Make a series of bumps and foot movements to gain the slab above.

name: Point Break
description: Fun short climb up the overhanging wave crest feature.. Stand start matched on ledge and move right and up through pockets and a ledge up to the tip of the wave

name: Poop Chute Arete
description: On the Cyclops boulder, climb the right arete of the upstream face, being careful not to use the detached boulder to your right. Exit early through the grovely Poop Chute, or start traversing up and left at the Poop Chute for a more fun finish at the lip.

name: Rap Alley
description: Start high with matched hands on a crimp rail and go up the mild diheadral.

name: Snoop Scoop
description: Start standing in the large scoop and climb straight up.

name: Spinning Tops
description: One of the first climbable boulders you come to when walking to the second concentration of climbs.  The boulder is 20 ft from the river facing upstream. The problem is "ok."  A lower start to the right is possible and would probably be a little better.

name: Teenage Direct
description: Same start as Teenage Drama (sit start with hands matched on a ledge at ~3 feet), but go straight up on much smaller holds to an interesting topout.

name: Uroboros
description: Start high right hand on a great pinch where the overlap ends and a left hand crimp on the face and go up with good pinches and crimps! Very good movement on fun holds!

name: Vulture Charmer
description: Stand start with right hand on sloping side pull and left on the corner of the lip, or any other way you can get on... With good right foot, slap and grovel with the sloping lip until you can mantle over onto the dirty slab to the top. The sit is definitely possible and will add a notch, maybe v6.

name: Wahrer Of The Worlds
description: This arete is awesome! Start standing with a good right hand side pull and a left hand pinch flake. Very fun moves!

name: White Tree Arête
description: SD. Start left hand on the small horn of the arête, right hand in a slanted, small crimp. Up the arête and top out.

name: Yard Sale
description: Start matched on a juggy ledge at ~5' and then go straight up with either a deadpoint or a solid lockoff.

name: Yard Sit
description: This is the sit start to "Yard Sale". Start sitting using small crimps at ~3 feet and then throw for the jug ledge above. Beware of dabbing!

name: Choppin' Block
description: Climb the crack, high crux.

name: Extreme Fishing
description: Second route from left on the wall.  Climb the edges up onto the flakes.

name: Let The Good Times Roll
description: Route is located on the face to the right of the crack.  Start on the overhang and climb up the folds on the face.

name: Potential Trouble Source
description: Start on the overhang and climb the face.  The moves on this route are a little gymnastic in nature.  The route is named after the flake, it looks good, but like any route at POB, approach with caution.

name: Reportedly Reputedly Repeatedly
description: First and left most route on the wall.  Climb to the second bolt and move left on the flake.  Going direct is a little bit harder.

name: Situational Buddhist
description: Start on the overhang, climb the tough starting moves to the face.  It's a good idea to spot or stick clip this one.

name: Thrash Cowboy
description: Thin face climbing left of the crack.  Locating holds can be difficult.

name: Escape from Paradise  (formerly unfinished route)
description: This route has sat unfinished for many years with only one bolt and two anchors.  It has been lead ground up and from traversing into it from Welcome to Paradise with only the one bolt.  Due to ground fall potential, lack of traffic, and the fact that it sat for so long unfinished we decided to finish it.    Start from the block just left of Welcome to Paradise.  Pull the ground level overhang through good edges until you catch the rail about midway up.  (PLEASE NOTE: it is possible to take a groundfall from here while clipping the second bolt...however you have a great hold and good feet for making the clip.  Just exercise caution.)  Finish on good edges at a 2 bolt belay.

name: Micheladas
description: Climb the face.

name: Sam-O-Rama
description: Not a gimme for the grade.  Difficult to read, sustained and sequence specific.  This route follows the crack.  Various beta for climbing this.  May require a fingerlock.

name: Scooter
description: Climb the chossy white face to the overhang via thin edges, sidepulls and pockets.

name: Stand and Deliver
description: Face climbing to vertical sidebar near the anchors.

name: Succulent Muffin Concept
description: Blind, hard to read face climbing.  Typical of POB.  Thins out as it gets higher.

name: Sweet Action
description: Route climbs the face on the dead roof to the right of the arete.  Standing on the pedestal step up onto the route onto a decent edge to clip the first bolt.  Thin and hard to locate pockets leads to a good crimp and incut sidepull out right. High feet leads to a sloping jug right of the 3rd bolt.  Follow the jugs to the anchors.  Fun climb, feels a bit exposed.

name: Upchuck Thrill
description: Climb the chossy white face to the obvious overhanging roof just right of the corner.  Crux is up high pulling the small crimps to the bigger crimp out left.  A heel hook if you're shorter may make cranking through the crimps easier. There is a good rest before the crux to give time to spot the holds.

name: Welcome To Paradise
description: Climb the obvious corner.  Good feet and hands on either side of the face lead to a good jug located just over the roof. The moves out to the anchor feel exposed and a little tricky, but the traverse is all on jugs and good feet.    This is the first route bolted at Paradise. It is a classic and a must do.

name: Age Wave
description: On the left side of the cave, climb the horizontal fingertip rail, sloth style, to the pronounced   jug at the lip (5.11a) nothing but air. Throw the heel, and get clipped. Getting established   on the headwall (crux) is a grunt. Holds return for the upper section (5.10), but they never   seem to be in your face? This roof is reminiscent of sandstone, rather than limestone;   classic features.   Note: Sometime late summer 2005, the section of roof delineated by the fingertip rail, and   jug, a sheet approximately 4.5ft x 10ft x 10in parted from the cave (see scar, and debris),   the victim of spontaneous rock fall. Alas, one of the most unique limestone routes around   has become talus food. Hangers were pulled for reuse.

name: Brother to Another
description: Starting off of a shallow 2-finger pocket, climb the arching feature. When prudent, balance   to a stance (committing, but at least the landing is good) on top. Protect in the horizontal   crack for insurance, before topping out on jugs.

name: Jack Black
description: From the guidebook:    Climb steep white rock to cool cave holds. Finish on black bulge, and pocket pulls.

name: Look Sharp
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the obvious jam-looking crack via mixed crack, and face maneuvers, on somewhat   sharp holds.

name: Love & War in Texas
description: From the guidebook:     Climb the face above the ground-level hang, skirting right of the bolts, on sidepulls, and thin   pockets. A variation skirting left of the bolts will be much harder.

name: Mississippi of Texas
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the centerpiece black face. A superb undercling leads to gastons and edges out   right, before pulling back to center.

name: Night Crawler
description: From the guidebook:    Start in the corner defining the right side of the cave, and stay in the corner above.

name: Pirates of the Brazos
description: From the guidebook:     Climb ground-level jugs, past thin pockets, to round hole. Thank you round-hole rest!   Continue on pleasantly awkward moves to the belay.

name: Pogo Factor
description: From the guidebook:    Start in the corner defining the right side of the cave, but climb the gray face, left of the   upper corner.   Note: Attempts have been made to remove the unnecessary, bad (i.e., damaged) bolt on   this route the FA party has indicated that theyll get it out sooner or later?

name: Ranchland Demographics
description: Pull, get the feet up, and slap for the cool single-hand jug. Above, getting stood up on the   mini-ridge is more off-balance than it might appear? There are variants getting to the belay:   tricky bulge (up & right / 5.10b), or sidestep left (5.10a) quasi joining Pirates of the Brazos.

name: Scope Creep
description: Start on Pogo Factor and griddle-traverse the headwall above the cave.

name: Texas Bros
description: Slightly overhanging face with small to medium  edges and pockets, side pulls, and a nice side/under-pull up high.  Climbers seem to agree the crux is just above the 2nd bolt.  Rock quality is good for POB.

name: Texas Tea
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the bulge right of the crack pockets-to-finger bucket-to-pockets. The high first bolt   is complimented by a sharp mono.

name: River Chimps
description: This steep climb is a jug hauling good time! Although it is right next to a crack, no crack moves required. According to the guidebook, the crack can be lead on gear (.4"-4").

name: Bio Hazard
description: From the guidebook:    Climb ground-level hang to bulge to face.  Small, but good edges... sustained for the rating.

name: Damn! I Wish I Was Your Lover
description: Pull the roof on thin holds over the lip, which leads to tricky face climbing.

name: Forester
description: This route was scoped out a couple of years ago and I never got around to equipping it.  I finally got out to finish it.  I named it "Forester" in honor of my late friend Jimmy Forester.    The Forester starts just right of Little Monster (the obvious small crack)     Climb up through the broken ledge to the overhang.  The first bolt is actually really easy to reach despite its high appearance. (this was done intentionally to try and prevent hitting the ledge while clipping the second bolt.  Climb up and right of the first bolt on small crimps (sequency crux).   The climbing is pretty sustained but eases off towards the top.  After the last bolt, trend right to a shared anchor with Stray Dog.      I called it 11a, but would be curious to see what others think.

name: Gumption Trap
description: From the guidebook:   Climb crack/seam right of tree

name: Little Monster
description: From the guidebook:    Climb face left of seam crack.  Clump holds, and side pulls.

name: Scrutinizer
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the gray face with white splotches.  Long move to match, hard crank getting established on headwall.  Climb to tree-hole, then traverse right to belay.  Cool features.

name: Stray Dog
description: Climb some steep stuff to the obvious jug above the hang (2nd bolt.)  There are variant paths to said jug; most opt to move right, then back left. Others reach long directly.  Tend right on improved features that may still feel a bit pumpy... until you can get your feet... then climb back left on even more improved holds, and the anchor... great stuff.

name: Twin Oaks
description: Start on the two jugs located on the overhang directly below the oaks that give the route it's name.  The first move is stout for the grade due to a big reach, but a properly placed left foot should make it much easier.  Once established on the wall, follow the crimps to the chains.  The route can also be started with via an easier variation traversing in from the left.

name: Burning Hand
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the blocky face, with a tricky spot up high... starts above tree at base.

name: C.F.I.T.
description: Crux is pulling a small overhang to start and getting established on face above at bolt 1. Move slightly right then up on improving holds to a pumpy stance right of bolt 2 (left hand clip). Go left then straight up on steep face with positive holds (strenuous) to anchor. C.F.I.T. stands for 'Controlled Flight Into Terrain,' an FAA/NTSB term used to to categorize aviation accidents. Don't let that scare you away from this bouldery but surprisingly well-protected route.

name: Gumby's First Ascent
description: From the guidebook:    Start on Scrambled Eggs to its first bolt, but instead of traversing way right, climb the face leading straight up right, past a hump-like feature, to the middle fixed belay.

name: Never Say Jack
description: From the guidebook:    Climb more gray rock with white streaks.  Jugs to pockets, funky crux at top getting to rim holds.

name: POB
description: From the guidebook:    Climb to the white shelf-hole, surmount the bulge, and climb the featured face above.

name: Scrambled Eggs
description: For better or worse, the first route established on the main Patio Wall, Scrambled Eggs (5.8), is a traversing affair. Over time, other routes, each with their own fixed belay, have been added that share, or intersect through parts of, this traversing route.    Climb the traversing route that starts left, but climbs way right. First bolt is located right of   the Patio Boulder. Climb to bolt, and traverse way right, ending up three fixed belays over.

name: Screaming Witch
description: From the guidebook:    Starting at ground level, climb the fractured, gray-white face... perhaps the best introductory beginner/warm-up route on the Patio?

name: Stratospheres Mishap
description: From the guidebook:    Start on Scrambled Eggs to its first bolt, but instead of traversing right, climb the face leading straight up left to the leftmost fixed  belay.

name: Turtle
description: Climb up talus to start, crank past the initial hang, and climb the face above. In light of the fall potential, and a choice of holds, some worse than they appear, getting the high first bolt may be precarious? Climb to the 2nd bolt, where most tend right to features, before moving back left to the belay.

name: Unintended Consequences
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the first line of bolts (dead tree/log at base;) thin face climbing, on gray rock with white streaks.

name: 3rd Degree Escape
description: Climb the first three bolts on Columbia and then move left and turn the lip and gain the ledge. From the ledge, move left and ascend the grey face using a cool pocket. Finish at the large tree that hangs over the wall and use this for an anchor.

name: Atlantis
description: From the guidebook:   Climb the blocky corner left of the cave.  Cool traversing moves.

name: Columbia
description: From the guidebook:   Climb the route on the left side of the cave (denoted in fixed draws).  This POB classic was named in honor of the space shuttle Columbia, which broke apart in blue skies over the crag (north Texas) on January 1st, 2003.

name: The Recliner
description: From the guidebook:    Climb jugs to steep bulge. It may feel like cheating, but the routes namesake no-hands rest   (basically a hanging, horizontal crevasse), enables one to de-pump (or take a nap) beforetackling the headwall bulge. There are two   headwall variations: a.) climb right of the   bolts for burlier action (5.11+), or b.) left of   the bolts for less so (5.11a).

name: Alamo Arete
description: Start on the right side of the obvious arete, where the first crux is a super-fun V2/3 boulder problem.  Surmount to the ledge for a no-hands rest before hopping onto the juggy face.  The second crux comes at the obvious protruding horn, where a slick high foot OR an awkward grunting leg-hook lurch may win the day.  Finish by turning the corner at the top under the roof.

name: Applicator
description: Climb face. 5.8 or 5.9.    Any routes setters who want enter the route info on their routes that I posted, let me know, I will transfer those routes to you.

name: Bad News Flake
description: Crux is between 1st and 2nd bolt.  After third bolt, veer right to anchor.

name: Bubbas in Brazos
description: Climb the break to the first bolt.  Follow the steep jugs to hard face climbing.  Very sequential.

name: Corin's Corner
description: Climb the corner, stemming on both walls.

name: Cowtown
description: Climb chossy lower section thru small roof about 9 feet up, then to slot hold, then go straight up to third bolt and to anchor straight above.  Crux (11b?) is on crimpers and small slots between second and third bolts.  Holds out left in groove make the rating ease off to 10d.

name: Curly
description: Climb face to deep groove near top.  Crux is getting into groove holds.

name: Dallas Route
description: Climb the face left of the arete.  Pull down on crimpers and small edges and slots past the third bolt to the groove, where the climbing eases off.  Climb up groove and veer right to the anchor shared with Alamo Arete.

name: Emmonjay's Favorite
description: Climb up the shelf into the corner system.  Trad gear can be placed in the shelf crack.  There are some loose holds and loose rock on this route, like many POB routes.

name: Fickle Finger of Fate
description: Start climbing The Monkey Lives Here and climb the right side of The Monkey Lives Here flake.

name: Hamlet
description: Climb the corner.

name: Joe
description: Climb face left of corner. Crux is last moves to anchor.

name: Larry
description: Climb right of dark water streak, up face to left of groove up high.

name: Made In Texas
description: Start below the left of two grooves at top of wall.  Make your way up to the groove, then up the groove and to the anchor at right.  Anchor is shared with Cowtown.

name: Mark Us Dubious
description: Start below the detached roof block up high.  Climb the crack with sharp edges in shallow left facing corner. Traverse left below the scary roof block that looks loose. After clipping the 3rd bolt, pulling and stepping over the overhang to get on the head wall is the airy crux.  On the head wall, clip the 4th bolt and climb left to 2-bolt/chain anchor.  Lower off into the trees.

name: Moe
description: Climb the water streak, with crux at 3rd bolt.

name: The Monkey Lives Here
description: A must-do route for sure.  Climb to the break and the first bolt.  Establish yourself on the undercling and work your way up the flake.

name: Niiice One
description: Climb the chossy shelf and clip the high first bolt. Grunt climb the crux overhang bulge and get set up on the gray vertical head wall. Climb less difficult but sustained moves up to anchor.

name: Route 1
description: Climb face right of the flake.  Lower part of route has chossy crumbly rock.

name: Smokin'  Wiliam
description: Climb left of water streak. Look for nice little 2-finger pocket near 2nd bolt. Chossy lower section, but fun moves after high first bolt.

name: Tex Appeal
description: Climb to the left of the bulge.  Climbing to the right of the bulge is easier at 5.7.

name: Thieving Monkey
description: Climb the chossy shelf and clip the high first bolt.  Climb the light-colored overhang using jugs. The airy and exciting crux is pulling over the lip of the overhang and getting set up on the gray head wall. On the head wall, climb easier moves to the anchors up and left.

name: Tribal Bros
description: Taller climbers might find this easier than 11c. Clip the high 1st bolt in overhang.  Climb the overhang using jugs and side-pulls.  Pulling and stepping over the lip of the overhang onto the head wall is the exciting airy crux.  On the head wall, clip the 4th bolt and climb to the anchor. Lower off into the trees.    10d variation: after 3rd bolt, traverse rightward and climb over lip of overhang to join Mark Us Dubious below 4th bolt.    Any routes setters who want enter the route info on their routes that I posted, let me know, I will transfer those routes to you.

name: Cross Timbers
description: Above the break, climb the blocky steps   (high first bolt), angling right to the gray   face above. Pull up to the hole, stay low,   and traverse right to the belay, or, climb up   to the rim, and traverse to the belay. Its   better low.

name: Get Spanked
description: Well protected route with a great angle.  Short, powerful, and fun.  Bouldering on a rope, POB style.

name: N.T.B.
description: Medium or long sling recommended on bolt 1 to avoid rope drag higher up. 10d/11a crux passing bolts 2 and 3, turning the lip of the roof and pulling onto the face above. Reachy with technical footwork. Stay right of bolt 3 and look for the horizontal finger slot right of the vertical seam. Stand up to classic layback at bolt 4 and then follow square holds on easier rock to the anchor.

name: Spoon Licker
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the mini-prowl with a crack-like seam.   Interesting features lurk. Its steeper than it   looks. The high first bolt is high, and   committing to get.

name: Tailgate Party
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the mini-buttress at the base of DC#1. The first bolt may look easier to get than it is. Traverse in from the right. There are variant paths to the 2nd bolt: coming up right from the first bolt  through the huecos)is easier, and more secure, than coming up from its left side. From a stance below the mini-hang, figure out how to  purchase, and leverage, the cool scoop-cup-like hold, and keep it together until rim holds come to the rescue.

name: Training Wheels
description: Climb easy terrain up a short wall.   Note: Currently, all lead/belay hangers   have been removed by the FA party.

name: Earth Prayers
description: From the guidebook:   Climb the right lane, tending right to steep buckets, and the gray headwall above.  The unique palm scum under the starting roof is superb.  Classic route.

name: Stone Remedy
description: Climb the steep face just right of the arete.  Cross over to the left side of the arete after the 2nd bolt.

name: Terra Therapy
description: Climb up the center of the wall following the line of bolts through the overhang.  There are a couple of different options to getting the third bolt.  Either go left and then up (easier) or up and then left (harder).  The moves to the big shelf up top are fun.

name: Apocalypto
description: Climb up a short face and follow the obvious overhanging arete left of "Hanna's Route". Fun route that is overhung the entire way, heel hooks and even a little dead point move thrown in for good measure. The steepest 11 at POB.

name: Black Face
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the black face, immediately right of the arête (lower bolted line). Start near the arête   proper, on steep jugs, and heel hooks. To retain the rating, track the arête, but copout   variants exist.   Cleaning beta: if not seconding, its easier to clean the first two draws from the ledge, then   down climb.   Note: Currently, all lead hangers have been removed by the FA party.

name: Brazos Bros
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the steep hang, to gray headwall above.  Align with a faint corner, left of the first bolt, starting with a mantle boulder problem (5.8) that leads to the break, and the beginning of the business.  The break provides a big ledge stance to clip from enaabling one to get protected before really committing.  A tiered series of buckets (5.10) leads to the lip where holds are less positive, and gravity starts to have its way.  Pull crux moves to get established on the headwall, and then take a diagnonal track to the belay.  The change-up from steep buckets, to off-balance, sideways face climbing is as stimulating as it is discombobulating.

name: Candygram for Mongo
description: Mount the break, and climb the steep face to roof left of the arete.

name: Get Spanked
description: Start about 8' right of Spoonlicker and climb the 30-degree overhanging wall past four bolts to a chained belay at the breakover. The crux is an intricate pocket and edge sequence above a small roof at bolt 3 that sets you up for either an extreme reach (for tall, skinny types) or a dyno to a very positive jug on a horizontal rail. Match, work your feet up above the roof, and hang on to make another reach to a higher rail and bolt 4. The chains are reached after one more move that's easier unless you're gassed by now. If you're not, try the last 'bonus' move past the anchors- another dyno to the small but positive point hold visible on the breakover next to the bolts, on the left.

name: The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the hueco-face, to hang, immediately right of Rock-About... perhaps another, but somewhat less committing first bolt.  Pull up through the huecos to a stance above (5.10b) that gets better after making a hard right.  Recoup strength below the hang, before taking steep moves back left to the chains (5.11a)

name: Hannah's Route
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the same black face as above, but stay in the corner (higher bolted line). Remain   under the hangs for push-you-out climbing, or traverse early for stay-on-your-feet climbing.

name: Happy Things
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the classic roof variation to The Good, The Bad, and The Ugly, and the better of the two lines

name: Rock-About
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the gray face, right of the arete.  Observe the high first bolt where somewhat committing moves and chalky rock advises for a helmet/spotter, and against a lackadaisical attitude.  on the other hand, eliminate the risk altogether and tame it with a stick clip.  Excluding the "mental" start, the challenges scrunch up under the roof, where a sneaky traverse leads back out to the edge of the arete then back up to the rim.

name: Silent Spring
description: This route starts few feet right of "Hanna's Route"  and climbs a slightly overhanging face up through two small roofs finishing on chain anchors.

name: Summer Lava
description: From the guidebook:    Climb the big roofs to headwall. Start via the boulder problem Log Jam (V0+ or 5.10c) to   gain the break, and traverse left a couple of steps on big holds to the 1st bolt. The   somewhat insecure moves can either be bouldered, or protected by fielders choice   (optional viable pro 1in to 1.5in, or stick clip). Once clipped, pull roof moves to cave slot.   Awkward body positioning, and a lack of holds presents the 1st crux in spanning the section   to the lip, where the features may return, albeit on hard, technical, and sustained terrain   (endurance crux). At the last bolt, veer left to gray rock, jugs, and less intense climbing   (5.10) to the belay.

name: Terminator
description: Starts with the first two bolts of "Brazos Brothers> and then trends left through and over the roof up the white and grey convergence to chain anchors.  It is advisable to put long draws on the first two bolts to help alleviate rope drag.

name: 5.8 Crack
description: Crack with TR anchors. Find anchors by scrambling uphill from Monopoly.

name: [Redacted]
description: Start from belay ledge and climb the slab.

name: Adrenaline
description: Climb Texas 2-Step and belay. Traverse left past Dancing With Too Many Women and climb the arete

name: Andy's Encore
description: To the right of belay ledge

name: Chimney Sweep
description: Start from the belay ledge and climb the obvious dihedral

name: Coup Stick
description: First route to the left of Slain Buffalo Ledge. 1st pitch climbs the black, pocketed face to a sloping ledge. 2nd pitch (5.12c) pulls the roof.

name: Cowboy Smarts
description: Start to the right of the shaded traverse cave. Shares the start with Wrangler Savvy and anchors with Giddy up.

name: Cresent Conundrum
description: Just around the corner from Texas 2-Step. Route starts right and trends left. A bolted direct variation starts to the left and comes in around 5.13

name: Dancing With Too Many Women
description: Start Texas 2 Step (5.9 crack) and continue on to the beautiful pocketed face. Clips are desperate    Video of the first ascent: vimeo.com/13190569

name: Fool's Way Out
description: Start in front of the large flat boulder referred to as "Lunch Rock.

name: Giddy-Up
description: Start to the right of Cowboy Smarts. Cool honey comb texture makes some nice underclings pulling the first bulge.

name: Hanging Judge
description: Start on the belay ledge and climb the slabby face.

name: Haute Cuisine
description: Climb the chimney then step towards river. Shares anchors with Monopoly & Shape Shifter

name: Jurisdiction
description: Last bolted line on the right side of Lawless Cove.

name: Monpoly
description: Downhill from Jurisdiction. First route past the cave.

name: The Real UT is in Tennessee
description: Start from belay ledge and climb the slab. Bolt should exist below the belay ledge if you want to start from the ground.

name: Running From the Law
description: Start in from of the large flat boulder referred to as "Lunch Rock"

name: Scott Free
description: Start from the belay ledge and climb the slab

name: Shaded Cave Traverse
description: A shaded traverse cave separates the left(North) side of Lawless Cove from the right (South side). Tons of little boulder problems

name: Shape Shifter
description: Climbs the Arete at the base of the corner then joins Monopoly

name: Texas 2 Step
description: Climb the obvious crack at the bottom left side of Lawless Cove. Dancing With Too Many Women and Adrenaline are both accessed by climbing this crack pitch.

name: War Path
description: Start to the right of Giddy-Up

name: The Way Out
description: First route to the left of the shaded traverse cave

name: Wrangler Savvy
description: Climb up and left of the tree growing out of the horizontal crack. Separate bolts exist that create a direct start from the Shaded Traverse Cave. Direct start is Basta 5.13a.

name: Cat on a Hot Tin Roof
description: Arching crack

name: Flaming Arrow
description: Get ready to pull out all the tricks...this route has a little bit of everything. Start by pulling a thuggy bulge, and then balance your way to the second bolt. From here follow a nice dihedral through cryptic sequences, alternating between delicate balance moves and power pulling. Some chossy rock near the 2nd and 3rd bolt - as well as some awkward clips - detract a little from the quality, but overall a fun route and a full value experience.   (Originally rated 12a, but that seems like a major sandbag; or maybe I just need to get better calibrated to the grades at the Pecos!)

name: Medicine Wheel
description: Arching crack to the right of Cat on a Hot Tin Roof

name: 5.7 Crack
description: Climb the obvious crack/flake system.

name: The Bear Paw
description: First route on the face left of the obvious arete

name: Frosted Flake
description: Fun route. Crux is finding good feet. Easily identified by the namesake "frosted flake' located mid route.

name: Shaman in a Bottle
description: Climb the obvious arete to the right of Bear Paw.

name: Spike Shabook
description: Climb right of the bulge. Good flow and fun movement at the crux.

name: Stab It & Steer
description: First route 10 feet right of 5.7 crack.

name: Tugboat Granny
description: Climb over the bulge

name: Unknown 5.10d
description: Starts over gap in belay ledges

name: Unknown 5.11
description: Route directly to the right of Spike Shabook.

name: Vertrible Anomaly
description: Climb the face left of the obvious crack/flake system.

name: Captain Dick
description: ends at a crimper. vertical/slighly overhung... work your way up sing large pockets in the wall. Finally getting to the crimper makes the route a 5.9. After that there lean left on the crimper and find whatever you can in the wall to bump up to a sloper. Unsure on the grade here... rock was wet...    About 5.10? Unable to finish... deep overhung 4 four funger pockets, with your occasional sloper. The crux is towards the top by working 4 fingers into a sidepull. Then laugh high and right to a big juggy hold. Water is approx 15' deep. Very safe, very overhung.

name: Dick's Blood
description: Start off on a steep overhanging stalactite. Work your way up a flake system with large holds on both sides. Transition to the left side of the flake, and it transitions into several lean back moves up to a half decent knee bar/resting spot. Immediately following the knee bar make a big reach to a large pocket with both hands. Work your feet high, and dyno up to the next juggy ledge. If your tall, you might be able to make it without your feet coming off, but still is a very long reach. From here you can either continue up, or traverse along the ledge to the left. The finish is once your feet are on top of the dyno hold. Extensions coming soon!

name: Off the Yak
description: River boulder problem that cannot be protected, but the holds are bomber so there’s no need. Start on jug, then go up and left using slabby jug techniques.

name: Who's your daddy Long Leg?!
description: This route is a little tricky for a DWS route because it is not completely overhung (hence the PG13), so make sure you push away from the wall if you happen to fall. The start and the finish are the hardest parts of this route. Work your way up a small crack along side an arete. Pull around to the left the arete to a sloper finish. Have fun topping out and jumping off the cliff.

name: The Witch
description: Really great boulder! The grade is height dependent. I've heard V7-9, the consensus seems to be 7+, I thought it was an 8 ¯\_(ツ)_/¯ .

name: Heel My Eye
description: Bit of an eliminate on this one. Start right hand lower on the smaller seam, left hand in the hueco, left heel in the hueco. Head straight up without using the big jug seam above the smaller one. Gain the arete and top out over the point.

name: The Northern Way
description: Start to the far left on a right hand crimp and left hand undercling pocket. Move up to the sloper rail and traverse right topping out using the right arete. Top out over the top instead of the side valley to make it more enjoyable.

name: Doorknob
description: Standing start on sharp undercling then up to finger pockets. Move right on pockets then large move up to hidden jug (doorknob). Traverse right and end by matching on hueco.

name: Easy Street Traverse
description: Start compressed on sharp flake then climb to the left and up along various flakes and edges, ending on obvious jug.

name: Phoenix
description: From the two little pockets to the crack/pocket was probably the most difficult part, and when u are shifting to the right side be careful, because there are sharp rocks below.

name: Support Tree
description: Start compressed and low on flake then up to large pocket. Climb up and slightly left. End matching on large hueco.

name: Grade A
description: A really fun problem starting on two small huecos up to some scrappy crimp action and tough footwork to surmount a bulge followed by a demanding slopey topout. Full value. Downclimb the rope.

name: The Blade
description: Start standing holding the two pinches at 4 feet. Up and left to arete and mantle.

name: Chinese Handcuffs
description: Sit as for Power Trip and use monos to pull the lip.

name: Opportunity
description: Climbs the steep arete from the low hueco to the tippy top.

name: Power Trip
description: Climbs the steep right hand wall of the Diamond. Low start. Get the right hand picket and left pinch. Aim for the bad sloper on the arete.

name: Hooks
description: An area classic. Starts in tiny dual huecos. A long pull gets a good pocket. Serious slopey business to top out.

name: Neverending
description: Good, if brittle, edges, small slopey pockets, and pencil-tip nubbins for feet will get you to the top.   Great delicate face climbing.

name: horseshoe
description: Start at the slanted side, work your way in a U shape around the Boulder. I placed Chalk marks so the route is obvious. You can also view a link i will post in comments to see how i came up with it.

name: It's dangerous business
description: Start at undercling and obvious first handhold. Work your way up and to the left to topout. Walk down other side of boulder.

name: Jupiter East
description: Pretty straight forward and easy. Can be recognized by the discoloration resembling the Eye of Jupiter near the center-top of the face

name: Jupiter West
description: nice under-hang on the left side and bulge on the right edge of slab to start while placing right foot on obvious, but small, center ledge. Bring left foot up to ledge near left under-hang hold. Step up on left foot and reach aggressively for obvious bomber jug/ledge with right hand. From there its a pretty straight forward line to top-out.  I'd suggest taping up right-hand fingers for this one, as the aforementioned jug can be quite sharp in spots. A misplaced grip or slip on the pop-up reach-and-grab could result in some unpleasant skin tearing.

name: North Neptune
description: Sparse, tiny foot holds and two bulging pinches. Proper foot-placement/CG displacement with some dynamic pop/reach is key.

name: South Neptune
description: Start on left side work up to middle/right top-out. Try to limit use of the cheater crimps.

name: Big Dipper
description: Vertical slab with small foot holds

name: Fence Line
description: Start at bottom left of face and traverse up and right to the peak. Falling, while unlikely, could result in injury due to chain-link fence in close proximity.

name: Little Dipper
description: Easy warm-up route with a slight slope

name: Backside Bellatrix
description: Climb from left to right trying to exercise minimal (if any) use of cheater crimps

name: East Rigel
description: Easy face with rectangular indentation

name: East Saiph
description: Easy Eastern face of Saiph Slab on Orion

name: Frontside Betelgeuse
description: Solid, juggy Limestone holds

name: Summer Sunrise
description: Exterior Face of the Summer Slab. Climb straight up the left side.

name: Summer Sunset
description: Pretty straight-forward ascent with nice ledge 3/4 of the way up.

name: Breakeation
description: Start on the rightmost hueco, bust a big move to a jug on the lip of the roof and move left to top out

name: Craw Magnen
description: Start on the big hueco on the back mid-left of cave and traverse right through another hueco to finish on the last big hueco near the ground (which is usually wet. Short problem and an eliminate, but fun!

name: Craw Magnen Direct
description: Lower start to cro magnen on an underclung rail. Still undone (as far as I know)

name: Cro Magnen
description: Start on obvious big hueco in the back of the cave and traverse right and up through more huecos. The last move is a huge dyno to a monster jug over the barbeque pit.

name: Cromagination
description: Link up between Cro Magnen and Breakeation

name: La Salida
description: Standing start on an angled boulder to the left of the bench and go for a flat ledge on the cave's headwall. After, move right to a sloping lip, follow the lip around to the right and top out on obvious jugs

name: Sucker Punch
description: Same start as wet snatch on wonder wall but go left hand into a slot crimp and right hand to a sloping crimp before moving to the lip

name: 4T (Tufa Tufa Tufa Traverse)
description: Start on the far left side of Hidden Cave on good opposing sidepulls. Traverse right through easy climbing that grows progressively harder until you reach the crux towards the right side of the cave. Round the bald arete and exit the cave. Top out on "I'm Lichen This" for an enjoyable, easy highball finish.

name: Bloc Problem
description: Start on the tufa in the middle of the cave. Move up through huecos and end at the hueco in the middle of the roof.

name: Flesh Wound
description: Standing start on two good holds at about head level. Go straight up and back through the large huecos in the roof and finally over the lip for the top out. Cruz is holding the swing in the 3rd hueco. Really fun route in roof with large holds and big moves.

name: Beech Nut
description: Slab climb on thin, crimpy edges to an easy topout.

name: Bull Frog
description: Jump to a big pocket and up through an awkward mantle

name: Virginia Creeper
description: Start low in small pockets on the obvious water streak dihedral and move straight up

name: Virginia Creeper Standing Start
description: Standing start to Virginia Creeper

name: The Board Walk
description: Start on the low undercling on the flake to the left of the broken diving board. Follow the flake up and right, transfer to the horizontal crack and traverse right to top out on the nearly vertical slab above.

name: Boogie Chillun
description: Start low, matched on crimps on a delicate looking flake. Move straight up to a small roof and over a scary top out

name: Channel Cat Indirect
description: Start on Boggie Chillun and move left into the water groove to finish on Channel Cat

name: Channel Cat Low Start
description: Start with your right hand on a poor, slopey sidepull, left hand goes in a small two finger pocket. Make two hard moves to finish the problem

name: Channel Cat Sit Start
description: Self explanatory, same route as channel cat with a sit start that has the normal right hand, but a hard under-cling crimp close to the ground

name: Channel Cat Stand
description: Start with right hand on slopey two finger pocket and left on the gaston sloper and go straight up the water groove. Guidebook says V3+, but its definitely sandbagged.

name: Crawford is for Lovers
description: Start on slopey hold that looks like a mouth. Straight up.

name: Crazy Eyes
description: Start just to the left of the two trees coming out of the rock on matching holds that look like eyes. Straight up.

name: The Devil Came to Crawford
description: Start with your right hand on a sidepull and left hand in a pocket before moving straight up through jugs

name: Full Of Moxy
description: Start sitting with both hands in the 2 foot wide finger slot. Get good feet (they're there!) and then throw for a slopey crimp dish. A few balancy moves later and you're at the top!

name: Fungus Among Us
description: Start sitting with a hard to find slanted crimper/side pull for your right and a big slopey dish for your left, get a good foot and a heel hook and make a big move with your left hand for a really good inset pocket. Then gun for the top! Guidebook lists this as a V3.

name: Green Machine
description: starts in low right of juggy section of main wall, and goes into left into good holds and up

name: Green Planet
description: Start in the middle of the wall on obvious matching jedge in the section with green moss. Move to green sidepull and move towards the nice jug for the top out

name: Guy Smiley
description: Start matching low on a crappy sloped flat edge and go straight up through the smiley face made of wide hueco pockets.

name: Idiot Free America
description: Start with right hand on a grainy side pull and left on a sloping dish. Go straight up on good holds with long move thrown in for good measure.

name: Karen's Problem
description: Start on big holds where the rock forms a small cave at about chest height. Go straight up!

name: Kung Fool
description: Start with your right hand on the Channel Cat sloper and your left on a crimp. Move straight up.

name: Kung Fool Low
description: Just like for Channel Cat Low, start on terrible sloper and shallow two finger pocket. Do the crux first move and then move left into Kung Fool stand.

name: Main Wall Unknown 1
description: Low start matched on the big flat ledge slopers and go straight up. Fun moves!

name: Main Wall Unknown 2
description: Low start matched in a slot and go straight up with fun moves.

name: Meet me at the Stardust
description: start on low holds and go up through jugs. a fun and easy problem with somewhat of a hard top out.

name: Miriams
description: Start on slopey ledge right beneath the broken diving board and climb straight up. The topout is difficult.

name: Moon Child
description: Start on right hand crimp and move straight up

name: Night Train
description: Sit start with your left hand on a nice sloper and right hand in a slotted crimp. Move with your left hand to a two finger crimp then up through slopers

name: Partnership for an Idiot Free America
description: Start in front of a tree on a streaked sidepull with bad feet. Move straight up

name: Slab Shot
description: start right of obvious diving board on slopers and go straight up to top out.  Fun problem.

name: Teenage Wasteland
description: Start with both hands on a slopey crimp with bad feet. Move up and left to sharp crimper then up through jugs

name: V Seventeen
description: Start matched on big jug that looks like a smile and is about at neck height. Make a few easy moves and pull the slopey topout.

name: V Seventeen Dyno Variation
description: Same start as "V Seventeen" (start matched on big jug that looks like a smile and is about at neck height), but instead of using the intermediates, double hand dyno straight to the top slopers.

name: Bacon
description: Same finish as Simmer Down. Start with your right hand on tufa crimps staying right of the jug/ledge foot

name: Filopian Tube
description: Start on the right side of the giant thread through the cave. Move through the tube inside the thread, pull out of the tube and exit straight up

name: The Nautilus Project
description: Start in the back of the cave on the Nautilus shell. Climb through awful crimps to reach a small pocket out on the lip

name: No Name
description: Same start as Not If You're Pregnant but move right through crimps to a jug. Guidebook doesn't have a rating for this one.

name: Not If You're Pregnant
description: Start in big hueco towards the left side of the cave and move directly through slopers to an awkward mantle

name: Simmer Down
description: On the left side of the right most Nautilus Cave, start squatted on the polished ledge. Go to a huge jug and then pull a hard, slopey topout.

name: Snakeskin
description: Start on the slab/arete just right of the first Nautilus Cave and climb straight up!

name: Afterburn LS
description: left side, start in cave and work out onto face/pockets, reach or throw to candle wax looking hold.  easy top out!

name: Arch Rival
description: Start on pocket underneath bulge and match hands on horizontal jug.  Throw to flat ledge with fun but tricky top out.

name: Hit The Deck
description: Climb the white water streak. Big Dyno

name: Secret  Nemesis
description: Starts in center of wall on pockets, go up to jug  and then lip.

name: Wind And Spirit
description: Start in front of the huge tree outside the cave and move up through pockets and crimps

name: I'm Lichen This
description: start on slab go up where Giant step is carved into rock.

name: Mary Bonita
description: Climb arete where slab and cave meet and climb to pocket on face and top out.

name: Mary's Arete
description: Awesome climb with really good footwork through.  Not the best landing, but with 4+ pads it is not too bad.

name: Pinch A Bonita
description: Starts on an undercling jug left of the left hand start of Mary Bonita. Climb straight up to a thin, vertical pinch on the left hand and then make a huge move to the arete/lip above you. Finish on Scary Bonita.

name: The Shield
description: Tricky slab problem starts on left side and goes straight up to a ledge.  highball prob

name: Summertime Whine
description: Awesome climb up the sharp arete.  Could potentially be climbed when water level is up as a shallow water solo.

name: Cosmonaut
description: Start right below the jug where the wall bends left on a small two finger pocket and sloping pinch. Grab the jug and top out on jugs straight up

name: Dead Beat
description: Start in low flat slots just to the left of the stairway and make two easy moves to the top

name: Free Born Man
description: Start in a two finger slot and two finger pocket and make easy moves to the top out

name: Little Brave
description: Start on crimpy, sloped pocket under the bulge and move straight up

name: Pow Pow
description: Begin where the wall starts to curve left on low pockets and move straight up

name: Pow Wow
description: Same start as Pow Pow but move left and top out on jugs

name: Steve's Way
description: Start on low jugs and move left through pockets. Finish on slopers before the wall bends back to the right.

name: Tonkawa Traverse
description: Start right where the stairs end and traverse to the left. Top out when the wall starts to curve left

name: The Two Youtes
description: Start between two small trees (be careful not to damage them!) on a ledge and move straight up.

name: Feel the choss
description: You start matched in the pocket shown in the bottom left of the picture.   Anything below the red line is on, otherwise it’s off. A good rule is if it seems too easy, it’s probably off. You’re traversing to the right, not going straight up.  Beta (super specific to avoid aid): Right hand to the pocket on the rightMatch left with an underclingRight hand to sloperLeft hand to hold slightly above the right hand sloper (be careful not to go over the red line on this, ruins the route) Right hand to shelf, then immediate bump to higher better shelf  Flag right leg and lift body up Match right hand Move feet over right  There is a good shelf where you end up with both your feet and that’s the end.   Since you can’t get your hands up above the line you end up doing a cool little slab traverse at the end

name: Living for the City
description: Start on a crimp rail, move towards a small crimp on the right, then go up and to the right through slopers to the finishing jug

name: Raggae Woman
description: Begin on a ledge, move left towards a slopey jug and up onto a short slab

name: Superstition
description: Start sitting with a good ledge for your right and a decent pocket for your left. Make a few tough moves and you're on the slab. Guidebook calls it V1, but I think that's a bit of a sandbag.

name: Wet Snatch
description: Start in a large right hand pocket and move up through an obvious and nasty sloped pocket before getting to the jugs

name: Wonder Wall Unknown 1
description: This fun and easy climb starts sitting just to the left of the bigger of the two trees that sit against Wonder Wall. Starting holds are opposing sidepulls. Go straight up the slab!

name: BLB Floor Hopper
description: Heady climbing on good crimps inside the BLB from the first floor to the second - first to third if you dare.  Don't pull on the glass.  The building closes around 11 pm, avoid the janitors and late-night frat meetings.

name: Library Chimney
description: Chimney up the library.  A D-ring sticker on the outside of the window marks the current high point.  Unlimited highball potential.

name: Maple Arete
description: climb until you poop your pants, then downclimb.

name: Seashell Wall
description: Climb pockets on the northwest arete.  Top out.

name: Amuse
description: Starts to the left of Ascension just above the cave at the bottom.

name: Ascension
description: Starts to the left of Dubstep.

name: Dubstep
description: Route goes up front right corner of main boulder. Starts with 2 sidepulls.

name: Hardtop
description: Sit start located directly to the right of Scrunch Sit. Left hand starts on slopey 1/2 pad crimp, right hand starts on full crimp. Shoot up to a mini door-knobish hold before working to a bomber pocket and continuing to a slopey topout.

name: Mjolnir (Odin’s Arete)
description: Sit start with right hand on Odin’s left hand gaston and left on a side pull with a small mono. Follow the arete to a crimp on the left and jug pinches on the right. Reach the top jugs only to top out on slopey holds.

name: Odin
description: On the back right side of the boulder to the left of the boulder with the house on it.

name: Scrunch
description: Stand start on a three finger pocket crimp and a half pad bar crimp. Dead point to the pocket jugs and finish the slopey top out.

name: Scrunch Sit
description: Sit start to Scrunch Start on the 1/3 pad crimp for left hand, slopey pinch crimp for right. Shoot for the pocket and then pull to the start holds of Scrunch and finish.

name: Sparks
description: Starts on the right front corner of the main boulder.

name: Tough Drive
description: Middle of the right side of the main boulder. Starts on a white colored crimp about 6 ft up and mono side-pull 4 ft up to the right.

name: Another north wall sit start
description: Another short climb with a struggly mantle crux

name: North Wall sit start
description: Good moves but a little short.  Low crux

name: Paycheck to paycheck
description: Sit start using huecos, then pockets, then dyno to the ledge

name: Rotgut
description: Sit start at right arete.  A much harder (V4) variation exists if you sit start in the Hueco to the left of the arete and stay left.

name: Skoal Boodle
description: Start with your right hand in the two finger pocket.

name: White Trash
description: Sit start using the rail.

name: Stickin' it solid
description: The crux is the very top of the boulder. Full two handed mantle on a sloper ending hold.

name: Whimpsical
description: Boulder name: Lonesome boulder.   When approaching the boulder you will notice the edge of near a tree. You will begin the route a left crimp, right hand slope and good feet. The crux would be moving from the start to a right inset pocket, just to finish the route!

name: Rec yourself
description: Start on the big brick in the middle of the wall. Top out on the top left ledge. Easy jugs in the beginning into some easy crimps. Take your time climbing down.
